  <key id="d0" for="node" attr.name="type" attr.type="string" />
  <graph edgedefault="undirected">
    <node id="&quot;LOGICAL ACCESS CONTROLS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Logical Access Controls" are security measures designed to prevent unauthorized access to data and software. These controls are embedded within the system itself and ensure that personnel can only access applications and data relevant to their job roles. They rely heavily on the use of passwords, which should be regularly changed to minimize potential damage if discovered. Additionally, logical access controls include mechanisms such as system passwords and usage logs to protect data or software from unauthorized access once physical access has been gained.</data>
      <data key="d2">9c567bb17d8b6e625f418a34b755de3d,9cb3ca1f088473aac339bd044b8a7507,dadf38de734316ede827c46363bb8d38</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">0</data>
      <data key="d6">b45241d70f0e43fca764df95b2b81f77</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PASSWORDS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A password is a sequence of characters known only to the user that allows access to a computer system. Effective passwords should be alphanumeric, include upper and lower case letters, and special characters. They should be changed regularly and not be easily guessable."</data>
      <data key="d2">9c567bb17d8b6e625f418a34b755de3d</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1</data>
      <data key="d6">4119fd06010c494caa07f439b333f4c5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;HACKING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Hacking is the deliberate unauthorized access to a system and its data. It can involve stealing, reading, or changing data, or altering system programs. Hacking can be external or internal and includes methods like password cracking and trapdoor attacks."</data>
      <data key="d2">9c567bb17d8b6e625f418a34b755de3d</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">2</data>
      <data key="d6">d3835bf3dda84ead99deadbeac5d0d7d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ENCRYPTION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Encryption is the process of making intelligible data unintelligible to prevent unauthorized access. It involves an algorithm and a key, and the data can only be read by decrypting it with a matching key."</data>
      <data key="d2">9c567bb17d8b6e625f418a34b755de3d</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">3</data>
      <data key="d6">077d2820ae1845bcbb1803379a3d1eae</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SOFTWARE AUDIT TRAIL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A software audit trail is a record of important data about each transaction, including user and terminal identifications, time and date, transaction type, quantities, values, and cross-references to related transactions. It allows transactions to be inspected and verified by third parties."</data>
      <data key="d2">9c567bb17d8b6e625f418a34b755de3d</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">4</data>
      <data key="d6">3671ea0dd4e84c1a9b02c5ab2c8f4bac</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SECURITY GUARDS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Security guards are personnel employed to protect physical access to computer systems, ensuring that only authorized individuals can enter secure areas."</data>
      <data key="d2">9c567bb17d8b6e625f418a34b755de3d</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">5</data>
      <data key="d6">19a7f254a5d64566ab5cc15472df02de</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CAMERAS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Cameras are used in physical access controls to monitor and record activities around computer systems, helping to deter and identify unauthorized access."</data>
      <data key="d2">9c567bb17d8b6e625f418a34b755de3d</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">6</data>
      <data key="d6">e7ffaee9d31d4d3c96e04f911d0a8f9e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TIME CONTROLS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Time controls restrict access to computer systems to specific times, ensuring that unauthorized access attempts outside of these times are prevented."</data>
      <data key="d2">9c567bb17d8b6e625f418a34b755de3d</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">7</data>
      <data key="d6">f7e11b0e297a44a896dc67928368f600</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ELECTRONIC DOOR LOCKS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Electronic door locks are part of physical access controls, requiring electronic authentication methods such as key cards or biometric scans to grant access."</data>
      <data key="d2">9c567bb17d8b6e625f418a34b755de3d</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">8</data>
      <data key="d6">1fd3fa8bb5a2408790042ab9573779ee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SYSTEM PASSWORDS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"System passwords are a type of logical access control used to restrict access to data or software, ensuring that only users with the correct password can gain access."</data>
      <data key="d2">9c567bb17d8b6e625f418a34b755de3d</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">9</data>
      <data key="d6">27f9fbe6ad8c4a8b9acee0d3596ed57c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;USAGE LOGS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Usage logs are records of user activities within a system, used as part of logical access controls to monitor and review access to data or software."</data>
      <data key="d2">9c567bb17d8b6e625f418a34b755de3d</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">10</data>
      <data key="d6">e1fd0e904a53409aada44442f23a51cb</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PASSWORD CRACKING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Password cracking is a hacking method that involves attempting to gain unauthorized access by repeatedly trying different passwords until the correct one is found."</data>
      <data key="d2">9c567bb17d8b6e625f418a34b755de3d</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">11</data>
      <data key="d6">de988724cfdf45cebfba3b13c43ceede</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TRAPDOOR ATTACKS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Trapdoor attacks are a hacking method where a hidden entry point is created in a system, allowing unauthorized access without detection."</data>
      <data key="d2">9c567bb17d8b6e625f418a34b755de3d</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">12</data>
      <data key="d6">96aad7cb4b7d40e9b7e13b94a67af206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TESTING SYSTEMS SECURITY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Testing systems security involves ensuring that security systems are effective. This can be done using in-house staff or external organizations that offer 'attack and penetration' services to test physical and logical access to the computer system."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4fd6778c3735e1144e70c31e7a057e5</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">13</data>
      <data key="d6">c9632a35146940c2a86167c7726d35e9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INTERNAL SOURCES OF MANAGEMENT INFORMATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Internal sources of management information include the accounting system, inventory system, payroll system, purchase processing system, sales processing system, and qualitative information systems. These systems provide detailed information on costs, revenues, inventory movements, employee costs, supplier information, customer purchases, and customer satisfaction."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4fd6778c3735e1144e70c31e7a057e5</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">7</data>
      <data key="d5">14</data>
      <data key="d6">9646481f66ce4fd2b08c2eddda42fc82</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXTERNAL SOURCES OF MANAGEMENT INFORMATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"External sources of management information are used for strategic purposes and include primary information tailored to an organization's needs, such as market research and competitor pricing, and secondary information produced for general use, such as government statistics, country reports, business directories, and trade magazines."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4fd6778c3735e1144e70c31e7a057e5</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">7</data>
      <data key="d5">15</data>
      <data key="d6">d91a266f766b4737a06b0fda588ba40b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;USE OF INFORMATION IN CONTROL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Different levels of management use information for control purposes: strategic managers use high-level information for long-term planning and control, tactical managers use detailed internal information for efficient operation, and operational managers use detailed transactional information from sub-systems."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4fd6778c3735e1144e70c31e7a057e5</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">16</data>
      <data key="d6">bc0e3f075a4c4ebbb7c7b152b65a5625</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STRATEGIC PLANNING AND CONTROL INFORMATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Information for strategic planning addresses high-level objectives, includes external information, is often ad hoc, and contains long-term forecasts. Examples include economic and market forecasts, competitor analysis, profits by business segment, and investment appraisal."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4fd6778c3735e1144e70c31e7a057e5</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">17</data>
      <data key="d6">254770028d7a4fa9877da4ba0ad5ad21</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TACTICAL PLANNING AND CONTROL INFORMATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Information for tactical planning contains detailed internal information, is provided regularly, and includes forecasts up to 12 months. Examples include annual budgets, sales analysis by product/customer/location, inventory levels, and cash flow projections."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4fd6778c3735e1144e70c31e7a057e5</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">18</data>
      <data key="d6">4a67211867e5464ba45126315a122a8a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPERATIONAL PLANNING AND CONTROL INFORMATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Operational planning requires transaction-based data, which is almost entirely internal and covers short-term periods. Examples include variances, receivables/payables levels, payroll details, customer complaints, and output records."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4fd6778c3735e1144e70c31e7a057e5</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">19</data>
      <data key="d6">04dbbb2283b845baaeac0eaf0c34c9da</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INFORMATION SYSTEMS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Information Systems are systems that monitor and manage the activities and transactions of an organization, encompassing management-level, operational-level, knowledge-level, and strategic-level systems. The four main types of information systems that support different levels of an organization include: Executive Information System (EIS) for strategic purposes, Decision Support System (DSS) and Management Information System (MIS) for tactical purposes, and Transaction Processing System (TPS) for operational purposes. Additionally, using a software package that integrates with the company's systems is recommended for managing a rolling budget. This approach ensures unified budgeting data, easy access, and updates by multiple users, although it may come at a substantial cost and require user support and training.</data>
      <data key="d2">16965b8a36bbe6bac45c7b81a6b17c48,9cb3ca1f088473aac339bd044b8a7507,d4fd6778c3735e1144e70c31e7a057e5</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">20</data>
      <data key="d6">1943f245ee4243bdbfbd2fd619ae824a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TRANSACTION PROCESSING SYSTEM (TPS)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">A Transaction Processing System (TPS) is responsible for capturing and processing data related to business transactions. It is a type of information system used by operational staff to capture data and make processes more efficient, thereby improving the accuracy and timeliness of information. TPS data is primarily high-frequency and short-term. As an operational information system, TPS processes transaction-based data, providing detailed and short-term information for operational planning and control.</data>
      <data key="d2">27b66fcc5173aa41f6af55ff955c7910,2ad6c0ee81f4b0da1c6b2f2821dff6b6,325c77c5edc123d6ed91f5bcbab95061,d4fd6778c3735e1144e70c31e7a057e5</data>
      <data key="d3">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">7</data>
      <data key="d5">21</data>
      <data key="d6">273daeec8cad41e6b3e450447db58ee7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXECUTIVE INFORMATION SYSTEM (EIS)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">An Executive Information System (EIS) is a strategic information system designed to provide high-level, summarized information to senior executives within an organization. It often includes features such as data visualizations and reporting tools, which aid in long-term planning and decision-making. The primary purpose of an EIS is to support executives by delivering critical information in a concise and accessible format, enabling them to make informed strategic decisions.</data>
      <data key="d2">27b66fcc5173aa41f6af55ff955c7910,2ad6c0ee81f4b0da1c6b2f2821dff6b6,325c77c5edc123d6ed91f5bcbab95061,d4fd6778c3735e1144e70c31e7a057e5</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">22</data>
      <data key="d6">e69dc259edb944ea9ea41264b9fcfe59</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DECISION SUPPORT SYSTEM (DSS)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">A Decision Support System (DSS) is a type of information system designed to support the tactical level of an organization by aiding managers in their decision-making processes. It provides relevant data, analytical tools, and models that help in analyzing information and exploring 'what-if' scenarios and outcomes based on various input variables. By offering these capabilities, a DSS assists managers in making informed and effective decisions.</data>
      <data key="d2">27b66fcc5173aa41f6af55ff955c7910,2ad6c0ee81f4b0da1c6b2f2821dff6b6,325c77c5edc123d6ed91f5bcbab95061,d4fd6778c3735e1144e70c31e7a057e5</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">23</data>
      <data key="d6">e2f5735c7d714423a2c4f61ca2644626</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MANAGEMENT INFORMATION SYSTEM (MIS)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">Management Information System (MIS) is a tactical information system that provides regular reports and summaries of data to help managers with planning, controlling, and decision-making. It is a type of information system that converts data from internal and external sources into information used by management at all levels and across all functions to make timely and effective decisions.</data>
      <data key="d2">325c77c5edc123d6ed91f5bcbab95061,d4fd6778c3735e1144e70c31e7a057e5</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">24</data>
      <data key="d6">deece7e64b2a4628850d4bb6e394a9c3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ACCOUNTING SYSTEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"COMPONENTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The accounting system is an internal source of management information that records financial transactions and provides data on costs, revenues, and financial performance."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4fd6778c3735e1144e70c31e7a057e5</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">25</data>
      <data key="d6">e657b5121ff8456b9a610cfaead8e0cb</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INVENTORY SYSTEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"COMPONENTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The inventory system is an internal source of management information that tracks inventory levels, movements, and valuations."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4fd6778c3735e1144e70c31e7a057e5</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">26</data>
      <data key="d6">bf4e255cdac94ccc83a56435a5e4b075</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PAYROLL SYSTEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"COMPONENTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The payroll system is an internal source of management information that manages employee compensation, benefits, and related costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4fd6778c3735e1144e70c31e7a057e5</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">27</data>
      <data key="d6">3b040bcc19f14e04880ae52881a89c1c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PURCHASE PROCESSING SYSTEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"COMPONENTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The purchase processing system is an internal source of management information that handles procurement activities, supplier information, and purchase orders."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4fd6778c3735e1144e70c31e7a057e5</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">28</data>
      <data key="d6">3d6b216c14354332b1bf1927ba168986</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES PROCESSING SYSTEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"COMPONENTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The sales processing system is an internal source of management information that manages customer orders, sales transactions, and customer information."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4fd6778c3735e1144e70c31e7a057e5</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">29</data>
      <data key="d6">1c109cfdc370463eb6d537e5b7b382fb</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUALITATIVE INFORMATION SYSTEMS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"COMPONENTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Qualitative information systems are internal sources of management information that provide non-quantitative data, such as customer satisfaction and employee feedback."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4fd6778c3735e1144e70c31e7a057e5</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">30</data>
      <data key="d6">3d0dcbc8971b415ea18065edc4d8c8ef</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARKET RESEARCH&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"COMPONENTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Market research is an external source of management information that provides primary data tailored to an organization's needs, such as customer preferences and market trends."</data>
      <data key="d2">9e697a6f98eb47e0e26d6fb7c2205aca,d4fd6778c3735e1144e70c31e7a057e5</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">31</data>
      <data key="d6">68105770b523412388424d984e711917</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COMPETITOR PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"COMPONENTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Competitor pricing is an external source of management information that provides primary data on the pricing strategies of competitors."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4fd6778c3735e1144e70c31e7a057e5</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">32</data>
      <data key="d6">85c79fd84f5e4f918471c386852204c5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GOVERNMENT STATISTICS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"COMPONENTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Government statistics are an external source of management information that provides secondary data produced for general use, such as economic indicators and demographic data."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4fd6778c3735e1144e70c31e7a057e5</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">33</data>
      <data key="d6">eae4259b19a741ab9f9f6af18c4a0470</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COUNTRY REPORTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"COMPONENTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Country reports are an external source of management information that provides secondary data on the economic, political, and social conditions of different countries."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4fd6778c3735e1144e70c31e7a057e5</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">34</data>
      <data key="d6">3138f39f2bcd43a69e0697cd3b05bc4d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BUSINESS DIRECTORIES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"COMPONENTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Business directories are an external source of management information that provides secondary data on companies, including contact information and business profiles."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4fd6778c3735e1144e70c31e7a057e5</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">35</data>
      <data key="d6">dde131ab575d44dbb55289a6972be18f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TRADE MAGAZINES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"COMPONENTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Trade magazines are an external source of management information that provides secondary data on industry trends, news, and developments."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4fd6778c3735e1144e70c31e7a057e5</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">36</data>
      <data key="d6">de9e343f2e334d88a8ac7f8813a915e5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BATCH PROCESSING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Batch processing is an approach where individual transactions of the same type are collected into batches and stored for later input to the computer. Processing proceeds in discrete runs, making it easier to control as data can be checked and validated before processing."</data>
      <data key="d2">325c77c5edc123d6ed91f5bcbab95061</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">37</data>
      <data key="d6">e2bf260115514fb3b252fd879fb3e7be</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REAL-TIME PROCESSING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Real-time processing is an approach where transactions are processed immediately as they occur, ensuring that information in the system is always up-to-date. However, it can be challenging to control, and the risk of errors is greater."</data>
      <data key="d2">325c77c5edc123d6ed91f5bcbab95061</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">38</data>
      <data key="d6">b462b94ce47a4b8c8fffa33f7242acec</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ELECTRONIC POINT OF SALE (EPOS)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">Electronic Point of Sale (EPOS) is a computerized system used to record sales transactions. It utilizes bar code readers to capture details of each sale and can be linked to other systems for real-time data processing and inventory management. In a supermarket setting, the Transaction Processing System (TPS) may include an EPOS system, where goods are scanned by the cashier using a bar-code reader when the customer is checking out.</data>
      <data key="d2">27b66fcc5173aa41f6af55ff955c7910,2ad6c0ee81f4b0da1c6b2f2821dff6b6,325c77c5edc123d6ed91f5bcbab95061</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">39</data>
      <data key="d6">17ed1d92075643579a712cc6c29e8ddb</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ELECTRONIC DATA INTERCHANGE (EDI)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">Electronic Data Interchange (EDI) is a system that enables the supermarket's system to communicate with the suppliers' systems, facilitating transactions such as placing orders, receiving goods, and making payments.</data>
      <data key="d2">27b66fcc5173aa41f6af55ff955c7910,325c77c5edc123d6ed91f5bcbab95061</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">40</data>
      <data key="d6">3ce7c210a21b4deebad7cc9308148d86</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ ON INFORMATION SYSTEMS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"QUIZ ON INFORMATION SYSTEMS" is a quiz that involves suggesting examples of information required from an information system for a market trader working in a fruit market and a materials purchasing department in a factory.</data>
      <data key="d2">27b66fcc5173aa41f6af55ff955c7910,325c77c5edc123d6ed91f5bcbab95061</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">41</data>
      <data key="d6">d64ed762ea924caa95c8d06f072a9a96</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TACTICAL LEVEL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATIONAL LEVELS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The tactical level of an organization involves short- to medium-term planning and decision-making by middle managers to implement strategies and achieve specific objectives."</data>
      <data key="d2">27b66fcc5173aa41f6af55ff955c7910,325c77c5edc123d6ed91f5bcbab95061</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">42</data>
      <data key="d6">adf4ee3fbe9b4d0381044838c4f889c8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPERATIONAL LEVEL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATIONAL LEVELS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The operational level of an organization involves day-to-day activities and decision-making by operational staff to ensure efficient and effective execution of tasks."</data>
      <data key="d2">27b66fcc5173aa41f6af55ff955c7910,325c77c5edc123d6ed91f5bcbab95061</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">43</data>
      <data key="d6">32ee140946e5461f9275db664dc541a5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INTERNAL INFORMATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"INFORMATION TYPES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Internal information refers to data generated within an organization, such as financial records, employee data, and internal reports."</data>
      <data key="d2">27b66fcc5173aa41f6af55ff955c7910,325c77c5edc123d6ed91f5bcbab95061</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">44</data>
      <data key="d6">c160b9cb27d6408ba6ab20214a2f3f81</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXTERNAL INFORMATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"INFORMATION TYPES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"External information refers to data obtained from outside an organization, such as market trends, competitor analysis, and regulatory requirements."</data>
      <data key="d2">27b66fcc5173aa41f6af55ff955c7910,325c77c5edc123d6ed91f5bcbab95061</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">45</data>
      <data key="d6">23527cd679ff4d5a988d52e7cd056078</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CRITICAL SUCCESS FACTORS (CSFS)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Critical Success Factors (CSFs) are the essential areas of activity that must be performed well for an organization to achieve its mission and objectives."</data>
      <data key="d2">27b66fcc5173aa41f6af55ff955c7910,325c77c5edc123d6ed91f5bcbab95061</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">46</data>
      <data key="d6">f1c6eed066f24cbdb376b910fce29ed4</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DATA ANALYSIS TOOLS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"TOOLS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Data analysis tools are software applications and methodologies used to analyze data, identify patterns, and support decision-making processes."</data>
      <data key="d2">27b66fcc5173aa41f6af55ff955c7910,325c77c5edc123d6ed91f5bcbab95061</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">47</data>
      <data key="d6">83a6cb03df6b41d8ad6ee5f6fef5f024</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BAR-CODE READER&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"DEVICES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A bar-code reader is a device used to scan and read barcodes, typically used in retail environments to track inventory and process sales transactions."</data>
      <data key="d2">27b66fcc5173aa41f6af55ff955c7910,325c77c5edc123d6ed91f5bcbab95061</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">48</data>
      <data key="d6">147c038aef3e4422acbbc5f7938c4ab8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SUPPLIERS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"STAKEHOLDERS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Suppliers are external entities that provide goods or services to an organization, playing a crucial role in the supply chain."</data>
      <data key="d2">27b66fcc5173aa41f6af55ff955c7910,325c77c5edc123d6ed91f5bcbab95061</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">49</data>
      <data key="d6">b7702b90c7f24190b864e8c6e64612a5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARKET TRADER&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"ROLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A market trader is an individual who sells goods, typically in a market setting, and requires information on inventory, sales, and market trends to operate effectively."</data>
      <data key="d2">27b66fcc5173aa41f6af55ff955c7910,325c77c5edc123d6ed91f5bcbab95061</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">50</data>
      <data key="d6">de6fa24480894518ab3cbcb66f739266</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIALS PURCHASING DEPARTMENT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"DEPARTMENTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The materials purchasing department in a factory is responsible for procuring raw materials and supplies needed for production, requiring information on inventory levels, supplier performance, and order status."</data>
      <data key="d2">27b66fcc5173aa41f6af55ff955c7910,325c77c5edc123d6ed91f5bcbab95061</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">51</data>
      <data key="d6">6fae5ee1a831468aa585a1ea09095998</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CHARACTERISTICS OF A SOUND CRM SYSTEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Characteristics of a sound CRM system include easy import of data from existing databases, ease of use (e.g., an intuitive interface and good user support), adaptability as the business grows, improved customer satisfaction, and easy reporting and tracking features."</data>
      <data key="d2">75aa284e3bf8d3b64f3e1feff1c7b3fb</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">52</data>
      <data key="d6">ef32c4b208d041cc856f6837915dc1b0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BIG DATA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Big data refers to vast data sets that may be analyzed to reveal patterns, trends, and associations, especially relating to human behavior and interactions. Essential characteristics of big data include volume, variety, velocity, veracity, and value."</data>
      <data key="d2">75aa284e3bf8d3b64f3e1feff1c7b3fb</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">53</data>
      <data key="d6">07b2425216bd4f0aa4e079827cb48ef5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STRUCTURED DATA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Structured data is data stored within defined fields within a defined record, along with similar data, according to the specifications laid down in a data model. The data model limits the data collected and how it can be processed."</data>
      <data key="d2">75aa284e3bf8d3b64f3e1feff1c7b3fb</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">54</data>
      <data key="d6">2670deebfa3f4d69bb82c28ab250a209</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;UNSTRUCTURED DATA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Unstructured data is information gathered in various forms and ways, not in accordance with any data model, and thus may be difficult to store or analyze."</data>
      <data key="d2">75aa284e3bf8d3b64f3e1feff1c7b3fb</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">55</data>
      <data key="d6">404309e89a5241d6bff42c05a45df206</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CHARACTERISTICS OF BIG DATA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The essential characteristics of big data include volume (a tremendous amount), variety (non-uniform, from internal and external sources), velocity (fast and continuous processing), veracity (validity and reliability of data), and value (cost-benefit analysis of big data)."</data>
      <data key="d2">75aa284e3bf8d3b64f3e1feff1c7b3fb</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">56</data>
      <data key="d6">b785a9025069417f94950ad231bb1441</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DATA ANALYTICS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Data Analytics" is the processing of big data to identify trends, patterns, and associations, and to transform data into a visual context. It involves various techniques such as data testing, data mining, predictive analytics, text analytics, and statistical analytics. The primary goal of data analytics is to identify patterns, relationships, and trends within data to inform decision-making.</data>
      <data key="d2">75aa284e3bf8d3b64f3e1feff1c7b3fb,9cb3ca1f088473aac339bd044b8a7507,a90ec32176608282b11bed138f7007da</data>
      <data key="d3">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d4">8</data>
      <data key="d5">57</data>
      <data key="d6">3b6cd96a27304614850709aba1c9598b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DATA TESTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Data testing involves testing models or hypotheses on existing data to validate assumptions and predictions."</data>
      <data key="d2">75aa284e3bf8d3b64f3e1feff1c7b3fb</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">58</data>
      <data key="d6">d54956b79dd147f894b67a8b97dcbef0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DATA MINING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Data mining involves analyzing data to identify patterns, relationships, and correlations. It includes finding relationships between variables, applying known structures to new data, identifying groups and structures within the data, spotting unusual items, and providing results in a user-friendly form."</data>
      <data key="d2">75aa284e3bf8d3b64f3e1feff1c7b3fb</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">59</data>
      <data key="d6">958beecdb5bb4060948415ffd75d2b03</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PREDICTIVE ANALYTICS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Predictive analytics is a type of data mining that uses statistical or machine learning techniques to predict future events, such as the likelihood that a customer may be persuaded to buy a more expensive product."</data>
      <data key="d2">75aa284e3bf8d3b64f3e1feff1c7b3fb</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">60</data>
      <data key="d6">b999ed77e19e4f85b7f1ae79af5c002a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TEXT ANALYTICS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Text analytics involves scanning emails and word documents to extract useful information, such as keywords that indicate an interest in a product. Voice analytics is a similar process but with audio data."</data>
      <data key="d2">75aa284e3bf8d3b64f3e1feff1c7b3fb</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">61</data>
      <data key="d6">48c0c4d72da74ff5bb926fa0c856d1a7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STATISTICAL ANALYTICS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Statistical analytics is used to identify trends, correlations, and changes in behavior within data."</data>
      <data key="d2">75aa284e3bf8d3b64f3e1feff1c7b3fb</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">62</data>
      <data key="d6">4f3c97517f794ebfb49c4c6315f9cf23</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BIG DATA (DIKW) PYRAMID&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Big Data (DIKW) Pyramid, developed by Ackoff and further by Jennifer Rowley, shows the stages of transforming initial unstructured data into material for reliable decision-making and accurate forecasting. The stages are Data, Information, Knowledge, and Wisdom."</data>
      <data key="d2">75aa284e3bf8d3b64f3e1feff1c7b3fb</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">63</data>
      <data key="d6">1745a2485a9443bab76587ad650e9be0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DATA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Data consists of raw facts and figures that may be provided from several sources, ideally in a format that enables links to be made between different items."</data>
      <data key="d2">75aa284e3bf8d3b64f3e1feff1c7b3fb</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">64</data>
      <data key="d6">32e6ccab20d94029811127dbbe424c64</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INFORMATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Information" is data that has been processed and organized in a meaningful way. It involves identifying relationships and establishing links between different data items, thereby transforming raw data into a form that is useful and meaningful.</data>
      <data key="d2">75aa284e3bf8d3b64f3e1feff1c7b3fb,9cc1a2ea3eea29b6f534abb18ab94b2d</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">65</data>
      <data key="d6">94a964c6992945ebb3833dfdfdc8d655</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;KNOWLEDGE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Knowledge" is information that has been comprehended and applied to make decisions or perform tasks. It involves the understanding of data relationships, providing more detail about the context of how and why the links between the data might arise. Further analysis of these relationships reveals specific connections and patterns, transforming data into knowledge.</data>
      <data key="d2">0300615aebb7ef4e2e5e1ed830623ea3,75aa284e3bf8d3b64f3e1feff1c7b3fb,9cc1a2ea3eea29b6f534abb18ab94b2d</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">66</data>
      <data key="d6">1eb829d0ace042089f0746f78729696c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;WISDOM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"WISDOM" is the ability to make sound judgments and decisions based on knowledge and experience. It involves improved decision-making from the understanding of data relationships, ensuring that the knowledge can be used to make informed decisions and accurate forecasts. By comprehending and utilizing data relationships effectively, wisdom enables individuals to make sound decisions and correct predictions.</data>
      <data key="d2">0300615aebb7ef4e2e5e1ed830623ea3,75aa284e3bf8d3b64f3e1feff1c7b3fb,9cc1a2ea3eea29b6f534abb18ab94b2d</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">67</data>
      <data key="d6">015e7b58d1a14b44beab3bbc9f912c18</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CUSTOMER INTERACTIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Customer interactions refer to the various ways in which a business engages with its customers, including communication through emails, phone calls, social media, and in-person meetings."</data>
      <data key="d2">75aa284e3bf8d3b64f3e1feff1c7b3fb</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">68</data>
      <data key="d6">26f88ab3e2e04c33a459ad6270ade565</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CUSTOMER DATA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Customer data includes any information related to customers, such as contact details, purchase history, preferences, and feedback."</data>
      <data key="d2">75aa284e3bf8d3b64f3e1feff1c7b3fb</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">69</data>
      <data key="d6">babe97e1d9784cffa1c85abc1e588126</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CUSTOMER SERVICE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">Customer service involves assisting and supporting customers before, during, and after a purchase to ensure a positive experience and satisfaction. It encompasses the assistance and advice provided by a company to those who buy or use its products or services. Customer service is vital in service industries and also critical in manufacturing industries.</data>
      <data key="d2">75aa284e3bf8d3b64f3e1feff1c7b3fb,e0207e68269c195f8b3bf7a33eedab96</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
