    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ACTUAL MATERIAL PRICE COSTS VS BUDGET ESTIMATES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Management has just received the final figures for actual material price costs last year and wants to compare them to the original budget estimates."</data>
      <data key="d2">a65f7c228e32e13ec5bad9f87503b9c1</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">101</data>
      <data key="d6">5c41f96be13e49dba649454297834546</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SIMPLE BAR CHART&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">A simple bar chart is typically used to present a single data series over several periods. For example, a simple bar chart can be used to present Franklyn's Football Factory sales data over three years.</data>
      <data key="d2">94bad6b839398ff56bb1fd1316fb6bc0,a65f7c228e32e13ec5bad9f87503b9c1</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">102</data>
      <data key="d6">7ea4afbf8a264f29af29950ce98105ba</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COMPOUND BAR CHART&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">A compound bar chart is used to present multiple data series over multiple periods, such as four quarters in a year or over several years. For example, it can be used to display total sales and total costs over five years. This type of chart, also known as a clustered bar chart, effectively visualizes the comparison of different data series across various time periods.</data>
      <data key="d2">94bad6b839398ff56bb1fd1316fb6bc0,a65f7c228e32e13ec5bad9f87503b9c1</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">103</data>
      <data key="d6">91ff849d12b24574b0691dbddf44968b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BAR CHARTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">Bar charts are graphical representations that are drawn with two axes: the independent variable on the x-axis and the dependent variable on the y-axis. Each bar in a bar chart represents a category of data, and the length of the bar corresponds to the value of that category. Bar charts must be drawn from the origin to reduce misinterpretation. They are best used for comparing different categories of data or for comparison between two data series.</data>
      <data key="d2">a65f7c228e32e13ec5bad9f87503b9c1,c29f0f482a2be0aca99305e718e34f55</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">104</data>
      <data key="d6">d73c1f2fb3094d8dace42ad2a76e9a52</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TABLE&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1">A table is suitable for summarizing the amount of numerical data for monthly sales for all ten stores. It is used to organize data in rows and columns, making it easy to compare different sets of data.</data>
      <data key="d2">94bad6b839398ff56bb1fd1316fb6bc0,a65f7c228e32e13ec5bad9f87503b9c1</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">105</data>
      <data key="d6">cdc8901e668749889bd49bebdc4ff1f6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SCATTER DIAGRAM&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1">A scatter diagram is used to display values for two variables for a set of data, often to determine if there is a relationship between them. Scatter diagrams plot data points on a chart with two variables for each axis.</data>
      <data key="d2">a65f7c228e32e13ec5bad9f87503b9c1,c29f0f482a2be0aca99305e718e34f55</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">106</data>
      <data key="d6">36084a9fab53433493f079e97e68bf65</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LINE CHART&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1">A line chart is used to display information as a series of data points called 'markers' connected by straight line segments. It is often used to track changes over periods of time.</data>
      <data key="d2">5ad3a043b58cedf0d850b61a9e407269,a65f7c228e32e13ec5bad9f87503b9c1</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">107</data>
      <data key="d6">eebcc7ec8e3e4df7aea83659bbdc2199</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BAR CHART&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">a65f7c228e32e13ec5bad9f87503b9c1</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">108</data>
      <data key="d6">ceadf262ef834e9ab146b20650912cae</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SIMPLE BAR CHART QUIZ&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">a65f7c228e32e13ec5bad9f87503b9c1</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">109</data>
      <data key="d6">7f65feab75424b53b24470d305ba331a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COMPOUND BAR CHART QUIZ&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">a65f7c228e32e13ec5bad9f87503b9c1</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">110</data>
      <data key="d6">fd9cb733b28d420cb5cef01e545a132c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PIE CHART&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">A pie chart is a visualization tool used to represent proportions of a whole for a single period. It typically displays data as slices of a circle, with each slice corresponding to a specific category's contribution to the total. This graphical representation helps in easily understanding the relative sizes of different components within a dataset.</data>
      <data key="d2">94bad6b839398ff56bb1fd1316fb6bc0,a65f7c228e32e13ec5bad9f87503b9c1</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">111</data>
      <data key="d6">0fbcca3f17c649a08aea64b5a7d9ef36</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COMPONENT BAR CHART&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A component (\"stacked\") bar chart presents the numerical amounts of data series that make up a total. Component can also be converted to proportions of a total (similar to a pie chart). This loses the numerical amounts."</data>
      <data key="d2">c29f0f482a2be0aca99305e718e34f55</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">112</data>
      <data key="d6">482027a59f32484c9c44fd700615c1b6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LINE CHARTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Line charts are drawn with two axes, usually with the independent variable on the x-axis and the dependent variable on the y-axis. Care must be taken during the production and interpretation of the chart if the axes of a line chart are not drawn from the origin (i.e. the point where the x and y axes intercept at x = 0 and y = 0). A line chart is best suited to observe trends over time."</data>
      <data key="d2">c29f0f482a2be0aca99305e718e34f55</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">113</data>
      <data key="d6">de837ff3d626451282ff6ac77a82216d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SIMPLE LINE CHART&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Example of Simple Line Charts: Give an example that shows a gentle increase in the sales trend over five years. By contrast, give another example of simple line chart that shows a more significant rate of change in total sales."</data>
      <data key="d2">c29f0f482a2be0aca99305e718e34f55</data>
      <data key="d3">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">114</data>
      <data key="d6">460295fed3ae4cd39f9f274cec9c2506</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MULTIPLE LINE CHART&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Example of Multiple Line Chart: draw a multiple line chart with two lines: one is for the Total sales, and the other for the Total costs. The Total sales is in blue color, and the Total costs in red color. The y-axis is not from the origin. The smaller scale means that the rate of change in the lines appears more significant. The gap between the lines is profit. The narrowing of the gap in 20X2 and 20X3 means that profit is shrinking. It is easy to see the sales and cost trends and how they compare."</data>
      <data key="d2">c29f0f482a2be0aca99305e718e34f55</data>
      <data key="d3">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">115</data>
      <data key="d6">553b285bba60460ab1ed8341ae61282b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PIE CHARTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Pie charts are most suitable for showing the proportions of multiple data series at a single period or point. The entire \"pie\" is 100%, with each data series representing a proportion of it. For example, 25% would be a quarter of the pie."</data>
      <data key="d2">c29f0f482a2be0aca99305e718e34f55</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">116</data>
      <data key="d6">cec95bf17e7e4c939b56c9c6f402a29f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF SCATTER DIAGRAM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The total monthly costs and outputs for a process are as follows: Jan 100 units, $2,500; Feb 110 units, $2,600; Mar 90 units, $2,200; Apr 100 units, $2,600; May 100 units, $2,550; Jun 130 units, $3,000; Jul 110 units, $2,650; Aug 90 units, $2,300; Sep 120 units, $2,800; Oct 130 units, $2,900; Nov 140 units, $2,950; Dec 100 units, $2,400. Plotting the pairs of data gives the following scatter diagram: There appears to be a relationship between output units and total costs (more output, higher cost), although some cost variations occur at some of the output levels. Where there appears to be a linear relationship between two variables, a trend can be estimated using a \"line of best fit\"."</data>
      <data key="d2">c29f0f482a2be0aca99305e718e34f55</data>
      <data key="d3">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">117</data>
      <data key="d6">599164aead034bc19446efacc77554d2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INAPPROPRIATE USE OF DATA VISUALISATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"It is essential to use the proper visualisation to convey the appropriate meaning to the user. The wrong type of chart will be misleading and may lead to dysfunctional decision-making."</data>
      <data key="d2">c29f0f482a2be0aca99305e718e34f55</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">118</data>
      <data key="d6">bbf148ae4d48422f8fdef754cfa2b9e4</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INFORMATION SYSTEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"An information system is an integrated set of components that collect, store, process and communicate information."</data>
      <data key="d2">c29f0f482a2be0aca99305e718e34f55</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">119</data>
      <data key="d6">de61b2670999433f807a6a1dc2b81e43</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONTROL PROCEDURES FOR DATA SECURITY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Control procedures to ensure the security of confidential data typically include physical and logical access controls, passwords, encryption, systems logs and audit trails."</data>
      <data key="d2">c29f0f482a2be0aca99305e718e34f55</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">120</data>
      <data key="d6">3e95dacfe57b4d57b5da4310ef2e157f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SOURCES OF INFORMATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sources of information are: Internal (e.g. transaction processing systems); and External, which may be primary (e.g. market research) or secondary (e.g. government statistics)."</data>
      <data key="d2">c29f0f482a2be0aca99305e718e34f55</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">121</data>
      <data key="d6">1f1545308e9347af91fd03b94aadc21f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;HISTOGRAM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A histogram is a type of bar chart that represents the frequency distribution of a set of continuous or discrete data."</data>
      <data key="d2">c29f0f482a2be0aca99305e718e34f55</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">122</data>
      <data key="d6">6ea81acaf232485e94fff638e03336e1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;AREA CHARTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Area charts are used to represent cumulative totals over time using numbers or percentages."</data>
      <data key="d2">c29f0f482a2be0aca99305e718e34f55</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">123</data>
      <data key="d6">d136b08d586d488f9e4188b524c85a29</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BUBBLE CHARTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Bubble charts are used to display three dimensions of data. Each point is represented by a bubble, with the position on the x and y axes representing two dimensions and the size of the bubble representing the third dimension."</data>
      <data key="d2">c29f0f482a2be0aca99305e718e34f55</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">124</data>
      <data key="d6">cccfa151fedc4b218a8d96adc7dceabe</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;HEAT MAPS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Heat maps use color to represent data values in a matrix. They are useful for showing the magnitude of data and patterns."</data>
      <data key="d2">c29f0f482a2be0aca99305e718e34f55</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">125</data>
      <data key="d6">ce54725672a74ebcabe6127577dacb2b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TREE MAPS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Tree maps display hierarchical data using nested rectangles. The size and color of the rectangles can represent different dimensions of the data."</data>
      <data key="d2">c29f0f482a2be0aca99305e718e34f55</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">126</data>
      <data key="d6">ea2b28ca1a974ffab4517811dc1d1e5c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RADAR CHARTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Radar charts are used to display multivariate data in the form of a two-dimensional chart of three or more quantitative variables represented on axes starting from the same point."</data>
      <data key="d2">c29f0f482a2be0aca99305e718e34f55</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">127</data>
      <data key="d6">aff21f1da1654e7babdcf3fb0e4a75fc</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GANTT CHARTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Gantt charts are used for project management. They show the start and finish dates of the various elements of a project."</data>
      <data key="d2">c29f0f482a2be0aca99305e718e34f55</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">128</data>
      <data key="d6">dc2cc9016e3f49dbac7232f05cce794d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;WATERFALL CHARTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Waterfall charts are used to show the cumulative effect of sequentially introduced positive or negative values."</data>
      <data key="d2">c29f0f482a2be0aca99305e718e34f55</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">129</data>
      <data key="d6">6ea0cef05f694dcea455478f40674e45</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FUNNEL CHARTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Funnel charts are used to represent stages in a process. They show the flow of data through each stage, with the width of each section representing the quantity."</data>
      <data key="d2">c29f0f482a2be0aca99305e718e34f55</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">130</data>
      <data key="d6">7ab5d53a872f4dfc98f3d386879f3c75</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ABSORPTION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Absorption is the process of allocating total overheads in each production department into the production units using methods such as direct labour hour rate, direct material cost rate, direct labour cost rate, prime cost percentage rate, machine hour rate, or unit of output rate."</data>
      <data key="d2">3bf18aba62dd4251358d43c53af411ae</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">131</data>
      <data key="d6">af1d0fec22114a3398b8016f5225f9ed</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OVERHEAD ABSORPTION QUIZ&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Overhead Absorption Quiz involves calculating the overhead absorption rate using different bases such as direct labour hours, direct materials cost, direct labour cost, prime cost, machine hours, and units of output. It also includes calculating the full absorption cost of a product."</data>
      <data key="d2">3bf18aba62dd4251358d43c53af411ae</data>
      <data key="d3">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">132</data>
      <data key="d6">b07a7f088364459098cd8511ff27a4c8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING (ABC)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">Activity-Based Costing (ABC) is a costing methodology that assigns costs to activities based on their use of resources, applicable in both service and manufacturing industries. This approach provides more accurate cost information by linking costs to specific activities and focusing on the activities that incur costs. ABC involves tracing resource consumption and costing final outputs by identifying cost drivers, which are used to attach activity costs to outputs. Overhead and indirect costs are assigned to related products and services through this method, ensuring a detailed and precise allocation of costs.</data>
      <data key="d2">03721d9b5064cc002df514cca9896c3b,3bf18aba62dd4251358d43c53af411ae,77faaf4508d4f0bb2edf2e8e59bafd89,836c03bc0c3a85400d4d39d4278e3a51,9cb3ca1f088473aac339bd044b8a7507,a9d0dc5f61fc7776a3e266a03f359f3f,b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa,c36ec781da5d279df58a22b1fd268ee9</data>
      <data key="d3">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">24</data>
      <data key="d5">133</data>
      <data key="d6">8870cf2b5df64d2cab5820f67e29b9f1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TRADITIONAL ABSORPTION COSTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">Traditional absorption costing is a method where overhead costs are allocated to products based on a single cost driver, such as labor hours or machine hours. This method typically uses direct labor hours or machine hours to apportion all overhead costs between products. For instance, in the case of the Deluxe model, the overhead cost would be only 20% more than that of a Basic model. However, this method may not accurately reflect the true product overhead costs, especially in modern factories with significant overhead costs.</data>
      <data key="d2">3bf18aba62dd4251358d43c53af411ae,7ec0c404cb341da6ab1e2341852f4c97,9eecb64d9d19d6470562caacce0026a3,f69a532ce3d34860e2e8d9e4cad4663f</data>
      <data key="d3">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">7</data>
      <data key="d5">134</data>
      <data key="d6">cd130938a2844050be991af70baf5ee0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COST DRIVER&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A cost driver is a factor that can cause a change in the cost of an activity. In ABC, cost drivers are used to apportion overhead costs to products based on the use of activities by each product."</data>
      <data key="d2">3bf18aba62dd4251358d43c53af411ae</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">135</data>
      <data key="d6">43544b99c3b04b059546198a0ae6366d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DIRECT LABOUR HOURS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"BASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Direct labour hours" are determined through time and motion studies to establish the most efficient production method and standard hours for job completion. Additionally, direct labour hours serve as a basis used in both re-apportionment and absorption to allocate costs based on the number of hours worked by direct labour.</data>
      <data key="d2">3bf18aba62dd4251358d43c53af411ae,dcfa6ded93f92d536f228009c8441446</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">136</data>
      <data key="d6">a671bf7fea2f4514b6e96ba99127fafd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MACHINE HOURS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"BASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Machine hours" refer to the total number of hours that machines are operated during the production process. They are used as a basis for both re-apportionment and absorption to allocate costs based on the number of hours machines are in operation. In traditional absorption costing, machine hours are often employed as the single cost driver to allocate fixed production overheads. Additionally, machine hours can act as a limiting factor in production, as seen in the context of month 1.</data>
      <data key="d2">002794ec024434f7ac2bd26217b3897d,3bf18aba62dd4251358d43c53af411ae,508d94702ceaf4b2c327ad21bf49dba3,5a645510a423feead88fce4460595798,e63689f85598b937bf7c871cd9494956,f69a532ce3d34860e2e8d9e4cad4663f</data>
      <data key="d7">1</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">137</data>
      <data key="d6">525f41ea20274a05af4e52b625b473f3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PARTS MOVEMENTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"BASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Parts movements is a basis used in re-apportionment to allocate costs based on the number of parts moved or handled."</data>
      <data key="d2">3bf18aba62dd4251358d43c53af411ae</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">138</data>
      <data key="d6">071a416efbec4f0886c19ac68f6d43cb</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VARIABLE OVERHEADS UTILIZED&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"BASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Variable overheads utilized is a basis used in re-apportionment to allocate costs based on the variable overheads consumed."</data>
      <data key="d2">3bf18aba62dd4251358d43c53af411ae</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">139</data>
      <data key="d6">6d8473ef3b1042bf87178a611e3dbcc6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DIRECT MATERIAL COST RATE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"BASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Direct material cost rate is a basis used in absorption to allocate costs based on the cost of direct materials used."</data>
      <data key="d2">3bf18aba62dd4251358d43c53af411ae</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">140</data>
      <data key="d6">30c9641543c24773938bd8ec57ea98ab</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DIRECT LABOUR COST RATE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"BASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Direct labour cost rate is a basis used in absorption to allocate costs based on the cost of direct labour."</data>
      <data key="d2">3bf18aba62dd4251358d43c53af411ae</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">141</data>
      <data key="d6">18b839da898e4026b81727d759d95c6a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRIME COST PERCENTAGE RATE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"BASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Prime cost percentage rate is a basis used in absorption to allocate costs based on a percentage of the prime cost."</data>
      <data key="d2">3bf18aba62dd4251358d43c53af411ae</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">142</data>
      <data key="d6">eeef6ae5c464400c8755900b4f1ac37a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;UNIT OF OUTPUT RATE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"BASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Unit of output rate is a basis used in absorption to allocate costs based on the number of units produced."</data>
      <data key="d2">3bf18aba62dd4251358d43c53af411ae</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">143</data>
      <data key="d6">422433aa45804c7ebb973b2fafce5da6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ACTIVITY COST POOL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"An activity cost pool is a grouping of all costs associated with a particular activity in the production process. Examples include cost pools for production scheduling, machining, dispatching, and inspections."</data>
      <data key="d2">508d94702ceaf4b2c327ad21bf49dba3,e63689f85598b937bf7c871cd9494956</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">1</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">144</data>
      <data key="d6">86505bca739d4bccaaa1a8e0f3baffdc</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OVERHEAD COST PER UNIT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Overhead cost per unit" is calculated by dividing the total overhead cost for manufacturing each product by the number of units produced. For example, the overhead cost per unit for Product Z is determined by dividing the total overhead cost for Product Z by the number of Zs produced. Additionally, this concept can be applied in a quiz format that involves calculating the overhead cost per unit of a product using Activity-Based Costing (ABC) based on given budgeted overheads and cost drivers.</data>
      <data key="d2">508d94702ceaf4b2c327ad21bf49dba3,9f953495ff86f9240435d79c4903fca7,e63689f85598b937bf7c871cd9494956</data>
      <data key="d3">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d7">1</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">145</data>
      <data key="d6">1af9faf341e14a5bbf4ddc9080e8dc0b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STEPS TO FIND TOTAL PRODUCT COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Steps to find total product costs involve identifying major activities, creating cost centers, determining cost drivers, calculating absorption rates, calculating total overhead costs, and calculating overhead cost per unit."</data>
      <data key="d2">508d94702ceaf4b2c327ad21bf49dba3,e63689f85598b937bf7c871cd9494956</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d7">1</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">146</data>
      <data key="d6">353d91abc68648639d65a549e59b5cf3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF ACTIVITY-BASED COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This example illustrates how a company assembles two product models, Basic and Deluxe, and calculates the overhead costs using activity-based costing. It includes steps for identifying cost drivers, calculating cost per unit of cost drivers, and determining total overhead costs for each product."</data>
      <data key="d2">508d94702ceaf4b2c327ad21bf49dba3,e63689f85598b937bf7c871cd9494956</data>
      <data key="d3">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d7">1</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">147</data>
      <data key="d6">7ce637e4f35b42e3a9f8272cab69cd22</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COST DRIVERS&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1">Cost drivers are factors that cause the cost of an activity to increase or decrease. Examples of cost drivers include machine setup costs, machine running costs, procurement costs, and delivery costs.</data>
      <data key="d2">508d94702ceaf4b2c327ad21bf49dba3,b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa,bc96081078db9cb11a132fcb669135c0,e63689f85598b937bf7c871cd9494956</data>
      <data key="d7">1</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">9</data>
      <data key="d5">148</data>
      <data key="d6">4d999d7744b04a998475f8f8531589f0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TOTAL OVERHEAD COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Total overhead cost is the sum of all indirect costs associated with the production of goods. This includes costs such as utilities, rent, and administrative expenses."</data>
      <data key="d2">508d94702ceaf4b2c327ad21bf49dba3,e63689f85598b937bf7c871cd9494956</data>
      <data key="d7">1</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">149</data>
      <data key="d6">9a6f414210e14841a5b0e661aedc898d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ABSORPTION RATE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Absorption rate is calculated by dividing the total overhead cost by the total number of units of the cost driver. For example, Absorption rate = Total overhead cost / Total number of machine hours."</data>
      <data key="d2">508d94702ceaf4b2c327ad21bf49dba3,e63689f85598b937bf7c871cd9494956</data>
      <data key="d7">1</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">150</data>
      <data key="d6">db541b7260974db8bac94e953009f60e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INDIRECT COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Indirect costs" are expenses that are not directly tied to a specific product or activity and cannot be directly traced to a specific cost object. Examples of indirect costs include utilities, rent, and administrative salaries. These costs are often allocated to different departments or products.</data>
      <data key="d2">00157cf30936c417d0c54f1dfce77654,002794ec024434f7ac2bd26217b3897d,01294aa83ab1143451866d43087f9eba,01d1ff33e985b6f8cd09ff45ebfedc0e,026b22934152d61a6b625fae071b3bcd,0279d26139c7d66d51896f7ebfe162ee,02defdad562458f44c0d0fa31dc9693d,03721d9b5064cc002df514cca9896c3b,039a2a6ce8c94f49aa8954c72332cea2,05e25a78a53e695fd01856df3a302292,0622f4f26dbe7479c871198b2e72b940,078e47b3223db97709a37da2a01302c5,08f6c24c7f87b7ffc3b8a5dfc505c552,0a1392ec8d4dc63bfee377dc6d552da3,0af2d78ba77677f806a697c0deb0ced3,0cafbc1007afddae5f416e6fb910386a,0d6ca97290394110da0bcfffa12dac11,0dbbae65ee89b4c5d53a1b0a83d84535,0e0632925a4598cac64c13be234f1755,0f59fe901f330c6a95c810cdae18b305,10a6cfb7beb226418463ca4749be7451,1198b5b37a51d0315db68af2bdb139bd,11b64c42e42e94e3f0881a9cd9457d74,122be7bb4778bacae6dba8d18b50c025,12bf561fb0f443af5c38c4055dae476d,14d295eb69556ed8203b13909d341a07,158846b2d51075f1de4279110c7a2ae1,16965b8a36bbe6bac45c7b81a6b17c48,181a68483be6482e8b136a2d540875a9,185572ab91ea67a36a262b55dffde450,1872b59f14e8fe91c616b29960e49fb9,19092af48cfe51bac1503c304f3ca707,1aa84a5288fe62c1d778b9f9013d51c3,1c07f0d21b37bda63c238ee6e4ed571b,1d33c979d505d0dcd027d816d2ab2695,1dbcdd2207ed07f8e45dc35658ecbd2a,1e37a7be9b892b604c2e7b6cf6a2c49f,1f06696499d837582d3dac671cb07649,2154b2cf6113011b3816974155d6ed8d,2207ef547588f07b856f3a5c961e39a0,22f7850b6ee24babd9cf367c0fc478a4,2343dedcae64d2e174ab981dfc3b23a0,2381a9a278f9cf058d7c71932fad4841,238ba7ae5def49a914d13c1bcf1e1332,24cd8c3feefdefe57b7e7da7db59d031,258563e1a008a7977296119e059fdf11,27370737012393c709c89a56df8ea2d4,27fde199847b14399dfca384e07a77a4,2922f29fc45ffc98655fc81f9a40fa79,299f4bc827fb4c62a74f3271557514e9,2a57a845054dd3fd23f0910ad239a201,2ad6c0ee81f4b0da1c6b2f2821dff6b6,2b35add90aa38f95a0510f9302a559f9,2df3be986166cb71a016998a16e5349a,2ec07a1112223c3286057400e3b2eca9,2f4d122e57ceca3100dab3886c99ca27,2fd1d6134ec72f26d7a900391b7261fd,303f0ef8328d2aefc4bfae1067a85f72,30748d6dcf5a2da70804db75296cee3c,312c3cf9edbc058c6e810c1e9c9cd81a