    <node id="&quot;BATCH SET-UPS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Batch set-ups refer to the preparation activities required to start a new production batch. This can include cleaning equipment, changing tools, and setting up machines."</data>
      <data key="d2">508d94702ceaf4b2c327ad21bf49dba3,e63689f85598b937bf7c871cd9494956</data>
      <data key="d7">1</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">155</data>
      <data key="d6">7282c73622b8408e97289d959faff483</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DISPATCH ORDERS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Dispatch orders are instructions to send goods to a specific destination. They are often used in logistics and supply chain management."</data>
      <data key="d2">508d94702ceaf4b2c327ad21bf49dba3,e63689f85598b937bf7c871cd9494956</data>
      <data key="d7">1</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">156</data>
      <data key="d6">3deb220d31f74103aa44870a36a63220</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INSPECTIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Inspections involve examining products or processes to ensure they meet specified standards and requirements."</data>
      <data key="d2">508d94702ceaf4b2c327ad21bf49dba3,e63689f85598b937bf7c871cd9494956</data>
      <data key="d7">1</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">157</data>
      <data key="d6">af7a1584dd15492cb9a4940e285f57fc</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ABC APPROACH&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Activity-Based Costing (ABC) approach allocates overhead costs based on multiple cost drivers, reflecting the actual effort and cost incurred in producing small batches. This approach results in a higher cost per unit for products like the Deluxe model, which should have a higher selling price to justify the higher costs incurred."</data>
      <data key="d2">f69a532ce3d34860e2e8d9e4cad4663f</data>
      <data key="d3">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">158</data>
      <data key="d6">6e8d9029ce4e4ea182367173ab2c7bbf</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING V ABSORPTION COSTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz compares the total cost for each product using traditional absorption costing and the ABC system. It involves calculating the cost per unit for products A and B under both costing methods and identifying the main reasons for the differences."</data>
      <data key="d2">f69a532ce3d34860e2e8d9e4cad4663f</data>
      <data key="d3">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d7">9</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">159</data>
      <data key="d6">cbf232211e7d4eb6abdbe182f71c2cf0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TOTAL COST FOR EACH PRODUCT USING TRADITIONAL ABSORPTION COSTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Total cost for each product using traditional absorption costing is calculated by adding direct material cost, direct labor cost, and fixed overhead cost based on machine hours. For example, for Product A, the total cost is $82, and for Product B, it is $116."</data>
      <data key="d2">f69a532ce3d34860e2e8d9e4cad4663f</data>
      <data key="d3">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d7">9</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">160</data>
      <data key="d6">bb0cff774a4440b289cc6f3b929fe13c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TOTAL COST FOR EACH PRODUCT USING ABC SYSTEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Total cost for each product using the ABC system is calculated by adding direct material cost, direct labor cost, and overhead costs traced to products based on multiple cost drivers. For example, for Product A, the total cost is $103.67, and for Product B, it is $112.75."</data>
      <data key="d2">f69a532ce3d34860e2e8d9e4cad4663f</data>
      <data key="d3">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d7">9</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">161</data>
      <data key="d6">ce55841ebfdd47008bab8c258f10372e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COMPARISON OF COSTS UNDER ABC AND ABSORPTION COSTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The comparison of costs under ABC and absorption costing shows significant differences in the cost per unit for products. For Product A, the cost increases by 26% under ABC, while for Product B, the cost decreases by 3%. The main reason for the difference is the allocation of set-up costs, which are more accurately reflected in the ABC system."</data>
      <data key="d2">f69a532ce3d34860e2e8d9e4cad4663f</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d7">9</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">162</data>
      <data key="d6">6090e736374d45fd84f0e4610a314f8f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OVERHEAD COST PER UNIT OF PRODUCT&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">f69a532ce3d34860e2e8d9e4cad4663f</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">163</data>
      <data key="d6">0e8d921ccd8d4a8594b65b7fd19f7120</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DIRECT MATERIAL COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"COST COMPONENTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Direct material cost refers to the cost of raw materials that are directly used in the production of a product. This cost is a part of the total cost calculation in both traditional absorption costing and the ABC system."</data>
      <data key="d2">f69a532ce3d34860e2e8d9e4cad4663f</data>
      <data key="d7">9</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">164</data>
      <data key="d6">59c726a8792d443e84ab052cb7942b4a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DIRECT LABOR COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"COST COMPONENTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Direct labor cost refers to the wages and salaries of employees who are directly involved in the production of a product. This cost is included in the total cost calculation in both traditional absorption costing and the ABC system."</data>
      <data key="d2">f69a532ce3d34860e2e8d9e4cad4663f</data>
      <data key="d7">9</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">165</data>
      <data key="d6">4f2c665decf242b0bfcaf7350b0e02ed</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FIXED OVERHEAD COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"COST COMPONENTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Fixed overhead cost" refers to the indirect costs that do not vary with the level of production. These costs include rent, utilities, salaries of administrative staff, and insurance. In traditional absorption costing, fixed overhead costs are allocated based on a single cost driver, such as machine hours.</data>
      <data key="d2">cdba52ee4f0e2669ccb29b10b23e609a,f69a532ce3d34860e2e8d9e4cad4663f</data>
      <data key="d7">9</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">166</data>
      <data key="d6">66cdf168f36d4a57a505028c97dc06e0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MULTIPLE COST DRIVERS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"COST COMPONENTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Multiple cost drivers refer to the various factors that cause overhead costs to be incurred, such as machine setups, production runs, and quality inspections. In the ABC approach, overhead costs are allocated based on these multiple cost drivers."</data>
      <data key="d2">f69a532ce3d34860e2e8d9e4cad4663f</data>
      <data key="d7">9</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">167</data>
      <data key="d6">38f51478f41f48db9bee570859b6f43e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LABOR HOURS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"COST DRIVERS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Labor hours refer to the total hours worked by employees directly involved in the production process. In traditional absorption costing, labor hours can be used as the single cost driver to allocate overhead costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">f69a532ce3d34860e2e8d9e4cad4663f</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">168</data>
      <data key="d6">896d2a51e8de47de85ba8ced108c3d53</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PREPARING THE OPERATING THEATRE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Preparing the operating theatre is an activity in ABC where the cost is driven by the number of operations. The cost does not vary significantly between different types of operations."</data>
      <data key="d2">b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">169</data>
      <data key="d6">14555b518e954637b83aa762dc03164e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ACTIVITY OF ANAESTHETIST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Activity of anaesthetist is an activity in ABC where the cost is driven by the number of operations, calculated separately for those requiring a general anaesthetic and those requiring only local anaesthetics."</data>
      <data key="d2">b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">170</data>
      <data key="d6">b1f6164116d44fe8b8f135d7f65b9e58</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ANAESTHETIC DRUGS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Anaesthetic drugs is an activity in ABC where the cost is driven by the time taken from entering the anaesthetic room until entering the recovery room."</data>
      <data key="d2">b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">171</data>
      <data key="d6">c8b2408617804483b620e1a6691ac90d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ACTIVITY OF THE PHYSICIAN&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Activity of the physician is an activity in ABC where the cost is driven by the time taken from initial incision to closure of incision on completion of surgery."</data>
      <data key="d2">b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">172</data>
      <data key="d6">a5e0d1644eb547ba9a5c3211aac4631a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONSUMABLE ITEMS DURING SURGERY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Consumable items during surgery is an activity in ABC where the cost is driven by an itemised list of consumables used during surgery, captured by a bar-coding device."</data>
      <data key="d2">b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">173</data>
      <data key="d6">5a28b94bc63b44edb30c54748fd14f15</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OVERHEAD ACTIVITY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Overhead activity is an activity in ABC where the cost is driven by a charge for management administration and staff training."</data>
      <data key="d2">b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">174</data>
      <data key="d6">f97011b2a99d44648e18d517e1eae15c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MANAGEMENT ACCOUNTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Management accounting is concerned with preparing and presenting accounting information to assist management in planning, controlling, and making decisions."</data>
      <data key="d2">b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">175</data>
      <data key="d6">35489ca6a63b47d6a8913cf333818bc1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ABSORPTION COSTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">Absorption costing is a traditional costing method that involves calculating the unit cost of a product or service by including all manufacturing costs. This includes direct materials, direct labor, and both variable and fixed manufacturing overheads. The process involves several steps: allocation and apportionment of costs to cost centers, re-apportionment of service center costs to production cost centers, and absorption of the total cost into the unit cost using an appropriate basis. Typically, a single overhead rate is used to allocate costs based on a common measure such as direct labor hours or machine hours.</data>
      <data key="d2">002794ec024434f7ac2bd26217b3897d,03721d9b5064cc002df514cca9896c3b,b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa,c1374ecc954703b220564a8e84b396b1</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">10</data>
      <data key="d5">176</data>
      <data key="d6">5d3344f45e654d2c808481672f2f08dd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARGINAL COSTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Marginal costing involves calculating the unit cost of a product or service by considering only variable costs. Fixed costs are treated as period costs and are not included in the unit cost."</data>
      <data key="d2">b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">177</data>
      <data key="d6">6fb57f83baec45c9b30490ee991f433f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TARGET COSTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Target costing" is a pricing strategy used in both manufacturing and service industries. It involves determining the desired profit margin and then working backward to establish the maximum allowable cost to achieve that margin. This strategy ensures that the product can be produced profitably at a competitive market price. The process includes deriving a target cost, which is influenced by external market prices, and designing out costs during the product design phase to meet the acceptable profit margin. While target costing is commonly applied in manufacturing, it presents challenges in service industries. To address these challenges, strategies are suggested to close any target cost gaps that may arise.</data>
      <data key="d2">14d295eb69556ed8203b13909d341a07,40bae0e7483c94ad06bd066f12884d9c,71a15e253f55633783cde51ebbef843e,9d54588af94d453794e574c052472b3e,a9d0dc5f61fc7776a3e266a03f359f3f,b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa,bf895221917dacb42684c64f347d269d,c072010f60f9a31fe566e35a7ad7d3cc,cdba52ee4f0e2669ccb29b10b23e609a,e38eef21c8adf52125bdece53d9dd6f3</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">22</data>
      <data key="d5">178</data>
      <data key="d6">68762e6f0d1c41cd857c6b964a8e76c3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LIFE-CYCLE COSTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"LIFE-CYCLE COSTING" is a comprehensive system that tracks and accumulates the actual costs and revenues attributable to each product from its development through to its abandonment. This approach involves identifying the costs incurred at different stages of the product's life cycle, deriving a life-cycle cost or profit in both manufacturing and service industries, and recognizing the benefits of life-cycle costing. By tracking cumulative costs and revenues throughout the product's stages, life-cycle costing encourages management to plan the pricing strategy for a product over its entire life cycle. Additionally, it is an Environmental Management Accounting (EMA) technique that considers the total cost of ownership, including acquisition, operation, and disposal costs.</data>
      <data key="d2">40bae0e7483c94ad06bd066f12884d9c,7b3dd175d38a9f290c9e33467fc9f8a0,836c03bc0c3a85400d4d39d4278e3a51,a9d0dc5f61fc7776a3e266a03f359f3f,ae4f9eb0f940c70c89837f1343567883,b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa,c072010f60f9a31fe566e35a7ad7d3cc,e38eef21c8adf52125bdece53d9dd6f3</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">11</data>
      <data key="d5">179</data>
      <data key="d6">70634e10a5e845aa8c6a32fe7e8eb2b2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;THROUGHPUT ACCOUNTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">Throughput Accounting is a management accounting approach that focuses on maximizing the throughput, which is the rate at which the system generates money through sales, while minimizing inventory and operating expenses. This methodology prioritizes products based on their return per hour of bottleneck resource, calculated as throughput per unit divided by the bottleneck hour required to produce one unit. By drawing management&#8217;s attention to bottleneck processes, Throughput Accounting aims to maximize the throughput generated per hour by eliminating these bottlenecks and focuses on throughput contribution, which is sales revenue less material cost.

Throughput Accounting involves discussing and applying the theory of constraints, calculating and interpreting a throughput accounting ratio (TPAR), and suggesting ways to improve this ratio. It is also applied to multi-product decision-making problems to enhance overall system efficiency. The technique emphasizes the importance of managing bottlenecks to maximize the throughput return per production hour, calculated as the selling price minus material cost divided by bottleneck hours per unit.</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37,238ba7ae5def49a914d13c1bcf1e1332,727bae9b2b77a13f165dd415aa129b20,a9d0dc5f61fc7776a3e266a03f359f3f,ac68069ef08bb5822225377a605ac206,b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa,bf895221917dacb42684c64f347d269d,c36ec781da5d279df58a22b1fd268ee9,cdba52ee4f0e2669ccb29b10b23e609a</data>
      <data key="d7">26</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">12</data>
      <data key="d5">180</data>
      <data key="d6">04085f7cf46544b79597fc49286ff84d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ACCOUNTING FOR ENVIRONMENTAL AND SUSTAINABILITY FACTORS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Accounting for environmental and sustainability factors involves discussing the issues organisations face in the management of environmental costs, describing different methods an organisation may use to account for its environmental costs, and discussing the role of the management accountant in supporting the business to develop sustainable practices."</data>
      <data key="d2">b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">181</data>
      <data key="d6">d203efdbfb2f4b2a899abfb31cf72e82</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TRADITIONAL MANAGEMENT ACCOUNTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Traditional management accounting is inward-looking, focusing on controlling costs. The most important techniques include costing systems (marginal and absorption costing), budgeting systems, standard costing and variance analysis, and working capital management."</data>
      <data key="d2">b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">182</data>
      <data key="d6">6731a665561840c2898ce8c9788e4c88</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BUSINESS ENVIRONMENT CHANGES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Business environment changes during the 1950s and 1960s included less protection in home markets, increased globalisation, the introduction of computerised manufacturing systems, shorter product lifecycles, the growth of service industries, larger multinational organisations, and more decentralised decision-making."</data>
      <data key="d2">b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">183</data>
      <data key="d6">4026806fa92f4e849a59a7f5c9a45c79</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GROWTH OF SERVICE INDUSTRIES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Growth of service industries is characterised by simultaneity, heterogeneity, and intangibility. These characteristics distinguish service industries from manufacturing and pose unique challenges for management accounting."</data>
      <data key="d2">b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">184</data>
      <data key="d6">68e0c60d2e8845d89d9d0ad397833648</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ACTIVITY COST POOLS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Activity cost pools are groups of individual costs that are associated with a specific activity in ABC."</data>
      <data key="d2">b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">185</data>
      <data key="d6">101572f552b54e529fe7765c05168981</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ABSORPTION RATES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Absorption rates are calculated in ABC to determine the overhead costs per unit of activity."</data>
      <data key="d2">b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">186</data>
      <data key="d6">60c58026b2764b40adffca6eaa31d6d9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OVERHEAD COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Overhead costs" are indirect expenses that are not directly traceable to a specific product or service but are allocated to them using costing methodologies such as Activity-Based Costing (ABC) and absorption costing. These ongoing expenses are essential for the operation of a business and include items such as rent, utilities, and administrative expenses.</data>
      <data key="d2">b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa,df5e50672b5795ed072403e633c26e7f</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">187</data>
      <data key="d6">ad1595a78935472999444c9330e7730e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FIXED PRODUCTION OVERHEADS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Fixed production overheads are costs that do not vary with the level of production and are included in the unit cost in absorption costing. These overheads encompass indirect costs of production, such as rent, salaries, depreciation, and utilities. They are typically associated with expenses that remain constant regardless of the output level, including the salaries of permanent staff.</data>
      <data key="d2">002794ec024434f7ac2bd26217b3897d,2df3be986166cb71a016998a16e5349a,b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">188</data>
      <data key="d6">735d19aea0744b2295556841c5c4c3fd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VARIABLE COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Variable Costs are expenses that vary directly with the level of production or sales. These costs include direct materials, direct labor, and other expenses such as machine set-up costs. They are relevant in decision-making as they will change with the decision to increase or decrease production. For example, in the production of keypads and display screens, variable costs encompass raw materials and direct labor. In Division B, variable costs include $13 for adaptors, $45 for other materials, and $35 for labor per battery, while in Division A, they include $3 for materials and $4 for labor per adaptor. Variable costs increase as production increases and decrease as production decreases, making them a crucial consideration in marginal costing and overall financial planning.</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37,23de7e5f5aa4638cfdebaec8afd6c5de,2b7c12bc08e4dff98f807210499e82ee,34f2c5c9d893c1b631ed1646193eebf4,35c28eb2f5a6b9394801984195b014d9,5c4312b5c5c803bc38cc120660340db3,98d761e221e6915f156753807cb8fbe1,b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa,e77413580f69933c7e20f96d9b9b60cf</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">9</data>
      <data key="d5">189</data>
      <data key="d6">c725babdb14a485582f8fbdf95429030</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PERIOD COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Period costs are fixed costs that are treated as expenses in the period in which they are incurred, rather than being included in the unit cost, as in marginal costing."</data>
      <data key="d2">b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">190</data>
      <data key="d6">a0047221896d418d849847d422fa4bb8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TARGET COST GAP&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Target cost gap is the difference between the current cost and the target cost, which needs to be closed to achieve cost objectives in target costing."</data>
      <data key="d2">b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">191</data>
      <data key="d6">98fc2ee593184c5a839454db4eec7013</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LIFE-CYCLE STAGES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Life-cycle stages are different phases in the life of a product or service, from development to decline, considered in life-cycle costing."</data>
      <data key="d2">b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">192</data>
      <data key="d6">80020a1da63042459e00266b2a605452</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LIFE-CYCLE COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Life-cycle cost is the total cost of a product or service over its entire life-cycle, calculated in life-cycle costing."</data>
      <data key="d2">b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">193</data>
      <data key="d6">31a7e680c4d54101afe4c8d52d246913</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LIFE-CYCLE PROFIT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Life-cycle profit is the total profit of a product or service over its entire life-cycle, calculated in life-cycle costing."</data>
      <data key="d2">b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">194</data>
      <data key="d6">351abba16e5c448994c6daf48121b14d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;THEORY OF CONSTRAINTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The Theory of Constraints is a management philosophy and methodology that focuses on identifying the most important limiting factor, or constraint, that stands in the way of achieving a goal. It posits that there is always at least one constraint, often referred to as a bottleneck, that limits the achievement of a goal. The approach involves systematically improving this constraint until it is no longer the limiting factor. This methodology is used in throughput accounting to enhance performance by managing these bottlenecks effectively. Additionally, there are quizzes available that test knowledge about which statements are consistent with the Theory of Constraints.</data>
      <data key="d2">8c5f3adb7ce0099b89e3e7e2687c2a68,a9d0dc5f61fc7776a3e266a03f359f3f,b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa,bf895221917dacb42684c64f347d269d,c072010f60f9a31fe566e35a7ad7d3cc,e38eef21c8adf52125bdece53d9dd6f3</data>
      <data key="d7">12</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">7</data>
      <data key="d5">195</data>
      <data key="d6">50ea7d3b69614bcdbfbff7ddbfbf3d34</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;THROUGHPUT ACCOUNTING RATIO (TPAR)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The Throughput Accounting Ratio (TPAR) is a metric used in throughput accounting to measure the efficiency of a production process. It is calculated as the Return per factory hour divided by the Cost per factory hour. The Return per factory hour is determined by dividing the Throughput per unit by the Hours of bottleneck resource used per unit. The Cost per factory hour is calculated by dividing the Other factory costs by the Bottleneck resource hours available.</data>
      <data key="d2">ad658b0aa1714f3d42793f96dd88140e,b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa</data>
      <data key="d7">26</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">196</data>
      <data key="d6">004f40a5aeca48a1879db728eb12bcba</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ENVIRONMENTAL COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Environmental costs" are expenses associated with the environmental impact of an organization's activities, considered in accounting for environmental and sustainability factors. These costs encompass conventional costs, potentially hidden costs, contingent costs, and image and relationship costs. Specifically, they include expenses related to resource consumption, pollution control, and waste management. Environmental costs can be categorized into conventional costs like resource usage, hidden costs embedded in overheads, contingent costs for future liabilities, and image costs related to environmental reputation. Additionally, these costs can be classified by their relation to quality, such as prevention, detection, internal failure, and external failure costs associated with managing environmental impacts.</data>
      <data key="d2">39e1257b70d1902a0d6b2502ce5b27b5,836c03bc0c3a85400d4d39d4278e3a51,a9d0dc5f61fc7776a3e266a03f359f3f,b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa,c072010f60f9a31fe566e35a7ad7d3cc,e38eef21c8adf52125bdece53d9dd6f3</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">8</data>
      <data key="d5">197</data>
      <data key="d6">4465efb7f6ed4dedad72a658184addd2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SUSTAINABLE PRACTICES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sustainable practices are business practices that aim to reduce environmental impact and promote sustainability, supported by management accountants in accounting for environmental and sustainability factors."</data>
      <data key="d2">b6aae482ada9c34bf0afb23a1a9ef1fa</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">198</data>
      <data key="d6">b0dd60e11dad4ff782623acf039b3948</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: TARGET COSTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves calculating the target cost of a new luxury car, the Z123 series, for Exclusive Motors. The car will have a lifecycle of 10 years, with an investment of $3 billion and a required profit of 20% per year. The marketing department expects to sell the car for $40,000 each, with 100,000 units manufactured and sold each year."</data>
      <data key="d2">9d54588af94d453794e574c052472b3e</data>
      <data key="d3">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">199</data>
      <data key="d6">db8c43fa4df947b09e5754d3b1393ead</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;APPLICATION TO SERVICE INDUSTRIES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Target costing is most appropriate in manufacturing industries where standard products are made in volume. However, it can also be applied to service industries, though there are challenges such as non-standard products, higher indirect expenses, and potential impacts on customer service or quality."</data>
      <data key="d2">9d54588af94d453794e574c052472b3e</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">200</data>
      <data key="d6">5dabc4cd05da425cb194a04482bf0c29</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF TARGET COSTING FOR SERVICES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Gates &amp; Jobs Co, a tax advisory business, decides to match a competitor's price of $100 for a basic tax return. The target cost is calculated by subtracting the required profit margin from the standard fee, resulting in a target cost of $80. The actual cost of a typical tax return is $100, creating a cost gap of $20. Methods to reduce this gap include reducing the time taken by senior advisers and partners, and reducing overheads."</data>
      <data key="d2">9d54588af94d453794e574c052472b3e</data>
      <data key="d3">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">201</data>
      <data key="d6">9d08f285a7be4c79b8f359c51d51db37</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NARROWING THE TARGET COST GAP&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Target costing relies on multi-disciplinary teams to reduce the gap between actual and target costs. Methods include reconsidering design to eliminate non-value-added elements, reducing the number of components, using less expensive materials, employing lower-grade staff, investing in new technology, outsourcing, and redesigning workflows. Techniques like tear-down analysis can assist in these methods."</data>
      <data key="d2">9d54588af94d453794e574c052472b3e</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">202</data>
      <data key="d6">adffed660d154b519c1817e514e83096</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INVESTMENT REQUIRED&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The initial amount of money needed to produce a product, which is a key component in calculating the target cost."</data>
      <data key="d2">9d54588af94d453794e574c052472b3e</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">203</data>
      <data key="d6">b7e9c9ef572c445a9574ca571e41fb96</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RETURN ON INVESTMENT (ROI)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Return on Investment (ROI) is a measure used to evaluate the efficiency and profitability of an investment or the performance of a division by comparing income with the operational assets used to generate that income. It is calculated in several ways, depending on the context:

1. ROI = (Controllable profit / Total net assets) * 100
2. ROI = Controllable profit / Capital employed * 100 for managers and ROI = Traceable profit / Capital employed * 100 for divisions
3. ROI = Operating profit / Capital employed
4. ROI = Net Profit / Net Assets
5. ROI = Net profit / Capital employed

These formulas highlight that ROI can be expressed as a percentage and is used to determine the target profit in target costing. For example, Division A has an ROI of 15.08%, and Division B has an ROI of 17.72%. This metric is crucial for assessing the efficiency of investments and comparing the performance of different investments or divisions.</data>
      <data key="d2">1d33c979d505d0dcd027d816d2ab2695,1f06696499d837582d3dac671cb07649,312c3cf9edbc058c6e810c1e9c9cd81a,35c28eb2f5a6b9394801984195b014d9,47433af962a352cae0761ce18f9b4b82,9d54588af94d453794e574c052472b3e</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">204</data>
      <data key="d6">dcb9f281cd6248c699e0ebb285a42a5e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TARGET PROFIT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Target profit" is the projected profit that a company aims to achieve, calculated as a percentage of target revenue. It represents the desired profit from the sale of a product, determined by dividing the total required profit by the number of units to be sold.</data>
      <data key="d2">9d54588af94d453794e574c052472b3e,afe505b1f94b0e6d25ef40e510dfada7</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">205</data>
      <data key="d6">072cdee531b74513984f49d99a8d64a0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TARGET PRICE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The price at which a product is expected to be sold in the market, used as a starting point in target costing to determine the target cost."</data>
      <data key="d2">9d54588af94d453794e574c052472b3e</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">206</data>
      <data key="d6">5ae335d9210a45fda3f92a9a028d6d9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TARGET COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Target cost" is the estimated total cost that a company aims to achieve to meet its target profit. It represents the maximum allowable cost to produce a product, calculated by subtracting the target profit per unit from the target price.</data>
      <data key="d2">9d54588af94d453794e574c052472b3e,afe505b1f94b0e6d25ef40e510dfada7</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">207</data>
      <data key="d6">5ac60a941a5b4934bdc43d2f87de601c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LIFECYCLE OF PRODUCT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The duration over which a product is expected to be produced and sold, which impacts the total investment and profit calculations in target costing."</data>
      <data key="d2">9d54588af94d453794e574c052472b3e</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">208</data>
      <data key="d6">d405c3154d0e48ce96fad4c28fe20590</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COST GAP&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"COST GAP" refers to the difference between the current or actual cost of producing a product and the target cost that needs to be achieved to meet the desired profitability. For example, in the case of a chair, if the target cost is $96 and the actual cost is $96.95, the cost gap would be $0.95 per chair. This gap represents the amount that needs to be reduced to achieve the target profit.</data>
      <data key="d2">30748d6dcf5a2da70804db75296cee3c,9d54588af94d453794e574c052472b3e,afe505b1f94b0e6d25ef40e510dfada7</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">209</data>
      <data key="d6">7923d8521c744bd9aab131c1aea91ffd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MULTI-DISCIPLINARY TEAMS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Teams composed of members from different functional areas, such as design, engineering, and finance, who collaborate to reduce the cost gap in target costing."</data>
      <data key="d2">9d54588af94d453794e574c052472b3e</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">210</data>
      <data key="d6">5bd156c87ec44e19ae6f8f62e6e50b9d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TEAR-DOWN ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"TECHNIQUES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A method used in target costing to analyze competitors' products by disassembling them to identify cost-saving opportunities."</data>
      <data key="d2">9d54588af94d453794e574c052472b3e</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">211</data>
      <data key="d6">c1a146d7fb16429ea6d0aa2a55ee597f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TEAR DOWN ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Tear down analysis, also known as reverse engineering, involves examining a competitor's product to identify possible improvements or cost reductions."</data>
      <data key="d2">40bae0e7483c94ad06bd066f12884d9c</data>
      <data key="d3">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">212</data>
      <data key="d6">ede9350632084da5b0b577ff799ab14b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VALUE ENGINEERING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Value engineering involves investigating the factors that affect the cost of a product or service. The aim is to improve the design of a product so the same functions can be provided for a lower cost or save cost by eliminating those the customer does not value."</data>
      <data key="d2">40bae0e7483c94ad06bd066f12884d9c</data>
      <data key="d3">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">213</data>
      <data key="d6">ed559fb4ebde45518849ec803b350fa3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FUNCTIONAL ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Functional analysis involves identifying the attributes/functions of a product that customers value. The price the customer is prepared to pay for each function is then determined. The function should be dropped if the cost of providing it exceeds the value it generates."</data>
      <data key="d2">40bae0e7483c94ad06bd066f12884d9c</data>
      <data key="d3">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">214</data>
      <data key="d6">f422035f8b78417f98e4d116971cf9f3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRODUCT LIFECYCLE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The product lifecycle consists of stages such as development, introduction, growth, maturity, and decline. It describes how demand conditions for a product, a brand, and whole markets change over time. Different pricing policies might be adopted at various stages to maximize profits and manage demand effectively.</data>
      <data key="d2">40bae0e7483c94ad06bd066f12884d9c,c1d1a5691f5cfea1fd89ecd71a3421ce</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">215</data>
      <data key="d6">c79d686eba044c5586c706cdc096817d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF LIFE-CYCLE COSTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Zany developed a new computer game during the year 20X2 for $200,000. The game will be launched in the year 20X3. Budgeted revenues and costs of the game over its lifecycle are presented, showing how life-cycle costing estimates and accumulates costs over a product's entire lifecycle."</data>
      <data key="d2">40bae0e7483c94ad06bd066f12884d9c</data>
      <data key="d3">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">216</data>
      <data key="d6">0f70db1e598d463fbbcdd1e288bd9490</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REDESIGNING WORKFLOWS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Redesigning workflows involves changing the sequence or methods of tasks to improve efficiency and reduce production costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">40bae0e7483c94ad06bd066f12884d9c</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">217</data>
      <data key="d6">b35c3d1a7daa4924b6bdb58bc69c354d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REVERSE ENGINEERING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Reverse engineering, also known as tear down analysis, involves examining a competitor's product to identify possible improvements or cost reductions."</data>
      <data key="d2">40bae0e7483c94ad06bd066f12884d9c</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">218</data>
      <data key="d6">a97e2ecd870944cfbe71c79bc0fcc752</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COST REDUCTION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Cost reduction involves strategies and methodologies aimed at lowering the costs associated with producing a product or delivering a service."</data>
      <data key="d2">40bae0e7483c94ad06bd066f12884d9c</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">219</data>
      <data key="d6">3e1b063bbfa9423d84e50311296d2f3c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRODUCT DESIGN&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Product design involves creating and developing a product's form and function, often with the goal of improving usability, aesthetics, and cost-efficiency."</data>
      <data key="d2">40bae0e7483c94ad06bd066f12884d9c</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">220</data>
      <data key="d6">9a8ce816ee954bdabd01ea2081538009</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BOTTLENECK IDENTIFICATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Identifying the system's bottlenecks involves determining which part of the production process limits the overall output. This is more complex in real-world scenarios compared to simplified examples."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">221</data>
      <data key="d6">09f18f81442d4d6d93a90f0fac683f9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXPLOITING BOTTLENECKS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Deciding how to exploit the identified bottlenecks involves determining which products to make, given the bottlenecks. This requires limiting factor analysis using the time spent on the bottleneck as the limiting factor."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">222</data>
      <data key="d6">e02be3e37ca0454883a4c1fd859c24bb</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SUBORDINATION TO BOTTLENECKS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Subordinating everything else to the decisions made about bottlenecks ensures that other resources do not produce at a higher rate than the bottleneck. This prevents work-in-progress build-up."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">223</data>
      <data key="d6">6e0c81bef5364c988b21bf9b709d9861</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ELEVATING BOTTLENECKS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Elevating the system's bottlenecks involves increasing production capacity, which can be done by buying additional machines, training operators, or reducing time spent on the bottleneck resource."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">224</data>
      <data key="d6">1dbc51475cb04dafa4a8833a8378635e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONTINUOUS IMPROVEMENT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Continuous improvement is the process of returning to bottleneck identification once a new constraint is broken, ensuring ongoing optimization of the production process."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">225</data>
      <data key="d6">c12b9ebd8b4e42b7896822a32e3fa6eb</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;THROUGHPUT CONTRIBUTION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Throughput contribution" is defined as the difference between sales revenue and direct material costs. It is used to measure performance, with all other costs considered fixed in the short run. This metric focuses on maximizing the value generated from production processes by minimizing bottlenecks and inefficiencies.</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37,a9d0dc5f61fc7776a3e266a03f359f3f</data>
      <data key="d7">3</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">226</data>
      <data key="d6">27505f6ade4b4e5f9316ffe9c34821f7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LIMITING FACTOR ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Limiting Factor Analysis (also known as Key Factor Analysis) is a method used to maximize contribution and profit by efficiently utilizing scarce resources on products that make the best use of them. This process involves identifying the limiting factor, calculating the contribution per unit of each product, and ranking the products according to the contribution per unit of the limiting factor. Additionally, Limiting Factor Analysis is employed to determine which products to produce when faced with a bottleneck, prioritizing those that generate the maximum throughput contribution per bottleneck hour."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37,e6f7ca658dc25c9178113951c7a31846</data>
      <data key="d7">3</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">227</data>
      <data key="d6">0ee7db2c6bea4630ba9f0c25e8a967ad</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONVERSION COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Conversion costs include overheads and labor, which are considered fixed elements in the throughput contribution technique."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">228</data>
      <data key="d6">5a6c1d15424149f69052cd8d91fbff75</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: LIMITING FACTOR ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">The "QUIZ: LIMITING FACTOR ANALYSIS" involves two main tasks. Firstly, it requires calculating the maximum contribution that can be achieved when Material R is restricted to 12,000 kg. This part of the quiz focuses on products H, I, and J, each of which has different contributions per unit and different amounts of Material R required per unit. Participants are required to rank these products and calculate the maximum contribution based on the given restriction.

Secondly, the quiz involves determining the optimum product mix for Beta Co, which produces three different products (E, F, and G) in the same factory. This part of the quiz takes into account a bottleneck resource with limited hours, requiring participants to calculate the best possible product mix to maximize efficiency and contribution given the constraints.

Overall, the quiz tests the ability to perform limiting factor analysis by managing restricted resources and optimizing product mixes to achieve maximum contribution.</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37,e6f7ca658dc25c9178113951c7a31846</data>
      <data key="d7">3</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">229</data>
      <data key="d6">d005bf75c31d4848ad7041f39651e59c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPTIMUM PRODUCT MIX CALCULATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The example shows the steps to calculate the optimum product mix for Beta Co, including calculating throughput per unit, return per factory hour, ranking products, and allocating the bottleneck resource."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37</data>
      <data key="d7">3</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">230</data>
      <data key="d6">9b3eef8f3a3a45e6873838db95295b8a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FIVE FOCUSING STEPS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Five Focusing Steps are a systematic approach within the Theory of Constraints to identify and manage constraints. They include: Identify, Exploit, Subordinate, Elevate, and Repeat."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">231</data>
      <data key="d6">fdc954b454744820804d7798f3e0b5de</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;IDENTIFY THE CONSTRAINT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The first step in the Five Focusing Steps, Identify the Constraint, involves determining the part of the process that limits the overall system performance."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">232</data>
      <data key="d6">49c1383836934ec495c3b35769100a73</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXPLOIT THE CONSTRAINT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The second step in the Five Focusing Steps, Exploit the Constraint, involves making the most of the constraint without major changes or investments."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">233</data>
      <data key="d6">859dedcc3736439a8a563419f16cb3d8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SUBORDINATE EVERYTHING ELSE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The third step in the Five Focusing Steps, Subordinate Everything Else, involves aligning all other processes to support the constraint."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">234</data>
      <data key="d6">6078b9980a6c4dcd9198d151b833ead7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ELEVATE THE CONSTRAINT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The fourth step in the Five Focusing Steps, Elevate the Constraint, involves making significant changes to increase the capacity of the constraint."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">235</data>
      <data key="d6">f93cd6b8213e46dda67af7e5382e1bd2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REPEAT THE PROCESS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The fifth step in the Five Focusing Steps, Repeat the Process, involves going back to the first step to identify and manage the next constraint."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">236</data>
      <data key="d6">496f17c2f74244c681db1b23c7a39c0c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DRUM-BUFFER-ROPE (DBR)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Drum-Buffer-Rope (DBR) is a scheduling process derived from the Theory of Constraints that ensures the system's throughput is maximized by protecting the constraint from disruptions."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">237</data>
      <data key="d6">da1684437ab04f23adac28ff70bd8429</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BUFFER MANAGEMENT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Buffer Management is a technique used in the Theory of Constraints to protect the system's constraint from variability and ensure a smooth flow of production."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">238</data>
      <data key="d6">4517768fc4e24bd2a790be0e08a7856e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONSTRAINT MANAGEMENT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Constraint Management is the practice of managing the bottleneck or constraint in a system to improve overall performance."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">239</data>
      <data key="d6">545edff337344e518f68d1301d745455</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BOTTLENECK RESOURCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">A Bottleneck Resource is a resource that limits the overall output of a production process due to its limited capacity. It is the part of the production process that has the least capacity and, as a result, restricts the overall output of the system.</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37,ac68069ef08bb5822225377a605ac206</data>
      <data key="d7">26</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">240</data>
      <data key="d6">9376ce8940e647a99e5e087514b88fa4</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;WORK-IN-PROGRESS (WIP)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Work-in-Progress (WIP) refers to the materials and components that are in the process of being transformed into finished products."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">241</data>
      <data key="d6">b38a636e86984600bb4b57c2e2df9747</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CAPACITY CONSTRAINT RESOURCE (CCR)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A Capacity Constraint Resource (CCR) is a resource that, while not the primary constraint, has the potential to become a bottleneck if not managed properly."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">242</data>
      <data key="d6">4bc7440b8f4b4e4cae65a5c49defa923</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;THROUGHPUT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Throughput is the rate at which a system generates money through sales, and it is a key focus in the Theory of Constraints."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">243</data>
      <data key="d6">5d1b038ce8be4533b54dd79d6496de9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPERATING EXPENSES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Operating Expenses are the costs associated with running a business, excluding the cost of direct materials."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">244</data>
      <data key="d6">ac6e5a44e0c04a4fa93589376fde4c34</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INVENTORY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Inventory refers to the raw materials, work-in-progress, and finished goods that a company holds to support production and sales."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f7a550d089ceb3dbcb11ef3bde8fa37</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">245</data>
      <data key="d6">40e4ef7dbc98473ba311bd837859a62a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRODUCT MIX&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Product Mix" refers to the variety and quantity of different products that a company produces and sells. It encompasses the total range of products that a company offers to its customers.</data>
