      <data key="d5">376</data>
      <data key="d6">8323efc8e539419e9ca3c98e758f6609</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MAKE-OR-BUY DECISIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Make-or-buy decisions involve comparing the costs and benefits of producing goods or services in-house versus outsourcing."</data>
      <data key="d2">836c03bc0c3a85400d4d39d4278e3a51</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">377</data>
      <data key="d6">a80c7c98c0b647f8b9f6f8cc09168e44</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INCREMENTAL COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Incremental costs" are the additional costs incurred if a particular decision is made. These costs arise when a company decides to increase its level of activity, such as further processing a product or continuing in-house production of components like keypads and display screens. Incremental costs include both variable and attributable fixed costs and are crucial for decision-making as they directly impact the profitability of the decision.</data>
      <data key="d2">2b7c12bc08e4dff98f807210499e82ee,5c4312b5c5c803bc38cc120660340db3,836c03bc0c3a85400d4d39d4278e3a51,853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">378</data>
      <data key="d6">2d66a15939294d21b83b3e277f0a4e46</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;AVOIDABLE COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Avoidable costs are those which would be avoided if a particular course of action were taken."</data>
      <data key="d2">836c03bc0c3a85400d4d39d4278e3a51</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">379</data>
      <data key="d6">47f6d6573cf34e1096c95e36251dd60c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONTROLLABLE COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Controllable costs are those that can be influenced by the actions of the person who controls the budget or cost center."</data>
      <data key="d2">836c03bc0c3a85400d4d39d4278e3a51</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">380</data>
      <data key="d6">2fbd74d5ccca4be99c5257b3ac95cfba</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: INCREMENTAL COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves identifying whether each cost in a wedding event scenario is incremental or not."</data>
      <data key="d2">836c03bc0c3a85400d4d39d4278e3a51</data>
      <data key="d3">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">381</data>
      <data key="d6">a2b1621a3e424ae29a6a73f00edbeca3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SUNK COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sunk costs are historical costs that have already been incurred and cannot be recovered. Examples include research and development costs already incurred and market research."</data>
      <data key="d2">27b66fcc5173aa41f6af55ff955c7910</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">382</data>
      <data key="d6">ec45e1c400654c4f875046926486ded7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COMMITTED COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Committed costs are future costs that a company has already committed to, such as contract rental and lease payments. These costs are not incremental and are irrelevant to decision-making unless the contract is cancellable."</data>
      <data key="d2">27b66fcc5173aa41f6af55ff955c7910</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">383</data>
      <data key="d6">047cd93e9d704c7d8dadb6e79f9458df</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DEPRECIATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Depreciation is a method of allocating the cost of a tangible asset over its useful life. It is not a cash flow but an accounting method for past capital expenditure."</data>
      <data key="d2">27b66fcc5173aa41f6af55ff955c7910</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">384</data>
      <data key="d6">5b71ee73a5b6484495b2a0a75219426c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;UNCONTROLLABLE COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Uncontrollable costs are costs that cannot be influenced directly by the person in charge of the budget or cost center. Examples include management charges and reallocated non-production overheads."</data>
      <data key="d2">27b66fcc5173aa41f6af55ff955c7910</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">385</data>
      <data key="d6">e1f524d4b9754ce2b64a0a4c8f73b854</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NOTIONAL COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Notional costs are hypothetical costs, such as recharges of head office costs or management charges, which do not increase as a result of the decision and are irrelevant."</data>
      <data key="d2">27b66fcc5173aa41f6af55ff955c7910</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">386</data>
      <data key="d6">ae1fe1c014c54ec4bcdf10dbdaed5068</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPPORTUNITY COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Opportunity cost" is the value of the next best alternative that is foregone when making a decision. It represents the cost of forgoing the next best option in favor of the chosen course of action. For instance, in the context of Division M, the opportunity cost is the lost contribution of $80 per unit when selling internally instead of externally. Similarly, for Push, the opportunity cost is the foregone sales proceeds of $3,000 when using a telephone system for a contract instead of selling it. Opportunity cost can also refer to the potential revenue from selling unused materials or the scrap value of materials not regularly used. It is a measure of the value of the benefit sacrificed when one course of action is chosen over another, highlighting the importance of considering the potential benefits of rejected alternatives. Lack of scarcity implies zero opportunity cost, as there would be no foregone alternatives.</data>
      <data key="d2">27b66fcc5173aa41f6af55ff955c7910,34f2c5c9d893c1b631ed1646193eebf4,77d0f2f7f5d6dc47dd22962bc1f3d777,7b2509b146e3ce8701f02f8110248a43,853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f,c0117b1a829ee89c41385c27964ebda4,e0431b989a9611549dff83d93fe89d4b</data>
      <data key="d7">18</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">8</data>
      <data key="d5">387</data>
      <data key="d6">92646910ee624bd7909fac2b5c0232e3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF OPPORTUNITY COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A company has been invited to tender for a contract to produce a component, R2D2. Production of R2D2 will require 100 hours of processing on Machine X. If Machine X is currently working at full capacity producing 50 units of Product Z an hour, each unit of Product Z makes a contribution of $2. If 100 hours of Machine X time is used to fulfill the new contract, the lost contribution of $10,000 (50 * $2 * 100) is an opportunity cost of producing R2D2 and should be taken into account when deciding how much to tender for the contract."</data>
      <data key="d2">27b66fcc5173aa41f6af55ff955c7910</data>
      <data key="d7">18</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">388</data>
      <data key="d6">05913bee89a94bca88449249e35ba74d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MINIMUM PRICE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The minimum price that makes a contract worthwhile is equal to the relevant cost. At this price, no profit or loss would be made on the contract."</data>
      <data key="d2">27b66fcc5173aa41f6af55ff955c7910</data>
      <data key="d7">18</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">389</data>
      <data key="d6">57b8930790c34dcba4a32c6be703ed78</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RELEVANT COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Relevant cost refers to the cost that will be affected by a decision. It is the cost that will change as a result of choosing one alternative over another. Relevant costs are future costs that will differ between alternatives."</data>
      <data key="d2">7b2509b146e3ce8701f02f8110248a43</data>
      <data key="d7">18</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">7</data>
      <data key="d5">390</data>
      <data key="d6">838c4498bc3c437f8d65428b580766a2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIALS FOR ONE-OFF CONTRACT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Guidance for determining the relevant cost of materials for a one-off contract includes considering whether the materials have already been acquired and whether they are used regularly in the business. If not acquired, the current market price is the relevant cost. If acquired and used regularly, the replacement cost is the relevant cost. If not used regularly, the opportunity cost, such as scrap value, is the relevant cost."</data>
      <data key="d2">7b2509b146e3ce8701f02f8110248a43</data>
      <data key="d7">18</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">391</data>
      <data key="d6">1b893f24eb98477aad6ce49c0f26737e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF RAW MATERIALS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Crocus Co is considering making a new product that requires several types of raw material. The example details the relevant costs for materials A, B, and C based on their current purchase prices, inventory levels, and alternative uses."</data>
      <data key="d2">7b2509b146e3ce8701f02f8110248a43</data>
      <data key="d7">18</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">392</data>
      <data key="d6">6573bc2af4f94596a3f4452a602d6fc4</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: RELEVANT COSTS OF MATERIALS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves determining the relevant costs for materials required by Bob, a carpenter, to make a special dining room table. The materials include oak wood, varnish, and hinges, each with different considerations for relevant cost calculation."</data>
      <data key="d2">7b2509b146e3ce8701f02f8110248a43</data>
      <data key="d7">18</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">393</data>
      <data key="d6">0dddcca0e5df4b16bc03a51a2d2d8e16</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REPLACEMENT COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Replacement cost refers to the cost to replace an asset or material at its current market price. It is often used as the relevant cost when materials are regularly used in the business and need to be replenished."</data>
      <data key="d2">7b2509b146e3ce8701f02f8110248a43</data>
      <data key="d7">18</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">394</data>
      <data key="d6">df40ad480a3c47299a6c8fad05349304</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SCRAP VALUE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Scrap value is the estimated residual value of an asset or material at the end of its useful life. It is considered as the relevant cost when materials are not used regularly and could be sold off instead of being used in a new project."</data>
      <data key="d2">7b2509b146e3ce8701f02f8110248a43</data>
      <data key="d7">18</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">395</data>
      <data key="d6">fe98fb197d294b0b837aee8d5a98dfb1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CURRENT MARKET PRICE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Current market price is the price at which an asset or material can be bought or sold in the market at the present time. It is used as the relevant cost for materials that have not yet been acquired for a one-off contract."</data>
      <data key="d2">7b2509b146e3ce8701f02f8110248a43</data>
      <data key="d7">18</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">396</data>
      <data key="d6">feb9ddd0ac2949178f26a36949aa5422</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INVENTORY LEVELS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Inventory levels refer to the quantity of materials or products that a business has on hand. When determining relevant costs, inventory levels help assess whether existing materials can be used or if new materials need to be purchased."</data>
      <data key="d2">7b2509b146e3ce8701f02f8110248a43</data>
      <data key="d7">18</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">397</data>
      <data key="d6">b4e4fa2e3dfc46e68d532d659b18d17d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ALTERNATIVE USES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Alternative uses refer to other potential applications or purposes for materials or resources. In relevant cost analysis, considering alternative uses helps determine the opportunity cost of using materials for a specific project."</data>
      <data key="d2">7b2509b146e3ce8701f02f8110248a43</data>
      <data key="d7">18</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">398</data>
      <data key="d6">f58813d090b947a48c1b4614b92c3ec3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CROCUS CO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Crocus Co is a hypothetical company used in an example to illustrate the relevant costs of raw materials for a new product. The example considers the current purchase prices, inventory levels, and alternative uses of materials A, B, and C."</data>
      <data key="d2">7b2509b146e3ce8701f02f8110248a43</data>
      <data key="d7">18</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">399</data>
      <data key="d6">30a251bc3d04430d82b5a1a98c7b8c75</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BOB THE CARPENTER&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Bob is a carpenter featured in a quiz scenario where he needs to determine the relevant costs of materials (oak wood, varnish, and hinges) to make a special dining room table. Each material has different considerations for relevant cost calculation."</data>
      <data key="d2">7b2509b146e3ce8701f02f8110248a43</data>
      <data key="d7">18</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">400</data>
      <data key="d6">93e1d19f9bfa4c6b8962d56d10ea9483</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REPLACEMENT COST OF VARNISH&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The relevant cost for the tins of varnish is the replacement cost, which is the current price of $20 per tin."</data>
      <data key="d2">be49d637f150920086e2c735dad312fa</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">401</data>
      <data key="d6">8046335ba70b434aa3188392a746fd78</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPPORTUNITY COST OF HINGES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The relevant cost for the hinges is the opportunity cost, which is zero since Bob has not used the hinges before and nobody would want to buy second-hand hinges."</data>
      <data key="d2">be49d637f150920086e2c735dad312fa</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">402</data>
      <data key="d6">5c02b1ab32064c64a0f8b27b219e358a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RELEVANT COST OF IDLE LABOUR&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"If the organization has spare (idle) labour time that can be used on the contract, the relevant cost is zero."</data>
      <data key="d2">be49d637f150920086e2c735dad312fa</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">403</data>
      <data key="d6">c5f77ba0c261408780db3d50346f16b7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RELEVANT COST OF ADDITIONAL LABOUR&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"If additional labour time is required and can be obtained without taking workers away from other activities, the direct cost of the labour is relevant. This may be paid at a higher rate if overtime is involved."</data>
      <data key="d2">be49d637f150920086e2c735dad312fa</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">404</data>
      <data key="d6">453ecf5476f64f4a8d5020b95baf1314</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RELEVANT COST OF LABOUR WITH LIMITED AVAILABILITY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"If there is a limit on the amount of labour available, a contract may require workers to be taken away from other profitable activities. In this case, the relevant cost of labour is the direct cost plus the lost contribution from the other activities."</data>
      <data key="d2">be49d637f150920086e2c735dad312fa</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">405</data>
      <data key="d6">6a1d83c9ce2b483dbd7de5ab3ae2487d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF LABOUR AT MAGNOLIA CO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Magnolia Co has a new project requiring three types of labour: unskilled, semi-skilled, and skilled. The relevant costs are calculated based on the availability and cost of hiring new staff or using existing staff."</data>
      <data key="d2">be49d637f150920086e2c735dad312fa</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">406</data>
      <data key="d6">66c3dffb7d7a4fa8bb6b48a22ca917a6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: RELEVANT COSTS OF LABOUR&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves calculating the relevant cost of labour for a new project at Hide Omega Consulting, considering the availability and cost of project managers, business consultants, and technical consultants."</data>
      <data key="d2">be49d637f150920086e2c735dad312fa</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">407</data>
      <data key="d6">6f3dd1fd6d7f4df4af0656ed0525c92e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REPLACEMENT COST OF OAK&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">be49d637f150920086e2c735dad312fa</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">408</data>
      <data key="d6">711eb39432794b0a91110358dd536517</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NON-FINANCIAL FACTORS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Non-financial factors are considerations beyond cost that Robber Co should evaluate when deciding whether to outsource production. These factors are crucial for management to take into account before making a final decision, even if the financial analysis suggests proceeding. Key non-financial factors include quality control, supply chain reliability, potential impacts on employee morale, the potential for reputational damage, ethical concerns, and the strategic benefits of gaining experience or enhancing the business's reputation. It is important to note that non-financial factors such as quality may be equally important as financial factors, but these are often ignored by variance analysis, which is a significant limitation of this analytical approach.</data>
      <data key="d2">2b7c12bc08e4dff98f807210499e82ee,5c4312b5c5c803bc38cc120660340db3,a54e72ff2ad2a8799c6e772418b1a195</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">8</data>
      <data key="d5">409</data>
      <data key="d6">0e00585b08044954a254116665400463</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SHUT-DOWN DECISION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves analyzing the financial impact of closing divisions within a company. It requires calculating the lost contribution and saved fixed costs to determine whether the divisions should be closed based on their impact on overall profits."</data>
      <data key="d2">2b7c12bc08e4dff98f807210499e82ee</data>
      <data key="d3">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">410</data>
      <data key="d6">db0147eff2204a20b5e5e6bec7a8bae5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRODUCTION LINE CLOSURE DECISION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">The "PRODUCTION LINE CLOSURE DECISION" quiz involves evaluating the financial impact of closing production lines within a company. It requires analyzing revenue, marginal costs, and other financial metrics to determine the best course of action.</data>
      <data key="d2">2b7c12bc08e4dff98f807210499e82ee,b172e19fb414304c0d4fa0f2db3a6499</data>
      <data key="d3">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">411</data>
      <data key="d6">67bb4f4678284819add02ba04f3b1103</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONTRIBUTION MARGIN&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Contribution margin is the difference between sales revenue and variable costs. It is calculated as the selling price per unit minus the variable cost per unit. This metric is crucial in decision-making processes such as shut-down decisions and production line closures. The contribution margin is used to cover fixed costs and generate profit.</data>
      <data key="d2">2b7c12bc08e4dff98f807210499e82ee,838dcacda5281e1aaade85379faf8828,abd4a68d8185b413e829914bc2f86480,e77413580f69933c7e20f96d9b9b60cf</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">412</data>
      <data key="d6">2033ec0487f04240abb3bdbe77b39087</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ETHICAL CONCERNS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Ethical concerns refer to the moral implications of a business decision. These concerns can impact the company's reputation and long-term success and should be considered alongside financial factors."</data>
      <data key="d2">2b7c12bc08e4dff98f807210499e82ee</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">413</data>
      <data key="d6">f026fab8fec948ae9e7baa2ad715e6ef</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REPUTATIONAL DAMAGE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Reputational damage refers to the negative impact on a company's reputation as a result of certain decisions. This can affect customer trust, brand value, and overall business performance."</data>
      <data key="d2">2b7c12bc08e4dff98f807210499e82ee</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">414</data>
      <data key="d6">d0d7ed36d6f54b5d986dfd854096b728</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STRATEGIC BENEFITS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Strategic benefits are the long-term advantages that a company gains from making certain decisions. These benefits can include market positioning, competitive advantage, and enhanced capabilities."</data>
      <data key="d2">2b7c12bc08e4dff98f807210499e82ee</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">415</data>
      <data key="d6">bf6a4c18f44042799eb7456a6b85b54a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NON-FINANCIAL FACTORS IN SHUTDOWN DECISIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Non-financial factors to consider when making shutdown decisions include potential redundancies, loss of specific skills, impact on demand for other products, potential for new product development, and the possibility of selling assets to raise finance."</data>
      <data key="d2">b172e19fb414304c0d4fa0f2db3a6499</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">416</data>
      <data key="d6">fac4a59c2278498d83f9f1b4231ad62e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;JOINT PRODUCTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Joint products" are two or more products that are generated simultaneously from a common input and production process. They are typically separated at the split-off point. Joint products arise when the manufacture of one product makes the manufacture of other products inevitable, and they have significant relative sales value. Costs incurred before the split-off point are joint costs and must be apportioned between the products.</data>
      <data key="d2">b172e19fb414304c0d4fa0f2db3a6499,f48e76ebf07d8d7de318d46534f42fd9</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">12</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">417</data>
      <data key="d6">d6d2b5862ddc4c4d87deee3423506817</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BY-PRODUCTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"By-products are produced alongside one or more main products but have a small relative sales value. They are unlikely to influence the decision to produce the main products."</data>
      <data key="d2">b172e19fb414304c0d4fa0f2db3a6499</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">12</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">418</data>
      <data key="d6">47d588d26e2b4cccb68fe2af4c147c8f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SPLIT-OFF POINT (SOP)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The split-off point is the stage in the production process where products produced are not separately identifiable until this point. Costs incurred before the SOP are joint costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">b172e19fb414304c0d4fa0f2db3a6499</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">12</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">419</data>
      <data key="d6">c0f2dc03d8df400db4997c1a0babd6ad</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FURTHER PROCESSING DECISION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"An example where two products, G and H, are created from a joint process. G can be sold immediately after split-off, while H requires further processing. The decision to further process H is based on comparing additional revenue against additional costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">b172e19fb414304c0d4fa0f2db3a6499</data>
      <data key="d3">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d7">12</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">420</data>
      <data key="d6">0211d61aae834229a3a1e004ff5cc658</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: FURTHER PROCESSING DECISION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The quiz involves determining whether Daisy Co should further process a chemical into two components, A and B, based on their sales value and allocated costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">b172e19fb414304c0d4fa0f2db3a6499</data>
      <data key="d3">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d7">12</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">421</data>
      <data key="d6">ccbbbcc055c34709abcf103208c2c299</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FOXGLOVE CO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"COMPANIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Foxglove Co is the company involved in the production line closure decision quiz."</data>
      <data key="d2">b172e19fb414304c0d4fa0f2db3a6499</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">422</data>
      <data key="d6">989add81cf874018a569239b68d17ff2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DAISY CO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"COMPANIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Daisy Co is the company involved in the further processing decision quiz."</data>
      <data key="d2">b172e19fb414304c0d4fa0f2db3a6499</data>
      <data key="d7">12</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">423</data>
      <data key="d6">fd7d94fbab084bc380480abeef6bfade</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRODUCT G&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"PRODUCTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Product G is one of the products created from a joint process and can be sold immediately after the split-off point."</data>
      <data key="d2">b172e19fb414304c0d4fa0f2db3a6499</data>
      <data key="d7">12</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">424</data>
      <data key="d6">cfb915c95caf41c6a25e99a9f37f03a2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRODUCT H&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"PRODUCTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Product H is a product with the second highest contribution per limiting factor, to be produced after Product I until the limiting factor is used up. It is one of the products created from a joint process and requires further processing before it can be sold.</data>
      <data key="d2">ac68069ef08bb5822225377a605ac206,b172e19fb414304c0d4fa0f2db3a6499</data>
      <data key="d7">12</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">425</data>
      <data key="d6">8815ed80f9b741dbb458d902024f34a4</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRODUCT A&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"PRODUCTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Product A is a versatile product associated with multiple companies. It is one of the components resulting from further processing a chemical in the Daisy Co quiz. Additionally, Product A is manufactured by Yam Co, where it has a selling price of $70, a raw materials cost of $3, a labor cost of $10, and requires 0.5 hours of pressing time per unit. Furthermore, Product A is also made and sold by Flopro, with specific costs and a selling price, although these details are not explicitly provided.</data>
      <data key="d2">8c5f3adb7ce0099b89e3e7e2687c2a68,b172e19fb414304c0d4fa0f2db3a6499,bc96081078db9cb11a132fcb669135c0</data>
      <data key="d7">12</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">426</data>
      <data key="d6">dddb831546354e088d29aebd154e3a31</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRODUCT B&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"PRODUCTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Product B is a product made and sold by Flopro, with specific costs and a selling price. It is one of the components resulting from further processing a chemical in the Daisy Co quiz. Additionally, Product B is manufactured by Yam Co. It has a selling price of $60, a raw materials cost of $2.5, a labor cost of $10, and a pressing time per unit of 0.5 hours.</data>
      <data key="d2">88e696361bcc111f3d87032d375208f9,8c5f3adb7ce0099b89e3e7e2687c2a68,b172e19fb414304c0d4fa0f2db3a6499,bc96081078db9cb11a132fcb669135c0</data>
      <data key="d7">12</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">427</data>
      <data key="d6">005d2154da754b21adcd90ac921bd5f7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FURTHER PROCESSING DECISION QUIZ&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Quiz: Further Processing Decision. Daisy Co buys a chemical for $12,000, which is broken down into two components. The quiz requires determining the optimal production plan to maximize profits."</data>
      <data key="d2">f48e76ebf07d8d7de318d46534f42fd9</data>
      <data key="d3">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">428</data>
      <data key="d6">711ba818354546cea69f1532b92a2f26</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OUTSOURCING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Outsourcing involves contracting out certain business activities or functions to external providers rather than producing or providing them internally. This practice can encompass a wide range of services, including office cleaning, canteen and catering services, payroll services, IT services, and security services. Companies may choose to outsource for various reasons, such as cost savings in the long run or to achieve higher quality, even if the cost of outsourcing is higher. For example, a company might contract a third-party supplier in Burgistan to produce keypads and display screens instead of manufacturing them in-house, comparing the cost of buying from the supplier to the in-house production costs.</data>
      <data key="d2">5c4312b5c5c803bc38cc120660340db3,f48e76ebf07d8d7de318d46534f42fd9,fd88b98a3550ab4e5c7f37314520bc3a</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">9</data>
      <data key="d5">429</data>
      <data key="d6">5c4d8a8f9c104176b87d2bfdf04ae0bd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ADVANTAGES OF OUTSOURCING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Advantages of outsourcing include lower cost, services becoming a variable cost, management focus on core competencies, higher quality from specialist suppliers, and access to a broader range of expertise."</data>
      <data key="d2">f48e76ebf07d8d7de318d46534f42fd9</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">430</data>
      <data key="d6">5a781604f1fb4719b730f43f534627f6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DISADVANTAGES OF OUTSOURCING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Disadvantages of outsourcing include reliance on a third party, loss of control, hidden costs, potential quality issues, operational dependence on the outsourcing company's financial stability, and potential workforce demotivation."</data>
      <data key="d2">f48e76ebf07d8d7de318d46534f42fd9</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">431</data>
      <data key="d6">ecdc1020b10e49ca869d399825e16fa3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MAKE VS. BUY DECISIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Make vs. Buy Decisions involve calculating the financial effect of outsourcing the manufacture of a particular component. This includes determining the costs saved if in-house production ceases and comparing this with the costs of buying the component from an external supplier."</data>
      <data key="d2">f48e76ebf07d8d7de318d46534f42fd9</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">432</data>
      <data key="d6">0d8fde01d7234726a00d7e73e2e01d66</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SPLIT-OFF POINT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The split-off point is the stage in the production process where joint products can be recognized as separate products. Costs incurred up to this point are considered common costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">f48e76ebf07d8d7de318d46534f42fd9</data>
      <data key="d7">12</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">433</data>
      <data key="d6">9c4bd60958fd4e09a6d5b9e2ab163b5a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INCREMENTAL REVENUE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"INCREMENTAL REVENUE" refers to the additional revenue generated from a new activity or decision, such as further processing a product beyond the split-off point. It is a key factor in making further processing decisions.</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f,f48e76ebf07d8d7de318d46534f42fd9</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">434</data>
      <data key="d6">39d31f770cf740e78d526a2e1101a1db</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VARIABLE COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Variable cost" refers to expenses that vary directly with the level of production or sales volume. These costs include items such as raw materials, direct labor, and sales commissions. In the context of outsourcing, services becoming a variable cost is considered an advantage. Specifically, the variable cost per customer is $1.20.</data>
      <data key="d2">4435163b259d1a0d68e055b03df87004,5ad3a043b58cedf0d850b61a9e407269,e6f7ca658dc25c9178113951c7a31846,f48e76ebf07d8d7de318d46534f42fd9</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">435</data>
      <data key="d6">9d282b2250f7408888504f1f93c202a8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CORE COMPETENCIES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Core competencies are the main strengths or strategic advantages of a business. Outsourcing allows management to focus on these core competencies."</data>
      <data key="d2">f48e76ebf07d8d7de318d46534f42fd9</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">436</data>
      <data key="d6">c063484895794a0eaae1b0ff070ad4c9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COMMON COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">f48e76ebf07d8d7de318d46534f42fd9</data>
      <data key="d7">12</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">437</data>
      <data key="d6">e8868920e21b4431aad16e86db977ecb</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BREAKEVEN POINT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The breakeven point is the level of activity at which neither a profit nor a loss is made. It is a measure of the lowest activity level at which the activity is viable, where total contribution equals total fixed costs. At this point, total sales equal total costs, ensuring that the company makes neither profit nor loss.</data>
      <data key="d2">08f6c24c7f87b7ffc3b8a5dfc505c552,98d761e221e6915f156753807cb8fbe1</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">6</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">8</data>
      <data key="d5">438</data>
      <data key="d6">aea3378bfff842e5b3f4b7a4b55b3879</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONTRIBUTION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Contribution" is the amount remaining from sales revenue after deducting variable costs, which contributes to covering fixed costs and generating profit. It is the difference between sales revenue and variable costs. For Division M, the contribution on external sales is $80 per unit. Contribution refers to earnings from sales after deducting variable costs and is computed by deducting variable costs from revenue. The funds available from contribution are used to cover fixed costs, and any excess over fixed costs is considered profit.</data>
      <data key="d2">23de7e5f5aa4638cfdebaec8afd6c5de,2df3be986166cb71a016998a16e5349a,34f2c5c9d893c1b631ed1646193eebf4,98d761e221e6915f156753807cb8fbe1</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">6</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">7</data>
      <data key="d5">439</data>
      <data key="d6">d562223c17d948bf98e34b4d97dde932</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONTRIBUTION TO SALES RATIO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The "Contribution to Sales Ratio" is calculated by dividing the contribution per unit by the selling price per unit. This ratio is used to determine the profitability of products in both single and multi-product situations.</data>
      <data key="d2">98d761e221e6915f156753807cb8fbe1,a5995fbeaf1e8bc061f219d79f9689d1</data>
      <data key="d3">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d7">6</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">440</data>
      <data key="d6">cde2d75c51d245879265b79d14b8699b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TARGET PROFIT OR REVENUE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Target profit or revenue is calculated by determining the sales volume needed to achieve a specific profit level. This involves adding the target profit to the fixed costs and dividing by the contribution per unit."</data>
      <data key="d2">98d761e221e6915f156753807cb8fbe1</data>
      <data key="d3">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d7">6</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">441</data>
      <data key="d6">44594467054849d4a1fadb46ddd51641</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BREAKEVEN CHART&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">A breakeven chart is a graphical representation that shows the point at which total costs and total revenue are equal. It plots revenue and costs against volume, with the intersection of the total cost and revenue lines indicating the breakeven point. This chart helps in visualizing the relationship between costs, revenue, and profit at different levels of activity.</data>
