    <node id="&quot;PROFIT-VOLUME CHART&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A profit-volume (PV) chart presents the same information as a breakeven chart but emphasizes profits and losses at different activity levels. It requires information on profit or loss at any level of sales and total fixed costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">98d761e221e6915f156753807cb8fbe1</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d7">6</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">443</data>
      <data key="d6">fd139ac75b0e4777ab67b7423eaaa37f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SIMPLIFYING ASSUMPTIONS OF CVP ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"SIMPLIFYING ASSUMPTIONS OF CVP ANALYSIS"

The main limitations of CVP (Cost-Volume-Profit) analysis for planning and decision-making stem from the necessary simplifying assumptions. These assumptions include the following: fixed costs remain constant, the variable cost per unit remains constant, and the selling price remains constant. Additionally, CVP analysis assumes that total cost behaves as a strictly linear semi-variable cost, unit selling prices do not change with volume, costs and income are matched, levels of efficiency and productivity do not change, and there is either only a single product or a constant sales mix of more than one product. These assumptions are critical for the analysis but can limit its applicability in more complex, real-world scenarios.</data>
      <data key="d2">08f6c24c7f87b7ffc3b8a5dfc505c552,98d761e221e6915f156753807cb8fbe1</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d7">6</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">444</data>
      <data key="d6">a701c349eb7142d48ba7efad89caf9d2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF DEPENDENCE ON SALES VOLUME&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Company A knows the sales price for product X will be around $50, and its variable costs are approximately $30. The contribution per unit is $20. With annual fixed costs of $200,000, Company A needs to sell 10,000 units to break even."</data>
      <data key="d2">98d761e221e6915f156753807cb8fbe1</data>
      <data key="d3">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d7">6</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">445</data>
      <data key="d6">e5d40a1b17f74b1db5d18279caedb04a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: BREAKEVEN CHART&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves drawing a breakeven chart for a product called gamma, with a selling price of $100 per unit, variable cost of $20 per unit, and fixed costs of $1,000,000 per year. The breakeven level of sales is determined to be 12,500 units."</data>
      <data key="d2">98d761e221e6915f156753807cb8fbe1</data>
      <data key="d3">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d7">6</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">446</data>
      <data key="d6">de25d06733d04385825ee082792f5e52</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CVP ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">98d761e221e6915f156753807cb8fbe1</data>
      <data key="d7">6</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
