      <data key="d6">3cf0ab4cf14e47ddabd49d500a3dc488</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TOTAL CONTRIBUTION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"TOTAL CONTRIBUTION" refers to the total contribution margin, which is calculated as total sales revenue minus total variable costs. This metric, expressed as "Total contribution = Total revenue - Total variable cost," is essential in financial analysis, particularly for breakeven and target profit calculations.</data>
      <data key="d2">23de7e5f5aa4638cfdebaec8afd6c5de,4435163b259d1a0d68e055b03df87004,e77413580f69933c7e20f96d9b9b60cf</data>
      <data key="d3">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d7">6</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">455</data>
      <data key="d6">a39b72f8921f43ef8ef295c7cc8f7294</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BREAKEVEN POINT (BEP)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The breakeven point (BEP) is the level of sales at which total revenue equals total costs, resulting in zero profit. At BEP, the total contribution equals the fixed cost. The formula to calculate the BEP is given by dividing the total fixed cost by the unit contribution. In this case, the BEP is calculated as 340,000 divided by 40, which equals 8,500 units.</data>
      <data key="d2">23de7e5f5aa4638cfdebaec8afd6c5de,e77413580f69933c7e20f96d9b9b60cf</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">3</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">456</data>
      <data key="d6">9f5adbeb6cf04f089abe78d86cfa6aba</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BREAKEVEN POINT FORMULA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The "BREAKEVEN POINT FORMULA" is a financial calculation used to determine the number of units that must be sold to cover total fixed costs. It is expressed as "Breakeven point = Total fixed cost / Unit contribution." This formula helps businesses understand the minimum sales volume required to avoid losses. The breakeven point is calculated by dividing the total fixed cost by the unit contribution, which is the amount each unit contributes to covering fixed costs after variable costs have been subtracted. Therefore, the number of units to be sold to breakeven is determined by this same formula: "Number of units to be sold to breakeven = Total fixed cost / Unit contribution."</data>
      <data key="d2">08f6c24c7f87b7ffc3b8a5dfc505c552,23de7e5f5aa4638cfdebaec8afd6c5de</data>
      <data key="d3">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d7">3</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">457</data>
      <data key="d6">efb6350e65964659bc20396c0166b296</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TARGET PROFIT FORMULA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sales volume to achieve a target profit = (Total fixed cost + required profit) / Unit contribution"</data>
      <data key="d2">23de7e5f5aa4638cfdebaec8afd6c5de</data>
      <data key="d3">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d7">3</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">458</data>
      <data key="d6">e095cc36da784300b27c6f8c60a96440</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BREAKEVEN REVENUE FORMULA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The "BREAKEVEN REVENUE FORMULA" is defined as "Breakeven revenue = Number of units at BEP * Unit selling price." This formula calculates the revenue needed to cover all fixed and variable costs, ensuring that the business neither makes a profit nor incurs a loss at the breakeven point.</data>
      <data key="d2">23de7e5f5aa4638cfdebaec8afd6c5de,abd4a68d8185b413e829914bc2f86480,e6f7ca658dc25c9178113951c7a31846</data>
      <data key="d3">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d7">3</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">459</data>
      <data key="d6">c68893ca39d74ba08c6eb138f24441e1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONTRIBUTION/SALES (C/S) RATIO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The contribution/sales ratio (also called contribution margin) is the proportion of the selling price which contributes to fixed overheads and profits."</data>
      <data key="d2">23de7e5f5aa4638cfdebaec8afd6c5de</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">460</data>
      <data key="d6">472b23bb92834173b4118d101040c726</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;C/S RATIO FORMULA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"C/S ratio = Contribution per unit / Selling price per unit or Total contribution / Total Sales revenue"</data>
      <data key="d2">23de7e5f5aa4638cfdebaec8afd6c5de</data>
      <data key="d3">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">461</data>
      <data key="d6">81869985b45a4fefbbbb23ea118a3de4</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BREAKEVEN REVENUE USING C/S RATIO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Breakeven revenue = Fixed cost / C/S ratio"</data>
      <data key="d2">23de7e5f5aa4638cfdebaec8afd6c5de</data>
      <data key="d3">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d7">3</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">462</data>
      <data key="d6">42b8584c5a874eb08fbd61f0c18f3ca0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARGIN OF SAFETY FORMULA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The "MARGIN OF SAFETY FORMULA" is a financial metric used to determine the difference between budgeted sales and break-even sales. It can be expressed in two ways: 

1. As a ratio, calculated by subtracting break-even sales units from budgeted sales units and then dividing the result by budgeted sales units. The formula is: Margin of safety = (Budgeted sales units &#8211; break-even sales units) / Budgeted sales units.

2. As a percentage, calculated by subtracting break-even sales from budgeted sales and then dividing the result by budgeted sales, multiplied by 100%. The formula is: Margin of safety = (Budgeted sales - Breakeven sales) / Budgeted sales * 100%.

Both expressions provide insight into how much sales can drop before the business reaches its break-even point, thus indicating the risk level associated with the current sales forecast.</data>
      <data key="d2">23de7e5f5aa4638cfdebaec8afd6c5de,b19ebe566f006f8d570bb588768ba2dd</data>
      <data key="d3">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d7">3</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">463</data>
      <data key="d6">824d93d9840a4b7c8b1f31bc6816b497</data>
    </node>
