    <node id="&quot;TARGET PROFIT CALCULATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Total contribution/Unit contribution = $380,000/40 = 9,500 units. Total revenue required: 9,500 &#215; $129 = $1,225,500"</data>
      <data key="d2">e77413580f69933c7e20f96d9b9b60cf</data>
      <data key="d3">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">469</data>
      <data key="d6">3073b33926bd4f33807ffa3befacefaf</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ASSUMPTION OF CVP ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"CVP analysis can be extended to multi-product situations if a constant pre-determined sales mix is applied. If the assumption of a standard mix is relaxed, there will be no unique BEP."</data>
      <data key="d2">e77413580f69933c7e20f96d9b9b60cf</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d7">3</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">470</data>
      <data key="d6">2b916117691c4872a9c4e4888d4fe4ab</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;WEIGHTED AVERAGE C/S RATIO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The weighted average C/S ratio, also known as the weighted average contribution to sales ratio, is a key metric used in multi-product breakeven analysis. It is calculated by taking the sum of the contribution to sales ratios of each product, weighted by their proportion of total sales. This ratio can be expressed through various formulas, such as:

1. Weighted average C/S ratio = (Contribution margin of product X * Sales mix percentage of product X) + (Contribution margin of product Y * Sales mix percentage of product Y) + ...
2. Weighted average C/S ratio = Budgeted total contribution / Budgeted total revenue.
3. Weighted average C/S ratio = Total contribution (from all products) / Total revenue (from all products).

The weighted average C/S ratio is used to determine breakeven revenue and the sales revenue required to generate a target profit. For instance, a specific calculation example provided is $34.60 / $80, which equals 0.4325. Additionally, the weighted average contribution to sales ratio has been noted to be 87.06%.</data>
      <data key="d2">2ec07a1112223c3286057400e3b2eca9,3ef6ffef196ce21eb853bd7cf7b00da2,4435163b259d1a0d68e055b03df87004,abd4a68d8185b413e829914bc2f86480,e6f7ca658dc25c9178113951c7a31846,e77413580f69933c7e20f96d9b9b60cf</data>
      <data key="d3">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d7">3</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">11</data>
      <data key="d5">471</data>
      <data key="d6">1f7b02bf486e4f42b23e9cb1a63207f3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF MULTI-PRODUCT ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Company A produces Product X and Y. The weighted average C/S ratio of 0.34375 or 34.375% is calculated by dividing the total contribution of X and Y by the total revenue of X and Y. BEP in sales revenue = Fixed costs/C/S ratio = $200,000/0.34375 = $581,819 sales revenue. To achieve a target profit of $300,000 = ($200,000 + $300,000)/0.34375 = $1,454,546."</data>
      <data key="d2">e77413580f69933c7e20f96d9b9b60cf</data>
      <data key="d3">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d7">3</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">472</data>
      <data key="d6">e744c118ae7f4638a01d060bbaedd6e9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: MULTI-PRODUCT ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Pear manufactures laptop computers and smartphones. The quiz involves calculating the breakeven revenue and the sales revenue required to make a target profit of $245,000 using the weighted average C/S ratio."</data>
      <data key="d2">e77413580f69933c7e20f96d9b9b60cf</data>
      <data key="d3">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d7">3</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">473</data>
      <data key="d6">e1c1080c717d437996def1a41772d179</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES MIX&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sales mix is the ratio of different products sold by a company. It is important in multi-product CVP analysis."</data>
      <data key="d2">e77413580f69933c7e20f96d9b9b60cf</data>
      <data key="d7">3</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">474</data>
      <data key="d6">63fba9a7c47a4f14ac0bee6bc90d0fea</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES REVENUE TO MAKE A PROFIT FORMULA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sales revenue to make a profit of $245,000 = (Fixed cost + Required profit) / Weighted average C/S ratio = (245,000 + 245,000) / 0.28 = $1,750,000"</data>
      <data key="d2">abd4a68d8185b413e829914bc2f86480</data>
      <data key="d3">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d7">3</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">475</data>
      <data key="d6">6bfc2395b4f54a528a1ebac94a43acb8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES UNITS AT BREAKEVEN REVENUE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"In multi-product situations, breakeven revenue shows the total revenue required to break even, assuming the budgeted sales mix. Decision makers may wish to analyze this revenue by product. This can be estimated by multiplying the total breakeven revenue by the revenue ratio for each product."</data>
      <data key="d2">abd4a68d8185b413e829914bc2f86480</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">476</data>
      <data key="d6">1cce5cebf437428eb1a60dffbdfa603f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REVENUE RATIO FOR PRODUCT X&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Revenue ratio for product X = Budgeted revenue for product X / Total budgeted revenue"</data>
      <data key="d2">abd4a68d8185b413e829914bc2f86480</data>
      <data key="d3">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">477</data>
      <data key="d6">dc94039d6643460ca3c66150b9087129</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REVENUE FROM PRODUCT X AT BREAKEVEN&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Revenue from product X = Total breakeven revenue * Revenue ratio for product X"</data>
      <data key="d2">abd4a68d8185b413e829914bc2f86480</data>
      <data key="d3">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">478</data>
      <data key="d6">f197d75f159943f8a3ff441199790bc7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MULTI-PRODUCT PROFIT-VOLUME (PV) CHARTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"In a multi-product environment, sales revenue is drawn on the horizontal axis (x axis) and profit is drawn on the vertical axis (y axis). Two approaches are taken to drawing the line denoting profit/loss: constant (fixed) sales mix; or ranking of products by profitability."</data>
      <data key="d2">abd4a68d8185b413e829914bc2f86480</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">479</data>
      <data key="d6">4d8890c699684c9381105b03b0b41b03</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONSTANT SALES MIX PV CHART&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Assuming a constant mix of products based on the budgeted sales, it is only necessary to know the profit for two values of sales (to plot on the graph and draw a straight line between them): The most straightforward point is where revenue = 0 (i.e. where the company makes a loss equal to fixed costs). For the second point it makes most sense to calculate profit for total budgeted sales."</data>
      <data key="d2">abd4a68d8185b413e829914bc2f86480</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">480</data>
      <data key="d6">b1658adfa43847eabad1437db235e858</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF MULTI-PRODUCT PROFIT-VOLUME CHART&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Zed Co makes two products, Exe and Wye. Details of these two products are as follows: Selling price ($/unit) Exe: 40, Wye: 60; Contribution ($/unit) Exe: 24, Wye: 18; Budgeted sales (units) Exe: 10,000, Wye: 10,000. Total fixed costs are budgeted at $100,000. When sales revenue = 0, loss = $100,000 (fixed costs). At total budgeted sales: Revenue = (10,000 * 40) + (10,000 * 60) = $1,000,000. Profit = Contribution - Fixed cost = (10,000 * 24) + (10,000 * 18) - 100,000 = 320,000."</data>
      <data key="d2">abd4a68d8185b413e829914bc2f86480</data>
      <data key="d3">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">481</data>
      <data key="d6">a1773cac7d4c4939aec965660e5015fe</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES BY PROFITABILITY PV CHART&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"An alternative assumption is that sales are not made in a standard sales mix but by prioritizing the most profitable products (i.e. the company produces and sells the product with the highest contribution first). Products are, therefore, ranked according to their C/S ratios. In this case, the PV chart will no longer be a straight line; it will be 'kinked'."</data>
      <data key="d2">abd4a68d8185b413e829914bc2f86480</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">482</data>
      <data key="d6">6a054cb59fb44cf494b93988b5f88833</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF SALES BY PROFITABILITY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Assuming now that Zed Co decides to produce and sell the product that has the highest C/S ratio up to the maximum budgeted (10,000 units), followed by the other product (again up to maximum 10,000 units). Selling price ($/unit) Exe: 40, Wye: 60; Contribution ($/unit) Exe: 24, Wye: 18; C/S ratio Exe: 0.6, Wye: 0.3; Ranking Exe: 1st, Wye: 2nd. The cumulative profit/(loss) corresponding to cumulative revenue is calculated as follows: Sales volume Exe 10,000: Contribution 240,000, Cumulative profit/loss 140,000, Revenue 400,000, Cumulative revenue 400,000; Sales volume Wye 10,000: Contribution 180,000, Cumulative profit/loss 320,000, Revenue 600,000, Cumulative revenue 1,000,000."</data>
      <data key="d2">abd4a68d8185b413e829914bc2f86480</data>
      <data key="d3">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">483</data>
      <data key="d6">e7b103a52e384e3e8bf14105223e7e82</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FIXED COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Fixed cost" refers to business expenses that are not dependent on the level of goods or services produced by the business. These costs do not change with the level of production or sales volume and remain constant regardless of the business's output. Examples of fixed costs include rent, salaries, and insurance.</data>
      <data key="d2">00157cf30936c417d0c54f1dfce77654,002794ec024434f7ac2bd26217b3897d,01294aa83ab1143451866d43087f9eba,01d1ff33e985b6f8cd09ff45ebfedc0e,026b22934152d61a6b625fae071b3bcd,0279d26139c7d66d51896f7ebfe162ee,02defdad562458f44c0d0fa31dc9693d,03721d9b5064cc002df514cca9896c3b,039a2a6ce8c94f49aa8954c72332cea2,05e25a78a53e695fd01856df3a302292,0622f4f26dbe7479c871198b2e72b940,078e47b3223db97709a37da2a01302c5,08f6c24c7f87b7ffc3b8a5dfc505c552,0a1392ec8d4dc63bfee377dc6d552da3,0af2d78ba77677f806a697c0deb0ced3,0cafbc1007afddae5f416e6fb910386a,0d6ca97290394110da0bcfffa12dac11,0dbbae65ee89b4c5d53a1b0a83d84535,0e0632925a4598cac64c13be234f1755,0f59fe901f330c6a95c810cdae18b305,10a6cfb7beb226418463ca4749be7451,1198b5b37a51d0315db68af2bdb139bd,11b64c42e42e94e3f0881a9cd9457d74,122be7bb4778bacae6dba8d18b50c025,12bf561fb0f443af5c38c4055dae476d,14d295eb69556ed8203b13909d341a07,158846b2d51075f1de4279110c7a2ae1,16965b8a36bbe6bac45c7b81a6b17c48,181a68483be6482e8b136a2d540875a9,185572ab91ea67a36a262b55dffde450,1872b59f14e8fe91c616b29960e49fb9,19092af48cfe51bac1503c304f3ca707,1aa84a5288fe62c1d778b9f9013d51c3,1c07f0d21b37bda63c238ee6e4ed571b,1d33c979d505d0dcd027d816d2ab2695,1dbcdd2207ed07f8e45dc35658ecbd2a,1e37a7be9b892b604c2e7b6cf6a2c49f,1f06696499d837582d3dac671cb07649,2154b2cf6113011b3816974155d6ed8d,2207ef547588f07b856f3a5c961e39a0,22f7850b6ee24babd9cf367c0fc478a4,2343dedcae64d2e174ab981dfc3b23a0,2381a9a278f9cf058d7c71932fad4841,238ba7ae5def49a914d13c1bcf1e1332,24cd8c3feefdefe57b7e7da7db59d031,258563e1a008a7977296119e059fdf11,27370737012393c709c89a56df8ea2d4,27fde199847b14399dfca384e07a77a4,2922f29fc45ffc98655fc81f9a40fa79,299f4bc827fb4c62a74f3271557514e9,2a57a845054dd3fd23f0910ad239a201,2ad6c0ee81f4b0da1c6b2f2821dff6b6,2b35add90aa38f95a0510f9302a559f9,2df3be986166cb71a016998a16e5349a,2ec07a1112223c3286057400e3b2eca9,2f4d122e57ceca3100dab3886c99ca27,2fd1d6134ec72f26d7a900391b7261fd,303f0ef8328d2aefc4bfae1067a85f72,30748d6dcf5a2da70804db75296cee3c,312c3cf9edbc058c6e810c1e9c9cd81a