    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CVP ANALYSIS ASSUMPTIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The usefulness of CVP analysis is limited by the simplifying assumptions that have to be made to make it work."</data>
      <data key="d2">e6f7ca658dc25c9178113951c7a31846</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">596</data>
      <data key="d6">33905debec1a45ecae1c65daac1d854c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LIMITING FACTOR DECISIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Limiting Factor Decisions involve identifying limiting factors in a scarce resource situation and selecting an appropriate technique to determine the optimal production plan where an organization is restricted by a single limiting factor."</data>
      <data key="d2">e6f7ca658dc25c9178113951c7a31846</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">3</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">597</data>
      <data key="d6">bfbe904780fe47daad1a04126b12923c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF LIMITING FACTOR IDENTIFICATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Company A uses two materials in production, Material J and Material K. Material J is restricted to 12,000 kg, while Material K is restricted to 24,000 kg. The demand and material use for Products A, B, and C are shown in the table. Given the data, Material J is identified as the limiting factor."</data>
      <data key="d2">e6f7ca658dc25c9178113951c7a31846</data>
      <data key="d3">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d7">3</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">598</data>
      <data key="d6">0614f00e932c4cd0b53928053811ebc1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: SALES RESTRICTIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves calculating the maximum contribution that can be achieved when Material R is restricted to 12,000 kg and sales of Product I are restricted to 4,000 units. The products H, I, and J have different contributions per unit and kg of R per unit. The quiz requires ranking the products and calculating the maximum contribution under sales restrictions."</data>
      <data key="d2">e6f7ca658dc25c9178113951c7a31846</data>
      <data key="d3">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d7">3</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">599</data>
      <data key="d6">9ef487dd0b574b108c60a56d6a2f146c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONTRIBUTION TO SALES RATIO (C/S RATIO)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METRICS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The contribution to sales ratio (C/S ratio) is calculated as the contribution per unit divided by the selling price per unit. It indicates the proportion of sales revenue that contributes to covering fixed costs and generating profit."</data>
      <data key="d2">e6f7ca658dc25c9178113951c7a31846</data>
      <data key="d7">3</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">600</data>
      <data key="d6">4067269e7f6943cdbc299ce02b7eadbd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MAXIMUM CONTRIBUTION CALCULATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The maximum contribution is calculated by prioritizing products based on their contribution per limiting factor and producing them up to their maximum demand or until the limiting factor is exhausted."</data>
      <data key="d2">ac68069ef08bb5822225377a605ac206</data>
      <data key="d3">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d7">12</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">601</data>
      <data key="d6">094a736ba43c4da48c556437f47f88d1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;KEY FACTOR ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Key Factor Analysis is a decision-making approach that prioritizes production based on the contribution per limiting factor, assuming a single objective of profit maximization and constant variable and fixed costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">ac68069ef08bb5822225377a605ac206</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">26</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">602</data>
      <data key="d6">563c2af32bb3476299e9b24a646097ab</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LIMITATIONS OF KEY FACTOR ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Limitations of Key Factor Analysis include assumptions of a single objective of profit maximization, constant variable and fixed costs, dealing with only one scarce resource, and applicability only to short-term capacity constraints."</data>
      <data key="d2">ac68069ef08bb5822225377a605ac206</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d7">26</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">603</data>
      <data key="d6">d59b49eb94ce442d89907e90c5d3a44e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SHADOW PRICE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Shadow Price" refers to the additional contribution generated if one more unit of a scarce resource becomes available. It represents the maximum premium over the normal price that a company would be willing to pay for each additional unit. In the context of linear programming, the shadow price is the change in the optimal value of the objective function per unit increase in the right-hand side of a constraint. Essentially, it is the amount by which the objective function, such as contribution, will increase if an extra unit of a scarce resource is obtained at the standard price. For example, for the company Cut and Stitch, the shadow price for fabric is $10 per meter. The shadow price is a critical measure as it indicates the maximum amount a company should pay for one more unit of a scarce resource, such as timber, based on the contribution that the additional unit would generate.</data>
      <data key="d2">238ba7ae5def49a914d13c1bcf1e1332,5a645510a423feead88fce4460595798,64dc637d9fd89ad41762620a1229b806,853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38,ac68069ef08bb5822225377a605ac206,e7783a6241d7d8fbb8f2530d08f784e9</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">26</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">604</data>
      <data key="d6">8ea7cef407df48098046551e303e1c64</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DECISIONS WITH A LIMITING FACTOR&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Decisions with a Limiting Factor involve determining which products to make in-house and which to outsource based on the savings per unit of scarce resource, prioritizing those with the greatest savings."</data>
      <data key="d2">ac68069ef08bb5822225377a605ac206</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">26</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">605</data>
      <data key="d6">186e60d2176547bf84e5bf87bd16bb40</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MAKE OR BUY QUIZ&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Make or Buy Quiz involves determining which components to make in-house and which to buy externally based on the savings per unit of scarce resource, given a limited supply of Material B."</data>
      <data key="d2">ac68069ef08bb5822225377a605ac206</data>
      <data key="d3">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d7">26</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">606</data>
      <data key="d6">e65017091c8d4c7daa45b6c8414e0465</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRODUCT J&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Product J is a product with the third highest contribution per limiting factor, to be produced after Product H until the limiting factor is used up."</data>
      <data key="d2">ac68069ef08bb5822225377a605ac206</data>
      <data key="d7">12</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">607</data>
      <data key="d6">a0f326b9597b49dda6563e9208316117</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRODUCT K&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Product K is a product with the fourth highest contribution per limiting factor, to be produced after Product J until the limiting factor is used up."</data>
      <data key="d2">ac68069ef08bb5822225377a605ac206</data>
      <data key="d7">12</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">608</data>
      <data key="d6">bff3db70f9af4f2c87a93df48ecbb6bc</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONTRIBUTION PER LIMITING FACTOR&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Contribution per limiting factor is calculated by dividing the contribution margin of a product by the amount of the limiting factor required to produce one unit of the product."</data>
      <data key="d2">ac68069ef08bb5822225377a605ac206</data>
      <data key="d7">12</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">609</data>
      <data key="d6">bf91f36307cb43e1ab1e967cb3ba8274</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RETURN PER HOUR OF BOTTLENECK RESOURCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Return per hour of bottleneck resource is calculated by dividing the throughput per unit by the bottleneck hours required to produce one unit."</data>
      <data key="d2">ac68069ef08bb5822225377a605ac206</data>
      <data key="d7">26</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">610</data>
      <data key="d6">cd58a8740ba54d86a77db9bb9544ef0d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LINEAR PROGRAMMING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Linear programming is a mathematical method used to determine the best possible outcome or solution from a given set of parameters or list of requirements, which are linear in nature. It involves formulating an objective function to either maximize contribution or minimize cost, and expressing constraints as linear equations. Linear programming is particularly useful for problems involving the rationing of scarce resources between products to achieve optimum benefit. The optimal solution can be identified graphically or solved algebraically using simultaneous equations."</data>
      <data key="d2">026b22934152d61a6b625fae071b3bcd,842c67915128905c66fae05fe8d55080,853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,88e696361bcc111f3d87032d375208f9,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d3">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d7">11</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">12</data>
      <data key="d5">611</data>
      <data key="d6">e96d3475d43b42a781b297ae7e650afe</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OBJECTIVE FUNCTION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The objective function in linear programming is a mathematical expression that defines the goal of the optimization, such as maximizing profit or minimizing cost. It quantifies the objective of a linear programming problem and is based on the assumption that both the objective and the constraints can be expressed as linear equations. In this context, there are two specific instances of objective functions provided: one is \(15x + 12y\), and another is \(9a + 23b\), where 'a' and 'b' represent the number of units of products A and B to be produced, respectively.</data>
      <data key="d2">026b22934152d61a6b625fae071b3bcd,238ba7ae5def49a914d13c1bcf1e1332,842c67915128905c66fae05fe8d55080,853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38,e7783a6241d7d8fbb8f2530d08f784e9</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">11</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">612</data>
      <data key="d6">1ce76a5547854d458878bd445f0ccbd6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONSTRAINTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Constraints are the limitations or requirements that must be satisfied in an optimization problem. They define the boundaries of the feasible region. In linear programming, constraints are limitations or restrictions on the decision variables, which can include resource constraints, production constraints, and levels of demand, and are typically expressed in terms of inequalities. Examples of constraints include:

1. Material constraints: \(3x + y \leq 4,200\)
2. Labour constraints: \(4x + 0.5y \leq 3,000\)
3. Non-negativity constraints: \(b \geq 0\)
4. Restriction on A: \(a \geq 1,000\)
5. Materials constraints: \(3a + 4b \leq 30,000\)
6. Labour constraints: \(5a + 3b \leq 36,000\)

These constraints ensure that the solutions to the optimization problem remain within the feasible region defined by these boundaries.</data>
      <data key="d2">026b22934152d61a6b625fae071b3bcd,238ba7ae5def49a914d13c1bcf1e1332,842c67915128905c66fae05fe8d55080,853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d7">11</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">613</data>
      <data key="d6">11e4325f59394ff1bc89892f79288702</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GRAPHING A LINEAR PROGRAMMING MODEL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The process of graphing a linear programming model includes defining unknowns, formulating the objective function, expressing constraints as inequalities, and plotting all constraints on a graph to identify the feasible region. The optimal solution can be solved using the objective function method or the simultaneous equation method."</data>
      <data key="d2">842c67915128905c66fae05fe8d55080</data>
      <data key="d3">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d7">11</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">614</data>
      <data key="d6">71743537a07c440ea1710a269da8b538</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF LINEAR PROGRAMMING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A company makes two products, cabinets and chests, which pass through carpentry and polishing departments. The time spent in each department and the available hours are given. The contribution to profit and fixed overheads is $100 for a cabinet and $150 for a chest. The optimal product mix to maximize total contribution to profit is calculated using linear programming."</data>
      <data key="d2">842c67915128905c66fae05fe8d55080</data>
      <data key="d3">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d7">11</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">615</data>
      <data key="d6">1389192ce5464be6b3b5749bc9536709</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FEASIBLE REGION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">In linear programming, the "FEASIBLE REGION" is the set of all possible points that satisfy all constraints. It is typically represented as a polygonal area on a graph where the optimal solution lies. Specifically, the feasible region is the area on a graph that satisfies all the constraints of the model. For example, in the context of Cut and Stitch, it is the region OABCD on the graph where the constraints for tailors' time, fabric, and production limits intersect. This region represents all possible values for the variables that meet the given constraints and is where the optimal solution for maximizing contribution can be found.</data>
      <data key="d2">64dc637d9fd89ad41762620a1229b806,842c67915128905c66fae05fe8d55080,853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,fb0f5765d523a19ec931f6834815662f</data>
      <data key="d7">11</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">9</data>
      <data key="d5">616</data>
      <data key="d6">b349041c0be64c62b964ab1234e055e6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SIMULTANEOUS EQUATIONS METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The Simultaneous Equations Method is an algebraic approach used in linear programming to find the optimal solution by solving the system of linear equations formed by the constraints. This method is utilized to identify the point of maximum contribution by calculating the contribution at each possible maximum point of intersection within the feasible region.</data>
      <data key="d2">842c67915128905c66fae05fe8d55080,fb0f5765d523a19ec931f6834815662f</data>
      <data key="d7">11</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">617</data>
      <data key="d6">969e1ea0b1e443a68e9a65dfef91d161</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OBJECTIVE FUNCTION METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The objective function method involves determining how contribution varies with product output. It uses iso-contribution lines to show all combinations of variables that produce a specific value of contribution. This method helps identify the optimal production mix that maximizes contribution within given constraints. Additionally, the objective function method involves evaluating the objective function at each vertex of the feasible region to determine which vertex yields the optimal solution.</data>
      <data key="d2">842c67915128905c66fae05fe8d55080,853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b</data>
      <data key="d7">11</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">618</data>
      <data key="d6">8e09e7cfea7d405db8b22ae2f836ccb1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RESOURCE CONSTRAINTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Resource constraints are limitations on the availability of resources such as time, materials, and labor in a linear programming problem. They are expressed as linear inequalities."</data>
      <data key="d2">842c67915128905c66fae05fe8d55080</data>
      <data key="d7">11</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">619</data>
      <data key="d6">490583524d394bf79289c5fe34f7dcf1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRODUCTION CONSTRAINTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Production constraints" refer to limitations on the production capacity or capabilities in a linear programming problem. These constraints are typically expressed as linear inequalities. Specifically, the production constraints include:

- Build time: \(24x + 20y \leq 1,800,000\)
- Program time: \(16x + 14y \leq 1,680,000\)
- Test time: \(10x + 4y \leq 720,000\)

Additionally, there are non-negativity constraints, which require that \(x\) and \(y\) be greater than or equal to 0. There are also sales constraints, which limit \(x\) to a maximum of 85,000 units and \(y\) to a maximum of 66,000 units.</data>
      <data key="d2">026b22934152d61a6b625fae071b3bcd,842c67915128905c66fae05fe8d55080</data>
      <data key="d7">11</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">620</data>
      <data key="d6">d7db38bb599c42cab7066f3fdd282282</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LEVELS OF DEMAND&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Levels of demand refer to the required quantities of products or services that must be met in a linear programming problem. They are expressed as linear inequalities."</data>
      <data key="d2">842c67915128905c66fae05fe8d55080</data>
      <data key="d7">11</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">621</data>
      <data key="d6">efd87a59d01e47c8adc02f63ef2c5c3e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ISO-CONTRIBUTION LINES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Iso-contribution lines are lines on a graph where every point on each line gives the same contribution value. These lines are parallel to each other and help in identifying the optimal solution for maximizing contribution."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b</data>
      <data key="d7">11</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">622</data>
      <data key="d6">80e3ce3de41e4601823a333e22b7bb3f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPTIMAL SOLUTION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The optimal solution is the combination of production quantities that maximizes the contribution within the feasible region. It is found at the point where the highest iso-contribution line intersects the boundary of the feasible region."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b</data>
      <data key="d7">11</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">623</data>
      <data key="d6">50eabc166e8944a49197e79c32f27597</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONTRIBUTION LINE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">A contribution line in a linear programming graph represents the value of the objective function, such as contribution or profit, at different points. For Cut and Stitch, a sample contribution line passes through the point where W = 200 and L = 0, with a contribution value of $9,600. This line shows all combinations of variables that produce a specific value of contribution and is used to identify the optimal solution for maximizing contribution. The slope of the contribution line helps in identifying the point of maximum contribution within the feasible region, representing the total contribution for different combinations of products.</data>
      <data key="d2">64dc637d9fd89ad41762620a1229b806,853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,fb0f5765d523a19ec931f6834815662f</data>
      <data key="d7">11</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">624</data>
      <data key="d6">5197a3fb02ef4677abd1900aa87e4efa</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GRAPHICAL METHOD FOR OPTIMIZATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The graphical method for optimization involves plotting constraints on a graph, identifying the feasible region, and using iso-contribution lines to find the optimal solution that maximizes contribution."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b</data>
      <data key="d7">11</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">625</data>
      <data key="d6">887f444240bb474da23cdfb6abf7a998</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VARIABLES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Variables are the quantities that can be adjusted in an optimization problem to achieve the best outcome. They are the inputs to the objective function."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">626</data>
      <data key="d6">5d29053f2ce74442aa1855b327ef3bb7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DECISION VARIABLES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Decision variables are the variables that decision-makers will decide the values of in order to achieve the best outcome in an optimization problem."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">627</data>
      <data key="d6">7e40cd12839a4577a95e33d785147a31</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BOUNDARY CONSTRAINTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Boundary constraints are the specific limits within which the variables must operate. They form the edges of the feasible region."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">628</data>
      <data key="d6">8fe58de8a04f4f8f807c77fb41829a3a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CORNER POINT METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The corner point method is a technique used in linear programming to find the optimal solution by evaluating the objective function at each vertex of the feasible region."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">629</data>
      <data key="d6">a9f50861273c4bb697d868a9d049d392</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SLACK VARIABLES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Slack variables are added to linear programming constraints to convert inequalities into equalities. They represent unused resources."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">630</data>
      <data key="d6">be4820f29fd942b282049fa49697b4ed</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SURPLUS VARIABLES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Surplus variables are subtracted from linear programming constraints to convert inequalities into equalities. They represent excess resources."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">631</data>
      <data key="d6">6deaefe707f84b3dbda979dea0d095ac</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SIMPLEX METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The simplex method is an algorithm for solving linear programming problems by moving from one vertex of the feasible region to an adjacent vertex to find the optimal solution."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">632</data>
      <data key="d6">d053ea9432a24fb192e8d6aa993b0caa</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DUAL PROBLEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The dual problem in linear programming is derived from the primal problem and provides bounds on the optimal value of the primal problem."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">633</data>
      <data key="d6">a3e683d294ed42a28d60d09a36cbeb54</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sensitivity analysis in linear programming examines how the optimal solution changes as the parameters of the objective function or constraints are varied."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">634</data>
      <data key="d6">39887ca8567141d5b857b87a2bca4086</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NON-NEGATIVITY CONSTRAINTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Non-negativity constraints require that the decision variables in a linear programming problem be greater than or equal to zero."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">635</data>
      <data key="d6">8df8563ab0394ee9a91b89dea7d59404</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BINDING CONSTRAINTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Binding constraints are constraints that hold as equalities at the optimal solution. They limit the value of the objective function."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">636</data>
      <data key="d6">12398f70065143839d812fd42ac4b2e7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REDUNDANT CONSTRAINTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Redundant constraints are constraints that do not affect the feasible region. They do not change the optimal solution."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">637</data>
      <data key="d6">74d43d20f251441baf8e3db64fedca43</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;UNBOUNDED SOLUTION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"An unbounded solution in linear programming occurs when the objective function can increase indefinitely without violating any constraints."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">638</data>
      <data key="d6">1b7a22f76f7741e8b140bdc3d8856d76</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INFEASIBLE SOLUTION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"An infeasible solution in linear programming occurs when no set of values for the decision variables satisfies all the constraints."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">639</data>
      <data key="d6">b823ba1bfe944fa9887edd8faf8a5f17</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DEGENERACY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Degeneracy in linear programming occurs when more than one optimal solution exists, or when the feasible region has a vertex where more than two constraints intersect."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">640</data>
      <data key="d6">d0bfb473fdc64643954cdb4675e2f389</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ALTERNATIVE OPTIMA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Alternative optima occur when there is more than one optimal solution to a linear programming problem."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">641</data>
      <data key="d6">a4db1b2a9c3e4d2d838725f8166c36b4</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INTEGER PROGRAMMING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Integer programming is a type of linear programming where some or all of the decision variables are required to be integers."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">642</data>
      <data key="d6">8dae140578c841ae9373cbc607c4a6e6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MIXED-INTEGER PROGRAMMING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Mixed-integer programming is a type of linear programming where some decision variables are integers and others can be non-integers."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">643</data>
      <data key="d6">b215cc33cf40434f87f284ff8f3506a4</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BINARY VARIABLES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Binary variables are decision variables in integer programming that can only take on the value of 0 or 1."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">644</data>
      <data key="d6">c1ff9d8e1b8745d6860c34ce26122d79</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BRANCH AND BOUND&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Branch and bound is an algorithm for solving integer programming problems by dividing them into smaller subproblems and solving them recursively."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">645</data>
      <data key="d6">9d1e6ca9ae8e4e068fb74631a633b20b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CUTTING PLANE METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The cutting plane method is an algorithm for solving integer programming problems by adding linear constraints to exclude non-integer solutions."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">646</data>
      <data key="d6">1d7b0deca7674777bf76c163ac065845</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;HEURISTIC METHODS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Heuristic methods are problem-solving techniques that use practical approaches to find good-enough solutions when exact methods are too costly or time-consuming."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">647</data>
      <data key="d6">03afe9988f864c9fa501bfbf043f74c0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;METAHEURISTIC METHODS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Metaheuristic methods are higher-level procedures designed to find, generate, or select a heuristic that may provide a sufficiently good solution to an optimization problem."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">648</data>
      <data key="d6">4084f614af494fa8ab73095fb5b6b07b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GENETIC ALGORITHMS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Genetic algorithms are search heuristics that mimic the process of natural selection to generate high-quality solutions to optimization and search problems."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">649</data>
      <data key="d6">3ce25564af6e47f390a0b16b6f9433a1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SIMULATED ANNEALING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Simulated annealing is a probabilistic technique for approximating the global optimum of a given function. It is useful for large optimization problems."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">650</data>
      <data key="d6">78213664d0eb45d1a9239ba4b85b10f7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TABU SEARCH&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Tabu search is a metaheuristic search method that guides a local heuristic search procedure to explore the solution space beyond local optimality."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">651</data>
      <data key="d6">1226e4a4077b4b3a970db4d2509b590c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ANT COLONY OPTIMIZATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Ant colony optimization is a probabilistic technique for solving computational problems which can be reduced to finding good paths through graphs."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">652</data>
      <data key="d6">b4c7de7a824a4a71b9f52193d2f1a10d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PARTICLE SWARM OPTIMIZATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Particle swarm optimization is a computational method that optimizes a problem by iteratively trying to improve a candidate solution with regard to a given measure of quality."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">653</data>
      <data key="d6">b609f1939dae4c7383c7d199bb3c7dc3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONSTRAINT PROGRAMMING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Constraint programming is a paradigm for solving combinatorial problems that involves stating constraints that need to be satisfied and finding solutions that meet these constraints."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">654</data>
      <data key="d6">aeee2f443dfb4e3ea80af6ae1d9197ce</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FEASIBILITY STUDY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A feasibility study is an assessment of the practicality of a proposed plan or method. It evaluates the likelihood of the plan's success."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">655</data>
      <data key="d6">8c46d37bc26e4d4dbd37d6ee26867bc6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPTIMIZATION PROBLEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"An optimization problem is a mathematical problem that involves finding the best solution from a set of feasible solutions."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">656</data>
      <data key="d6">58a8fa7f29e347bdb9689b70b065a779</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LINEAR CONSTRAINTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Linear constraints are restrictions in a linear programming problem that are represented by linear equations or inequalities."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">657</data>
      <data key="d6">fae3fe31deb141ab93143ac411f1eaaa</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NONLINEAR PROGRAMMING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Nonlinear programming is a process of solving optimization problems where some of the constraints or the objective function are nonlinear."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">658</data>
      <data key="d6">a2cb46c226b94831853a5d28c5d94b0a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONVEX OPTIMIZATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Convex optimization is a subfield of optimization that studies the problem of minimizing convex functions over convex sets."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">659</data>
      <data key="d6">d3511ecd27cd4166bdb39e757e275300</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GLOBAL OPTIMIZATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Global optimization is the process of finding the best solution from all feasible solutions, not just local optima, in an optimization problem."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">660</data>
      <data key="d6">de3b561f5cce4c83bccb39180e362c97</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LOCAL OPTIMIZATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Local optimization is the process of finding the best solution in a neighborhood of the current solution in an optimization problem."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">661</data>
      <data key="d6">5bfefaa0fce04002851733337bed714c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MULTI-OBJECTIVE OPTIMIZATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Multi-objective optimization involves optimizing two or more conflicting objectives simultaneously in a mathematical model."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">662</data>
      <data key="d6">b5fed5609f154df58c6a9f74e55fc0ba</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PARETO EFFICIENCY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Pareto efficiency is a state where it is impossible to make any one individual better off without making at least one individual worse off. It is used in multi-objective optimization."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">663</data>
      <data key="d6">91ae5251eaab4c08afe6cd4cbefcaa6b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STOCHASTIC OPTIMIZATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Stochastic optimization involves optimization problems that include randomness. It is used when the objective function or constraints are uncertain."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">664</data>
      <data key="d6">bbdd53a15e99452a9deff05d1de2d965</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DETERMINISTIC OPTIMIZATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Deterministic optimization involves optimization problems with no randomness. The objective function and constraints are known with certainty."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">665</data>
      <data key="d6">532bf54d5a924ff48aee254970efb914</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DYNAMIC PROGRAMMING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Dynamic programming is a method for solving complex problems by breaking them down into simpler subproblems. It is applicable to optimization problems."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">666</data>
      <data key="d6">2489232bd2bb492babe00617e7290282</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NETWORK OPTIMIZATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Network optimization involves finding the optimal way to design and operate a network, such as a transportation or communication network."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">667</data>
      <data key="d6">d2ed972353af4d1db74702638bfdbb58</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SUPPLY CHAIN OPTIMIZATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Supply chain optimization involves improving the efficiency and effectiveness of a supply chain by optimizing the flow of goods, information, and finances."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">668</data>
      <data key="d6">575befc8d64c47eb95af8b1096e02963</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PORTFOLIO OPTIMIZATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Portfolio optimization involves selecting the best portfolio of assets to maximize return and minimize risk."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">669</data>
      <data key="d6">d6e6366617e04b0ba6732fd1d2d76429</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SCHEDULING OPTIMIZATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Scheduling optimization involves finding the best schedule for tasks or activities to achieve specific objectives, such as minimizing completion time or maximizing resource utilization."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">670</data>
      <data key="d6">b4c4354c8edb40db984942799fe0c8b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ROUTING OPTIMIZATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Routing optimization involves finding the best routes for vehicles or data packets to minimize travel time, distance, or cost."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">671</data>
      <data key="d6">170507a64973429f818067b80506d428</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRODUCTION PLANNING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Production planning involves determining the optimal production schedule to meet demand while minimizing costs and maximizing efficiency."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">672</data>
      <data key="d6">fd9b298e6aea4685bbb2064b05fcda79</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INVENTORY OPTIMIZATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Inventory optimization involves determining the optimal inventory levels to minimize costs while meeting demand and service level requirements."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">673</data>
      <data key="d6">eeecb159cc8a4c8989f8da0f3df09f2a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TRANSPORTATION PROBLEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The transportation problem is a type of optimization problem that involves finding the most efficient way to transport goods from multiple sources to multiple destinations."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">674</data>
      <data key="d6">70f22b1d7336492dbade94b8edefe457</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ASSIGNMENT PROBLEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The assignment problem is a type of optimization problem that involves finding the most efficient way to assign tasks to agents or resources to jobs."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">675</data>
      <data key="d6">66e098dc431146e19fc4bc2ea37efbd9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;KNAPSACK PROBLEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The knapsack problem is a type of optimization problem that involves selecting a subset of items with given weights and values to maximize the total value without exceeding a weight limit."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">676</data>
      <data key="d6">932e213c57134098a07073febd51dcc2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TRAVELING SALESMAN PROBLEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The traveling salesman problem is a type of optimization problem that involves finding the shortest possible route that visits a set of locations and returns to the starting point."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">677</data>
      <data key="d6">9593428ad36746ae8af6d8ce639834ef</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VEHICLE ROUTING PROBLEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The vehicle routing problem is a type of optimization problem that involves finding the most efficient routes for a fleet of vehicles to deliver goods to a set of locations."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">678</data>
      <data key="d6">1bcaeb58479d42a6963a073c09f3f397</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FACILITY LOCATION PROBLEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The facility location problem is a type of optimization problem that involves finding the best locations for facilities to minimize costs and maximize service levels."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">679</data>
      <data key="d6">1ef0c1c59ce946668ccf1a6a4f5ab7cc</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CUTTING STOCK PROBLEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The cutting stock problem is a type of optimization problem that involves cutting raw materials into smaller pieces to meet demand while minimizing waste."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">680</data>
      <data key="d6">d734746e3d6146f780af91827e578dfd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BIN PACKING PROBLEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The bin packing problem is a type of optimization problem that involves packing objects of different sizes into a finite number of bins in the most efficient way."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">681</data>
      <data key="d6">21ed913271614cbeb1b754cdbbef13af</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;JOB SHOP SCHEDULING PROBLEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The job shop scheduling problem is a type of optimization problem that involves scheduling jobs on machines to minimize completion time or maximize efficiency."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">682</data>
      <data key="d6">1505dfebbfb04652b0ba57de1a251d67</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FLOW SHOP SCHEDULING PROBLEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The flow shop scheduling problem is a type of optimization problem that involves scheduling jobs in a production process to minimize completion time or maximize efficiency."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">683</data>
      <data key="d6">907ec65076e5494a8631efffb81b3178</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PROJECT SCHEDULING PROBLEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The project scheduling problem is a type of optimization problem that involves scheduling project activities to meet deadlines and resource constraints."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">684</data>
      <data key="d6">2dc7f6b230db452190a09643ca3d5ec0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RESOURCE-CONSTRAINED PROJECT SCHEDULING PROBLEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The resource-constrained project scheduling problem is a type of optimization problem that involves scheduling project activities with limited resources to meet deadlines."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">685</data>
      <data key="d6">c20ecfc93b3a4875ade5c92cfe4b94a1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUADRATIC PROGRAMMING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Quadratic programming is a type of optimization problem where the objective function is quadratic and the constraints are linear."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">686</data>
      <data key="d6">4bc7dc91ede345dfb63d7d4f7ac3554f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONVEX PROGRAMMING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Convex programming is a type of optimization problem where the objective function is convex and the constraints form a convex set."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">687</data>
      <data key="d6">0b2b815c9f834aaaac0c341097def9ba</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NON-CONVEX OPTIMIZATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Non-convex optimization involves optimization problems where the objective function or constraints are non-convex, leading to multiple local optima."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">688</data>
      <data key="d6">424ae71c56024094a02e6fd9bfcfbb04</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ROBUST OPTIMIZATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Robust optimization involves finding solutions that remain effective under uncertainty and variability in the optimization problem's parameters."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">689</data>
      <data key="d6">400d10f2ee1d49be9a66efa34dada0e6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COMBINATORIAL OPTIMIZATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Combinatorial optimization involves finding the best solution from a finite set of possible solutions in problems with discrete variables."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">690</data>
      <data key="d6">91deb9f152264e958d106d481ff2e1ee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONSTRAINT SATISFACTION PROBLEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A constraint satisfaction problem is a type of problem where the goal is to find a solution that satisfies a set of constraints."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">691</data>
      <data key="d6">586cf02da9494088aed9b3419725638f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LINEAR OBJECTIVE FUNCTION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A linear objective function is an objective function in a linear programming problem that is a linear combination of the decision variables."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">692</data>
      <data key="d6">229d85a2783e4a2991f17d2ab5750af7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NONLINEAR OBJECTIVE FUNCTION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A nonlinear objective function is an objective function in an optimization problem that is a nonlinear combination of the decision variables."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">693</data>
      <data key="d6">b7f97d1909a3433abef8ca8e9334fafa</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FEASIBLE SOLUTION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A feasible solution is a set of values for the decision variables that satisfies all the constraints in an optimization problem."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">694</data>
      <data key="d6">b7fdfffc38b94bf7872eabe9b022c8fd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPTIMAL VALUE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The optimal value is the best value of the objective function that can be achieved in an optimization problem."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">695</data>
      <data key="d6">6242e0c237a348908d0256ea790a0211</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OBJECTIVE SPACE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The objective space is the space defined by the objective functions in a multi-objective optimization problem."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">696</data>
      <data key="d6">7cc9f26737e1442595e53253e98015ef</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DECISION SPACE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The decision space is the space defined by the decision variables in an optimization problem."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">697</data>
      <data key="d6">1868fec1493643208dbdcad7bc97dfa0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PARETO FRONT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Pareto front is the set of all Pareto efficient solutions in a multi-objective optimization problem."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">698</data>
      <data key="d6">a87aa935dccf49cd98b40fb5afe7ad5c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MULTI-CRITERIA DECISION ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Multi-criteria decision analysis involves evaluating and comparing multiple conflicting criteria to make decisions in complex problems."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">699</data>
      <data key="d6">36870a3393f6413e9bf647168eb6977a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GOAL PROGRAMMING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Goal programming is a type of multi-objective optimization that involves finding solutions that satisfy multiple goals to the greatest extent possible."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">700</data>
      <data key="d6">4fe3ff52700c491f8cc650aadb4d7cb0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LEXICOGRAPHIC OPTIMIZATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Lexicographic optimization involves optimizing multiple objectives in a pre-specified order of importance."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">701</data>
      <data key="d6">f1f6f6435a444e388d67e16e847afca6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EPSILON-CONSTRAINT METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The epsilon-constraint method is a technique for solving multi-objective optimization problems by converting them into single-objective problems with constraints on the other objectives."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">702</data>
      <data key="d6">0af2ca1c090843ea92679fd14c1fbc9a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;WEIGHTED SUM METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The weighted sum method is a technique for solving multi-objective optimization problems by combining the objectives into a single objective using weighted sums."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">703</data>
      <data key="d6">1b06d3e53ffd4771952fbef04d1e666c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INTERACTIVE METHODS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Interactive methods involve the decision-maker in the optimization process to iteratively find the most preferred solution in multi-objective optimization problems."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">704</data>
      <data key="d6">b8e966b34cba4b11b9995106767212ba</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EVOLUTIONARY ALGORITHMS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Evolutionary algorithms are a class of optimization algorithms inspired by natural evolution, including genetic algorithms, genetic programming, and evolution strategies."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">705</data>
      <data key="d6">f6de923de6474d2cab6a9c2f0d81fa59</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MEMETIC ALGORITHMS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Memetic algorithms are a class of optimization algorithms that combine evolutionary algorithms with local search techniques."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">706</data>
      <data key="d6">6915637e8d124fdc8473111d501e3703</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;HYBRID OPTIMIZATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Hybrid optimization involves combining different optimization techniques to leverage their strengths and overcome their weaknesses."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">707</data>
      <data key="d6">2233f31929194eac89333ce8731a5584</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SWARM INTELLIGENCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Swarm intelligence involves using the collective behavior of decentralized, self-organized systems, such as ant colonies or bird flocks, to solve optimization problems."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">708</data>
      <data key="d6">61f1dc4267314470ac820b6a46c61f7b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ARTIFICIAL NEURAL NETWORKS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Artificial neural networks are computational models inspired by the human brain that are used for pattern recognition, classification, and optimization."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">709</data>
      <data key="d6">f0c578614b224345974c3e4c110878af</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REINFORCEMENT LEARNING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Reinforcement learning is a type of machine learning where an agent learns to make decisions by taking actions in an environment to maximize cumulative reward."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">710</data>
      <data key="d6">7ffb88ebc729492c897ccfb569d7f6d0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARKOV DECISION PROCESSES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Markov decision processes are mathematical models for decision-making in situations where outcomes are partly random and partly under the control of a decision-maker."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">711</data>
      <data key="d6">60dce7d8bc1b4729a038178a400b9a59</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BAYESIAN OPTIMIZATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Bayesian optimization is a strategy for optimizing expensive-to-evaluate functions by building a probabilistic model and using it to select the most promising solutions."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">712</data>
      <data key="d6">4cbb4e238c5b4656803fb9b4b6c3512e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GRADIENT DESCENT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Gradient descent is an optimization algorithm that iteratively adjusts the variables in the direction of the negative gradient of the objective function to find the minimum."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">713</data>
      <data key="d6">652873bcd6d5432187e5deafc4fc5211</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STOCHASTIC GRADIENT DESCENT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Stochastic gradient descent is a variant of gradient descent that uses a randomly selected subset of data to compute the gradient, making it more efficient for large datasets."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">714</data>
      <data key="d6">78f9b30c08134ac5abb4f4e0bff0f7f2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONJUGATE GRADIENT METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The conjugate gradient method is an optimization algorithm for solving large systems of linear equations and large-scale optimization problems."</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">715</data>
      <data key="d6">f33e4e897b1e422bb516e8a2c941d9dc</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NEWTON'S METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Newton's</data>
      <data key="d2">853d45efddaa3a59672a25aa124ddf0b,8f4de102f0f6dd238b08498336b2ce30,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">716</data>
      <data key="d6">fac4e1553a9840e990bbfff46e64ff27</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LINEAR PROGRAMMING QUIZ&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Linear Programming Quiz involves a problem where a manufacturer produces two types of garden furniture and needs to determine the optimal production plan to maximize contribution each week, given constraints on materials and labor."</data>
      <data key="d2">fb0f5765d523a19ec931f6834815662f</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">717</data>
      <data key="d6">029a55d327ee4fb3a8314b36d52bdf34</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LINEAR PROGRAMMING MODEL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Linear Programming Model for the given problem is: Objective function to maximize contribution (C) = 35x + 10y, subject to constraints: 3x + 2y &#8804; 120 (Materials), 5x + 2y &#8804; 140 (Skilled labor), 4x + y &#8804; 100 (Unskilled labor), and x, y &#8805; 0 (Non-negative)."</data>
      <data key="d2">fb0f5765d523a19ec931f6834815662f</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">718</data>
      <data key="d6">5a636c894c384532bff66212cf9d5824</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ASSUMPTIONS OF GRAPHICAL METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The assumptions of the graphical method include linearity, infinite divisibility of products and resources, dependency on the quality of input data, and the consideration of only one quantifiable objective."</data>
      <data key="d2">fb0f5765d523a19ec931f6834815662f</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">719</data>
      <data key="d6">a9c468ef78704e9aabfc0317a5b1b42d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SLACK&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Slack is the difference between maximum resources available and resources used at the optimal point in linear programming problems. For binding constraints, the value of slack is zero."</data>
      <data key="d2">a45353a0c40dc9060f109521e6aadaa7</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">720</data>
      <data key="d6">5df80c25d33a4d148a14aa614343cc6b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NON-BINDING AND BINDING CONSTRAINTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"In linear programming, non-binding constraints are those where not all of the available supply of one or more inputs is used at the optimal point, while binding constraints are fully utilized."</data>
      <data key="d2">a45353a0c40dc9060f109521e6aadaa7</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">721</data>
      <data key="d6">6a87f06ed55a46f29b24f77e548a3f1d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;IMPLICATIONS OF SLACK&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Knowing the amount of slack is useful for planning additional supplies of resources or utilizing excess resources elsewhere in the business."</data>
      <data key="d2">a45353a0c40dc9060f109521e6aadaa7</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">722</data>
      <data key="d6">0daf88ac4ec94cbb868e27e956c6d7f1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MORE THAN TWO VARIABLES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Linear programming can be formulated for any number of variables and constraints, but graphical methods are limited to two variables. Methods for more than two variables include the dual problem and simplex."</data>
      <data key="d2">a45353a0c40dc9060f109521e6aadaa7</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">723</data>
      <data key="d6">9ed120043e6247be9965e4904920991b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LINEAR PROGRAMMING SUMMARY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Summary of linear programming steps: define variables, define the objective function, formulate constraints, plot constraints, identify the feasible area, find the optimal point, and calculate maximum profit."</data>
      <data key="d2">a45353a0c40dc9060f109521e6aadaa7</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">724</data>
      <data key="d6">94d81d7de9254ae4b3b16fcc69aa22ea</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRICING DECISIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Pricing decisions involve factors influencing product pricing, price elasticity of demand, demand equations, optimum selling price, and various pricing strategies."</data>
      <data key="d2">a45353a0c40dc9060f109521e6aadaa7</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">725</data>
      <data key="d6">60c9212246f84ae5b6ab254127a39262</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FULL COST PLUS PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Full cost plus pricing" is a long-term pricing strategy that ensures prices cover all variable and fixed costs. The price of a product using full cost plus pricing is calculated by adding a markup to the full cost per unit.</data>
      <data key="d2">35cfdb511a04dc63dee7570f6be9f000,a45353a0c40dc9060f109521e6aadaa7,bfcf79d5de016af045c8328487a8850c,e63689f85598b937bf7c871cd9494956</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">726</data>
      <data key="d6">0f8d0c36a4274526a9eddedae5e63881</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FULL COST PLUS PRICING FORMULA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Selling price per unit = (Total budgeted production cost + Total budgeted non-production cost + Mark-up) / Budgeted sales units"</data>
      <data key="d2">e63689f85598b937bf7c871cd9494956</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">727</data>
      <data key="d6">6aedd377efbe4f07ae42e546996e7bfa</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ADVANTAGES OF FULL COST PLUS PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Advantages of full cost plus pricing include: profit will be made if the budget sales level is achieved, the full cost should be readily available if a system of standard costing is in operation, it is appropriate where fixed costs are significant, useful for justifying prices and price rises, and it is simple and cheap to operate."</data>
      <data key="d2">e63689f85598b937bf7c871cd9494956</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">728</data>
      <data key="d6">1aa8484562784f378851c33843c89687</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DISADVANTAGES OF FULL COST PLUS PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Disadvantages of full cost plus pricing include: the method of accounting for overheads will have a large impact on the costs calculated for different products, losses may occur if actual sales are below budget, it ignores external factors like demand/price relationship and competitors' prices, the size of the mark-up is arbitrary, and it may not maximize profits."</data>
      <data key="d2">e63689f85598b937bf7c871cd9494956</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">729</data>
      <data key="d6">f1a65d05dd5d456b889217020475ef80</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARGINAL COST PLUS PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Marginal cost plus pricing is a short-term pricing strategy that involves calculating the selling price per unit by adding a mark-up percentage to the budgeted variable production and non-production costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">e63689f85598b937bf7c871cd9494956</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">730</data>
      <data key="d6">c077d92b48b6477db91e1a0460600f52</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARGINAL COST PLUS PRICING FORMULA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Selling price per unit = (Budgeted Variable production cost + Budgeted Variable non-production cost + Mark-up) / Budgeted sales units"</data>
      <data key="d2">e63689f85598b937bf7c871cd9494956</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">731</data>
      <data key="d6">5ca888df9b884e54accdd2ff29d125c1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ADVANTAGES OF MARGINAL COST PLUS PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Advantages of marginal cost plus pricing include: the mark-up represents contribution, which is useful in short-term pricing decisions like market penetration policy, and it treats fixed costs by their nature and not using an arbitrary allocation."</data>
      <data key="d2">e63689f85598b937bf7c871cd9494956</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">732</data>
      <data key="d6">8290a6212d6c4430ae0056c7e8eccd5f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DISADVANTAGES OF MARGINAL COST PLUS PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Disadvantages of marginal cost plus pricing include: it may lead to failure to recover fixed costs, and it is not appropriate for long-term pricing, particularly where fixed costs are significant, because in the long-term, fixed costs may also vary and not be sufficiently covered by mark-up."</data>
      <data key="d2">e63689f85598b937bf7c871cd9494956</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">733</data>
      <data key="d6">14f8ac195fdb4e06a0b9ebc6ef391180</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RETURN ON INVESTMENT (ROI) PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"ROI pricing is a long-term pricing method where prices are set to achieve a target percentage return on the capital invested in production."</data>
      <data key="d2">e63689f85598b937bf7c871cd9494956</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">734</data>
      <data key="d6">667ee58a79194316ae2b82eadd3fc575</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ROI PRICING FORMULA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Selling price per unit = Budgeted full cost + (target ROI percentage x capital employed) / Budgeted sales units"</data>
      <data key="d2">e63689f85598b937bf7c871cd9494956</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">735</data>
      <data key="d6">b0e3ee2324054c88adacdf80db13278f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ADVANTAGES OF ROI PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Advantages of ROI pricing include: it links price to both short-term costs and long-term capital employed, it is consistent with ROI as a performance measure, and the target ROI can be set to take account of risk."</data>
      <data key="d2">e63689f85598b937bf7c871cd9494956</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">736</data>
      <data key="d6">28b7457ca5dc4a38a488946a3f8e207e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DISADVANTAGES OF ROI PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Disadvantages of ROI pricing include: it ignores external factors, there are problems in calculating capital employed (e.g., whether to use book values or replacement cost), and there is a subjective split of shared investment between products."</data>
      <data key="d2">e63689f85598b937bf7c871cd9494956</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">737</data>
      <data key="d6">8029a14d15404e6db95ddf5e2bf9fc15</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: COST PLUS AND TARGET ROI&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves calculating the selling price of a new product using different pricing strategies: full cost plus 20%, marginal cost plus 40%, and target ROI of 10%. It also includes a question on calculating profit if actual sales are below budget."</data>
      <data key="d2">e63689f85598b937bf7c871cd9494956</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">738</data>
      <data key="d6">389314ca89d445888c8d4985864dd733</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RELEVANT COST PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Relevant cost pricing" involves setting prices based on the costs that will be incurred if a specific order is fulfilled, focusing on future incremental costs. This pricing strategy is often used for one-off projects, special orders, and tenders for contracts. It involves using existing resources and a relevant costing approach, where the price is calculated as the sum of relevant costs plus a mark-up. Additionally, relevant cost pricing, also known as opportunity cost pricing, is employed to set a minimum acceptable price to discourage new entrants and meet specific strategic goals. This approach is typically a short-term strategy aimed at pricing individual contracts or orders effectively.</data>
      <data key="d2">33d735a6b75645248eabb5d1c5835d61,45374dd90ff15ce3c8e2a87bc484b028,bceecc7fff5018cf612741035c7415d8,c0117b1a829ee89c41385c27964ebda4</data>
      <data key="d7">18</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">739</data>
      <data key="d6">87fe1462b9064d5692641ab48e826301</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: OPPORTUNITY COST PRICE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves calculating the price Bobco Engineering should bid for a one-off contract, ensuring the costing is competitive and commercially rational. It includes various cost components such as standard steel, specialty steel, unskilled labor, semi-skilled labor, skilled labor, use of equipment, and exclusive use of a piece of manufacturing equipment."</data>
      <data key="d2">c0117b1a829ee89c41385c27964ebda4</data>
      <data key="d7">18</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">740</data>
      <data key="d6">a55175ac57014df696ca09d0def9604b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LIFECYCLE COST PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Lifecycle cost pricing considers all costs over a product's life, including design, manufacture, production, and closedown costs, ensuring that total revenue covers these expenses."</data>
      <data key="d2">a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">741</data>
      <data key="d6">1766e8858d7b45ed97f71cb5a39e96ea</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LIMITATIONS OF COST-BASED APPROACHES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The limitations of cost-based approaches include ignoring external factors like demand and competition, not maximizing profit, revenue, or market share due to subjective mark-ups, potentially resulting in prices different from competitors, and underestimating product features that could justify higher prices."</data>
      <data key="d2">a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">742</data>
      <data key="d6">6191e014f3f64e46a0777063ed4ac19a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DEMAND CURVE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The demand curve represents the total quantity of a product or service that buyers in a market would wish to buy at different prices over a given period. It typically shows that as the price falls, demand rises."</data>
      <data key="d2">a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">743</data>
      <data key="d6">21b0499cf14342269c46170c291d0535</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DEMAND CURVE EQUATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The demand curve equation is P = a - bQ, where P is the price, Q is the quantity demanded, a is the price when Q = 0, and b is the slope of the line indicating the change in price needed to achieve a given change in demand."</data>
      <data key="d2">a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">744</data>
      <data key="d6">c1ef05b38b3f4d59888150fc0dd26826</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF DEMAND&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Alex's bakery example demonstrates the demand curve equation. If the price of a doughnut is $5.00, demand is zero. For every 50 cents decrease in price, demand increases by 20 units. The demand equation is P = 500 - 2.5Q."</data>
      <data key="d2">a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">745</data>
      <data key="d6">74cb9b3510e84498b9aee0d904316e8b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARGINAL REVENUE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Marginal revenue is the increase in total revenue from selling one additional unit of a product or service. It considers both the additional revenue generated from the extra unit sold and the potential reduction in total revenue due to the price decrease for all units sold.</data>
      <data key="d2">35cfdb511a04dc63dee7570f6be9f000,a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d7">24</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">746</data>
      <data key="d6">043d764b2e1b4d1294651ff938df5391</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARGINAL REVENUE EQUATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The marginal revenue equation is derived from the demand function and is represented as MR = a - 2bQ. In this equation, MR stands for marginal revenue, a is the intercept, and b is the slope. The constants a and b are derived from the demand equation.</data>
      <data key="d2">a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38,e9af4ee0f71d2417558dad6417e70848</data>
      <data key="d7">24</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">747</data>
      <data key="d6">31f2170fef004f3281c533a4a60dc3f3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: MARGINAL REVENUE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves plotting the demand function on a graph, finding its equation, determining the total revenue function, and deriving the marginal revenue function. It helps illustrate the relationship between price, quantity, total revenue, and marginal revenue."</data>
      <data key="d2">a8e02bf8056e93a035c9327f23da7d38</data>
      <data key="d7">24</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">748</data>
      <data key="d6">57f186c5c2754483ba66750e98222f95</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DEMAND FUNCTION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The demand function for air conditioning units is represented as P = 750 - 0.015Q, where P is the price and Q is the quantity. This demand function follows the general form P = a - bQ, where P is the price, Q is the quantity, a is the intercept (750 in this case), and b is the slope (0.015 in this case).</data>
      <data key="d2">10a6cfb7beb226418463ca4749be7451,e9af4ee0f71d2417558dad6417e70848</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">749</data>
      <data key="d6">4b3fc569d91f4a7aa6501ad4fcf67b7a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARGINAL COST FUNCTION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The marginal cost function is typically represented as MC = x, where MC is the marginal cost and x is a constant value."</data>
      <data key="d2">e9af4ee0f71d2417558dad6417e70848</data>
      <data key="d7">24</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">750</data>
      <data key="d6">cbc1667556f84a5eadf867a823e6986c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TABULAR APPROACH&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The tabular approach is an alternative method to identify the profit maximising point of output by calculating marginal revenue and marginal cost for each set of data when the relationship between price and demand is not linear or there is insufficient data to calculate a price equation accurately."</data>
      <data key="d2">e9af4ee0f71d2417558dad6417e70848</data>
      <data key="d7">24</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">751</data>
      <data key="d6">a876d1ab79864396bc47a039225fd5c7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: TABULAR METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves using a tabular approach to calculate marginal revenue and marginal cost at each price and output level for a baker's new type of cake, and determining the price and quantity that maximise profit."</data>
      <data key="d2">e9af4ee0f71d2417558dad6417e70848</data>
      <data key="d7">24</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">752</data>
      <data key="d6">c09f67d4f25448c99f7c0552c30b7706</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PROFIT MAXIMISING OUTPUT AND PRICE IDENTIFICATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">e9af4ee0f71d2417558dad6417e70848</data>
      <data key="d7">24</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">753</data>
      <data key="d6">c0866306dc8c4da2a8a81c0c3a78b657</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ECONOMIST'S MODEL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The economist's model is a theoretical framework used to estimate demand curves and determine optimal pricing strategies. It assumes that demand for products is independent and ignores exogenous variables."</data>
      <data key="d2">79e44403e70b46e0f04809babf4aeaa1</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">754</data>
      <data key="d6">3884c37eb13a4c9097ee2c5be4eeefaf</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRACTICAL DISADVANTAGES OF THE ECONOMIST'S MODEL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The practical disadvantages of the economist's model include difficulty in estimating demand curves accurately, ignoring exogenous variables, interrelated demand for products, and the existence of alternative company strategies."</data>
      <data key="d2">79e44403e70b46e0f04809babf4aeaa1</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">755</data>
      <data key="d6">90764eb2cab74cffb1c7d72d28b965cc</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRODUCTION AND SALES LEVELS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Production and sales levels refer to the quantity of goods produced and sold by a company. Decisions to increase these levels should consider relevant costs, marginal revenue, and marginal cost, as well as other factors like storage space, selling price, and product quality."</data>
      <data key="d2">79e44403e70b46e0f04809babf4aeaa1</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">756</data>
      <data key="d6">01abe16e67c241a887aa62abe22d155c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARKET SKIMMING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Market skimming" is a pricing strategy where an initially high price is set to maximize revenue from customers willing to pay more for the latest technology or unique products. This approach is particularly suitable for products with high development costs, short life cycles, and significant barriers to entry, which can deter competitors. The high initial price helps to 'skim' segments of the market willing to pay a premium before gradually lowering the price to attract more price-sensitive customers. This strategy is often used for breakthrough products or those that confer status. However, it is not suitable for objectives such as discouraging new entrants and shortening the initial period of the product life cycle, as in the case of Skulpt Co.</data>
      <data key="d2">0279d26139c7d66d51896f7ebfe162ee,45374dd90ff15ce3c8e2a87bc484b028,79e44403e70b46e0f04809babf4aeaa1,a9f233b9fbfc7657e915ecc09cb7519c</data>
      <data key="d7">19</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">757</data>
      <data key="d6">37049be0a2c240c6a06acf9339237b8b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLES OF BREAKTHROUGH PRODUCTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Examples of breakthrough products include the car, penicillin, laptop computer, Windows operating system, ATM, and iPad. Breakthrough services include the Internet and online shopping."</data>
      <data key="d2">79e44403e70b46e0f04809babf4aeaa1</data>
      <data key="d7">19</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">758</data>
      <data key="d6">e785c52881704d95bf4ec03d2720f8ae</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARKET PENETRATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Market penetration is a pricing strategy where a low price is set initially to attract new customers, often leading to short-term losses. The price is increased once a customer base is established. It is used for commodity-type products, price-sensitive products, and products with economies of scale."</data>
      <data key="d2">79e44403e70b46e0f04809babf4aeaa1</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">759</data>
      <data key="d6">654689c65613476b9905d7afb3809cd2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COMPLEMENTARY PRODUCT PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">Complementary product pricing involves setting prices for products that are used together, such as printers and ink cartridges. The price of one product may be set low to drive demand for the complementary product, which is priced higher. However, this strategy is not suitable for Skulpt Co's objectives.</data>
      <data key="d2">45374dd90ff15ce3c8e2a87bc484b028,79e44403e70b46e0f04809babf4aeaa1</data>
      <data key="d7">19</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">760</data>
      <data key="d6">15dfb45a6ffa4d34ad72cfe4b3c5cc0d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF COMPLEMENTARY PRODUCTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"An example of complementary products is printers and print cartridges. Printers are often sold at a low price, while the cartridges are sold at a high price to maximize profit margins."</data>
      <data key="d2">79e44403e70b46e0f04809babf4aeaa1</data>
      <data key="d7">19</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">761</data>
      <data key="d6">427c3b7458f148d8bace1b768e2b5b7c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRICE DISCRIMINATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Price discrimination involves setting different prices for a product or service in different markets to achieve the maximum price in each market. Barriers between markets are necessary to prevent reselling."</data>
      <data key="d2">79e44403e70b46e0f04809babf4aeaa1</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">762</data>
      <data key="d6">95d506750fd94e72bbd9cf2d3fe18e28</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLES OF PRICE DISCRIMINATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Examples of price discrimination include: selling a product for unique moments in time (e.g., airline tickets for a specific flight that cannot be resold), unique locations (e.g., return airline or train tickets priced differently based on the starting location), offering heavy discounts for educational users, and charging different tariffs and service charges for commercial and residential customers."</data>
      <data key="d2">bceecc7fff5018cf612741035c7415d8</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">763</data>
      <data key="d6">bf0138ccbcc740089a55fd0c24897360</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LOSS LEADERS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A loss leader is a product that is sold at a loss to attract customers who will then buy other products. Loss leaders are common in supermarket promotions, where products are advertised at very low, loss-making prices. The supermarkets know that once customers have entered the store to buy the promotional product, they are likely to also buy other goods."</data>
      <data key="d2">bceecc7fff5018cf612741035c7415d8</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">764</data>
      <data key="d6">83cd5df42643494396b00d6cb6376def</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GOING-RATE PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Going-rate pricing means charging the prevailing market price. This approach might be used in competitive markets where charging above market price would lead to a loss of the majority of customers and selling below market price would not bring additional customers. Going-rate pricing is common for homogeneous products that have minimum variation, such as commodities like aluminium or diesel."</data>
      <data key="d2">bceecc7fff5018cf612741035c7415d8</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">765</data>
      <data key="d6">909d28e443fd4e0bac189373125c8309</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRODUCT-LINE PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Product-line pricing involves setting the price of products in a product line together. There are two prevalent approaches: product bundling (selling a group of products together for a price that is less than the total of the individual products) and setting differentials between different products in a range (e.g., a basic car with a small engine priced differently from a larger engine version)."</data>
      <data key="d2">bceecc7fff5018cf612741035c7415d8</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">766</data>
      <data key="d6">efbc2439e5034801af83ac1a0b440535</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VOLUME DISCOUNTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Volume discounting involves offering discounts to customers who buy a certain number of products. This strategy is used to offer a more competitive price overall and to acknowledge the law of diminishing marginal utility, encouraging consumers to buy additional units even though the satisfaction derived from them declines."</data>
      <data key="d2">bceecc7fff5018cf612741035c7415d8</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">767</data>
      <data key="d6">b9a2ef791a064f038cac2059ebea1138</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LEVEL OF DEMAND&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Demand is the quantity of a good or service which consumers want, and are willing and able to pay for. The level of demand influences pricing; the higher the demand, the higher the price that can be charged. Demand is influenced by factors such as income, price of substitute goods, price of complementary goods, consumer tastes and fashion, advertising, and consumer views and capacity to pay."</data>
      <data key="d2">bceecc7fff5018cf612741035c7415d8</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">768</data>
      <data key="d6">1ce2b24bc93442148dc2240d3c6223b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRICE ELASTICITY OF DEMAND (PED)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The price elasticity of demand (PED) is the degree of sensitivity of demand for a good to changes in the price of that good. It is calculated using the formula PED = % change in demand / % change in price. Generally, PED will be negative since a rise in price typically leads to a fall in demand, but the minus sign is conventionally ignored.</data>
      <data key="d2">bceecc7fff5018cf612741035c7415d8,c1d1a5691f5cfea1fd89ecd71a3421ce</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">769</data>
      <data key="d6">804c1e94e7974332a817931363ddb643</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ELASTIC DEMAND&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Elastic demand means that demand is very responsive to changes in price. The change in the quantity of goods demanded will be relatively greater (i.e., in percentage terms) than the change in price. The PED will be greater than one."</data>
      <data key="d2">c1d1a5691f5cfea1fd89ecd71a3421ce</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">770</data>
      <data key="d6">32dc0b572ad84c75a64a2007788eb981</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INELASTIC DEMAND&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Inelastic demand means that a change in price will have little impact on demand. Demand will change by a relatively small amount (i.e., in percentage terms) than the change in price. The PED will be less than one."</data>
      <data key="d2">c1d1a5691f5cfea1fd89ecd71a3421ce</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">771</data>
      <data key="d6">f5c11a5ac94e40068bca8be178a6bcd6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: PRICE ELASTICITY OF DEMAND&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves calculating the price elasticity of demand based on changes in price for a baker's doughnuts. It includes scenarios where the current price per doughnut is $4 and $2, requiring the calculation of elasticity and interpretation of results."</data>
      <data key="d2">c1d1a5691f5cfea1fd89ecd71a3421ce</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">772</data>
      <data key="d6">ea28ff7f127e4677a913952595dce2f5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COMPETITORS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Competitors are other businesses offering similar products or services in the market. The presence of competitors can influence a company's pricing strategy and market power."</data>
      <data key="d2">c1d1a5691f5cfea1fd89ecd71a3421ce</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">773</data>
      <data key="d6">192a6d23595045f38b0d46a3d8e52fd6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CUSTOMERS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Customers are the buyers of a company's products or services. The relationship with customers, including dominant customers and bulk buying, can affect pricing strategies."</data>
      <data key="d2">c1d1a5691f5cfea1fd89ecd71a3421ce</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">774</data>
      <data key="d6">ef67c9fc60284b50aa15ac655b06a155</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PERFECT COMPETITION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Perfect competition is a theoretical market structure characterized by many sellers and buyers, identical or homogeneous products, and no barriers to entry. In this market, there is perfect information available to all participants, meaning that all buyers and sellers have full knowledge of prices and products. The sale and purchase of goods occur at the market clearing (or equilibrium) price, where supply and demand are equal, ensuring there is no excess or shortage. Market participants in perfect competition are 'price takers,' meaning they must accept the market price and cannot influence it.</data>
      <data key="d2">35cfdb511a04dc63dee7570f6be9f000,c1d1a5691f5cfea1fd89ecd71a3421ce</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">775</data>
      <data key="d6">cc8201cce1024b5192056fe8e98fda22</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COST PLUS PRICING METHODS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Cost plus pricing methods involve adding a given margin to the cost of a product. The cost may be the marginal cost, the full cost, or even the relevant cost."</data>
      <data key="d2">35cfdb511a04dc63dee7570f6be9f000</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">776</data>
      <data key="d6">97e097f9022540b88ab7c13d2805c25f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPPORTUNITY COST PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Opportunity cost (relevant cost) pricing is suitable for short-term pricing decisions."</data>
      <data key="d2">35cfdb511a04dc63dee7570f6be9f000</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">777</data>
      <data key="d6">829a6299a5fa4e7b8ff4020020a0be05</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARGINAL COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Marginal cost" refers to the cost of producing one additional unit of a product. It is equal to the variable cost per unit, at least until full capacity is reached. In the context of Division M, the marginal cost is $740.</data>
      <data key="d2">34f2c5c9d893c1b631ed1646193eebf4,35cfdb511a04dc63dee7570f6be9f000</data>
      <data key="d7">24</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">778</data>
      <data key="d6">dde2742459c24fb4a91172aa5c1a7620</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRICE ELASTICITY OF DEMAND&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Price elasticity of demand (PED) measures the responsiveness of the quantity demanded of a good to a change in its price. It is calculated as the percentage change in quantity demanded divided by the percentage change in price. If demand is price elastic, a decrease in price will lead to an increase in revenue. A value greater than 1 indicates elastic demand, meaning demand is sensitive to price changes. In essence, PED is a measure of the degree of sensitivity of demand for a good to changes in the price of that good.</data>
      <data key="d2">0279d26139c7d66d51896f7ebfe162ee,238ba7ae5def49a914d13c1bcf1e1332,33d735a6b75645248eabb5d1c5835d61,35cfdb511a04dc63dee7570f6be9f000,952e2d04d2cd9b755ccdb34c8be68396,bfcf79d5de016af045c8328487a8850c</data>
      <data key="d7">19</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">779</data>
      <data key="d6">323979a67d79498fa271acdf8cd1a0c2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RISK&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Risk is the existence of several possible outcomes, which are known in advance along with the related probability."</data>
      <data key="d2">35cfdb511a04dc63dee7570f6be9f000</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">780</data>
      <data key="d6">c7e8b188b45841a0a1bcb22f3445ea6e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;UNCERTAINTY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Uncertainty refers to the potential outcomes of a decision that are not known in advance."</data>
      <data key="d2">35cfdb511a04dc63dee7570f6be9f000</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">781</data>
      <data key="d6">5a4ad077106a4a3f951f43d2e01499b0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXPECTED VALUE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Expected value (EV) = Weighted arithmetic mean of possible outcomes = &#931; (xi p(xi)). This formula represents the sum (&#931;) of each possible outcome (Xi) multiplied by its probability of occurring (p(xi))."</data>
      <data key="d2">35cfdb511a04dc63dee7570f6be9f000</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">782</data>
      <data key="d6">a7ec8df038d7461689d28f1bdea84d9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF EXPECTED VALUE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"When an unbiased six-sided die is thrown, each side has an equal chance (1/6) of being obtained. The expected value of throwing a dice many times is calculated as: EV = 21/6 or 3.5. This means that if the dice is thrown many times, the average value of the throws would be 3.5."</data>
      <data key="d2">35cfdb511a04dc63dee7570f6be9f000</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">783</data>
      <data key="d6">8ddefa32e2ed4eaf8f76d17a676f74f3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: EXPECTED VALUE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A decision-maker must select one of three mutually exclusive projects. The outcome from each project depends on the state of the market, which can be diminishing, static, or expanding. The profit for each project under each of the three outcomes is shown in a payoff table. The decision rule is to choose the project with the highest EV."</data>
      <data key="d2">66accb1b51ba74b0372b89d8b1038268</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">784</data>
      <data key="d6">95ec30ce8dbe4ca28714e3e3735da8f3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ADVANTAGES OF EV&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Advantages of EV include reducing information to one number for each choice and the idea of an average being easily understood."</data>
      <data key="d2">66accb1b51ba74b0372b89d8b1038268</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">785</data>
      <data key="d6">259e7f5e2ec04418937513413b6d51d1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LIMITATIONS OF EV&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Limitations of EV include difficulties in estimating probabilities, the average may not correspond to any possible outcomes, it is unsuitable for one-off decisions, and it ignores the spread of possible results (risk)."</data>
      <data key="d2">66accb1b51ba74b0372b89d8b1038268</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">786</data>
      <data key="d6">2289f06dd3804a3c84371dda0bab091e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PROFIT TABLES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A profit table, also known as a payoff matrix, shows all possible payoffs (NPVs, contribution, profits, etc.) resulting from a decision-maker's chosen strategy."</data>
      <data key="d2">66accb1b51ba74b0372b89d8b1038268</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">787</data>
      <data key="d6">34ff8ef897804691842071f9ff78708e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: PROFIT TABLE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A baker sells a cake that costs $0.10 to make for $0.30 each. At the end of a day, any unsold cakes must be thrown away. The level of demand follows a probability distribution. The quiz requires constructing a profit table to show possible outcomes and calculating the daily order to maximize expected daily profits."</data>
      <data key="d2">66accb1b51ba74b0372b89d8b1038268</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">788</data>
      <data key="d6">a7401447d994439993da7cc57f127649</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXPECTED VALUE (EV)&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">039a2a6ce8c94f49aa8954c72332cea2,66accb1b51ba74b0372b89d8b1038268</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">789</data>
      <data key="d6">754b0f2616064b18abb90f409ef0539a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CHANCE FORK&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A chance fork occurs where there are several possible outcomes. Normally, for each decision taken, there will be two or more possible outcomes."</data>
      <data key="d2">e5de3d497edf33e49e77c7a76b7f5c2e</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">790</data>
      <data key="d6">acd35bb6b3cb4979a3f3fb68a86b3b05</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;KEY POINT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The sum of the probabilities of all outcomes (branch) at each chance fork must equal 1 or 100%."</data>
      <data key="d2">e5de3d497edf33e49e77c7a76b7f5c2e</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">791</data>
      <data key="d6">9e1e7f67ba044c7fbf64723af1ade58e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DECISION TREE PROCESS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The decision tree process involves calculating the expected outcome at each decision fork by starting at the right-hand side of the decision tree and working back to each decision fork to identify the best decision at each fork."</data>
      <data key="d2">e5de3d497edf33e49e77c7a76b7f5c2e</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">792</data>
      <data key="d6">57e16ff087a84b8ebd70de1e7e534225</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF DECISION TREE PROCESS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A company is considering investing in a new machine. This would involve an initial expenditure of $50,000 on patent rights, and profit in the coming year could be: $300,000 with probability 0.6 or $200,000 with probability 0.4. If the company does not invest in the machine, profits for next year will be: $250,000 with probability 0.7 or $150,000 with probability 0.3. The expected profits and decision outcomes are calculated to determine the best decision."</data>
      <data key="d2">e5de3d497edf33e49e77c7a76b7f5c2e</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">793</data>
      <data key="d6">bbf4007dc9c0486b8ea76d616045467a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: DECISION TREES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves drawing a decision tree to illustrate the possible decisions and their associated potential outcomes for Slim Foods considering launching a non-sugar snack bar into a new market. It includes calculating the value of the imperfect information provided by the market research company."</data>
      <data key="d2">e5de3d497edf33e49e77c7a76b7f5c2e</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">794</data>
      <data key="d6">9535f4d754044e128cd3951a9d2e3702</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXPECTED PRESENT VALUE OF PROFITS WITH MARKET RESEARCH&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The expected present value of profits with market research is calculated by considering the probability of success and failure, and the associated profits and losses. The formula used is: EV = (Probability of Success * Profit) + (Probability of Failure * Loss)."</data>
      <data key="d2">9e697a6f98eb47e0e26d6fb7c2205aca</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">795</data>
      <data key="d6">e1ed13e29ee946d4aaafac50aaa3b68f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXPECTED PRESENT VALUE OF PROFITS WITHOUT MARKET RESEARCH&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The expected present value of profits without market research is calculated by considering the probability of success and failure, and the associated profits and losses. The formula used is: EV = (Probability of Success * Profit) + (Probability of Failure * Loss)."</data>
      <data key="d2">9e697a6f98eb47e0e26d6fb7c2205aca</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">796</data>
      <data key="d6">eb961d47a30c4870a1134b4a4672a8b2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VALUE OF IMPERFECT INFORMATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The value of imperfect information is the difference between the expected value if market research is commissioned and the expected value if it is not. It quantifies the benefit of having additional information that is not perfect but still useful."</data>
      <data key="d2">9e697a6f98eb47e0e26d6fb7c2205aca</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">797</data>
      <data key="d6">5b019e8652264136b95306bac70a2e25</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;THREE TYPES OF DECISION-MAKERS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"There are three types of decision-makers based on their attitude towards risk: risk-seekers, risk-neutral, and risk-averse. Risk-seekers aim for the maximum possible return, risk-neutral consider the most likely outcome, and risk-averse aim to minimize potential loss."</data>
      <data key="d2">9e697a6f98eb47e0e26d6fb7c2205aca</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">798</data>
      <data key="d6">325fc9e2b37043b7af9f6ad338b09469</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DECISION RULES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Decision rules are criteria used by decision-makers to choose among alternatives. The main decision rules are: MAXIMAX (optimistic), MAXIMIN (pessimistic), MINIMAX REGRET (minimizing regret), and EXPECTED VALUE (risk-neutral)."</data>
      <data key="d2">9e697a6f98eb47e0e26d6fb7c2205aca</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">799</data>
      <data key="d6">6bb11aa08b414232b5b45f10f5766f62</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF DECISION OUTCOMES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"An example involving an ice cream seller deciding on the order size based on weather forecasts. The payoff table shows the profits for different order sizes under various weather conditions, illustrating the application of decision rules like MAXIMAX, MAXIMIN, and EXPECTED VALUE."</data>
      <data key="d2">9e697a6f98eb47e0e26d6fb7c2205aca</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">800</data>
      <data key="d6">179737fd23c943babdfae01ac5c6bfc3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MOTIVATION THROUGH BUDGETING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Motivation through budgeting involves setting performance targets for managers, which can improve their performance. However, if the targets are too difficult, it can demotivate them."</data>
      <data key="d2">2f4d122e57ceca3100dab3886c99ca27</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">801</data>
      <data key="d6">65a31e4da283411fb7c971f63d606723</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PLANNING THROUGH BUDGETS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Planning through budgets involves creating a financial plan that forces managers to consider market conditions and how they will respond to them, leading to better decision-making."</data>
      <data key="d2">2f4d122e57ceca3100dab3886c99ca27</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">802</data>
      <data key="d6">de31810d43174a52aa2f31b72f4542f5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EVALUATION OF MANAGERS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Evaluation of managers involves assessing their performance against the budget they are given. In some organizations, this evaluation can affect bonuses and promotions."</data>
      <data key="d2">2f4d122e57ceca3100dab3886c99ca27</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">803</data>
      <data key="d6">a6ae1d99330443fcacb06ace15a0d937</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COMMUNICATION THROUGH BUDGETS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Communication through budgets involves superiors using budgets to communicate their expectations to the managers below them."</data>
      <data key="d2">2f4d122e57ceca3100dab3886c99ca27</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">804</data>
      <data key="d6">5174cdabb6024de0975762d3a80b059f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ETHICAL AND SUSTAINABILITY CONSIDERATIONS IN BUDGETING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Ethical and sustainability considerations in budgeting involve incorporating ethical and sustainability elements into the budget-setting process to manage risks and opportunities related to sustainability."</data>
      <data key="d2">2f4d122e57ceca3100dab3886c99ca27</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">805</data>
      <data key="d6">e379fba901174b529250169e62d98c09</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SUSTAINABLE BUDGETING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sustainable budgeting focuses on how budgeting decisions affect sustainability and societal well-being measures, such as climate impact and local community effects."</data>
      <data key="d2">2f4d122e57ceca3100dab3886c99ca27</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">806</data>
      <data key="d6">81ee8bb20bbb4d37bc0db642f1c75b8e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LONG-TERM PLANNING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Long-term planning involves setting out the long-term, strategic objectives of the organization and determining the actions needed to achieve those objectives."</data>
      <data key="d2">2f4d122e57ceca3100dab3886c99ca27</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">807</data>
      <data key="d6">93b4aa6ce6e44123a861d4c3b3d509a2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MISSION STATEMENT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A mission statement describes the reason for an organization's existence, including its business type, policies, standards of behavior, values, and culture."</data>
      <data key="d2">2f4d122e57ceca3100dab3886c99ca27</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">808</data>
      <data key="d6">ee8414e314f547eeb369849cdb51bac2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STRATEGIC OBJECTIVES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"STRATEGIC OBJECTIVES" are high-level goals that support an organization's mission and guide its performance measurement and management. These objectives are specific and quantifiable goals that an organization must achieve to fulfill its mission.</data>
      <data key="d2">2f4d122e57ceca3100dab3886c99ca27,3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">809</data>
      <data key="d6">9f77aa8888bd4f94abba8a77c4b0565c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;UNIT OBJECTIVES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Unit objectives are goals set for each business unit within an organization, consistent with the strategic objectives."</data>
      <data key="d2">2f4d122e57ceca3100dab3886c99ca27</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">810</data>
      <data key="d6">dcf33412678340319e7ec8f7be267ef9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PERFORMANCE HIERARCHY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">The performance hierarchy is a structure used to set out the long-term, strategic objectives of an organization. It organizes these objectives into a structured framework, typically including the mission, corporate objectives, subsidiary objectives, and business unit objectives. This hierarchical arrangement ensures that the organization's mission and strategic objectives are clearly defined and systematically cascaded down to the various business units, aligning all levels of the organization towards common goals.</data>
      <data key="d2">2f4d122e57ceca3100dab3886c99ca27,3b375b22ae26edc86618262ee6ace048</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">811</data>
      <data key="d6">4aa1e0fa00c048939a5d006bfd305fb4</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ROLE OF BUDGETING IN LONG-TERM PLANNING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The role of budgeting in long-term planning involves creating detailed financial plans for the budget period that align with the long-term strategic plan. This process includes implementing the long-term plan for the budget period, with the budget being more detailed than the long-term plan.</data>
      <data key="d2">2f4d122e57ceca3100dab3886c99ca27,bba1095f6b9a360e21d80bc3dc45ff30</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">812</data>
      <data key="d6">03053ab4a9054384a5f5e88d28841621</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SETTING STRATEGIES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Setting strategies involves determining the actions needed to achieve the organization's objectives, often outlined in a long-term plan."</data>
      <data key="d2">bba1095f6b9a360e21d80bc3dc45ff30</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">813</data>
      <data key="d6">9fd0f20997d541bca46c4ec9843a5d0f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MASTER BUDGET&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The master budget consolidates all subsidiary budgets and is presented as a statement of profit or loss, a statement of financial position, and a cash flow statement. It requires board approval and ensures control over operations and expenditures."</data>
      <data key="d2">bba1095f6b9a360e21d80bc3dc45ff30</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">814</data>
      <data key="d6">27168beee1ff456696c330c9c3b3259f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FUNCTIONAL BUDGETS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Functional budgets are prepared by operational managers and include primary budgets such as sales, production, materials, labor, and capital. These budgets must be prepared in sequence and reviewed for consistency."</data>
      <data key="d2">bba1095f6b9a360e21d80bc3dc45ff30</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">815</data>
      <data key="d6">e1c20e06aeac436788a9c6e918bcb844</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PROFIT CENTRE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A profit centre is a business segment where revenues are received and expenditures are incurred."</data>
      <data key="d2">bba1095f6b9a360e21d80bc3dc45ff30</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">816</data>
      <data key="d6">344417f626ef4da4be4539ef4037bf3f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INVESTMENT CENTRE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"An investment centre is a profit centre that also has some control over its capital expenditure (investment in assets)."</data>
      <data key="d2">bba1095f6b9a360e21d80bc3dc45ff30</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">817</data>
      <data key="d6">8b1fff87c350475fb1d411a26c3c5b0c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TOP-DOWN BUDGETING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">Top-down budgeting involves senior management preparing budgets centrally, often with little to no input from junior managers. In this approach, budgets are prepared by senior management and then imposed on the departments responsible for achieving them.</data>
      <data key="d2">bba1095f6b9a360e21d80bc3dc45ff30,ce28acd80f4f32bfd3e5299109f2279e</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">818</data>
      <data key="d6">898a9458adfb4c13a1eafacf6a1068f6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BOTTOM-UP BUDGETING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Bottom-up budgeting," also known as participative budgeting, is a budgeting approach where departments and managers at various levels actively participate in preparing their own budgets. These budgets are then reviewed and adjusted by senior management. This method contrasts with top-down budgeting, where senior management prepares the budget with little to no input from lower-level managers. Understanding the implications of transitioning from a top-down to a bottom-up system of budgeting is crucial for effective financial planning and management.</data>
      <data key="d2">8cf592364030d479cf1085a135ca8d22,bba1095f6b9a360e21d80bc3dc45ff30,ce28acd80f4f32bfd3e5299109f2279e</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">819</data>
      <data key="d6">5448f05781de44ea96e3dea40b285842</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FACTORS TO CONSIDER IN BUDGET PARTICIPATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Factors to consider in deciding the level of participation in budgeting include the attitudes and skills of junior managers, interdependence between departments, financial difficulty, local knowledge of senior managers, and organizational culture."</data>
      <data key="d2">bba1095f6b9a360e21d80bc3dc45ff30</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">820</data>
      <data key="d6">76b1e69904b84d09ba05c4b7efc48f32</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PROBLEMS WITH ROLLING BUDGETS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Problems with rolling budgets include the process being more time-consuming and costly due to regular updates, and the potential for budgets to be changed to hide operational inefficiencies."</data>
      <data key="d2">5b0efd3d58d424aeff8ca50cc4afeacd</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">821</data>
      <data key="d6">3f5590a604894d268603b4b27c3348b5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;APPROPRIATENESS OF ROLLING BUDGETS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Rolling budgets are more appropriate in dynamic industries where external changes can quickly make the original budget outdated. In stable industries, continuously updating the budget may offer little benefit."</data>
      <data key="d2">5b0efd3d58d424aeff8ca50cc4afeacd</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">822</data>
      <data key="d6">68f998c9c8c34bb7a994de5a998bb9a0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: ROLLING BUDGETS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz asks whether rolling budgets would be appropriate for organizations in various industries, such as food retailing, mobile device manufacturing, airlines, advertising agencies, and retail banking."</data>
      <data key="d2">5b0efd3d58d424aeff8ca50cc4afeacd</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">823</data>
      <data key="d6">aafc13d02ade40adae13d3bee241817a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF ROLLING BUDGETS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This example shows how Company A computed a 2-quarter rolling budget for one of its outlets, including adjustments for rental increases, new labor regulations, and cheaper material supplies."</data>
      <data key="d2">5b0efd3d58d424aeff8ca50cc4afeacd</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">824</data>
      <data key="d6">81a4818e5cf84ea085abf09de385c86e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: ROLLING BUDGETS FOR HOMELAND AIRWAYS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves updating Homeland Airways' quarterly budget based on changes in fuel costs, labor costs, and assumptions for the next year's budget."</data>
      <data key="d2">5b0efd3d58d424aeff8ca50cc4afeacd</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">825</data>
      <data key="d6">b69851bf63e34ced83827b0021628543</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INCREMENTAL BUDGETING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">Incremental budgeting is a traditional budgeting method where the new budget is prepared using the previous period's budget or actual performance as a base, with incremental amounts added for the new budget period. Adjustments are made for expected changes such as inflation, planned increases in sales prices, and costs. This method is straightforward, easy, and quick to perform, making it suitable for stable environments. However, it can encourage inefficiency, carry forward errors, and may not be suitable for volatile industries due to its less flexible nature.</data>
      <data key="d2">2343dedcae64d2e174ab981dfc3b23a0,6cf39866faa0b75b5fd5a86e16914122,c0c7c7a6b8fff04d639a29c1521d727f,ce28acd80f4f32bfd3e5299109f2279e,dcff42ba3ed5843954c648603089a728,e8a4cdc58604c69a847f56ea49d24b6c,ed11d697d920edcbfc6a01ce2c257056</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">10</data>
      <data key="d5">826</data>
      <data key="d6">b83a4e11bfa64559954327714b73293f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF INCREMENTAL BUDGETING IN A SCHOOL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A school has budgeted $1.5 million for staff salaries this year. When preparing the budget for the next year, the head teacher estimates: two new members of staff will be needed to teach languages, with a salary of $30,000 each (before any pay rises); all staff members will be awarded a pay increase of 5% in line with inflation. The budget for staff will then be $1.638 million [($1.5m + $30k + $30k) * 1.05], an overall increase of 9.2%."</data>
      <data key="d2">c0c7c7a6b8fff04d639a29c1521d727f</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">827</data>
      <data key="d6">de23b974cc90497eb4363e26d931a57c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;USEFULNESS OF INCREMENTAL BUDGETING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Incremental budgeting may be appropriate for a stable business with good cost control. Managers need only justify the increments. The system is relatively simple to operate and easy to understand. Conflicts should be avoided if departments can be seen to be treated similarly. Coordination between budgets is easier to achieve, as increments in functional budgets are easily aggregated into master budgets. The effect of change can be seen quickly."</data>
      <data key="d2">c0c7c7a6b8fff04d639a29c1521d727f</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">828</data>
      <data key="d6">a9de65176e234a9f9073b8df9d675e90</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PROBLEMS WITH INCREMENTAL BUDGETING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Incremental budgeting assumes activities and methods of working will continue in the same way regardless of whether they are needed. It gives no incentive for developing new ways of working or the reduction of costs. It encourages a 'spend it or lose' mentality so that the budget is maintained next year. The budget may become out of date and no longer relate to the level of activity or type of work being carried out. The priority for resources may have changed since the budgets were set originally. Any budgetary slack in a previous budget is not reviewed. It is also easier to add and justify budgetary slack to make achieving budgets easier. When a budgeting system has been in operation for some time, there is a tendency for the following year's budget to be justified by referencing the levels currently being achieved. However, the analysis process should consider all changes affecting the organisation's future activities. Even using such an analytical base, some organisations find that historical comparisons, particularly the current resource constraints, can inhibit innovative budget changes. This can severely handicap an organisation because the budget should be the first year of the long-term strategic plan. If changes are not started in the budget period, it will be more difficult for the organisation to make the progress necessary to achieve long-term objectives."</data>
      <data key="d2">c0c7c7a6b8fff04d639a29c1521d727f</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">829</data>
      <data key="d6">09a1bd11eb9347a9b466edad1a562cc5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ZERO-BASED BUDGETING (ZBB)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">Zero-Based Budgeting (ZBB) is a budgeting method where all expenses must be justified for each new period, starting from a 'zero base.' This approach requires the costs and benefits of all activities to be quantified and justified, making it particularly useful in the public sector, although it is costly and time-consuming to implement. ZBB involves developing the budget from an assumption of no existing resources, necessitating that all resources be justified and compared with alternatives.

The process of ZBB includes three main steps: identifying activities and creating decision packages, ranking these packages by their benefits, and allocating resources based on priority. Managers are required to identify activities, consider different ways of performing them, and describe them in a 'decision package' that analyzes costs, states purposes, and identifies alternative methods. This method forces managers to justify all expenses and consider alternative ways of performing activities, ensuring an efficient allocation of resources. Every function within an organization is analyzed for its needs and costs, promoting a thorough and rational approach to budgeting.</data>
      <data key="d2">16965b8a36bbe6bac45c7b81a6b17c48,c0c7c7a6b8fff04d639a29c1521d727f,ce28acd80f4f32bfd3e5299109f2279e,e8a4cdc58604c69a847f56ea49d24b6c,f39e983f452f0497b116e09b2dd273ee</data>
      <data key="d7">5</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">9</data>
      <data key="d5">830</data>
      <data key="d6">11d74eab1dcb4fcba7c45def5f0ee22d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FEATURES OF ZBB&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"FEATURES OF ZBB" include focusing on activities or programs, asking critical questions about the necessity and cost of activities, and breaking the budgetary process into three stages: identifying activities, reviewing and ranking decision packages, and allocating resources. Unlike traditional budgets, which are typically produced using a 'line item' approach that lists each type of expense and the amount budgeted by each department, ZBB emphasizes the activities or programs each department would like to undertake. It considers questions such as the necessity and efficiency of each activity.</data>
      <data key="d2">8cdfffc4f5f91dc3af2a0e1a32d28ab4,c0c7c7a6b8fff04d639a29c1521d727f</data>
      <data key="d7">5</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">831</data>
      <data key="d6">4f6a6fd018a948f4bd0e630266b8bf61</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DECISION PACKAGE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">A decision package in zero-based budgeting (ZBB) is a comprehensive document that serves multiple purposes. It analyzes the cost of an activity, states its purpose, identifies alternative methods of achieving the same purpose, establishes performance measures, and assesses the consequences of not performing the activity or performing it at different levels. Essentially, a decision package is a mini-budget prepared for each activity a manager wishes to undertake. This includes a base level package and incremental packages, which help in analyzing the cost and benefits of each activity.</data>
      <data key="d2">8cdfffc4f5f91dc3af2a0e1a32d28ab4,f39e983f452f0497b116e09b2dd273ee</data>
      <data key="d7">5</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">7</data>
      <data key="d5">832</data>
      <data key="d6">17dbfbecfaf0436bb11ed8f867c0caa1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BENEFITS OF ZBB&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Benefits of ZBB include re-evaluating every activity, linking resource allocation to results and needs, developing a questioning attitude, encouraging a bottom-up approach to budgeting, and preventing budget creep."</data>
      <data key="d2">8cdfffc4f5f91dc3af2a0e1a32d28ab4</data>
      <data key="d7">5</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">833</data>
      <data key="d6">2b1ec99684574c2ab26bb050d5b57a4d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DRAWBACKS OF ZBB&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Drawbacks of ZBB include the need for training, the unmanageable amount of paperwork in large organizations, difficulty in ranking packages, time constraints for top-level management, complexity and time consumption, inability to react to changes during the year, and potential prioritization of short-term goals over long-term objectives."</data>
      <data key="d2">8cdfffc4f5f91dc3af2a0e1a32d28ab4</data>
      <data key="d7">5</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">834</data>
      <data key="d6">1ccce5d1892a4b6995bbaec22882d34d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;WHEN ZBB IS APPROPRIATE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"ZBB is most appropriate in organizations with a high portion of discretionary costs, such as research and development, training, and advertising. It enables reassessment of spending on discretionary items."</data>
      <data key="d2">8cdfffc4f5f91dc3af2a0e1a32d28ab4</data>
      <data key="d7">5</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">835</data>
      <data key="d6">51cd93f89fbe4bcf883cdb2ca6774cd6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;USE OF ZBB IN THE PUBLIC SECTOR&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"ZBB is more prevalent in public sector bodies due to its transparency in showing budgets based on activities rather than line items, and its usefulness in ranking decision packages to allocate limited resources effectively."</data>
      <data key="d2">8cdfffc4f5f91dc3af2a0e1a32d28ab4</data>
      <data key="d7">5</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">836</data>
      <data key="d6">5f353b18fadb438f95ba0ea8feae137c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ZBB&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1">Zero-Based Budgeting (ZBB) is a budgeting method where all expenses must be justified for each new period, starting from a 'zero base.' Every function within an organization is analyzed for its needs and costs.</data>
      <data key="d2">8cdfffc4f5f91dc3af2a0e1a32d28ab4,ed1f837be30c9135b0fe794ec0162540</data>
      <data key="d7">5</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">8</data>
      <data key="d5">837</data>
      <data key="d6">947d70dd14b34cf398a1ab6dbdc51161</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;WEEKLY BUDGETED COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Weekly budgeted costs include the total direct costs and total indirect costs. Direct costs are calculated based on materials and direct labor, while indirect costs include machine set-ups, purchase orders, and storage costs. The total costs are the sum of direct and indirect costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">43b0942a38155115a834866ac07fe119</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">838</data>
      <data key="d6">90f5597a558a4652bded9001a4ec2e56</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ADVANTAGES OF ABB&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Advantages of Activity-Based Budgeting (ABB) include focusing management attention on controllable activities, providing opportunities for cost reductions, and identifying non-value adding activities that can be eliminated."</data>
      <data key="d2">43b0942a38155115a834866ac07fe119</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">839</data>
      <data key="d6">9532cf83e9324ea0a46e5ac89bac407d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DISADVANTAGES OF ABB&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Disadvantages of Activity-Based Budgeting (ABB) include its complexity and expense to implement, especially if direct costs are more significant than indirect costs and the product range is narrow. ABB may also provide misleading information if many fixed costs do not vary with changes in the volume of drivers in the short run."</data>
      <data key="d2">43b0942a38155115a834866ac07fe119</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">840</data>
      <data key="d6">8919fa72a9e74d1daff801e8f4c15b2b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;APPROPRIATENESS OF ABB&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Activity-Based Budgeting (ABB) is most appropriate in large companies with high overheads, many different activities (drivers) to which the overheads relate, and many products with differing production times and methods."</data>
      <data key="d2">43b0942a38155115a834866ac07fe119</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">841</data>
      <data key="d6">bef38889bb86413895d7dd25b4c3137c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FEEDBACK CONTROL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Feedback control is a system in which outputs are monitored against a predetermined standard, and action is taken to remedy any deviations. A budgetary control system is an example of a feedback control system."</data>
      <data key="d2">43b0942a38155115a834866ac07fe119</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">842</data>
      <data key="d6">f770bc07cecf4aba8fe2d2c33fdc5542</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CLOSED-LOOP SYSTEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A closed-loop system is any system with feedback, making it reactive rather than proactive. It includes a standard, sensor, comparator, and effector to control actions."</data>
      <data key="d2">43b0942a38155115a834866ac07fe119</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">843</data>
      <data key="d6">13cd49512d5642989c2c72bb5e674807</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPEN-LOOP SYSTEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"An open-loop system is a system without feedback. Feedback may be absent because it is not produced or not used appropriately."</data>
      <data key="d2">43b0942a38155115a834866ac07fe119</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">844</data>
      <data key="d6">e5c5c87a281b43868c344ff60f44c100</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;POSITIVE AND NEGATIVE FEEDBACK&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Positive feedback means the output has achieved or exceeded the plan, while negative feedback means the output is below the plan. Both types of feedback should be investigated to determine corrective actions or repeat favorable outcomes."</data>
      <data key="d2">43b0942a38155115a834866ac07fe119</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">845</data>
      <data key="d6">a562ffbe986247b7943990e7151f4d69</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FEED-FORWARD CONTROL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Feed-forward control systems compare predicted future results against the desired outcome. If the desired result will not be achieved based on the current prediction, action can be taken now to ensure it is achieved."</data>
      <data key="d2">43b0942a38155115a834866ac07fe119</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">846</data>
      <data key="d6">7ea0bc1467e84184842de2d5e5bdd78e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FORECASTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A budget is effectively a forecast of what can be achieved. The forecast has to make assumptions about the external environment, including factors like economic performance, competitor actions, employee performance, market prices of inputs, and demand for new products."</data>
      <data key="d2">a7378184f81737c3d34db742775b2255</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">847</data>
      <data key="d6">056f23eb710f471393ae5dc417d83fd9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FLEXIBLE BUDGETS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Flexible budgeting involves preparing two or more budgets using different assumptions for each about the level of sales or production. At the end of the financial period, the budget is flexed to the actual activity level for comparison to actual performance."</data>
      <data key="d2">a7378184f81737c3d34db742775b2255</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">848</data>
      <data key="d6">e1ae27016d63447a8dfa021370cba0fa</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FLEXED BUDGETS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"At the end of the year, prior to comparing the actual figures against the budget, the budgets are re-calculated (flexed) using the original budget assumptions but the actual activity levels. This means that the comparison is more valid."</data>
      <data key="d2">a7378184f81737c3d34db742775b2255</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">849</data>
      <data key="d6">f8c10f61a8f344cea7bdafa2d8af14b8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;HIGH-LOW METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">The High-Low Method is a technique used to calculate costs by analyzing the highest and lowest levels of activity and their associated costs. It is employed to estimate the fixed and variable components of a cost by examining these extreme activity levels and their corresponding costs. This method involves selecting the costs associated with the highest and lowest levels of activity and assuming a straight-line relationship between these two points. By doing so, it helps in estimating the fixed and variable elements of a semi-variable cost, enabling more accurate forecasts of costs. Specifically, the High-Low Method calculates the variable overhead cost per unit by taking the difference in costs at the highest and lowest levels of activity and dividing it by the difference in activity levels.</data>
      <data key="d2">02defdad562458f44c0d0fa31dc9693d,a7378184f81737c3d34db742775b2255,ac59038d88c0dcce6b890bd17e7b2544,ce28acd80f4f32bfd3e5299109f2279e,f00d919ad915af3f9caac5db3ddec274</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">8</data>
      <data key="d5">850</data>
      <data key="d6">aa7d003f25624e19bc88d3951d4dc943</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LEARNING CURVE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The concept of the "Learning Curve" represents the rate at which individuals or groups improve their performance with experience. It is commonly used in budgeting to predict how costs will decrease as production increases. Graphically, a learning curve illustrates how an increase in learning comes from greater experience; the more frequently a task is performed, the better and more efficient the individual becomes at it, resulting in reduced time to complete the task.

The learning curve concept specifically refers to the reduction in time taken to produce each unit as workers gain more experience, leading to increased efficiency and reduced costs over time. This is often expressed as a percentage, indicating the rate at which learning and efficiency improve. For example, in the production of Parapain, which is extremely difficult to handle, an 80% learning curve exists. This means that the time taken to produce the drug decreases as more batches are produced, up to the first 1,000 batches.

Overall, the learning curve is a valuable tool for estimating the learning rate and learning effect, providing a graphical representation of how the time required to perform a task decreases with increasing repetitions.</data>
      <data key="d2">02defdad562458f44c0d0fa31dc9693d,303f0ef8328d2aefc4bfae1067a85f72,324c0fb49870acc800392f7d78685514,a7378184f81737c3d34db742775b2255,ce28acd80f4f32bfd3e5299109f2279e,d4cbc64c9c49dd951f9997a26ee9d9f9,df5e50672b5795ed072403e633c26e7f</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">7</data>
      <data key="d5">851</data>
      <data key="d6">1c97184ce5ea4049be417a3fd125357b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ADVANTAGES OF FLEXIBLE BUDGETS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The requirement to prepare more than one fixed budget means that managers are required to consider a range of forecasts, and actual results can be compared more meaningfully against the budget for the closest level of activity."</data>
      <data key="d2">a7378184f81737c3d34db742775b2255</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">852</data>
      <data key="d6">13a044c404394c34af1e9b07c48aa985</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DISADVANTAGES OF FLEXIBLE BUDGETS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Difficulty in separating fixed and variable elements of indirect costs (overheads), and cost may not behave as assumed (e.g., linearly or as predicted by a learning curve)."</data>
      <data key="d2">a7378184f81737c3d34db742775b2255</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">853</data>
      <data key="d6">69ef1ac7b1f44372979149e82ecbc860</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FLEXED PRODUCTION COST QUIZ&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves calculating the flexed total production cost for production at 80% of maximum capacity for Corfe Co, which manufactures computer laptop batteries."</data>
      <data key="d2">a7378184f81737c3d34db742775b2255</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">854</data>
      <data key="d6">6e26ce67bacc4fa089296843463f69ad</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OBJECTIVES OF A BUDGETARY CONTROL SYSTEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The main objectives of a budgetary control system are planning, coordination of the activities of the organisation, and ensuring better resource utilisation."</data>
      <data key="d2">ce28acd80f4f32bfd3e5299109f2279e</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">855</data>
      <data key="d6">ae0d3104647f4e6ab3ec2cf8e60be5ca</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ROLLING BUDGET&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"ROLLING BUDGET" is a continuous budgeting process where the budget is updated regularly, typically every quarter, to reflect changes in the market and business environment. This approach is more flexible and responsive to changes compared to traditional annual budgets. A rolling budget is continuously updated and is most suitable in a rapidly changing environment where the original budget quickly becomes outdated.</data>
      <data key="d2">ce28acd80f4f32bfd3e5299109f2279e,dcff42ba3ed5843954c648603089a728</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">856</data>
      <data key="d6">49e24b5f2c1d40d7857afe327db4f554</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ACTIVITY-BASED BUDGETING (ABB)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Activity-based budgets use ABC principles to calculate the budgeted overhead costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">ce28acd80f4f32bfd3e5299109f2279e</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">857</data>
      <data key="d6">587f39a32e93412395d9c22ad0ac2f94</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BEYOND BUDGETING MODEL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Beyond Budgeting model aims to replace traditional budgetary control systems with a more modern approach which replaces financial targets with key performance indicators."</data>
      <data key="d2">ce28acd80f4f32bfd3e5299109f2279e</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">858</data>
      <data key="d6">8d9ded5fc9cf4c4faba8c6c8cd50e2f4</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CORRELATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Correlation" is an analysis technique used to measure the strength and direction of the relationship between two variables. It refers to the closeness of the relationship between two or more variables and can be positive, negative, perfect, or zero, indicating the degree to which variables move together.</data>
      <data key="d2">58b93b93f50c76736f349d9791a3fb60,ce28acd80f4f32bfd3e5299109f2279e</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">859</data>
      <data key="d6">595a841aa6034c93bd3dc55681e17710</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REGRESSION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Regression" is an analysis technique used to model the relationship between a dependent variable and one or more independent variables. Specifically, regression analysis is used to forecast the value of one variable based on the value of another by assuming a linear relationship described by the equation y = a + bx. The values of a and b in this equation can be determined using the least squares regression method.</data>
      <data key="d2">b7a62bba0de24771bb330cb53b263dc1,ce28acd80f4f32bfd3e5299109f2279e</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">860</data>
      <data key="d6">d0e58b78e8e84a0c8796e707b1f95f65</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TIME SERIES ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Time series analysis" involves analyzing data points collected or recorded at specific time intervals to identify trends, cycles, and seasonal variations. It can be applied to any figures that vary over time, including sales, production, and costs. The main components of a time series are trend, seasonal variations, cyclical variations, and random variations.</data>
      <data key="d2">ac59038d88c0dcce6b890bd17e7b2544,ce28acd80f4f32bfd3e5299109f2279e</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">861</data>
      <data key="d6">215fcc6a3b5e452da123aa7f9ef0cbc9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GEOMETRIC MEAN&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The geometric mean is used to calculate average growth rates and is most commonly used in business and finance to calculate growth rates in percentages. It is calculated as the nth root of the product of n numbers."</data>
      <data key="d2">ce28acd80f4f32bfd3e5299109f2279e</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">862</data>
      <data key="d6">0d0fc5d4ecb548079b28979186f19bf6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF GEOMETRIC MEAN&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The sales of Beta during the last three years were as follows: Year Sales in $000 20X2 100 20X3 180 20X4 210 20X5 300. The growth rate of sales each year is as follows: 20X3 80% (180 - 100)/100 20X4 16.67% (210 - 180)/180 20X5 42.9% (300 - 210)/210. The simple average growth rate is 46.5%, calculated as (80% + 16.67% + 42.9%)/3. However, this overstates the rate of growth: If the 20X2 sales of $100,000 were to increase by 46.5% each year for three years, the sales in 20X5 would be $314,000, not $300,000. The more accurate growth rate is obtained using the geometric mean. This is used to calculate average growth rates and is most commonly used in business and finance to calculate growth rates in percentages. Growing by 80% is the same as multiplying by 1.8, so the geometric mean for the three years is cube root(1.8 * 1.1667 * 1.429) = 1.442, so the average growth rate is 44.2%. This can then be used to calculate expected sales in future periods."</data>
      <data key="d2">ce28acd80f4f32bfd3e5299109f2279e</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">863</data>
      <data key="d6">e7d3fe0f87ff47f5a4c8d9572d27245a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves questions related to cost analysis and budgeting techniques."</data>
      <data key="d2">ce28acd80f4f32bfd3e5299109f2279e</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">864</data>
      <data key="d6">6f7165b558ae427ca14b2b16d1e8e204</data>
    </node>
