      <data key="d5">866</data>
      <data key="d6">16d5a528d6374612b87a5656e8d95193</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;HIGH-LOW METHOD QUIZ&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The High-Low Method Quiz involves calculating the estimated maintenance cost for production of a battery at 80% of maximum demand, using historical machine hours and maintenance costs data."</data>
      <data key="d2">ac59038d88c0dcce6b890bd17e7b2544</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">867</data>
      <data key="d6">40293e74dbc643e8ab6546dff759ac7c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TREND&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Trend refers to the underlying long-term movement in values over time."</data>
      <data key="d2">ac59038d88c0dcce6b890bd17e7b2544</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">868</data>
      <data key="d6">1834b753dc7f4a8b98c2317a551b56ee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF TREND&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This example shows sales data of three products (Red, Blue, and Green) over several years, illustrating different trends: a downward trend for Blue, an upward trend for Red, and a constant trend for Green."</data>
      <data key="d2">ac59038d88c0dcce6b890bd17e7b2544</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">869</data>
      <data key="d6">d9b127eab2f64e338d7adcd186786a45</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SEASONAL VARIATIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Seasonal variations" refer to short-term fluctuations in value caused by differing circumstances affecting results at different times of the day, week, month, year, etc. These fluctuations are influenced by factors such as weather, annual events, and customer shopping habits. Seasonal variations specifically pertain to the regular intervals at which these fluctuations occur, impacting sales or other metrics. These variations are typically calculated by comparing actual sales to trend factors for each season.</data>
      <data key="d2">ac59038d88c0dcce6b890bd17e7b2544,bb165972f0b8b6fbf29cb666c55127ec,ed92008c96a21c35ce8df85cad7122a3</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">870</data>
      <data key="d6">a18f7c9f58ca49d6acf18e1ca69d3033</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF SEASONAL VARIATIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The sales for one of Leybourne Co's products over each season in the last three years show significant seasonal variations, with higher sales in summer and lower sales in winter, indicating an overall upward trend despite seasonal fluctuations."</data>
      <data key="d2">ed92008c96a21c35ce8df85cad7122a3</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">871</data>
      <data key="d6">f3c3dd44cf50495c81e362174991242e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CYCLICAL VARIATIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Cyclical variations are medium-term changes in values resulting from factors that repeat in cycles, such as economic cycles alternating between booms and recessions."</data>
      <data key="d2">ed92008c96a21c35ce8df85cad7122a3</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">872</data>
      <data key="d6">86c2b3749a3c4342bbb3a8c70c3a76a0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MOVING AVERAGES METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The moving averages method removes seasonal variations from data by averaging the results of a fixed number of periods, smoothing out data sets to reveal their overall trend."</data>
      <data key="d2">ed92008c96a21c35ce8df85cad7122a3</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">873</data>
      <data key="d6">571f65acb3134490932feeb91b01cca3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ADDITIVE MODEL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">The additive model is a forecasting method that separates time series data into trend, seasonal, and irregular components. It assumes that the observed data is the sum of these components. The model operates under the assumption that the components of the time series are independent, meaning the trend will not affect the seasonal variations. Seasonal variations are calculated by subtracting the trend figure from the actual data.</data>
      <data key="d2">7560b5e17dc87876b42de897b9956b6f,ed92008c96a21c35ce8df85cad7122a3</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">874</data>
      <data key="d6">d3faf86c153f440eaa410305b3dc6617</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF SEASONAL VARIATIONS - ADDITIVE MODEL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Frances opens a cafe from Tuesday to Saturday each week. A sales trend is calculated using a 5-day moving average, and daily variations are calculated as the difference between actual sales and the trend for each day."</data>
      <data key="d2">ed92008c96a21c35ce8df85cad7122a3</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">875</data>
      <data key="d6">f85786004b0540349192d2ca05b15264</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SEASONAL VARIATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Seasonal variation" refers to the periodic fluctuations in data that occur at regular intervals due to seasonal factors. These variations can be identified and measured to adjust the data for better trend analysis. Seasonal variation is often added to trend forecasts to improve accuracy and is calculated as the difference between the actual value and the trend value. This concept is commonly applied to fluctuations in sales or other metrics, helping to provide a clearer understanding of underlying trends by accounting for predictable seasonal patterns.</data>
      <data key="d2">53222550364887a73cb33009b37a0a6b,7560b5e17dc87876b42de897b9956b6f,df5e50672b5795ed072403e633c26e7f</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">876</data>
      <data key="d6">cf56bfc9fa7d47fe9cb553dd09f2b412</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: ADDITIVE MODEL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves calculating the trend and seasonal variations using the additive model based on Dewie Co's quarterly profits over three years."</data>
      <data key="d2">7560b5e17dc87876b42de897b9956b6f</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">877</data>
      <data key="d6">a077dbcd38b644f6929cf05272c2fb9d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TREND AND SEASONAL VARIATION CALCULATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The process of calculating trend and seasonal variations using the multiplicative model involves determining the moving totals, moving averages, and seasonal variations for a given set of data. This method helps in understanding the underlying trend and seasonal patterns in the data."</data>
      <data key="d2">53222550364887a73cb33009b37a0a6b</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">878</data>
      <data key="d6">d2659a32b9de406eb750a35d078c9774</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MULTIPLICATIVE MODEL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The multiplicative model is a method used in time series analysis where the observed data is assumed to be the product of the trend, seasonal, and random components. This model is particularly useful for data with proportional seasonal variations."</data>
      <data key="d2">53222550364887a73cb33009b37a0a6b</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">879</data>
      <data key="d6">0b26876307ad4cc48839b61a21a1d03a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SEASONALLY-ADJUSTED DATA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Seasonally-adjusted data, also known as deseasonalized data, is the actual data that has been adjusted to remove the effects of seasonal variations. This adjustment allows for a clearer analysis of the underlying trend and any remaining random components."</data>
      <data key="d2">53222550364887a73cb33009b37a0a6b</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">880</data>
      <data key="d6">c68e6c694a554256846d12178ddb12dc</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LIMITATIONS OF TIME SERIES ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Limitations of Time Series Analysis include the need for ordered data over time, the dependency on the amount of data for reliability, the loss of data in moving averages, the influence of random factors, and the decreasing reliability of extrapolation over longer periods."</data>
      <data key="d2">58b93b93f50c76736f349d9791a3fb60</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">881</data>
      <data key="d6">ff25ce2e8ace4bdcb765c863b483852b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TYPES OF CORRELATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Types of Correlation include positive correlation (both variables increase together), negative correlation (one variable increases while the other decreases), perfect correlation (a change in one variable is matched by an equal change in the other), and zero correlation (no relationship between variables)."</data>
      <data key="d2">58b93b93f50c76736f349d9791a3fb60</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">882</data>
      <data key="d6">757e402cb7ee4601ac1bc8c4fafb5207</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CORRELATION COEFFICIENT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The correlation coefficient (r) measures the degree of correlation between two variables, indicating the strength and direction of their linear relationship. It ranges from -1 to 1, where +1 indicates a perfect positive correlation, -1 indicates a perfect negative correlation, and 0 indicates no correlation. The formula for calculating the correlation coefficient is: r = (n&#931;xy - &#931;x&#931;y) / &#8730;[(n&#931;x&#178; - (&#931;x)&#178;)(n&#931;y&#178; - (&#931;y)&#178;)].</data>
      <data key="d2">58b93b93f50c76736f349d9791a3fb60,df5e50672b5795ed072403e633c26e7f</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">883</data>
      <data key="d6">62e8f5f04cd04384b246291cef3a9e4d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF CORRELATION COEFFICIENT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"An example of calculating the correlation coefficient involves determining the relationship between the number of ice-creams sold and the average daily temperature. The calculated correlation coefficient of 0.98 indicates a high positive correlation."</data>
      <data key="d2">58b93b93f50c76736f349d9791a3fb60</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">884</data>
      <data key="d6">c04abbd5e59b4c64b023908f6db05498</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: CORRELATION COEFFICIENT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves calculating the correlation coefficient for the life of a component at different machine speeds. The data provided includes machine speed (revolutions per second) and the life of the component (hours)."</data>
      <data key="d2">58b93b93f50c76736f349d9791a3fb60</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">885</data>
      <data key="d6">6bb9bed2e39c4e31a81f12479af3d16c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CORRELATION COEFFICIENT CALCULATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The correlation coefficient measures the strength and direction of the linear relationship between two variables. In this case, it is calculated using the formula: r = [(n&#931;xy) - (&#931;x&#931;y)] / sqrt[(n&#931;x^2 - (&#931;x)^2)(n&#931;y^2 - (&#931;y)^2)]. The result is -0.95, indicating a high negative correlation between machine speed and the life of the component."</data>
      <data key="d2">b7a62bba0de24771bb330cb53b263dc1</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">886</data>
      <data key="d6">26c926c6016d4639b05427f01ba629f5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INTERPRETATION OF R&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A high correlation between two variables does not necessarily imply a causal relationship. The correlation could be spurious, meaning it might be due to an indirect connection or coincidence."</data>
      <data key="d2">b7a62bba0de24771bb330cb53b263dc1</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">887</data>
      <data key="d6">8f6872eeb81b432b91405d327636113c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SPURIOUS CORRELATION EXAMPLE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"An example of spurious correlation is the close correlation between total annual video game sales and total nuclear energy production over the last 60 years. Both variables have increased steadily due to the growing global population, but there is no causal relationship between them."</data>
      <data key="d2">b7a62bba0de24771bb330cb53b263dc1</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">888</data>
      <data key="d6">ac80a99fda2b488285d29596dd4d1471</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COEFFICIENT OF DETERMINATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The coefficient of determination (r&#178;) indicates the proportion of the variance in the dependent variable that is predictable from the independent variable. It is calculated as the square of the correlation coefficient (r) and is always a positive number. This measure helps to understand how much of the total change in one variable can be explained by the change in another variable.</data>
      <data key="d2">b7a62bba0de24771bb330cb53b263dc1,df5e50672b5795ed072403e633c26e7f,e6dcb0a0bf01250a84f45fc9b4de8a13</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">889</data>
      <data key="d6">67d6a3481e4b419292247cef5cd5b737</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COEFFICIENT OF DETERMINATION EXAMPLE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"If the correlation coefficient between the number of quality control tests and the number of customer complaints is -0.8, the coefficient of determination is 0.64. This means that 64% of the changes in customer complaints can be explained by changes in the number of quality control tests."</data>
      <data key="d2">b7a62bba0de24771bb330cb53b263dc1</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">890</data>
      <data key="d6">904cd052ec194654bb72f4027e43daa3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REGRESSION FORMULAE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The formulae for calculating the regression coefficients are: a = &#931;y/n - b&#931;x/n and b = (n&#931;xy - &#931;x&#931;y)/(n&#931;x^2 - (&#931;x)^2). These formulae help determine the line of best fit for the data."</data>
      <data key="d2">b7a62bba0de24771bb330cb53b263dc1</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">891</data>
      <data key="d6">7e88fd2e835147fbb71866612735e8d4</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BENEFITS OF CORRELATION AND REGRESSION ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">The "BENEFITS OF CORRELATION AND REGRESSION ANALYSIS" encompass several key advantages. Correlation analysis can indicate the existence of associations between variables, providing insights into the strength and direction of these relationships. When used in conjunction with regression analysis, it enhances the understanding of the relationship indicated by the regression equation. Least squares regression, which uses all pairs of data, is more accurate than the high-low method and is less affected by extreme values. Together, correlation and regression analysis help identify trends, make predictions, and support better decision-making and forecasting by providing a comprehensive understanding of the relationships between variables.</data>
      <data key="d2">576fefef6a12e37650232e33fae8babf,b7a62bba0de24771bb330cb53b263dc1</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">892</data>
      <data key="d6">029d1a8c3b184aa5bb21228f40cd12fd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FORMULA FOR A&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"a = &#931;y/n - b&#931;x/n"</data>
      <data key="d2">576fefef6a12e37650232e33fae8babf</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">893</data>
      <data key="d6">a1ebc53a0bc74a0eb6dbdd18cf3c88cd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FORMULA FOR B&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"b = (n&#931;xy - &#931;x&#931;y)/(n&#931;x2 - (&#931;x)2)"</data>
      <data key="d2">576fefef6a12e37650232e33fae8babf</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">894</data>
      <data key="d6">a51d063ad4c744049edb359eb88407b7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LIMITATIONS OF CORRELATION AND REGRESSION ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A limited amount of data may reduce the reliability of forecasts made. The reliability of the analysis and forecasts also depends on the quality of the data. High correlation does not necessarily indicate a linear relationship, and there may be no direct connection between highly correlated variables. Linear regression analysis is based on the assumptions of a linear relationship, which may not be valid, and assumes that the dependent variable depends solely on the independent variable, whereas it may depend on a number of variables. Forecasts that extrapolate values outside the range of data from the past may be invalid and must be interpreted with caution."</data>
      <data key="d2">576fefef6a12e37650232e33fae8babf</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">895</data>
      <data key="d6">b67268f90338474e8e53b9a6715b6833</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LEARNING EFFECT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The learning effect refers to the reduction in time and cost as workers become more efficient with experience. Specifically, it describes the tendency for labor hours per unit to fall as workers become more familiar with the task. Each time cumulative production doubles, the cumulative average time per unit falls to a fixed percentage of the previous average time, known as the learning rate. For the chair, the learning rate is 95%, and the time for the 128th chair will be the time for all subsequent chairs.</data>
      <data key="d2">30748d6dcf5a2da70804db75296cee3c,576fefef6a12e37650232e33fae8babf</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">896</data>
      <data key="d6">acb53370e72b4430a752d9ea18c17352</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LEARNING CURVE FORMULA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"y = a * x raised to the power of b, where y is the cumulative average time per unit to produce x units, a is the time taken for the first unit of output, x is the cumulative number of units produced, and b is the index of learning (log LR/log2), with LR being the learning rate as a decimal."</data>
      <data key="d2">576fefef6a12e37650232e33fae8babf</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">897</data>
      <data key="d6">a8738c7de11543df930169741381c252</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TABULATION QUIZ&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A quiz that involves completing a table and drawing a graph based on a product that takes 100 hours for the first unit, with an 80% learning curve applied."</data>
      <data key="d2">576fefef6a12e37650232e33fae8babf</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">898</data>
      <data key="d6">3f8b5b2727924ba0b62e6286063b6861</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LEARNING CURVE FORMULA QUIZ&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A quiz that involves calculating the time it will take to produce the seventh unit of a new product, given that it takes 500 hours to produce the first unit and workers have a 95% learning effect."</data>
      <data key="d2">576fefef6a12e37650232e33fae8babf</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">899</data>
      <data key="d6">bb5010633113442eaf814852995cfa22</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LABOUR COST QUIZ&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A quiz that involves calculating the budgeted labor cost for a new business, McSporran, which is producing kilts with an 85% learning effect applied."</data>
      <data key="d2">576fefef6a12e37650232e33fae8babf</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">900</data>
      <data key="d6">9eb8c635538243a690366f8bc1de34e0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LEAST SQUARES REGRESSION METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">576fefef6a12e37650232e33fae8babf</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">901</data>
      <data key="d6">050c5b770d51409cb40f9c52f02d1329</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STEADY STATE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Steady state is achieved when the incremental time per unit is constant. Even after steady state is reached, the cumulative average time per unit would still be decreasing."</data>
      <data key="d2">e29d70715a4cd006db3df9656dc3da81</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">902</data>
      <data key="d6">9e12f514d26d48dfab65807568a6cff9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: LEARNING CURVE AND STEADY STATE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves calculating the labour time per unit for the 30th and subsequent units and the total labour time to make the first 100 units of the XY123 model, considering a learning rate of 85%."</data>
      <data key="d2">e29d70715a4cd006db3df9656dc3da81</data>
      <data key="d7">17</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">903</data>
      <data key="d6">97f98b1623104f48aa93196a1f7dede2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LEARNING RATE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The "Learning Rate" refers to the rate at which workers improve their efficiency and reduce the time taken to complete tasks as they gain experience. It is a measure of how quickly production efficiency improves as more units are produced. Specifically, it indicates the rate at which labour time per unit decreases as workers become more efficient with experience. In the context of Bokco, a 90% learning rate was initially used, meaning that the time taken to produce a unit decreases by 10% with each doubling of the number of units produced. However, an engineer later suggested an 85% learning rate, indicating a more rapid improvement in efficiency.</data>
      <data key="d2">01d1ff33e985b6f8cd09ff45ebfedc0e,9cf602e35df4af3581c4dce0d3f93396,a971d00d99d6f7f6fe13faf691b0e018,dde6d5d3f80c5f7be94b41e612ddb0c0,e29d70715a4cd006db3df9656dc3da81</data>
      <data key="d7">17</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">10</data>
      <data key="d5">904</data>
      <data key="d6">87718ef799a34104b6ef9c2df6621cbc</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LABOUR TIME FOR THE 30TH AND SUBSEQUENT UNITS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Labour time for the 30th and subsequent units is calculated as the difference between the total time taken to make the first 30 units and the total time taken to make the first 29 units, resulting in 0.347 hours."</data>
      <data key="d2">e29d70715a4cd006db3df9656dc3da81</data>
      <data key="d7">17</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">905</data>
      <data key="d6">f64e87431d674f298c533f6878458b95</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TOTAL LABOUR TIME FOR THE FIRST 100 UNITS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Total labour time for the first 100 units is calculated as the sum of the total time taken to make the first 30 units and the time taken to make the next 70 units, resulting in 37.80 hours."</data>
      <data key="d2">e29d70715a4cd006db3df9656dc3da81</data>
      <data key="d7">17</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">906</data>
      <data key="d6">e6d44d0db58f42799a02eacbd6b14543</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ESTIMATING THE LEARNING RATE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Estimating the learning rate involves using a tabular approach based on production to date and the time taken, especially when cumulative units are given in exponentials of 2. The learning rate stops when the incremental time per unit becomes constant."</data>
      <data key="d2">e29d70715a4cd006db3df9656dc3da81</data>
      <data key="d7">17</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">907</data>
      <data key="d6">64961fbc3a1641378be10bcb3b0955e1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: LEARNING RATE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves calculating the learning rate that applied to the new PC and estimating the point at which the learning period finishes, based on the incremental time taken for each unit."</data>
      <data key="d2">e29d70715a4cd006db3df9656dc3da81</data>
      <data key="d7">17</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">908</data>
      <data key="d6">59bcc2ec512c4c1ba44272446b419230</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;END OF THE LEARNING PERIOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The learning period ends when the incremental time per unit becomes constant. In this case, the learning effect ends after the 8th unit, as the time taken per unit becomes constant at 120.5 minutes from the 9th to the 16th unit."</data>
      <data key="d2">9cf602e35df4af3581c4dce0d3f93396</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">909</data>
      <data key="d6">8f39ae56f8b54b1b94faf04dbd0b9d11</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ALGEBRAIC APPROACH TO LEARNING RATE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"An algebraic approach is used to determine the learning rate when only cumulative average time information is available for two levels of output that are not exponentials of 2. This method involves solving for the learning rate using algebraic equations."</data>
      <data key="d2">9cf602e35df4af3581c4dce0d3f93396</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">910</data>
      <data key="d6">f3018b934ac241639a33c925c24bc507</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF ALGEBRAIC APPROACH TO LEARNING RATE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This example demonstrates the algebraic approach to calculate the learning rate. The first unit took 300 minutes, and the total time for the first 8 units was 2,056 minutes, resulting in a cumulative average time of 257 minutes per unit. The learning rate is calculated to be approximately 95%."</data>
      <data key="d2">9cf602e35df4af3581c4dce0d3f93396</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">911</data>
      <data key="d6">ddedfd5179e64700adced4803c75cdba</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: EXPECTED AND ACTUAL LEARNING RATES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves calculating the actual learning rate experienced by Go Fast Cars in manufacturing a new model of its 'lightning' sports car. The quiz compares the budgeted and actual cumulative total times for the first 16 units and requires calculating the actual learning rate and suggesting reasons for the discrepancy."</data>
      <data key="d2">9cf602e35df4af3581c4dce0d3f93396</data>
      <data key="d7">17</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">912</data>
      <data key="d6">07d501edd4614e1d9d08d01b702688a3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STANDARD COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Standard costs" are predetermined costs that serve as a benchmark for measuring performance. They help keep management informed about the economy, efficiency, and effectiveness of production processes and facilitate supervisory personnel being made directly responsible for the variances under their control. Additionally, standard costs represent the predetermined costs of manufacturing a single unit or a number of units during a specific period under current or anticipated operating conditions.</data>
      <data key="d2">42571f76beb61dce71423b12481ee276,a2b172963f635500ceb4bcd40e29a190,dcfa6ded93f92d536f228009c8441446</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">10</data>
      <data key="d5">913</data>
      <data key="d6">f745075dedcf444daa9370cf32403d31</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Variances are differences between actual prices and standard prices, and actual quantities and standard quantities. They provide a measure of the fairness of standards and facilitate further analysis, investigation, and action to eliminate causes of undesirable variances."</data>
      <data key="d2">42571f76beb61dce71423b12481ee276</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">914</data>
      <data key="d6">1ef48284d238405f94190125092a3e28</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VARIANCE ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Variance analysis" is a detailed and quantitative investigation into why actual profits differ from the budget, comparing actual costs against standards. This process involves calculating and interpreting variances to understand the nature and magnitude of these differences. By comparing actual financial performance with budgeted or standard performance, variance analysis helps in identifying and explaining variances. This analysis is crucial for maintaining control over a business, improving operational performance, and aiding in performance evaluation and decision-making.</data>
      <data key="d2">42571f76beb61dce71423b12481ee276,489fab3b5f0c197b72dfe8f1b4118478,6e10c6a7a8877899e48accd3826451e1,f97d81426ba6b512862db11eb6fe561a</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">13</data>
      <data key="d5">915</data>
      <data key="d6">8806b817446447e3b50f5bc85ff497e1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STANDARD COST CARD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"An example of a standard cost card for Product XYZ includes sales price, production costs (materials, labor, variable overhead, fixed overhead), standard cost of production, and standard profit per unit."</data>
      <data key="d2">42571f76beb61dce71423b12481ee276</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">916</data>
      <data key="d6">7303ee20690449db8c168df3fe008bc5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUANTITY STANDARDS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Quantity standards specify how much resource (raw materials, labor) should be input to produce a unit of product/service."</data>
      <data key="d2">42571f76beb61dce71423b12481ee276</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">917</data>
      <data key="d6">2f1c535a14b14758bf1cacca81c74878</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRICE STANDARDS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Price (or cost) standards stipulate how much should be paid for each unit of resource."</data>
      <data key="d2">42571f76beb61dce71423b12481ee276</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">918</data>
      <data key="d6">3b78cc7ce8224afcab3e4bbe550cde10</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VARIANCE INVESTIGATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The main purpose of variance investigation is to improve operational performance by comparing actual cost and performance with the standard cost of actual performance, understanding the nature and magnitude of variances, and taking corrective actions."</data>
      <data key="d2">42571f76beb61dce71423b12481ee276</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">919</data>
      <data key="d6">29ec9dd9f5864170a7e75c46c11c0090</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;USES OF STANDARD COSTING SYSTEMS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Standard costing systems assist in planning, establishing budgets, controlling costs, directing and motivating employees, measuring efficiencies, highlighting opportunities for cost reductions, simplifying the costing of products, and providing a cost basis for tendering contracts or setting sales prices."</data>
      <data key="d2">42571f76beb61dce71423b12481ee276</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">920</data>
      <data key="d6">7893ee15f0e941cbacad8cc1feaacbaf</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLES OF USE OF STANDARD COSTING SYSTEMS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Examples include manufacturing companies using standard cost cards, service centers setting standard labor times and parts for car maintenance, restaurant and drink retail outlets having standards for ingredients and service speed, and hotel chains using standards for laundry, housekeeping, and restaurant operations."</data>
      <data key="d2">42571f76beb61dce71423b12481ee276</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">921</data>
      <data key="d6">f53397f743ca4d7397c0a694fe787da0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;USE OF STANDARDS IN BUDGETING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Standards in budgeting facilitate control, highlight possibilities for cost reductions, use predetermined costs for the budget period, and provide information for reports comparing actual costs with predetermined costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">42571f76beb61dce71423b12481ee276</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">922</data>
      <data key="d6">0041db9da3694ad397f37c76f8477770</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BUDGETS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Budgets are statements of expected costs that direct activities to an agreed action plan, highlighting the volume of activity and level of costs to be maintained as desired by management."</data>
      <data key="d2">dcfa6ded93f92d536f228009c8441446</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">923</data>
      <data key="d6">a7c2a64e06374091adce74adb36801ab</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STANDARDS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Standards" in performance measurement refer to the principles applied in setting targets for managers, including ownership, achievability, and equity. Additionally, standards specify what costs should be for a level of performance achieved, highlighting the level to which costs should be reduced to increase profit.</data>
      <data key="d2">dcfa6ded93f92d536f228009c8441446,e4d4bacb7d841448ad6095b3ddafc290</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">924</data>
      <data key="d6">107568a67cac472c89dfce4bbe11157c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SETTING STANDARDS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Setting standards involves the combined expertise of those responsible for procuring resource inputs and overseeing their use. It aims to encourage efficient future operations and eliminate inefficiencies."</data>
      <data key="d2">dcfa6ded93f92d536f228009c8441446</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">925</data>
      <data key="d6">3d78aa9d14714ac189e4020f78b15d24</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;IDEAL STANDARDS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"IDEAL STANDARDS" refer to benchmarks that can only be attained under perfect operating conditions. These standards do not account for any machine breakdowns, interruptions, or idle time, implying that they represent the highest possible efficiency and performance levels achievable in an ideal scenario.</data>
      <data key="d2">ae2d4ea94e8ed5a50e75345ffd684969,dcfa6ded93f92d536f228009c8441446</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">926</data>
      <data key="d6">ce0366abadef410d9b65e2bfbbf0b0f9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BASIC STANDARDS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Basic standards are long-run average standards based on historical data, which may be out of date and too easy to achieve in the future."</data>
      <data key="d2">dcfa6ded93f92d536f228009c8441446</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">927</data>
      <data key="d6">f4370806deb84d0eb7e85e742e7d4bbf</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CURRENT STANDARDS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Current standards are established for use over a short period, reflecting current conditions. They are time-consuming and costly to implement."</data>
      <data key="d2">dcfa6ded93f92d536f228009c8441446</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">928</data>
      <data key="d6">c92392d168c2443e8ed7b04992d0c92b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ATTAINABLE STANDARDS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Attainable standards are challenging but achievable under existing operating conditions, making allowances for normal machine breakdowns and workforce breaks."</data>
      <data key="d2">dcfa6ded93f92d536f228009c8441446</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">929</data>
      <data key="d6">b5800c807edd4087a2420007272d15d0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INFORMATION USED FOR SETTING STANDARDS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Information used for setting standards includes price per unit of input and quantity used per unit of output, determined through various methods such as market prices, bills of materials, time and motion studies, and wage rates."</data>
      <data key="d2">dcfa6ded93f92d536f228009c8441446</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">930</data>
      <data key="d6">aa247540e90d4a7abc5bca6fafaaffa1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRICE PER UNIT OF INPUT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The price per unit of input is usually set to reflect current market prices for the budgeted period, with adjustments made for external factors."</data>
      <data key="d2">dcfa6ded93f92d536f228009c8441446</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">931</data>
      <data key="d6">34537afa1e954e08bdb52ead3a49e2f3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUANTITY OF MATERIALS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Quantities of materials are determined by a bill of materials prepared by product design, engineering, or a works foreman, with allowances for expected levels of waste."</data>
      <data key="d2">dcfa6ded93f92d536f228009c8441446</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">932</data>
      <data key="d6">ae043af0299f4b32a98cf187efd2a5db</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;WAGE RATES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Wage rates are determined by company policy or negotiations between management and unions, sometimes set before annual wage negotiations are concluded."</data>
      <data key="d2">dcfa6ded93f92d536f228009c8441446</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">933</data>
      <data key="d6">6016863be3414d5a92397f2d45fdfd78</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VARIABLE OVERHEADS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Variable overheads are calculated as a rate per unit of activity, usually direct labour hours or machine hours, based on past data if no direct relationship between resources and output is observable."</data>
      <data key="d2">dcfa6ded93f92d536f228009c8441446</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">934</data>
      <data key="d6">a9b900821b8444d69f432da08a77539f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FIXED OVERHEADS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Fixed overheads" are the fixed costs that do not change with the level of production. They are largely independent of changes in activity and remain constant over wide ranges in the short term, making a fixed overhead rate per unit of activity inappropriate for control purposes. Division B has annual fixed overheads of $5,460,000, while Division A has annual fixed overheads of $2,200,000.</data>
      <data key="d2">34f2c5c9d893c1b631ed1646193eebf4,dcfa6ded93f92d536f228009c8441446</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">935</data>
      <data key="d6">1fee51d6f4614127a3e1cc80d018506e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONTROLLABILITY PRINCIPLE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The controllability principle states that managers should be judged only on things within their control, with performance judged by variances attributed to their department and differences between actual and budgeted figures."</data>
      <data key="d2">dcfa6ded93f92d536f228009c8441446</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">936</data>
      <data key="d6">00dc2c0748214e52bc799ca3e25204e9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: CONTROLLABILITY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz tests understanding of the controllability principle, where managers are judged based on factors within their control, such as variances and differences between actual and budgeted figures."</data>
      <data key="d2">dcfa6ded93f92d536f228009c8441446</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">937</data>
      <data key="d6">42d1a9e749ad40daa34c7b0b695f8751</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sales variances" are calculated to determine the difference between actual sales and budgeted sales. These variances can be broken down into several components, including sales volume variance, sales price variance, market size variance, and market share variance. The process involves using a flexed budget approach to analyze the variances, given the budgeted and actual sales data. This comprehensive analysis helps in understanding the underlying factors contributing to the differences in sales performance.</data>
      <data key="d2">002794ec024434f7ac2bd26217b3897d,ae2d4ea94e8ed5a50e75345ffd684969,c1374ecc954703b220564a8e84b396b1</data>
      <data key="d7">28</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">938</data>
      <data key="d6">20de9a1af6ab4e88acf003cb7be0217c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIALS VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Materials variances are calculated to determine the difference between actual materials costs and standard materials costs. It includes materials price variance and materials usage variance."</data>
      <data key="d2">c1374ecc954703b220564a8e84b396b1</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">939</data>
      <data key="d6">f3229f10a5a54cb1b91a26ffa6ee77a3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LABOUR VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Labour variances are calculated to determine the difference between actual labor costs and standard labor costs. It includes labor rate variance, idle time variance, and labor efficiency variance."</data>
      <data key="d2">c1374ecc954703b220564a8e84b396b1</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">940</data>
      <data key="d6">5154b4a4f3ac43729703c69fccb54633</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VARIABLE OVERHEAD VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Variable overhead variances are calculated to determine the difference between actual variable overhead costs and standard variable overhead costs. It includes variable overhead rate variance and variable overhead efficiency variance."</data>
      <data key="d2">c1374ecc954703b220564a8e84b396b1</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">941</data>
      <data key="d6">2091070e709e45f5ae56d40a9da45520</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FIXED OVERHEAD VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Fixed overhead variances are calculated to determine the difference between actual fixed overhead costs and budgeted fixed overhead costs. It includes fixed overhead expenditure variance."</data>
      <data key="d2">c1374ecc954703b220564a8e84b396b1</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">942</data>
      <data key="d6">09045ef5c4314dde9a631a206274563f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FIXED OVERHEAD EXPENDITURE VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Fixed Overhead Expenditure Variance is calculated by comparing the actual fixed overhead costs incurred with the budgeted fixed overhead costs. The formula for this calculation is: Fixed Overhead Expenditure Variance = Actual fixed cost - Budgeted fixed cost. For example, if the actual fixed overhead cost is $125,400 and the budgeted fixed overhead cost is $115,300, the fixed overhead expenditure variance would be $10,100, which is considered favorable.</data>
      <data key="d2">3e31b0e19c2c3d14cdeebdb3d493eb6b,5725a64a66ba9d34bcfa7d683ea0f78e,a2b172963f635500ceb4bcd40e29a190,a4cf47e869a95203a8e59aeeab342090,b2fef5f7c017e4d460ee5bc5f0a369ef,cf5ffdad7bc11ae55dc09b0b12eb911a,e319e69deae19a71cfd0dee161ba1059,e6dcb0a0bf01250a84f45fc9b4de8a13</data>
      <data key="d7">20</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">8</data>
      <data key="d5">943</data>
      <data key="d6">1b9baa98ede84164883e8cdcbc7000c1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FIXED OVERHEAD VOLUME VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Fixed Overhead Volume Variance is calculated by comparing the actual production with the budgeted production, multiplied by the standard fixed overhead rate per unit. The formula is: Fixed Overhead Volume Variance = (Actual production - Budgeted production) x standard fixed overhead rate per unit. This variance measures the difference between the budgeted output and the actual output, providing insight into how well the production levels align with the budgeted expectations.</data>
      <data key="d2">3e31b0e19c2c3d14cdeebdb3d493eb6b,a4cf47e869a95203a8e59aeeab342090,e319e69deae19a71cfd0dee161ba1059</data>
      <data key="d7">20</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">944</data>
      <data key="d6">e4f3fcc475a74756925b730caffcb70d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FIXED OVERHEAD CAPACITY VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Fixed Overhead Capacity Variance is calculated by comparing the actual labor hours worked with the budgeted labor hours, multiplied by the standard rate per hour. The formula for this calculation is: Fixed Overhead Capacity Variance = (Actual labor hours - Budgeted labor hours) x standard rate per hour. This variance measures the difference between the actual hours worked and the budgeted hours, using the standard fixed overhead absorption rate per hour.

An example calculation of the fixed overhead capacity variance is given as: 119,680 - 125,400 = $5,720 (Adverse). This indicates an adverse variance, meaning the actual labor hours were less than the budgeted labor hours, resulting in a lower capacity to absorb fixed overheads.

A favorable variance, on the other hand, would indicate that the firm has increased capacity to absorb fixed overheads due to more actual labor hours than budgeted. The concept is often tested in quizzes involving the calculation of fixed overhead capacity variance given budgeted and actual production and labor hours.</data>
      <data key="d2">01294aa83ab1143451866d43087f9eba,3e31b0e19c2c3d14cdeebdb3d493eb6b,5725a64a66ba9d34bcfa7d683ea0f78e,a4cf47e869a95203a8e59aeeab342090,ae2d4ea94e8ed5a50e75345ffd684969,cf5ffdad7bc11ae55dc09b0b12eb911a,e319e69deae19a71cfd0dee161ba1059</data>
      <data key="d7">20</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">7</data>
      <data key="d5">945</data>
      <data key="d6">7f3d5282303f4fc3a009e04f7de0ad84</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FIXED OVERHEAD EFFICIENCY VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Fixed Overhead Efficiency Variance" is calculated by comparing the actual labor hours worked with the standard labor hours for actual output, multiplied by the standard rate per hour. The formula for this calculation is: Fixed Overhead Efficiency Variance = (Actual labor hours - Standard labor hours for actual output) x Standard rate per hour. This variance measures the difference between the actual hours worked and the standard hours allowed for the actual output, using the standard fixed overhead absorption rate per hour.</data>
      <data key="d2">3e31b0e19c2c3d14cdeebdb3d493eb6b,a4cf47e869a95203a8e59aeeab342090,cf5ffdad7bc11ae55dc09b0b12eb911a,e319e69deae19a71cfd0dee161ba1059</data>
      <data key="d7">20</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">946</data>
      <data key="d6">1219a14eaf5f49ab84c9287ebf58db7a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES VOLUME VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sales Volume Variance" is a financial metric that measures the difference between the actual quantity of units sold and the budgeted quantity expected to be sold, valued at the standard contribution per unit. It can be calculated using several formulas, including:

1. Sales volume variance = (Actual quantity sold - Budgeted quantity sold) x Standard selling price
2. Sales volume variance = (Actual sales - Budgeted sales) * Standard profit per unit
3. Sales volume variance = (Actual sales quantity - Budgeted sales quantity) * Standard contribution per unit
4. Sales volume variance = (Actual sales volume - Budget sales volume) * Standard contribution

This variance indicates whether more or fewer units were sold than expected and shows the effect on profit of selling more or less than the budgeted quantity. Additionally, sales volume variance can be analyzed into a market size (planning) variance and a market share (operational) variance.</data>
      <data key="d2">002794ec024434f7ac2bd26217b3897d,24cd8c3feefdefe57b7e7da7db59d031,31513de544b09bc77695e746ff044232,3b375b22ae26edc86618262ee6ace048,4ae58f51790b98226f6ec0a6232803a9,9c725f949895b6929ff9aaf34a59aa27,a2b172963f635500ceb4bcd40e29a190,a971d00d99d6f7f6fe13faf691b0e018,e319e69deae19a71cfd0dee161ba1059</data>
      <data key="d7">28</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">16</data>
      <data key="d5">947</data>
      <data key="d6">efaa386bd5e9454b87e1851cd8b28ac3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES PRICE VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sales Price Variance" is a financial metric used to measure the impact on profit due to differences between the actual selling price and the standard selling price. It is calculated by comparing the actual price to the standard price, multiplied by the actual volume sold. The formula for sales price variance is (Actual Selling Price - Standard Selling Price) * Actual Quantity Sold. This variance highlights the effect on profit when products are sold at prices higher or lower than the standard price.</data>
      <data key="d2">002794ec024434f7ac2bd26217b3897d,4ae58f51790b98226f6ec0a6232803a9,5083b641e457d160a51be1a4c3595318,9c725f949895b6929ff9aaf34a59aa27,a2b172963f635500ceb4bcd40e29a190,b2fef5f7c017e4d460ee5bc5f0a369ef,e319e69deae19a71cfd0dee161ba1059</data>
      <data key="d7">28</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">10</data>
      <data key="d5">948</data>
      <data key="d6">073241be9b6a4952ad01dd14b94fb89c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIALS PRICE VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Materials price variance is a financial metric used to measure the difference between the actual cost of materials and the standard cost, multiplied by the actual quantity used or purchased. It is calculated by comparing the actual materials purchased at the actual price with the actual materials purchased at the standard price. This variance helps in understanding whether materials were purchased at a higher or lower price than expected, thereby indicating the impact of price changes on material costs.

For example, for Material X, if the actual cost is $27,000 and the standard cost is $29,700, the resulting variance is favorable by $2,700. Conversely, for Material Y, if the actual cost is $11,000 and the standard cost is $10,600, the variance is adverse by $400. The total materials price variance in this case would be $2,300 favorable.

Additionally, there are different types of price variances such as Traditional Price/Rate Variance, Planning Price Variance, and Operational Price Variance. The Traditional Price/Rate Variance is calculated as the actual quantity multiplied by the actual price minus the actual quantity multiplied by the standard price. The Planning Price Variance is the actual quantity multiplied by the original standard price minus the actual quantity multiplied by the revised standard price. The Operational Price Variance is the actual quantity multiplied by the actual price minus the actual quantity multiplied by the revised standard price.</data>
      <data key="d2">00157cf30936c417d0c54f1dfce77654,24cd8c3feefdefe57b7e7da7db59d031,4ae58f51790b98226f6ec0a6232803a9,6e10c6a7a8877899e48accd3826451e1,b2fef5f7c017e4d460ee5bc5f0a369ef,b36e620f2b07237acde3e68683584a9a,e319e69deae19a71cfd0dee161ba1059</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">11</data>
      <data key="d5">949</data>
      <data key="d6">f7ac6bc4a9ca4250ad29a3adb5d08657</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIALS USAGE VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Materials Usage Variance" is a metric used to measure the efficiency of material usage in production. It is calculated by comparing the actual quantity of materials used to the standard quantity expected for the actual output, and then multiplying the difference by the standard cost per unit. Specifically, the formula is: Materials usage variance = (Actual materials used - Standard quantity for actual output) * Standard cost per kg.

For example, in the case of Material X, the actual quantity used was 9,900 kg, while the standard quantity was 10,000 kg, resulting in a favorable variance of $300. Conversely, for Material Y, the actual quantity used was 5,300 kg compared to a standard quantity of 5,000 kg, leading to an adverse variance of $600. Overall, the total materials usage variance amounted to $300 adverse.

This variance helps in understanding the efficiency of material usage by highlighting the differences between actual and expected material consumption, thereby providing insights into potential areas for improvement in the production process.</data>
      <data key="d2">4ae58f51790b98226f6ec0a6232803a9,6e10c6a7a8877899e48accd3826451e1,b36e620f2b07237acde3e68683584a9a,cf9ca8218733c08007a0ce22b5760713,e319e69deae19a71cfd0dee161ba1059</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">8</data>
      <data key="d5">950</data>
      <data key="d6">ac2ee54e75a2492c8db372dadfccd083</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LABOUR RATE VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Labour rate variance is a financial metric used to measure the difference between the actual hourly wage rate paid and the standard rate expected to be paid, multiplied by the actual hours worked. It is calculated by comparing the actual hours paid at the actual rate with the actual hours paid at the standard rate. This can be expressed mathematically as (Standard Rate - Actual Rate) * Actual Hours paid. Essentially, it evaluates the effect of the actual labor rate differing from the standard labor rate, using the actual hours worked. The quiz on labour rate variance involves calculating this variance given budgeted and actual labour costs and hours.</data>
      <data key="d2">31513de544b09bc77695e746ff044232,4ae58f51790b98226f6ec0a6232803a9,a2b172963f635500ceb4bcd40e29a190,a971d00d99d6f7f6fe13faf691b0e018,ae2d4ea94e8ed5a50e75345ffd684969,b2fef5f7c017e4d460ee5bc5f0a369ef,cf5ffdad7bc11ae55dc09b0b12eb911a,e319e69deae19a71cfd0dee161ba1059</data>
      <data key="d7">20</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">951</data>
      <data key="d6">ee895ad0b8cd40c29465e8527748d847</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;IDLE TIME VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Idle time variance is calculated as the difference between hours paid and hours worked, multiplied by the standard hourly rate."</data>
      <data key="d2">e319e69deae19a71cfd0dee161ba1059</data>
      <data key="d7">20</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">952</data>
      <data key="d6">fe38c996c2d64bc899eabd6389034075</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LABOUR EFFICIENCY VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Labour efficiency variance is a measure used to evaluate the difference between the actual hours worked and the standard hours expected for actual production, multiplied by the standard hourly wage rate. It is calculated by comparing the actual labour hours worked with the standard hours for the actual output, and then multiplying this difference by the standard cost per hour. This variance helps in assessing the efficiency of labour by highlighting the impact of deviations in actual hours worked from the standard hours, using the standard labour rate.</data>
      <data key="d2">31513de544b09bc77695e746ff044232,4ae58f51790b98226f6ec0a6232803a9,a2b172963f635500ceb4bcd40e29a190,a971d00d99d6f7f6fe13faf691b0e018,b2fef5f7c017e4d460ee5bc5f0a369ef,cf5ffdad7bc11ae55dc09b0b12eb911a,cf9ca8218733c08007a0ce22b5760713,e319e69deae19a71cfd0dee161ba1059</data>
      <data key="d7">20</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">11</data>
      <data key="d5">953</data>
      <data key="d6">c0e28ae832c94405b8ddd4d2ad978be5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VARIABLE OVERHEAD RATE VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Variable Overhead Rate Variance is a financial metric used to measure the difference between the actual variable overhead costs incurred and the expected (or standard) variable overhead costs based on labor hours worked. The calculation can be expressed in several ways, but fundamentally, it involves comparing the actual variable overhead cost to the standard cost derived from labor hours and the standard rate. The formula for Variable Overhead Rate Variance is:

Variable Overhead Rate Variance = Actual variable overhead cost - (Labor hours worked x Standard variable overhead rate per hour).

Alternatively, it can also be expressed as:

Variable Overhead Rate Variance = (Standard Rate - Actual Rate) x Actual Hours worked.

In essence, this variance helps in understanding how well a company is managing its variable overhead costs relative to its labor hours and standard rates.</data>
      <data key="d2">4ae58f51790b98226f6ec0a6232803a9,a4cf47e869a95203a8e59aeeab342090,cf5ffdad7bc11ae55dc09b0b12eb911a,e319e69deae19a71cfd0dee161ba1059</data>
      <data key="d7">20</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">954</data>
      <data key="d6">7a4573a19ef94e25b4480cb4d953ae7a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VARIABLE OVERHEAD EFFICIENCY VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1">"Variable Overhead Efficiency Variance" is calculated by comparing the actual labor hours worked with the standard labor hours for actual production, multiplied by the standard variable overhead rate per hour. The formula can be expressed as: Variable Overhead Efficiency Variance = (Labor hours worked - Standard labor hours for actual production) x Standard variable overhead rate per hour. This variance represents the difference between the actual hours worked and the standard hours expected to be worked, multiplied by the standard variable overhead rate.</data>
      <data key="d2">4ae58f51790b98226f6ec0a6232803a9,a2b172963f635500ceb4bcd40e29a190,a4cf47e869a95203a8e59aeeab342090,cf5ffdad7bc11ae55dc09b0b12eb911a,e319e69deae19a71cfd0dee161ba1059</data>
      <data key="d7">20</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">955</data>
      <data key="d6">05f6639803524537b67a7f2b0c66ad23</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPERATING STATEMENT RECONCILIATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The operating statement is a formal reconciliation of budgeted profit to actual profit under absorption costing. It includes reconciling items such as individual variances for sales margin, materials, labor, and overheads."</data>
      <data key="d2">a4cf47e869a95203a8e59aeeab342090</data>
      <data key="d7">20</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">956</data>
      <data key="d6">21bfd14cbc1f4cbc8ac59f7fd8c75b31</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LABOUR IDLE TIME VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Labour idle time variance is calculated as (Standard Hours - Actual Hours paid) * Standard Rate."</data>
      <data key="d2">cf5ffdad7bc11ae55dc09b0b12eb911a</data>
      <data key="d7">20</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">957</data>
      <data key="d6">c19cf2d7b067421990ab9f3acec9e736</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARGINAL COSTING OPERATING STATEMENT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A pro-forma operating statement under marginal costing includes budgeted contribution, sales margin variances, standard profit on actual sales, cost variances, and actual profit."</data>
      <data key="d2">cf5ffdad7bc11ae55dc09b0b12eb911a</data>
      <data key="d7">20</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">9</data>
      <data key="d5">958</data>
      <data key="d6">3e1981b9301c4d339a9228ae7a089a04</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INVENTORY VALUATION AT ACTUAL COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Inventory valued at actual cost includes sales minus costs plus closing inventory. This method carries forward some of the current period's production cost variances in the inventory value."</data>
      <data key="d2">cf5ffdad7bc11ae55dc09b0b12eb911a</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">959</data>
      <data key="d6">0948efa844814529b4c023aacbc23d64</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INVENTORY VALUATION AT STANDARD COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"For internal management control, inventory is usually valued at its standard cost to highlight variances and encourage remedial action."</data>
      <data key="d2">cf5ffdad7bc11ae55dc09b0b12eb911a</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">960</data>
      <data key="d6">fcdc0cc5ff93453eb0b94b9254760999</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GENERAL CAUSES OF VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"General causes of variances include planning errors, measurement errors, random factors, and operational factors."</data>
      <data key="d2">cf5ffdad7bc11ae55dc09b0b12eb911a</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">961</data>
      <data key="d6">0ec4ad4398a8457ab3d71bd2561858dc</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SPECIFIC CAUSES OF VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Specific causes of variances can be categorized as favourable or adverse, such as bulk discounts, market price increases, better quality materials, defective materials, lower skilled labour, wage rises, and strikes."</data>
      <data key="d2">cf5ffdad7bc11ae55dc09b0b12eb911a</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">962</data>
      <data key="d6">3c06988555334a389eab093f98679e85</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: RECONCILIATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves preparing an operating statement for the period under marginal costing, including budgeted contribution, sales margin variances, standard profit on actual sales, cost variances, and actual profit."</data>
      <data key="d2">cf5ffdad7bc11ae55dc09b0b12eb911a</data>
      <data key="d7">20</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">963</data>
      <data key="d6">81ceb8db419b4697ad24e9d7f46422ff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LABOUR RATE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Labour rate refers to the cost of labor, which can be influenced by factors such as lower skilled labor, wage rises, overtime working, and bonus payments."</data>
      <data key="d2">489fab3b5f0c197b72dfe8f1b4118478</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">964</data>
      <data key="d6">fd05d8198d0947b39b8fa1b16f3ecf5f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;IDLE TIME&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Idle time is the period when employees or machines are not productive due to factors like strikes, lack of material, breakdowns, injury/illness, or lack of orders."</data>
      <data key="d2">489fab3b5f0c197b72dfe8f1b4118478</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">965</data>
      <data key="d6">d984f08ad62f47ab9aabb9aeec1b245e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LABOUR EFFICIENCY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Labour efficiency measures the productivity of labor, which can be positively influenced by motivation, higher pay, better equipment, learning effect, better material, and higher skill, or negatively influenced by lower pay, poor equipment, slow working, poor material, and lower skill."</data>
      <data key="d2">489fab3b5f0c197b72dfe8f1b4118478</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">966</data>
      <data key="d6">43603c7868164ac38c659bce7a77f45a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OVERHEAD EXPENDITURE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Overhead expenditure refers to the costs associated with running a business that are not directly tied to production. These can include cost savings/cutbacks, cost increases, excessive service usage, and incorrect split of semi-variable and fixed costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">489fab3b5f0c197b72dfe8f1b4118478</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">967</data>
      <data key="d6">54a20cc6062d4b7193d023b6ff20461f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OVERHEAD EFFICIENCY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Overhead efficiency measures how effectively overhead costs are managed, often related to labor efficiency."</data>
      <data key="d2">489fab3b5f0c197b72dfe8f1b4118478</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">968</data>
      <data key="d6">6bb190069a704ccca3d8e1648a384185</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OVERHEAD CAPACITY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Overhead capacity refers to the productive hours available for overheads, which can be affected by increases in productive hours, excessive idle time, and shortage of plant capacity."</data>
      <data key="d2">489fab3b5f0c197b72dfe8f1b4118478</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">969</data>
      <data key="d6">47d2036509bf408095ab440bd052ac24</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES PRICE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The "Sales Price" is the amount at which a product or service is sold to customers, measured in dollars. It is a critical factor in determining the revenue and profitability of a business. The sales price can be influenced by various factors, including market shortages, the need to increase sales volume, changes in product quality, responses to competitors, and the necessity to pass on cost changes.</data>
      <data key="d2">489fab3b5f0c197b72dfe8f1b4118478,8cdb68f181943c62464c2058a7ab3d96,afe505b1f94b0e6d25ef40e510dfada7</data>
      <data key="d7">13</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">7</data>
      <data key="d5">970</data>
      <data key="d6">c20e6b1418a140389c31c7b71a6eba0c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INTERDEPENDENCE OF VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Interdependence of variances refers to the situation where two or more variances are caused by the same operational factor, necessitating consideration of the overall effect when taking action."</data>
      <data key="d2">489fab3b5f0c197b72dfe8f1b4118478</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">971</data>
      <data key="d6">ad96e5294247465a9c7d5ea8161dc305</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VARIANCE ANALYSIS FORMULAE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Formulae for variances include calculations for sales volume, sales price, materials price, materials usage, labor rate, idle time, labor efficiency, variable overhead rate, variable overhead efficiency, fixed overhead expenditure, fixed overhead volume, fixed overhead capacity, and fixed overhead efficiency."</data>
      <data key="d2">489fab3b5f0c197b72dfe8f1b4118478</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">972</data>
      <data key="d6">25c968bf5a4f48369fded6c260f71540</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ADVANCED VARIANCE ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Advanced variance analysis includes material mix and yield variances, sales mix and quantity variances, and performance analysis."</data>
      <data key="d2">489fab3b5f0c197b72dfe8f1b4118478</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">973</data>
      <data key="d6">269b441634a144219f539202309bc9fb</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIAL MIX AND YIELD VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Material mix and yield variances involve calculating, identifying causes, and explaining variances related to the mix and yield of materials used in production."</data>
      <data key="d2">489fab3b5f0c197b72dfe8f1b4118478</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">974</data>
      <data key="d6">d0baf2392635468db7f5657f89eb2024</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES MIX AND QUANTITY VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sales mix and quantity variances involve calculating, identifying causes, and explaining variances related to the mix and quantity of sales."</data>
      <data key="d2">489fab3b5f0c197b72dfe8f1b4118478</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">975</data>
      <data key="d6">4f29bcf5377d4c9f94ff3f8ca2f8d941</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PERFORMANCE ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Performance analysis involves analyzing and evaluating past performance using the results of variance analysis."</data>
      <data key="d2">489fab3b5f0c197b72dfe8f1b4118478</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">976</data>
      <data key="d6">e7072a582d9b4c1ea8b171ee940d4d6e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;THE CONCEPT OF VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The concept of variances includes basic variances for materials price and usage, assuming a single type of material, while real-world products often use multiple materials."</data>
      <data key="d2">489fab3b5f0c197b72dfe8f1b4118478</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">977</data>
      <data key="d6">cb6fcf84e3d04ef59b01f97ac94823a1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES MIX VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Sales mix variance compares the actual quantities of goods sold to the actual quantities sold at the standard mix. It measures the effect of selling a different mix of products than the budgeted mix, evaluated using the standard contribution per unit. This variance shows the impact on contribution or profit of selling a different mix compared to the standard. An adverse mix variance indicates that customers are buying less of the higher-margin products and are instead purchasing lower-margin products. By analyzing sales mix variance, businesses can understand how changes in the sales mix impact overall profitability.</data>
      <data key="d2">2a57a845054dd3fd23f0910ad239a201,31513de544b09bc77695e746ff044232,6e10c6a7a8877899e48accd3826451e1,838dcacda5281e1aaade85379faf8828</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">978</data>
      <data key="d6">97a21db5f5954e2c8868b298a3f0090e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES QUANTITY VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sales quantity variance" compares the actual quantity of goods sold in the standard mix with the budgeted quantity sold in the standard mix. It measures the effect on contribution or profit of selling a different quantity than budgeted. This variance evaluates the impact of the actual total sales volume differing from the budgeted total sales volume, using the standard contribution per unit. By assessing the variation in the total quantity of products sold compared to the budgeted quantity, sales quantity variance helps in understanding how changes in total sales volume affect overall profitability. An adverse variance may be due to factors such as poor economic conditions or the emergence of a new competitor, and it identifies elements that influence the sales of all products.</data>
      <data key="d2">2a57a845054dd3fd23f0910ad239a201,31513de544b09bc77695e746ff044232,6e10c6a7a8877899e48accd3826451e1,838dcacda5281e1aaade85379faf8828</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">979</data>
      <data key="d6">c8f3e6cadcf34c8fafe8987e4a9b66f8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MIX VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"MIX VARIANCE" is a metric used to measure the effect of using different proportions of materials compared to the standard mix. It is calculated using the formula: Mix variance = (Actual mix percentage - Budgeted mix percentage) x Total actual quantity x Standard contribution per unit. This metric helps in understanding how changes in the mix of materials impact overall costs.</data>
      <data key="d2">6e10c6a7a8877899e48accd3826451e1,9c725f949895b6929ff9aaf34a59aa27</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">980</data>
      <data key="d6">26c9c44e5059429bb8abc3308bc6c814</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;YIELD VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Yield variance" is calculated as the difference between the actual output and the expected output, given the input, multiplied by the standard cost per unit. It measures the difference between the actual output and the expected output based on the actual input, and it helps in understanding the efficiency of the production process. Additionally, yield variance indicates whether the production process was more or less efficient than expected, based on the standard input quantities.</data>
      <data key="d2">0af2d78ba77677f806a697c0deb0ced3,24cd8c3feefdefe57b7e7da7db59d031,6e10c6a7a8877899e48accd3826451e1</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">9</data>
      <data key="d5">981</data>
      <data key="d6">7cea9903153f43b895c0b23d25bc90a3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF MIX AND YIELD VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A perfume is made by mixing essential oils with alcohol. Essential oils cost $15,000 per litre. Alcohol costs $10 per litre. In the standard, 1% of the liquid input is essential oil, and 99% is alcohol. If the production manager uses more oil and less alcohol, this would lead to a more expensive mix, as essential oil costs more than alcohol. This would result in an adverse mix variance. A normal loss of 37.5% of input occurs when making one litre of perfume. Therefore, the standard specifies using 1.6 litres of liquid to make one litre. If the production manager inputs 1.6 litres of inputs and produces more than 1 litre, this would result in a favourable yield variance."</data>
      <data key="d2">6e10c6a7a8877899e48accd3826451e1</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">982</data>
      <data key="d6">b54436ccc23745c88d24edcc3fdd8ed1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CALCULATING THE MIX VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A tabular approach best illustrates how to calculate the mix variance: Actual quantity used (column A) describes the actual amount of each material employed in production. Actual quantity in the standard mix equals the total actual quantity used (total column A) multiplied by the standard proportions. The quantity totals for columns A and B will be the same. Variance due to materials mix equals the third column multiplied by the standard price for each unit of input."</data>
      <data key="d2">6e10c6a7a8877899e48accd3826451e1</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">983</data>
      <data key="d6">977c895bb98d4136a76e8749533154b6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CALCULATING YIELD VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The yield variance compares actual output with the output expected based on the actual input. It amounts to the difference between expected and actual output multiplied by standard cost per unit."</data>
      <data key="d2">6e10c6a7a8877899e48accd3826451e1</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">984</data>
      <data key="d6">8d75cfea884248aba1f372de5e1b82a9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: MATERIALS MIX AND YIELD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves calculating various material variances, including total materials cost, materials price, materials mix, materials yield, and materials usage, based on given data for a product's standard and actual material usage and costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">6e10c6a7a8877899e48accd3826451e1</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">985</data>
      <data key="d6">90f4ee186bcd4996ad8002888569fffc</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES VOLUME VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">6e10c6a7a8877899e48accd3826451e1</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">986</data>
      <data key="d6">4bb78401581b4240b0967309e96af00b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIALS MIX VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Materials mix variance" measures the difference between the actual mix of materials used in production and the standard mix, valued at the standard cost. It indicates whether more or less of certain materials were used than expected. For Material X, the actual quantity used is 9,900 kg compared to the standard mix of 10,133 kg, resulting in a favorable variance of $699. For Material Y, the actual quantity used is 5,300 kg compared to the standard mix of 5,067 kg, resulting in an adverse variance of $466. The total materials mix variance is $233 favorable.</data>
      <data key="d2">24cd8c3feefdefe57b7e7da7db59d031,b36e620f2b07237acde3e68683584a9a</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">7</data>
      <data key="d5">987</data>
      <data key="d6">a18dd9ea4143411cb32e261db056cf0c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIALS YIELD VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Materials yield variance is calculated by comparing the actual output with the expected yield based on the standard usage. The actual output is 5,000 units, while the expected yield is 5,067 units, resulting in an adverse variance of $536. An alternative approach calculates the variance by comparing the actual quantity in the standard mix with the standard quantity for actual output, resulting in an adverse variance of $533."</data>
      <data key="d2">b36e620f2b07237acde3e68683584a9a</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">988</data>
      <data key="d6">cd8d9795f540413390927ea2a9e77c26</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIALS MIX AND YIELD QUIZ&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The quiz for Materials Mix and Yield involves calculating the materials mix variance and yield variance for Chemical X, which is made by combining three substances in a furnace. The standard cost and actual inputs are provided, and the variances are calculated based on the differences between actual and standard quantities and costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">b36e620f2b07237acde3e68683584a9a</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">989</data>
      <data key="d6">2917f3b478b04ffcacd4b47602f4d0f5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TOTAL MATERIALS COST VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">b36e620f2b07237acde3e68683584a9a</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">990</data>
      <data key="d6">3984bd063b384901862e68506c77cc68</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STANDARD PROPORTIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Standard proportions are the predetermined ratios of materials expected to be used in production. For example, Material A: 60%, Material B: 20%, Material C: 20%."</data>
      <data key="d2">0af2d78ba77677f806a697c0deb0ced3</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">991</data>
      <data key="d6">4137a2c7dd884bc2a8469b7fa937346c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ACTUAL QUANTITY IN STANDARD MIX&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Actual quantity in standard mix is calculated by applying the standard proportions to the actual quantity used."</data>
      <data key="d2">0af2d78ba77677f806a697c0deb0ced3</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">992</data>
      <data key="d6">60b6bf585ccc477d830d4b69b8c7b62a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STANDARD YIELD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Standard yield is the expected output from a given input, expressed as a percentage. For example, 125 kg of input yields 100 kg of output, so the standard yield is 80%."</data>
      <data key="d2">0af2d78ba77677f806a697c0deb0ced3</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">993</data>
      <data key="d6">4330f73cb78a4bb39a384eb29112201b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INTERPRETING MATERIAL MIX AND YIELD VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Interpreting material mix and yield variances involves understanding the implications of variances on cost and quality. A favourable mix variance means cheaper materials were used, while a favourable yield variance means more output was achieved than expected."</data>
      <data key="d2">0af2d78ba77677f806a697c0deb0ced3</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">994</data>
      <data key="d6">45c4ed77967746e485ec9e52c0dcc0d2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INTER-RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN PRICE, MIX AND YIELD VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The inter-relationship between price, mix, and yield variances highlights how changes in one can affect the others. For example, cheaper materials may lead to favourable price variances but unfavourable yield variances due to lower quality."</data>
      <data key="d2">0af2d78ba77677f806a697c0deb0ced3</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">995</data>
      <data key="d6">17c2cc25d00347c3bf2422d4f7a4ad7e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF VARYING MATERIALS MIX&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"An example of varying materials mix is cooking a meal at home and not following the recipe precisely, leading to a different mix of ingredients."</data>
      <data key="d2">0af2d78ba77677f806a697c0deb0ced3</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">996</data>
      <data key="d6">0057fb2ddc0e4088ae5099b7ffa137da</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REASONS FOR VARYING THE MIX&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Reasons for varying the mix include changes in material prices, inaccurate measurement, or intentionally using a cheaper mix to achieve a favourable mix variance."</data>
      <data key="d2">0af2d78ba77677f806a697c0deb0ced3</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">997</data>
      <data key="d6">d67d67cc3698438db76eb4a7f75e1ea0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;IMPACT OF VARYING THE MIX&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The impact of varying the mix includes achieving a favourable mix variance but potentially leading to lower yield and quality, which can affect long-term sales and customer satisfaction."</data>
      <data key="d2">0af2d78ba77677f806a697c0deb0ced3</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">998</data>
      <data key="d6">c23761290af24cf29adc1ee8644bdad0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ALTERNATIVE METHODS OF CONTROLLING PRODUCTION PROCESSES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Alternative methods of controlling production processes involve evaluating managers on more than just material mix and yield variances to ensure quality and other important factors are considered."</data>
      <data key="d2">0af2d78ba77677f806a697c0deb0ced3</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">999</data>
      <data key="d6">de51b828ce1f442bbb19a7b20bce9dda</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIAL MIX&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">0af2d78ba77677f806a697c0deb0ced3</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">7</data>
      <data key="d5">1000</data>
      <data key="d6">4a3ff6a3471945fd8c7fd5c171c56d56</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CALCULATING THE SALES MIX VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sales mix variance = (Actual sales units - Actual sales units in budgeted mix) * Standard margin"</data>
      <data key="d2">2a57a845054dd3fd23f0910ad239a201</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1001</data>
      <data key="d6">31bb84eb2a834dabacc0ed51af4fcefd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CALCULATING THE SALES QUANTITY VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sales quantity variance = (Actual sales in budgeted mix - Budgeted sales) * Standard margin"</data>
      <data key="d2">2a57a845054dd3fd23f0910ad239a201</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1002</data>
      <data key="d6">5070012e83e7442381bcba1cdacdb7d8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES PRICE, MIX AND QUANTITY VARIANCES QUIZ&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves calculating the sales price variance, sales mix contribution variance, and sales quantity variances for three related products Q, P, and R based on given budgeted and actual sales data."</data>
      <data key="d2">2a57a845054dd3fd23f0910ad239a201</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1003</data>
      <data key="d6">5eda9074df124f5497f17b61badd52ac</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF CONTRIBUTION MARGIN&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A coffee drinker decides to stop buying an expensive coffee beverage from a coffeehouse chain and switches to a cheaper drink from the same chain but continues to buy the same number of cups of coffee. This would reduce the contribution margin of the coffee seller."</data>
      <data key="d2">838dcacda5281e1aaade85379faf8828</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1004</data>
      <data key="d6">4cf4107b0e2842778aaa658a1a85f3b3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PLANNING AND OPERATIONAL VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Planning and operational variances" are utilized to calculate a revised budget, identify and explain factors that could and could not be allowed to revise an original budget, and calculate, identify the cause of, and explain variances for sales, materials, and labor. These variances are instrumental in distinguishing between those caused by changes in planning assumptions and those resulting from operational performance. They help in identifying whether variances are due to external factors or internal inefficiencies, thereby providing a comprehensive understanding of the underlying reasons for budget deviations.</data>
      <data key="d2">838dcacda5281e1aaade85379faf8828,f6982a4563820b317a7b745f9ea9c299</data>
      <data key="d7">17</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">1005</data>
      <data key="d6">7f4857f94b4e4e49be7236a42071e167</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BUDGET REVISIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"BUDGET REVISIONS" form a critical component of performance management systems. Initially, a budget is established to serve as a benchmark against which an organization's actual results can be compared to assess performance. While changes to the budget can be permitted under certain circumstances, these revisions must be meticulously controlled to prevent potential abuse. The process of revising budgets involves identifying factors that justify a revision and those that do not, as well as applying specific principles to ensure the integrity of the budgetary process. This topic is explored in a quiz that includes questions about the criteria for revising an original budget and the principles that should guide such revisions.</data>
      <data key="d2">398230bc0b5f27c6546a25d2a2e97611,838dcacda5281e1aaade85379faf8828</data>
      <data key="d7">17</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1006</data>
      <data key="d6">d21a1fef903f4a399bd3cd366aad3c9e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRINCIPLES OF BUDGET REVISIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The principles of budget revisions include revising the budget if something occurred during the budget period that was outside the control of the manager, not revising budgets to hide inefficiencies, and ensuring that senior management approves only appropriate revisions."</data>
      <data key="d2">838dcacda5281e1aaade85379faf8828</data>
      <data key="d7">17</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1007</data>
      <data key="d6">fc596a598ff74a4c843e405b597551b5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: BUDGET REVISIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves discussing which events should result in budget revisions for an airline, considering factors like increased fuel prices, a strike, and a volcanic eruption. The quiz aims to evaluate understanding of when budget revisions are appropriate."</data>
      <data key="d2">00157cf30936c417d0c54f1dfce77654</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1008</data>
      <data key="d6">e2aacff6b4404574b818e7a3ece57b5b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TRADITIONAL VARIANCE ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Traditional variance analysis compares actual performance versus expected performance. Management should consider revising standards if the actual environment differs from what was anticipated or if hindsight shows an unrealistic standard was used."</data>
      <data key="d2">00157cf30936c417d0c54f1dfce77654</data>
      <data key="d7">28</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1009</data>
      <data key="d6">2ec5cae98c7a485881f0680fbca6d67f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PLANNING VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Planning variance" arises when an original budget is revised with the benefit of hindsight, i.e., after the fact. It can relate to any element of the standard product specification or to sales/production volumes. Planning variance is the difference between the original standard cost and the revised standard cost of actual output. In this case, it is $390,400 (A). Additionally, planning variance refers to the difference between the original budgeted performance and the revised budgeted performance, which can be attributed to changes in external factors or inaccurate initial forecasts.</data>
      <data key="d2">00157cf30936c417d0c54f1dfce77654,9c725f949895b6929ff9aaf34a59aa27,be8ddb66c7e66aaac8c9da8e08378f00</data>
      <data key="d7">28</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">9</data>
      <data key="d5">1010</data>
      <data key="d6">c87b815d61af448596d3194a804b57b3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPERATIONAL VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Operational variance" arises when actual performance differs from a revised standard. It is calculated similarly to traditional variances but uses a revised standard. This variance refers to the difference between the actual performance and the expected performance, which can be attributed to factors within the control of the management, such as efficiency and effectiveness in operations.</data>
      <data key="d2">00157cf30936c417d0c54f1dfce77654,9c725f949895b6929ff9aaf34a59aa27</data>
      <data key="d7">28</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">1011</data>
      <data key="d6">2f92fc82c3b74417896bad3bd8e61f5e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PLANNING COST VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Planning cost variances are calculated by analyzing traditional variances into planning and operational variances. This approach is preferred for performance management exams."</data>
      <data key="d2">00157cf30936c417d0c54f1dfce77654</data>
      <data key="d7">28</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1012</data>
      <data key="d6">fb61c68efe5b4d69a9623e531e7c639c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: MATERIALS PRICE VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves calculating traditional material price variance, planning price variance, and operational price variance for Material X, and commenting on how the operational price variance provides a fairer indication of the purchasing manager's performance."</data>
      <data key="d2">00157cf30936c417d0c54f1dfce77654</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1013</data>
      <data key="d6">dc61e34c1ca8419e923aeeff7d83d949</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PLANNING PRICE VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The "PLANNING PRICE VARIANCE" is a financial metric used to measure the difference between the revised standard price and the original standard price of materials, multiplied by the actual quantity used. Specifically, it is calculated as (Revised standard price - Original standard price) * Actual quantity. For example, if the revised standard price is $2.80, the original standard price is $2.50, and the actual quantity is 86,000 units, the planning price variance would be $25,800 adverse. This variance helps in comparing the actual cost of materials at the original standard price with the actual cost at the revised standard price, highlighting any discrepancies.</data>
      <data key="d2">303f0ef8328d2aefc4bfae1067a85f72,cf9ca8218733c08007a0ce22b5760713</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1014</data>
      <data key="d6">697fb824eef34759852f1d5588921aec</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPERATIONAL PRICE VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Operational Price Variance" is calculated by comparing the actual cost of materials at the actual price with the actual cost of materials at the revised standard price. The formula for operational price variance is (Actual price - Revised standard price) * Actual quantity. For example, if the actual price is $3.00, the revised standard price is $2.80, and the actual quantity is 86,000 units, the operational price variance would be (3.00 - 2.80) * 86,000, resulting in an adverse variance of $17,200.</data>
      <data key="d2">303f0ef8328d2aefc4bfae1067a85f72,cf9ca8218733c08007a0ce22b5760713</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1015</data>
      <data key="d6">b872fcc5b18a4f32b976f4693f22e88e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PLANNING USAGE VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Planning usage variance" is calculated by comparing the original standard quantity for actual output with the revised standard quantity for actual output, multiplied by the original standard price per unit. Specifically, it is determined using the formula: (Original standard quantity for actual output - Revised standard quantity for actual output) * Original standard price. For example, if the original standard quantity is 88,000 units and the revised standard quantity is 82,500 units, with an original standard price of $2.50 per unit, the planning usage variance would be (88,000 - 82,500) * 2.50, resulting in a $13,750 favorable variance.</data>
      <data key="d2">303f0ef8328d2aefc4bfae1067a85f72,cf9ca8218733c08007a0ce22b5760713</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1016</data>
      <data key="d6">64be9b98299f4d349e0f4358685ca235</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPERATIONAL USAGE VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Operational usage variance" is calculated by comparing the actual quantity used with the revised standard quantity for actual output, multiplied by the original standard price per unit. In this case, it is determined as follows: (Actual quantity used - Revised standard quantity for actual output) * Original standard price. Specifically, it is (86,000 - 82,500) * 2.50, resulting in an adverse variance of $8,750.</data>
      <data key="d2">303f0ef8328d2aefc4bfae1067a85f72,cf9ca8218733c08007a0ce22b5760713</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1017</data>
      <data key="d6">8302a03f6ede471bb955c0bbf44a4b3c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PLANNING EFFICIENCY VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Planning efficiency variance is calculated by comparing the original standard hours for actual output with the revised standard hours for actual output, multiplied by the standard rate per hour."</data>
      <data key="d2">cf9ca8218733c08007a0ce22b5760713</data>
      <data key="d7">20</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1018</data>
      <data key="d6">a02263dd89964a1c8ab2d0e9aba0f4eb</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPERATIONAL EFFICIENCY VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Operational efficiency variance" is calculated by comparing the actual hours worked with the revised standard hours for actual output, multiplied by the standard rate per hour. This metric measures the difference in hours between actual performance and revised standards, indicating how efficiently labor was used. It is measured in hours.</data>
      <data key="d2">303f0ef8328d2aefc4bfae1067a85f72,cf9ca8218733c08007a0ce22b5760713</data>
      <data key="d7">20</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1019</data>
      <data key="d6">6b7aa6ce4cac4edbaaab831286e67e5e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: LABOUR EFFICIENCY VARIANCES AND OPERATIONAL VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves calculating traditional labour efficiency variance, planning efficiency variance, and operational efficiency variance for a new product, and commenting on how the operational efficiency variance provides a more appropriate indication of the factory manager's performance."</data>
      <data key="d2">cf9ca8218733c08007a0ce22b5760713</data>
      <data key="d7">20</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1020</data>
      <data key="d6">655d40ea08e348ad94ae49785797da90</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TRADITIONAL PRICE VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1">"TRADITIONAL PRICE VARIANCE" refers to the difference between the standard price and the actual price of a product, multiplied by the actual quantity purchased. Specifically, it is calculated using the formula: Price variance = (Standard price - Actual price) * Actual quantity. For example, if the standard price is $2.50, the actual price is $3.00, and the actual quantity is 86,000 units, the traditional price variance would be (2.50 - 3.00) * 86,000, resulting in an adverse variance of $43,000.</data>
      <data key="d2">303f0ef8328d2aefc4bfae1067a85f72,cf9ca8218733c08007a0ce22b5760713</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1021</data>
      <data key="d6">254cea99330f4f2aa062c771146da7ea</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TRADITIONAL EFFICIENCY VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Traditional efficiency variance is the difference between the actual hours worked and the standard hours for actual output, multiplied by the standard rate per hour. It reflects the efficiency of labor usage."</data>
      <data key="d2">303f0ef8328d2aefc4bfae1067a85f72</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1022</data>
      <data key="d6">a2836232227c4e3383d166db860cb2a3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REVISED STANDARD HOURS FOR ACTUAL OUTPUT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Revised standard hours for actual output are the adjusted standard hours that reflect a more realistic measure of the time required to produce the actual output. In this case, it is 300 hours."</data>
      <data key="d2">303f0ef8328d2aefc4bfae1067a85f72</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1023</data>
      <data key="d6">8a9247ee9bac45bdbf69c9d0bb8419b5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LABOUR OPERATIONAL EFFICIENCY VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Labour operational efficiency variance is the difference between the actual hours worked and the revised standard hours for actual output, multiplied by the standard rate per hour. For the month of May, the labour operational efficiency variance is calculated as follows: Actual labour hours minus the revised standard quantity for actual output, multiplied by the standard rate per hour. In this specific instance, the variance is $200 adverse. Additionally, this calculation involves considering the premium paid to labor to meet the deadline for an urgent order placed by Goalby Co&#8217;s biggest customer.</data>
      <data key="d2">1aa84a5288fe62c1d778b9f9013d51c3,303f0ef8328d2aefc4bfae1067a85f72,9c3ce103fc83f7ae19dde7d2e5b4ef01</data>
      <data key="d7">20</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1024</data>
      <data key="d6">757a0f78fcdd4bf6b8326a75fcee9e15</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: MATERIALS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves calculating traditional variances, analyzing price and usage variances into planning and operational components, and comparing the results to understand material cost efficiency."</data>
      <data key="d2">303f0ef8328d2aefc4bfae1067a85f72</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">7</data>
      <data key="d5">1025</data>
      <data key="d6">b5235cb24b8f440389f250ebd5b6e2f8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TRADITIONAL USAGE VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Usage variance = (Standard quantity for actual output - Actual quantity) * Standard price. In this case, it is (22,000 * 4 - 86,000) * 2.50 = $5,000 favorable."</data>
      <data key="d2">303f0ef8328d2aefc4bfae1067a85f72</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1026</data>
      <data key="d6">bdee1849252749efa2e671ed87641f61</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OVERALL MATERIAL VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Overall material variance is the sum of price variance and usage variance. In this case, it is $43,000 adverse + $5,000 favorable = $38,000 adverse."</data>
      <data key="d2">303f0ef8328d2aefc4bfae1067a85f72</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1027</data>
      <data key="d6">057641c1476247958d8c357e17095d8e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: LEARNING CURVES AND VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves calculating traditional labor rate and efficiency variances, and re-calculating them considering the learning curve effect."</data>
      <data key="d2">303f0ef8328d2aefc4bfae1067a85f72</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1028</data>
      <data key="d6">b61dfd0b24664f37af4046bdf0cb7b19</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RE-CALCULATED LABOUR EFFICIENCY VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Re-calculated labour efficiency variance = Actual labour hours * Standard rate - Standard hours for actual production (taking into account the learning rate) * Standard rate"</data>
      <data key="d2">a971d00d99d6f7f6fe13faf691b0e018</data>
      <data key="d7">17</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1029</data>
      <data key="d6">0bc00f14e6194df7b0fe9ef9ba28d34f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARKET SIZE VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Market size variance" is a financial metric used to measure the difference between actual and expected market performance. It can be calculated using several formulas. One method is: (Actual market size * Budgeted market share - Budgeted sales quantity) * Standard contribution/profit per unit. Another approach is: (Revised sales volume - Budget sales volume) * Standard contribution. A third formula is: (Original budget quantity - Revised standard quantity) * Standard contribution/profit per unit. Each of these methods provides a way to assess the impact of market size changes on profitability.</data>
      <data key="d2">002794ec024434f7ac2bd26217b3897d,3b375b22ae26edc86618262ee6ace048,a971d00d99d6f7f6fe13faf691b0e018</data>
      <data key="d7">28</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">1030</data>
      <data key="d6">b823c5d22037423da919eee6c35c4c8b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARKET SHARE VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Market share variance (sales volume operational variance) measures the difference between the actual sales volume and the revised budgeted sales volume, based on the actual market size. It helps in understanding the impact of market share changes on sales volume. The formula for calculating market share variance is: (Actual sales quantity - Revised budgeted quantity) * Standard contribution/profit per unit. Alternatively, it can also be expressed as (Actual sales volume - revised sales volume) * standard contribution. Essentially, market share variance is the difference between the actual sales and the budgeted market share of the actual market. For instance, in a quiz scenario involving Riley Co, the market share variance would be calculated by considering the actual market size and sales achieved compared to the budgeted market share and sales."</data>
      <data key="d2">002794ec024434f7ac2bd26217b3897d,24cd8c3feefdefe57b7e7da7db59d031,3b375b22ae26edc86618262ee6ace048,9c3ce103fc83f7ae19dde7d2e5b4ef01,a971d00d99d6f7f6fe13faf691b0e018,be74ed4bd34df6912280d8d2f063e164</data>
      <data key="d7">28</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">7</data>
      <data key="d5">1031</data>
      <data key="d6">cd7f555e4ab948ba94bade14e262ff84</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES PLANNING AND OPERATIONAL VARIANCES QUIZ&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves calculating the traditional sales volume variance, market size variance, and market share variance for Acme based on given sales data."</data>
      <data key="d2">a971d00d99d6f7f6fe13faf691b0e018</data>
      <data key="d7">28</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1032</data>
      <data key="d6">86cd53087b2542f898d6cecca31e6145</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ADVANTAGES AND DISADVANTAGES OF VARIANCE ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Advantages include distinguishing between variances caused by planning or operating factors and providing feedback control. Disadvantages are not provided in the text."</data>
      <data key="d2">a971d00d99d6f7f6fe13faf691b0e018</data>
      <data key="d7">28</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1033</data>
      <data key="d6">5dc3480806b04fdd8089a3be46e22540</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STANDARD LABOUR COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1">The "STANDARD LABOUR COST" was calculated as 2 hours of labor at a rate of $10 per hour.</data>
      <data key="d2">1aa84a5288fe62c1d778b9f9013d51c3,a971d00d99d6f7f6fe13faf691b0e018</data>
      <data key="d7">20</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1034</data>
      <data key="d6">50c91820a91f488d8606198540aba894</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ADVANTAGES OF VARIANCE ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Advantages of variance analysis include distinguishing between variances caused by bad planning or unavoidable factors and those resulting from operating factors, providing feedback control on processes needing correction, updating standards to current conditions, and improving motivation by assessing managers only on variances under their control."</data>
      <data key="d2">be74ed4bd34df6912280d8d2f063e164</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1035</data>
      <data key="d6">a38eace89e7e40de8f007fde24597e9e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DISADVANTAGES OF VARIANCE ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Disadvantages of variance analysis include extra data requirements, being time-consuming, potential manipulation by managers claiming external causes for adverse variances and internal causes for favorable variances, and operational managers blaming poor standard setting for adverse variances."</data>
      <data key="d2">be74ed4bd34df6912280d8d2f063e164</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1036</data>
      <data key="d6">5d75097d065e4b049a1678deab40949b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MANIPULATION OF BUDGETS AND STANDARDS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Manipulation of budgets and standards refers to the revision of budgets and standards at the end of the year to hide adverse variances, which should be prevented by strict rules and independent, verifiable evidence."</data>
      <data key="d2">be74ed4bd34df6912280d8d2f063e164</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1037</data>
      <data key="d6">c277134d380a42cd886a14a953554792</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EFFECT ON STAFF MOTIVATION AND ACTION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Effect on staff motivation and action refers to how variance analysis and standard costing can impact the motivation of managers and staff, potentially leading to morale issues if used insensitively, and causing employees to conceal adverse variances or take actions that may not be in the company's best interests."</data>
      <data key="d2">be74ed4bd34df6912280d8d2f063e164</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1038</data>
      <data key="d6">b680be879404440885b1d3af5b9af583</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PERFORMANCE EVALUATION USING VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Performance evaluation using variances involves using variance analysis to assess the performance of managers and staff, identifying the causes of variances, and determining who is responsible for them."</data>
      <data key="d2">be74ed4bd34df6912280d8d2f063e164</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1039</data>
      <data key="d6">4cc609b1a64a442aac6b72078a315ac6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CAUSES OF VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Causes of variances can include factors such as buying cheaper materials leading to favorable price variances but adverse usage variances, and other common factors affecting multiple variances."</data>
      <data key="d2">be74ed4bd34df6912280d8d2f063e164</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1040</data>
      <data key="d6">a3ee323c9c9a4f81b5907030122b80d2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RESPONSIBILITY FOR VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Responsibility for variances typically lies with specific departments and managers, such as the purchasing department for materials price variance, human resources or factory manager for labor rate variances, and production manager for material usage variances."</data>
      <data key="d2">be74ed4bd34df6912280d8d2f063e164</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1041</data>
      <data key="d6">19aa5f0b738c4f4a96668c80c3e93331</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MIX AND YIELD VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Mix and yield variances are typically controlled by the production manager, who supervises the production process. However, these may also be affected by the quality of materials used, which could be the responsibility of the purchasing manager."</data>
      <data key="d2">a54e72ff2ad2a8799c6e772418b1a195</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1042</data>
      <data key="d6">f8402b10349f4db888ac4fb6fd81723a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OVERHEAD VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Overhead variances are the responsibility of the appropriate managers, such as equipment maintenance expenditure depending on the maintenance manager."</data>
      <data key="d2">a54e72ff2ad2a8799c6e772418b1a195</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1043</data>
      <data key="d6">5927f9089289429da4adf2bbd5641e44</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPERATIONAL VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Operational variances" are a better reflection of the underlying performance of managers and are calculated using the revised standard. They are generally a more reliable indicator of performance than traditional variances and should be revised if they become outdated or unreasonable.</data>
      <data key="d2">a54e72ff2ad2a8799c6e772418b1a195,dde6d5d3f80c5f7be94b41e612ddb0c0</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">7</data>
      <data key="d5">1044</data>
      <data key="d6">60724b8b268044b69a4b3d939f1757e2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF NON-FINANCIAL FACTORS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A past exam question involved a company that manufactured soup. The production manager kept costs down, reporting large favourable mix and yield variances, but this led to a decline in product quality and customer complaints, ultimately threatening long-term demand and profits."</data>
      <data key="d2">a54e72ff2ad2a8799c6e772418b1a195</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1045</data>
      <data key="d6">d931685d35e149909472f736114ca62f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;IMPROVING FUTURE PERFORMANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"After identifying the causes of variances, appropriate actions can be taken to ensure future performance improves, such as including non-financial factors in managers' appraisal systems, regularly reviewing and updating variances, and using target costing to identify ways to reduce costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">a54e72ff2ad2a8799c6e772418b1a195</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1046</data>
      <data key="d6">3f5e9927a4114a958d75f5ed313526a8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RELEVANCE OF VARIANCES IN THE MODERN ENVIRONMENT OF JIT AND TQM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Variance analysis may not be relevant in the modern, rapidly changing business world and can lead to dysfunctional behaviour. JIT and TQM environments emphasize qualitative performance and tailored production, making traditional variance analysis less meaningful."</data>
      <data key="d2">a54e72ff2ad2a8799c6e772418b1a195</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1047</data>
      <data key="d6">4728bf0cb7564bbd85c90ceaa846f290</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BEHAVIOURAL PROBLEMS IN RAPIDLY CHANGING ENVIRONMENTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Standard costing and variance analysis can have adverse effects on behaviour in a rapidly changing environment, such as focusing too much on internal standards and not reflecting learning curves associated with new products."</data>
      <data key="d2">a54e72ff2ad2a8799c6e772418b1a195</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1048</data>
      <data key="d6">cdac6338c3234797a0d3a32cd68d1b2e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SUMMARY OF VARIANCE ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Actual performance is compared with budgets at the end of each budget period. Standards may be revised before performing variance analysis, and traditional cost variances can be analyzed into planning and operational variances."</data>
      <data key="d2">a54e72ff2ad2a8799c6e772418b1a195</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1049</data>
      <data key="d6">372f78df13f9452b84d898c703a1ba95</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIAL USAGE VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">a54e72ff2ad2a8799c6e772418b1a195</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1050</data>
      <data key="d6">7af06d2b32a941a4b044579a7c423371</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STANDARD COSTING AND VARIANCE ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Standard costing and variance analysis aim to improve operational efficiency by comparing actual performance to standard performance and analyzing variances."</data>
      <data key="d2">3b375b22ae26edc86618262ee6ace048</data>
      <data key="d7">28</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1051</data>
      <data key="d6">a10b8fad74744ae981747dadf7234b78</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FINANCIAL PERFORMANCE INDICATORS (FPIS)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Financial performance indicators (FPIs) include measures such as profitability, liquidity, efficiency, and gearing. These traditional performance measures focus on financial aspects such as return on capital, profit margins, and liquidity ratios."</data>
      <data key="d2">3b375b22ae26edc86618262ee6ace048,3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">7</data>
      <data key="d5">1052</data>
      <data key="d6">0cb2118ecc87439a91409deef7ef9830</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NON-FINANCIAL PERFORMANCE INDICATORS (NFPIS)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Non-financial performance indicators (NFPIs) are measures that focus on qualitative aspects of performance, such as product quality, customer satisfaction, and staff morale. These indicators assess aspects of performance that are not directly related to financial metrics and are used to supplement financial measures. By evaluating these qualitative factors, NFPIs provide a more comprehensive understanding of an organization's overall performance.</data>
      <data key="d2">3b375b22ae26edc86618262ee6ace048,3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1053</data>
      <data key="d6">ea27218042d640fd81c23eb64aff6b46</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RETURN ON EQUITY (ROE)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Return on equity (ROE) is a financial metric used to measure the profitability of a company in relation to its equity. It is calculated as Profit after tax divided by the sum of Share capital and reserves, multiplied by 100. Alternatively, ROE can also be expressed as Profit before or after tax divided by Equity. This ratio provides insight into how effectively a company is using its equity to generate profits.</data>
      <data key="d2">3b375b22ae26edc86618262ee6ace048,92d19303f11122ce7fe6d2e698547f59</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1054</data>
      <data key="d6">9e5d626681094933abf87cf797f2fa46</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RETURN ON CAPITAL EMPLOYED (ROCE)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Return on Capital Employed (ROCE) is a financial metric used to measure the profitability and efficiency of a company's capital investments. It is calculated as the operating profit divided by the sum of equity and long-term liabilities, multiplied by 100. Alternatively, ROCE can also be expressed as the product of asset turnover and operating profit margin. Another way to calculate ROCE is by dividing profit before interest and tax by capital employed, then multiplying by 100. This metric provides insight into how well a company is generating profits from its capital and is a key indicator of financial performance.</data>
      <data key="d2">3b375b22ae26edc86618262ee6ace048,92d19303f11122ce7fe6d2e698547f59,bc0524558467e4e3eec1a2e2e05b5d33</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1055</data>
      <data key="d6">545358ff14f84601a22e9f39f5ef1534</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CAPITAL EMPLOYED&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Capital employed" is the total amount of capital used for the acquisition of profits. It is equivalent to total assets less current liabilities or total equity plus long-term debt. This includes non-current assets, inventory, and trade receivables, minus trade payables.</data>
      <data key="d2">312c3cf9edbc058c6e810c1e9c9cd81a,3b375b22ae26edc86618262ee6ace048</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">1056</data>
      <data key="d6">1b0e7dbc7c5944a7833f6540bde1fa4f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PROFIT MARGINS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"PROFIT MARGINS" are a financial performance indicator that measures the profitability of an organization relative to its revenue. Profit margins relate profit to revenue and can be calculated at different levels of profit reported in the financial statements.</data>
      <data key="d2">3b375b22ae26edc86618262ee6ace048,3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f,ef397e6799b0f28d4dca7dd76974e0a1</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1057</data>
      <data key="d6">0c0f2d8c623949f1ae89c67d0753aeab</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPERATIONAL USAGE (EFFICIENCY) VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">3b375b22ae26edc86618262ee6ace048</data>
      <data key="d7">28</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1058</data>
      <data key="d6">20c3844c80a140ac97b62dc444feee41</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GROSS PROFIT MARGIN&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The "Gross Profit Margin" is a financial metric calculated as Gross Profit divided by Revenue, multiplied by 100. It represents the percentage of revenue that exceeds the cost of goods sold, thereby indicating the profitability of a product or service. This metric is crucial for assessing the efficiency and effectiveness of a company's management in generating profit from sales. For instance, the gross profit margin increased from 27.7% to 36.3% in 20X9, reflecting positively on management's performance. Additionally, the gross profit margin for quarter 1 is 52%, and for quarter 2, it is 50%, further illustrating the company's profitability over different periods.</data>
      <data key="d2">963bb5be84f30224d6e25ea423602dfd,afe505b1f94b0e6d25ef40e510dfada7,e46ba1df72ea3be49ae00b5c572153aa,ef397e6799b0f28d4dca7dd76974e0a1</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">1059</data>
      <data key="d6">c5fac1bea509464d9dc934275d938039</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MEANING OF GROSS PROFIT MARGIN&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A falling gross profit margin over time means that either the selling price at which the company sells its goods is declining, or the cost of making or buying those goods is increasing, but those increases cannot be passed on to customers. It suggests that the company's products or services are losing popularity, which raises concerns for the viability of the business. Gross profit margins may also reflect an organisation's pricing strategy."</data>
      <data key="d2">ef397e6799b0f28d4dca7dd76974e0a1</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1060</data>
      <data key="d6">45b64fbddd8f4abdb86a9c3c6f53f802</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;METHODS TO IMPROVE GROSS PROFIT MARGINS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Gross profit margins may be improved by introducing new products that are popular with customers, using target costing to reduce the cost of sales, and reclassifying direct expenses as administrative."</data>
      <data key="d2">ef397e6799b0f28d4dca7dd76974e0a1</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1061</data>
      <data key="d6">0e504b58cbda4d9188050bc43004c01f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NET PROFIT MARGIN&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The net profit margin is calculated using the formula: Net profit after tax divided by Revenue, multiplied by 100. This metric is used to assess the profitability of a company by determining the percentage of revenue that remains as net profit after all expenses, including taxes, have been deducted. In the context of a quiz, participants are required to calculate Fraser's net profit margin using figures from the statement of profit or loss. These figures include revenue, gross profit, profit before interest and tax, profit before tax, and profit after tax.</data>
      <data key="d2">9c3ce103fc83f7ae19dde7d2e5b4ef01,ef397e6799b0f28d4dca7dd76974e0a1</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1062</data>
      <data key="d6">c06bd37e120e4af49ec8bd6ce399473b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MEANING OF NET PROFIT MARGIN&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Net profit, sometimes called 'the bottom line', shows overall profits (after deducting all costs) as a percentage of revenue. Net profit margin reflects the underlying popularity of the company's products and services, the amount of control the company has over administrative-type expenses, and costs of debt financing."</data>
      <data key="d2">ef397e6799b0f28d4dca7dd76974e0a1</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1063</data>
      <data key="d6">5d507985f2f540d8a1fa2d1191eae2a8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;WAYS TO IMPROVE THE NET PROFIT MARGIN&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Ways to improve the net profit margin include introducing new products that are popular with customers, using target costing to reduce the cost of sales, increasing sales volume, better control over administrative expenses, and using less debt finance."</data>
      <data key="d2">ef397e6799b0f28d4dca7dd76974e0a1</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1064</data>
      <data key="d6">8e0b5b4011d74bbb8dc09fa05d88369c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ASSET TURNOVER RATIO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The "Asset Turnover Ratio" is calculated as Revenue divided by Capital Employed. This ratio measures how efficiently a company uses its assets to generate sales.</data>
      <data key="d2">bc0524558467e4e3eec1a2e2e05b5d33,ef397e6799b0f28d4dca7dd76974e0a1</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1065</data>
      <data key="d6">5d8184f5d52040d8bb67d1a6b889e9fe</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ANALYSIS OF RETURN ON CAPITAL EMPLOYED&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Return on capital employed ratio (ROCE) is the product of the operating profit margin and the asset turnover. ROCE = Operating profit margin * Asset turnover. This relationship can provide insights into the ROCE for a particular business and help identify the underlying causes of a decline in ROCE."</data>
      <data key="d2">ef397e6799b0f28d4dca7dd76974e0a1</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1066</data>
      <data key="d6">b3bf669489ae4913bb60ddfe50e41697</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LIQUIDITY RATIOS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Liquidity ratios" are financial performance indicators that measure an organization's ability to meet its short-term obligations. These ratios assess the organization's capacity to fulfill its liabilities as they become due. Operating cash flows are considered the ultimate measure of liquidity, reflecting the organization's ability to generate sufficient cash to cover its immediate financial commitments.</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f,ef397e6799b0f28d4dca7dd76974e0a1</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1067</data>
      <data key="d6">0eba9d55a3ff46298665a0c292e2237f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CURRENT RATIO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The "Current Ratio" is calculated as the ratio of current assets to current liabilities at the end of a period. The formula for the current ratio is: Current ratio = Current assets (at period end) / Current liabilities (at period end). The purpose of the current ratio is to measure the adequacy of current assets to meet current liabilities without the need to raise additional finance. A ratio of less than 1 indicates that current liabilities exceed current assets.</data>
      <data key="d2">a9270f89beee9fd6503ba50d0151c2e4,ef397e6799b0f28d4dca7dd76974e0a1</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1068</data>
      <data key="d6">55e3f4a200eb4619ae2b6efb645464d1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPERATING CASH FLOWS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Operating cash flows represent the ultimate measure of liquidity. If a company generates positive operating cash flows sufficient to replace non-current assets, it is less likely to experience liquidity problems."</data>
      <data key="d2">a9270f89beee9fd6503ba50d0151c2e4</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1069</data>
      <data key="d6">c44324c171674d00a743413042e9b944</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INVENTORY HOLDING PERIOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Inventory Holding Period (days) = 365 * Average Inventory ($) / Cost of Sales ($). The purpose of the inventory holding period is to measure the amount of time inventory is held before it is sold, measured in days. The shorter the period, the lower the holding costs of inventory and the faster inventory can be converted into cash."</data>
      <data key="d2">a9270f89beee9fd6503ba50d0151c2e4</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1070</data>
      <data key="d6">4bdaba79a3274241ab98e27aeaf98f57</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RECEIVABLES COLLECTION PERIOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Receivables Collection Period (days) = 365 * Average Receivables ($) / Total Credit Sales ($). The purpose of the receivables collection period is to measure the amount of time receivables are held before they are collected, measured in days. The shorter the period, the lower the financing costs of receivables, and the faster receivables can be converted into cash. Shorter periods also indicate a lower risk of bad debt."</data>
      <data key="d2">a9270f89beee9fd6503ba50d0151c2e4</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1071</data>
      <data key="d6">7c8c464ed7044a7896adfeb35f58a04d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PAYABLES PAYMENT PERIOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Payables Payment Period (days) = 365 * Average Payables ($) / Total Credit Purchases ($). The purpose of the payables payment period is to measure the amount of time payables are held before they are paid, measured in days. Payables can be used as a form of interest-free financing. The longer the payables payment period, the lower the financing cost. Longer periods also indicate more cash retention. However, this needs to be balanced against the risk of losing access to payables financing if suppliers are no longer willing to provide it."</data>
      <data key="d2">a9270f89beee9fd6503ba50d0151c2e4</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1072</data>
      <data key="d6">5fa2eec73bec481b85eba22ea7a2a927</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUICK RATIO (ACID TEST RATIO)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Quick ratio = (Current assets - Inventory at period end) / Current liabilities at period end. The quick ratio measures immediate liquidity by eliminating the least liquid asset, inventory, from current assets. Sometimes referred to as the 'acid test' ratio, the quick ratio is a more conservative version of the current ratio. A low or declining ratio may indicate an inability to meet its liabilities as they come due."</data>
      <data key="d2">a9270f89beee9fd6503ba50d0151c2e4</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1073</data>
      <data key="d6">e6aa5eedca984c56b5fa5e179127951d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF QUICK RATIO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"An international food retailer, which regularly reports a current ratio of about 0.3, illustrates the fallacy of using a single current ratio target to indicate satisfactory liquidity. The company has low inventory, as food only lasts a few days. It has few receivables, as most of its sales are for cash. It invests cash balances in non-current assets and holds low cash balances. Also, the company does not pay its suppliers for three months, so it has large payables balances. Far from indicating liquidity problems, the company uses its suppliers as a free source of financing."</data>
      <data key="d2">a9270f89beee9fd6503ba50d0151c2e4</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1074</data>
      <data key="d6">1c4bd4ba4ef64a93acd55faa8fd97ca9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;WAYS TO INCREASE LIQUIDITY RATIOS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Acceptable ways of increasing (i.e., improving) liquidity ratios include using long-term finance (loans and equity) to finance acquisitions of non-current assets, generating positive cash flows to repay short-term liabilities on time. Liquidity ratios may also be increased by adjusting year-end balances ('window dressing'); however, this is not a genuine improvement."</data>
      <data key="d2">a9270f89beee9fd6503ba50d0151c2e4</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1075</data>
      <data key="d6">5b85c70d578c4d67b5cb4743552bd559</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: QUICK RATIO (WINDOW DRESSING)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves calculating the quick ratio from given financial data and re-calculating it after making payments just before the year-end. It helps in understanding the impact of 'window dressing' on liquidity ratios."</data>
      <data key="d2">a9270f89beee9fd6503ba50d0151c2e4</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1076</data>
      <data key="d6">956113fb770840c38bce65bb5832f988</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GEARING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Gearing (or 'leverage') measures the portion of a company's finance provided by debt. The advantage of debt is that it is a relatively cheap source of financing. Providers of debt require a lower return than providers of equity finance because they face less risk, as they receive preferential repayment in the event of default. Interest on debt is also a tax-deductible expense, which further reduces the cost of debt. However, companies with too much debt (gearing) increase the risk of being unable to repay the debt's interest and principal."</data>
      <data key="d2">a9270f89beee9fd6503ba50d0151c2e4</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1077</data>
      <data key="d6">785bb55e79954b0c84a4a53cd7f0b454</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GEARING RATIOS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Gearing Ratios are financial performance indicators that measure the proportion of an organization's capital that is financed by debt. These ratios specifically assess the proportion of long-term borrowed funds, which pay a fixed return, relative to equity capital, also known as shareholders' funds. Gearing Ratios provide critical information about a company's financial risk due to its debt burden. Two commonly used Gearing Ratios are: Equity/Debt * 100, which gives gearing as a percentage, and Debt/Equity plus debt * 100.</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f,a9270f89beee9fd6503ba50d0151c2e4</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1078</data>
      <data key="d6">1239281fd3774b91a99358c9c1e6ee1c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DELIVERY PERFORMANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Delivery performance is measured by the percentage of orders delivered within 30 minutes. It is an essential aspect of the quality of service."</data>
      <data key="d2">e0207e68269c195f8b3bf7a33eedab96</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1079</data>
      <data key="d6">32b29a842b224f4c99fa1d5c764efc9a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CUSTOMER RATINGS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Customer ratings are scores given by customers to rate the quality of meals and service. These ratings provide insight into customer satisfaction and perceived quality."</data>
      <data key="d2">e0207e68269c195f8b3bf7a33eedab96</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1080</data>
      <data key="d6">f5ae7dc11fd64822a3a15e7d3839031a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ONLINE SALES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Online sales refer to the number of sales made through the company's website. It is an important metric for assessing the effectiveness of the online platform."</data>
      <data key="d2">e0207e68269c195f8b3bf7a33eedab96</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1081</data>
      <data key="d6">e1e254e67719488894eaa3553112a8cf</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;WEBSITE VISITS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Website visits refer to the number of times the company's website is accessed by users. It indicates the level of interest and visibility of the website."</data>
      <data key="d2">e0207e68269c195f8b3bf7a33eedab96</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1082</data>
      <data key="d6">ebdd79169d7d41b99faf09b039a66204</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COMPLAINTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Complaints" are expressions of dissatisfaction from customers regarding the service or product quality. The number of complaints can indicate areas needing improvement. Recently, the number of complaints has increased significantly, rising by 283% from 12 to 46. Additionally, complaints per customer visit have increased from 0.15% (12 complaints out of 8,000 visits) to 0.45% (46 complaints out of 10,225 visits).</data>
      <data key="d2">e0207e68269c195f8b3bf7a33eedab96,f41491fbf8c72d2afdc444dec24f9e1e</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1083</data>
      <data key="d6">e036534e17b24dd2895167a20873230f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STAFF TURNOVER&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Staff turnover is the rate at which employees leave the company and are replaced. Low staff turnover is a positive sign indicating employee satisfaction and stability. Additionally, staff turnover is used as a metric in quizzes to assess the element of value for money."</data>
      <data key="d2">3d86fa6cff193e8919165e686b8e6427,e0207e68269c195f8b3bf7a33eedab96</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1084</data>
      <data key="d6">a00bc5e4be634b08b1f084b6a07abafd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STAFF UTILISATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Staff utilisation is calculated by dividing the number of meals sold by the number of staff. It measures how effectively the staff is being used."</data>
      <data key="d2">e0207e68269c195f8b3bf7a33eedab96</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1085</data>
      <data key="d6">ce8241c964724429bb361b7b53867007</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NON-FINANCIAL PERFORMANCE ASSESSMENT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Non-financial performance assessment involves evaluating aspects of a business that are not directly related to financial metrics, such as customer satisfaction, service quality, and employee performance."</data>
      <data key="d2">e0207e68269c195f8b3bf7a33eedab96</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1086</data>
      <data key="d6">61cd7f168f7f44d6a23415e9497f1e65</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TRAINING FOR CUSTOMER SERVICE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Training to ensure staff understand the importance of customer service. It helps improve performance in customer service."</data>
      <data key="d2">e0207e68269c195f8b3bf7a33eedab96</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1087</data>
      <data key="d6">3be77a7b57e34c55acc1f1dfbc64ee10</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INCENTIVES FOR CUSTOMER SERVICE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Incentives to staff to reward improvements in customer service, such as 'employee of the month' rewards and prizes for good performance."</data>
      <data key="d2">e0207e68269c195f8b3bf7a33eedab96</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1088</data>
      <data key="d6">751c564f8ff6444d9d4c8de4a677e655</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TARGET SETTING IN QUALITATIVE AREAS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Target setting in qualitative areas" involves establishing goals in non-financial aspects of the business, such as customer satisfaction and service quality. This process can be complicated due to the subjective nature of qualitative metrics and the challenges associated with non-financial performance measurement.</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f,e0207e68269c195f8b3bf7a33eedab96</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1089</data>
      <data key="d6">96963c158fb64680bded290f442ff9aa</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CUSTOMER SERVICE TRAINING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Training to ensure staff understand the importance of customer service."</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1090</data>
      <data key="d6">bdbfbde5dd244447a2a0674b30ae3e8f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CUSTOMER SERVICE INCENTIVES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Incentives to staff to reward improvements, such as 'employee of the month' rewards and prizes for good performance."</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1091</data>
      <data key="d6">f970bfe31db74929abff6ea38e5d18e6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUALITATIVE AREAS OF PERFORMANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The most critical qualitative areas of performance include quality of product or service, customer satisfaction, delivery, and after-sales service."</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1092</data>
      <data key="d6">6f0c2a8b79e6406a8ab7a20864ae2ce2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DIFFICULTIES OF SETTING TARGETS FOR QUALITATIVE AREAS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Challenges in setting targets for qualitative areas include identifying drivers of improved performance, measuring qualitative factors, staff behavior in response to targets, and setting the appropriate level of difficulty for targets."</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1093</data>
      <data key="d6">7b09e60e33f44ffdab9c656c5b9c1d50</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF CALL CENTRE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A call centre introduced a target of two minutes per call to increase the number of calls handled, but staff hung up on customers after two minutes to avoid a variance."</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1094</data>
      <data key="d6">8b7beab7c0a143aea7bffc31df7528d5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BALANCED SCORECARD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">The Balanced Scorecard is a strategic management technique developed by Kaplan and Norton that provides top management with an integrated set of performance measures from four perspectives: financial, customer, internal business processes, and learning and growth. This approach to performance management ensures that internal systems and processes support customer and financial objectives, encourages integration between departments, and allows for performance measurement and control actions. It is used to align business activities with the vision and strategy of the organization, improve internal and external communications, and monitor organizational performance against strategic goals. The Balanced Scorecard comprises an integrated framework of financial and non-financial performance measures that aim to clarify, communicate, and manage strategy implementation across the four perspectives.</data>
      <data key="d2">1d33c979d505d0dcd027d816d2ab2695,3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f,5a3ea6b3010def70205c6c8c68b8cfc4,92d19303f11122ce7fe6d2e698547f59</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">22</data>
      <data key="d5">1095</data>
      <data key="d6">d03eb34a0612420680555ab9f10d03d5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BALANCED SCORECARD PHILOSOPHY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The balanced scorecard philosophy involves setting measures and performance targets across four perspectives: customer, internal business process, learning and growth, and financial, ensuring that these perspectives complement each other."</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1096</data>
      <data key="d6">b066746cdff7440c8a3591f0c098201d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SETTING MEASURES AND PERFORMANCE TARGETS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"For each perspective in the balanced scorecard, management needs to identify objectives, measures, targets, and initiatives to improve performance."</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1097</data>
      <data key="d6">1e2eded8ef7b4b458c33fbc2d36c4380</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LEADING AND LAGGING INDICATORS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Leading indicators predict future performance, while lagging indicators reflect past performance. Both are used in the balanced scorecard to provide a comprehensive view of performance."</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1098</data>
      <data key="d6">c59e3e931b0f4cf888c2eb70857ee753</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CRITICAL SUCCESS FACTOR&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A performance outcome that an organisation requires to achieve success."</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1099</data>
      <data key="d6">305b80bb4df5488b8a34129daeeae0c7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VALUE FOR MONEY (VFM)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"VALUE FOR MONEY (VFM)" is a measure used to evaluate the performance of an organization, particularly in the public sector, based on the principles of economy, efficiency, and effectiveness. It assesses how well resources are utilized to achieve intended results. As a public sector objective, VFM involves achieving the 3Es: economy, efficiency, and effectiveness.</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f,963bb5be84f30224d6e25ea423602dfd</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1100</data>
      <data key="d6">66fa0de756da440bad8da583306410c4</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;3ES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The 3Es stand for economy, efficiency, and effectiveness, which are used to achieve Value for Money (VFM) in the public sector."</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1101</data>
      <data key="d6">d1e9c550a0e74c48ae81c319f26ccafc</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PERFORMANCE ANALYSIS IN PRIVATE SECTOR, PUBLIC SECTOR AND NOT-FOR-PROFIT ORGANISATIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Performance analysis involves explaining and interpreting the balanced scorecard, considering external factors, and addressing specific issues in not-for-profit and public sector organisations."</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">1102</data>
      <data key="d6">3730b5d759ba4fd28a54af0a02151f09</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PROBLEMS OF NON-QUANTIFIABLE OBJECTIVES IN PERFORMANCE MANAGEMENT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Challenges in performance management when objectives cannot be quantified, often seen in not-for-profit organisations and the public sector."</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1103</data>
      <data key="d6">82b7f7c27e2348f880c94ffb80942de7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PROBLEMS OF MULTIPLE OBJECTIVES IN NOT-FOR-PROFIT ORGANISATIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Issues arising from having multiple objectives in not-for-profit organisations, which can complicate performance measurement and management."</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1104</data>
      <data key="d6">0980c4f558654466b4d691d0cb7ce16d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;WAYS TO MEASURE PERFORMANCE IN NOT-FOR-PROFIT ORGANISATIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Methods to measure performance in not-for-profit organisations, considering their unique objectives and challenges."</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1105</data>
      <data key="d6">f1e47cf5daa441649c3474c3339bb704</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXTERNAL CONSIDERATIONS IN PERFORMANCE MANAGEMENT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The need to account for external factors such as stakeholders, market conditions, and competitors in performance management."</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1106</data>
      <data key="d6">0964dcfbff934c92af8961155673ac7f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MISSION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The fundamental purpose or goal of an organisation, which guides its strategic objectives and performance measurement."</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1107</data>
      <data key="d6">51b82bcdffe04056bad1c082c3830047</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;HIERARCHY OF OBJECTIVES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The ranking of an organisation's objectives from its mission and strategic objectives down to lower-level goals."</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1108</data>
      <data key="d6">c62bb148852b49a98e2779ca23a0919d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RETURN ON CAPITAL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A financial performance indicator that measures the profitability of an organisation relative to its capital."</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1109</data>
      <data key="d6">72b5a0c357c24b739084d501b9354bc1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ASSET TURNOVER RATIOS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Financial performance indicators that measure how efficiently an organisation uses its assets to generate revenue."</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1110</data>
      <data key="d6">c827b62ebf134e55a3ccf0b63f976870</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INTEREST COVER&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A financial performance indicator that measures an organisation's ability to meet its interest payments on debt."</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1111</data>
      <data key="d6">b51ef388758845e880e736309ae791e3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;KAPLAN AND NORTON&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Developers of the balanced scorecard approach, which integrates financial and non-financial performance measures."</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1112</data>
      <data key="d6">0a841cd4b6664423b033f22e3a80f33c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PERFORMANCE MEASURE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A quantitative or qualitative characterisation of performance used to evaluate progress toward an objective."</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1113</data>
      <data key="d6">16911c51c65b42f8a2d04c05f45b2c58</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OBJECTIVE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A specific, measurable statement of what will be done to achieve goals within a defined time frame."</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1114</data>
      <data key="d6">fc3f77f29574410d991a2aa333950bf6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INITIATIVES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Actions taken to improve performance in line with the objectives and measures identified in the balanced scorecard."</data>
      <data key="d2">3c3175f58893c9a4a545210c49b7c25f</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1115</data>
      <data key="d6">4f847eb72cbe48678d5634dcf93fc0e2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COMPETITIVENESS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"COMPETITIVENESS" is a dimension of Fitzgerald and Moon's Building Block Model that measures the attractiveness of services compared to competitors. It is concerned with market share and the growth of new business areas. Specifically, it evaluates the rate of restaurant turnover relative to the turnover of all restaurants in the locality, as well as the success rate of new event proposals and contracts won. Competitiveness reflects an organization's ability to maintain and gain market share in its industry, often measured by market share and the ability to outperform competitors. It can also be assessed by comparing the company's revenue to the total revenue of the industry.</data>
      <data key="d2">05e25a78a53e695fd01856df3a302292,3a3c8da0ae62c6ab3fba8e1cfd8e4025,e4d4bacb7d841448ad6095b3ddafc290,e7d75450db353b8413fb68bdd98ac99c</data>
      <data key="d4">8</data>
      <data key="d5">1116</data>
      <data key="d6">829e64159ae04301982e88e93a2f0e49</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUALITY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Quality" in a service organization refers to the standard of service delivered to customers. It encompasses the standard of products or services provided by the organization, ensuring they meet customer expectations and regulatory requirements. Quality can be measured by targets such as on-time delivery rates or the average time taken to process an order.</data>
      <data key="d2">3a3c8da0ae62c6ab3fba8e1cfd8e4025,e4d4bacb7d841448ad6095b3ddafc290</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">1117</data>
      <data key="d6">cf37d3d4bc154f65b3d79c831c587763</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INNOVATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"INNOVATION" is a dimension of Fitzgerald and Moon's Building Block Model that measures the ability to introduce new and improved services or processes. In a business context, innovation refers to the introduction of new ideas, products, or methods to improve efficiency and competitiveness. It can be measured by the percentage of customers using new technologies, such as a smartphone app. Overall, innovation involves the introduction of new ideas, products, services, or processes that enhance an organization's performance and competitiveness.</data>
      <data key="d2">3a3c8da0ae62c6ab3fba8e1cfd8e4025,e4d4bacb7d841448ad6095b3ddafc290,e7d75450db353b8413fb68bdd98ac99c</data>
      <data key="d4">7</data>
      <data key="d5">1118</data>
      <data key="d6">4b4fce341d554012bc73d7886860749e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FLEXIBILITY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"FLEXIBILITY" is a dimension of Fitzgerald and Moon's Building Block Model that measures the ability of an organization to adapt to changes in the environment, customer demands, and market conditions. It emphasizes the importance of being responsive to changes and customer needs, ensuring that the organization remains competitive and effective in a dynamic market.</data>
      <data key="d2">a5a7a3e9a59209ce811c1f9470684fa6,e4d4bacb7d841448ad6095b3ddafc290,e7d75450db353b8413fb68bdd98ac99c</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1119</data>
      <data key="d6">9f6e7a08bd814d19b45fac58928027f8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RESOURCE UTILISATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Resource utilisation" measures how efficiently a company uses its resources, such as delivery vehicles, staff, and rented property, to reduce costs and improve profitability. It can be assessed using standards like average delivery time, the number of deliveries per day, and the degree to which properties are utilized, exemplified by a 27.8% increase in clients serviced in a year. Overall, resource utilisation refers to the efficient and effective use of an organization's resources, including human, financial, and physical assets, to achieve its objectives.</data>
      <data key="d2">3a3c8da0ae62c6ab3fba8e1cfd8e4025,e4d4bacb7d841448ad6095b3ddafc290,f41491fbf8c72d2afdc444dec24f9e1e</data>
      <data key="d4">8</data>
      <data key="d5">1120</data>
      <data key="d6">ff9410fed5e64c04a875e040e3d182b2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OWNERSHIP&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Ownership in the context of performance targets means that managers should take responsibility for and believe in the targets set for them. This increases their commitment to achieving these targets."</data>
      <data key="d2">e4d4bacb7d841448ad6095b3ddafc290</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1121</data>
      <data key="d6">1161272728914953b568f384d7a9f2f1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ACHIEVABILITY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Achievability refers to setting performance targets that are challenging yet attainable, motivating managers to strive for them without feeling overwhelmed."</data>
      <data key="d2">e4d4bacb7d841448ad6095b3ddafc290</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1122</data>
      <data key="d6">f09c82eb89944ae9846df82135123b90</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EQUITY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Equity in performance measurement means maintaining fairness and unbiased assessment across all business areas, ensuring that targets are realistic and comparable."</data>
      <data key="d2">e4d4bacb7d841448ad6095b3ddafc290</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1123</data>
      <data key="d6">d221b743a51d464b87de3b72b85f6b59</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CLARITY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Clarity in reward schemes means that employees must understand the performance measurement criteria and how their performance will be evaluated."</data>
      <data key="d2">e4d4bacb7d841448ad6095b3ddafc290</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1124</data>
      <data key="d6">9fd31a28e1384b40a9d1658a765871cd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONTROLLABILITY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Controllability refers to the principle that managers should be evaluated based on factors they can control, ensuring fair and accurate performance assessments."</data>
      <data key="d2">e4d4bacb7d841448ad6095b3ddafc290</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1125</data>
      <data key="d6">0119f233c8394b9584e55fadcce173f0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MOTIVATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Motivation" in the context of participative budgeting refers to encouraging managers to perform well by involving them in the budget-setting process. When managers believe the budget is realistic, they are more likely to strive to achieve it. Additionally, motivation in the context of reward schemes means that bonuses and incentives should encourage employees to achieve their performance targets.</data>
      <data key="d2">dcff42ba3ed5843954c648603089a728,e4d4bacb7d841448ad6095b3ddafc290</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1126</data>
      <data key="d6">5c20b469b92446dabb1b68976807be7c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FITZGERALD AND MOON MODEL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Fitzgerald and Moon model identifies six dimensions of performance that organizations should measure: financial performance, competitiveness, quality, resource utilization, flexibility, and innovation. It is similar to the balanced scorecard model."</data>
      <data key="d2">e4d4bacb7d841448ad6095b3ddafc290</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1127</data>
      <data key="d6">2c2392247a35456da663adfcffd12e73</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE 2 CAR DEALER'S PERFORMANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This example illustrates how a large car dealer network in the UK uses various performance dimensions and measures, such as financial performance, competitiveness, quality of service, and resource utilization, to assess and improve its operations."</data>
      <data key="d2">e4d4bacb7d841448ad6095b3ddafc290</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1128</data>
      <data key="d6">167a32ff67ce4471baa8cf019ee7c17b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REWARD SCHEMES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Reward schemes are systems that link performance to compensation, such as bonuses, to motivate managers to achieve their targets. Key principles include clarity, motivation, and controllability."</data>
      <data key="d2">e4d4bacb7d841448ad6095b3ddafc290</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1129</data>
      <data key="d6">3280fc12ef414827838e6ac7089f0618</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF BUILDING BLOCK MODEL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This example describes how SmartC, a package delivery company, applies the building block model to measure and improve its performance across various dimensions, including financial performance, competitiveness, quality, flexibility, innovation, and resource utilization."</data>
      <data key="d2">e4d4bacb7d841448ad6095b3ddafc290</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1130</data>
      <data key="d6">556fba72a0854ce4831f6cfea6fd035e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PERFORMANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">e4d4bacb7d841448ad6095b3ddafc290</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1131</data>
      <data key="d6">8e2e6eeed5a04c9f80efbcfc624ced95</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FLEXIBILITY OF SERVICE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Flexibility of service refers to a company's ability to meet customer demands and preferences. It can be measured by targets such as the percentage of orders scheduled to customers' requests."</data>
      <data key="d2">3a3c8da0ae62c6ab3fba8e1cfd8e4025</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">1132</data>
      <data key="d6">ea6d546f1caa4b4aaacdad8b8af195ec</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REWARDS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Rewards refer to the compensation package provided to employees, which can include financial and non-financial benefits. Effective reward systems contribute to employee motivation by meeting their different needs and linking rewards to performance."</data>
      <data key="d2">3a3c8da0ae62c6ab3fba8e1cfd8e4025</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1133</data>
      <data key="d6">267ce44e6dae43ee94d0d375ec08ef17</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TYPES OF NOT-FOR-PROFIT ORGANISATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The non-profit sector includes public sector bodies like schools and hospitals, not-for-profit (NFP) organizations, and non-governmental organizations (NGOs). These organizations typically do not have profit as their primary objective and focus on providing public goods and services."</data>
      <data key="d2">3a3c8da0ae62c6ab3fba8e1cfd8e4025</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1134</data>
      <data key="d6">b37e5d15f3154ee39df016b8eac8de66</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF STATE-FUNDED UNIVERSITY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A state-funded university is accountable to multiple stakeholders with potentially conflicting objectives, such as students desiring small class sizes and the government wanting to minimize costs per student. Designing a performance measurement system for such an institution is complex."</data>
      <data key="d2">3a3c8da0ae62c6ab3fba8e1cfd8e4025</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1135</data>
      <data key="d6">e13eb574e885414b80f0b66992767ef2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CHARITIES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Charities are a type of not-for-profit organization that exists solely to benefit defined groups in society. They may receive favorable tax treatment, rely on public and business financial support, and often depend on voluntary managers and workers."</data>
      <data key="d2">3a3c8da0ae62c6ab3fba8e1cfd8e4025</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1136</data>
      <data key="d6">93f4140f654e41ccba908c6f6dc65f17</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VALUE FOR MONEY OBJECTIVES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The value for money (VFM) framework evaluates the performance of non-profit and other non-commercial organizations by assessing how well they achieve their objectives given the funding received. It uses three performance indicators known as the '3Es'."</data>
      <data key="d2">3a3c8da0ae62c6ab3fba8e1cfd8e4025</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1137</data>
      <data key="d6">a102d091986749ef90b45d411e707bef</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EFFECTIVENESS OF CHARITY IN REDUCING THE EFFECTS OF A DISEASE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Effectiveness of a charity in reducing the effects of a disease can be measured by the fall in the number of cases of the disease reported each period and the number of people inoculated against the disease. These indicators reflect the charity's impact on disease reduction and its operational efforts."</data>
      <data key="d2">e24dc649a0643841a501b7b1025dee78</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1138</data>
      <data key="d6">cd6ae38a5a6742899d14f4a064f42c19</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUALITY OF CLINICAL CARE IN A HOSPITAL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Quality of clinical care in a hospital can be measured by the percentage of patients cured and not readmitted within three months and the waiting time for operations. These indicators reflect the level of clinical care and efficiency in patient treatment."</data>
      <data key="d2">e24dc649a0643841a501b7b1025dee78</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1139</data>
      <data key="d6">fe18688bd4ef44d1a184ec6d1451a5cf</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EFFECTIVENESS OF LOCAL POLICE FORCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Effectiveness of the local police force can be measured by the percentage of arrested criminals convicted. This indicator reflects the police's ability to collect sufficient evidence to ensure criminals are convicted."</data>
      <data key="d2">e24dc649a0643841a501b7b1025dee78</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1140</data>
      <data key="d6">0f1282bdfedb4f6e8765007a90dd2959</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SETTING TARGETS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Setting targets involves comparing actual performance with targets and investigating when targets are missed. This process is similar to comparing financial performance against budgets or using standard costing and variance analysis. Setting qualitative targets in non-financial performance (NFP) organizations can be challenging due to factors like target difficulty, external environment differences, manager buy-in, and the nature of qualitative measures."</data>
      <data key="d2">e24dc649a0643841a501b7b1025dee78</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1141</data>
      <data key="d6">540af5c5d4cd41ceb29c40c5fb02e2fe</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ASSESSING PERFORMANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Assessing performance in the non-financial performance (NFP) sector involves considering the organization's objectives. Traditional performance measures like return on capital employed may be meaningless for NFP organizations. Performance assessment should focus on achieving organizational objectives and balancing cost reduction with maintaining service quality."</data>
      <data key="d2">e24dc649a0643841a501b7b1025dee78</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1142</data>
      <data key="d6">bbf83708095f47019eaee93d6879bc77</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EVALUATION OF PERFORMANCE QUIZ&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Evaluation of Performance quiz involves analyzing the financial performance of Ayersome Leisure (AL), a sports center owned by the council of Bigton. The quiz includes comparing financial reports for the last two financial years and the budget for the most recent year, as well as evaluating the utilization and revenue of different sporting activities offered by the center."</data>
      <data key="d2">e24dc649a0643841a501b7b1025dee78</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1143</data>
      <data key="d6">245a56f01d1b48a7b4d88ed0e354155a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SWIMMING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Swimming is a sport offered at the sports centre, available for 10 hours each day with 70% utilization both during the day and evening, generating $203,000 in revenue."</data>
      <data key="d2">815ea5664d4945f13e6fb2c2dc05867f</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1144</data>
      <data key="d6">d3aa564fb4eb430a8ca6813ca76bfff6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GYM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Gym is a facility offered at the sports centre, available for 12 hours each day with 15% daytime and 50% evening utilization, generating $252,000 in revenue."</data>
      <data key="d2">815ea5664d4945f13e6fb2c2dc05867f</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1145</data>
      <data key="d6">d9b948357d96419ca135065ce1c360ef</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BADMINTON&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Badminton is a sport offered at the sports centre, available for 6 hours each day with 50% utilization both during the day and evening, generating $50,000 in revenue."</data>
      <data key="d2">815ea5664d4945f13e6fb2c2dc05867f</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1146</data>
      <data key="d6">20a79ddd91ba48e4bb7bc194c79baaf6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FREE ACCESS POLICY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"AL offers free access to all facilities to local schools to encourage sports development and to those over 60 years old to promote healthy lifestyles. Free-access users comprise 30% of all users, with 60% of these users likely to continue using the facilities if they had to pay the standard charges."</data>
      <data key="d2">815ea5664d4945f13e6fb2c2dc05867f</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1147</data>
      <data key="d6">b95728a0b96b405cbccafa6c12fd8722</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FINANCIAL PERFORMANCE EVALUATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The financial performance evaluation of the sports centre for the most recent year shows a deficit of $194,000, which is almost four times that of the prior year and 80% higher than the budgeted deficit. The main reason for the failure to meet the budget is the decline in revenue due to the opening of a new health club in Bigton."</data>
      <data key="d2">815ea5664d4945f13e6fb2c2dc05867f</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1148</data>
      <data key="d6">5d6dc034d2014e8c930fde69c31b99cf</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NON-FINANCIAL PERFORMANCE EVALUATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The non-financial performance evaluation highlights the high utilization rates of the sports centre's facilities, the provision of free facilities to the over 60s and schools, and the centre's role in promoting healthy living and satisfying a social need by encouraging people to exercise."</data>
      <data key="d2">815ea5664d4945f13e6fb2c2dc05867f</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1149</data>
      <data key="d6">127cbb53940f4efa8e1807b4452375ba</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COST REDUCTION STRATEGIES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">Cost reduction strategies refer to the methods and actions taken to decrease expenses and improve profitability. These strategies can include negotiating lower material costs, optimizing production processes, and implementing various other measures to cut costs. In the context of improving the financial performance of a sports centre, specific cost reduction strategies might involve discontinuing less profitable activities such as badminton, reducing staff costs, adjusting operating hours to align with less busy times, and potentially modifying the free access policy to increase revenue.</data>
      <data key="d2">815ea5664d4945f13e6fb2c2dc05867f,853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1150</data>
      <data key="d6">f1ea6ef9539043ab887bcce22ccf9625</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DIVISIONAL PERFORMANCE EVALUATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The Divisional Performance Evaluation involves assessing the performance of different business units or divisions within an organization. This process includes measuring and controlling divisional performance and implementing fair transfer pricing. The use of fair transfer prices is crucial to objectively assess and motivate divisional performance.</data>
      <data key="d2">0622f4f26dbe7479c871198b2e72b940,421ca5734d703d01e7e43fa8cb11733f</data>
      <data key="d7">25</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1151</data>
      <data key="d6">b50c4f053f0546029c4095b7b93aa05e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DECENTRALISATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Decentralisation" is the delegation of authority to make decisions, involving the creation of autonomous business units or divisions to align responsibility with decentralised authority. This approach allows senior managers to focus on strategy rather than operations, promotes faster and better decision-making, and may better motivate divisional managers. However, decentralisation may also result in a loss of central control, incongruence of goals and strategies, and increased information requirements.</data>
      <data key="d2">421ca5734d703d01e7e43fa8cb11733f,4e87d1e76027b0ff68b56a7c9c9c92c1</data>
      <data key="d7">25</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">9</data>
      <data key="d5">1152</data>
      <data key="d6">0cea7f7a7fab49339cdd6fb02d0d183e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REVENUE CENTRES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Revenue centres are business units where managers are responsible for decisions about revenue generation, usually including selling costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">421ca5734d703d01e7e43fa8cb11733f</data>
      <data key="d7">25</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1153</data>
      <data key="d6">5b89f0d8101c419b86e1959cca2db848</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COST CENTRES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Cost centres are business units where managers are responsible for decisions about costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">421ca5734d703d01e7e43fa8cb11733f</data>
      <data key="d7">25</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1154</data>
      <data key="d6">cdb407fc600b45caa6f94f82e89d2e4f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PROFIT CENTRES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Profit centres are business units where managers are responsible for decisions about both costs and revenues."</data>
      <data key="d2">421ca5734d703d01e7e43fa8cb11733f</data>
      <data key="d7">25</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1155</data>
      <data key="d6">7f4905fcb43e4d6ca23e6d2b40f6958e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INVESTMENT CENTRES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Investment centres are business units where managers are responsible for decisions about costs, revenues, and asset investments."</data>
      <data key="d2">421ca5734d703d01e7e43fa8cb11733f</data>
      <data key="d7">25</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1156</data>
      <data key="d6">f5ad4fe84df544c69db25f0e30c6eace</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BENEFITS OF DECENTRALISATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Benefits of decentralisation include allowing senior management to concentrate on strategy, faster decision-making, better decision-making by specialist managers, increased motivation, training and career progression for divisional managers, and tax advantages."</data>
      <data key="d2">421ca5734d703d01e7e43fa8cb11733f</data>
      <data key="d7">25</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1157</data>
      <data key="d6">237a46cc973b41dc9af4190c71c5c9e1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PROBLEMS OF DECENTRALISATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Problems of decentralisation include lack of goal congruence, increased information requirements, lost economies of scale, and loss of central control."</data>
      <data key="d2">421ca5734d703d01e7e43fa8cb11733f</data>
      <data key="d7">25</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1158</data>
      <data key="d6">aaa27aa0b1024e3aa3c87a6ec821a348</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONDITIONS FOR SUCCESSFUL DECENTRALISATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Conditions for successful decentralisation include carefully designed performance evaluation systems, having several separate business activities, central policies to integrate and control, and ensuring divisions are independent from each other."</data>
      <data key="d2">421ca5734d703d01e7e43fa8cb11733f</data>
      <data key="d7">25</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1159</data>
      <data key="d6">f0a28fe3f68546dba7850815f7933275</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MEASUREMENT CHARACTERISTICS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Measurement characteristics for decentralisation include goal congruence, timeliness, and controllability to ensure decisions are in the company's best interests."</data>
      <data key="d2">421ca5734d703d01e7e43fa8cb11733f</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1160</data>
      <data key="d6">45b59feba7134bc18632cb42530c189a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;POSSIBLE MEASURES FOR DIVISIONAL PERFORMANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Possible measures for divisional performance include variance analysis, ratio analysis, non-financial measures, return on investment (ROI), and residual income (RI)."</data>
      <data key="d2">421ca5734d703d01e7e43fa8cb11733f</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1161</data>
      <data key="d6">7747cd2048f94d378e83265b9561d921</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RATIO ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Ratio analysis includes profitability measures, liquidity measures, and other measures such as contribution per key factor, sales per employee, and industry-specific cost-related ratios."</data>
      <data key="d2">421ca5734d703d01e7e43fa8cb11733f</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1162</data>
      <data key="d6">c4e9532dbc734264a0e3e827bc8014c6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NON-FINANCIAL MEASURES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">Non-financial measures are metrics that do not involve financial data but are used to assess various aspects of an organization's performance. Examples of non-financial measures include staff turnover, new customers gained, proportion of repeat bookings, orders received, set-up times, new products developed, percentage of returns, percentage of rejects/reworks, on-time deliveries, client contact hours, and training time per employee.</data>
      <data key="d2">1f06696499d837582d3dac671cb07649,421ca5734d703d01e7e43fa8cb11733f</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1163</data>
      <data key="d6">003e5d505a01434596c6d65ff20b0bdf</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MEASURES BY DIVISION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Measures by Division include both financial and non-financial metrics used to assess the performance of different types of divisions within an organization. Revenue centers focus on sales variances and customer satisfaction, cost centers on cost variances and labor turnover, profit centers on controllable profit and customer returns, and investment centers on return on investment and new products developed."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f06696499d837582d3dac671cb07649</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1164</data>
      <data key="d6">f79358f3535045d9aad3b828df59293b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONTROLLABLE AND TRACEABLE PROFIT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Controllable profit refers to the profit that a manager can influence through their decisions, while traceable profit includes costs and revenues that can be directly attributed to a division but are outside the manager's control. A pro forma statement is often used to distinguish between these two types of profit."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f06696499d837582d3dac671cb07649</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1165</data>
      <data key="d6">7d375c18c1e2415faecd9f7397068a32</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COMPONENTS OF CAPITAL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Capital investment usually has two components: fixed capital, which refers to non-current assets, and working capital, which refers to net current assets. These components are crucial for calculating ROI and assessing divisional performance."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f06696499d837582d3dac671cb07649</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1166</data>
      <data key="d6">dfa0e847a6704c93a0fe014b01858ff7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: ROI&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves evaluating the potential investment projects for Division X and Division Y using return on investment (ROI) as the primary measure of divisional performance. The quiz provides details of the potential projects, including controllable investment, controllable profit, current division ROI, and company cost of capital."</data>
      <data key="d2">1f06696499d837582d3dac671cb07649</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1167</data>
      <data key="d6">9e91823feb174cd1b6a3bf8d0a5cb86b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DIVISION Y&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Division Y is another division being evaluated for potential projects, with a current ROI of 9%."</data>
      <data key="d2">6cd8b16b5edca25e8d811b4efcefe5fb</data>
      <data key="d7">25</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1168</data>
      <data key="d6">ad76c8dc8dd94412a5e79005cf8e0f2f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COMPANY COST OF CAPITAL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The company's cost of capital is 13%, which is used as a benchmark for evaluating the profitability of potential projects."</data>
      <data key="d2">6cd8b16b5edca25e8d811b4efcefe5fb</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1169</data>
      <data key="d6">26a03482961e41918ea049018080af7a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INVESTMENT DECISIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Investment decisions involve determining whether the divisional managers would accept the project available to their respective divisions based on ROI."</data>
      <data key="d2">6cd8b16b5edca25e8d811b4efcefe5fb</data>
      <data key="d7">25</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1170</data>
      <data key="d6">1cfd220ff4d2493ca4b92d725d171d32</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GOAL CONGRUENCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Goal congruence" ensures that transfer prices encourage divisional managers to make decisions in the best interests of the organization as a whole. It is the alignment of individual or divisional objectives with the overall objectives of the organization. Specifically, goal congruence refers to the alignment of divisional managers' decisions with the organization's primary objective of maximizing shareholders' wealth.</data>
      <data key="d2">0622f4f26dbe7479c871198b2e72b940,4e87d1e76027b0ff68b56a7c9c9c92c1,6cd8b16b5edca25e8d811b4efcefe5fb</data>
      <data key="d7">25</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1171</data>
      <data key="d6">97738fe0830d405ba53598b5cb1e5e38</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ADVANTAGES OF ROI&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Advantages of ROI include ease of comparison between divisions, focus on scarce capital resources, encouragement of reduction in non-essential investment, and easily understood percentages."</data>
      <data key="d2">6cd8b16b5edca25e8d811b4efcefe5fb</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1172</data>
      <data key="d6">354cea4f6e164a48ad12122c28a5b30d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DISADVANTAGES OF ROI&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Disadvantages of ROI include the risk of dysfunctional decision-making, subjective definition of capital employed, potential increase in ROI over time due to depreciation, and risk of window-dressing."</data>
      <data key="d2">6cd8b16b5edca25e8d811b4efcefe5fb</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1173</data>
      <data key="d6">1ee2380c1eda4ebb8c9304820750ac88</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RESIDUAL INCOME (RI)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Residual Income (RI) is the amount of income that an individual or company has after all expenses have been paid. It is calculated by subtracting the imputed interest charge from the net profit. RI serves as a measure of the profitability of an investment after accounting for the cost of capital. Specifically, it is determined by taking the divisional profit and deducting the imputed interest charge. For instance, Division A has a Residual Income of $2.552 million, while Division B has a Residual Income of $2.322 million. This metric focuses on wealth creation by deducting an imputed interest expense from the pre-tax profit.</data>
      <data key="d2">1d33c979d505d0dcd027d816d2ab2695,6cd8b16b5edca25e8d811b4efcefe5fb,ffdd70ec71109628006ce6c01c1335ad</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">1174</data>
      <data key="d6">57e00d4d4e0e4679a150f048deb80af3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;IMPUTED INTEREST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Imputed interest" is a notional interest charge calculated on the capital employed by the head office. It is determined by multiplying the capital employed by the interest rate. This imputed interest is used in the calculation of residual income.</data>
      <data key="d2">312c3cf9edbc058c6e810c1e9c9cd81a,6cd8b16b5edca25e8d811b4efcefe5fb</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1175</data>
      <data key="d6">c1e4a9dbe55c4fb89f0d927c9fb067a4</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: ROI AND RESIDUAL INCOME&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves calculating the current ROI and residual income for Division X and showing how they would change under two proposals."</data>
      <data key="d2">6cd8b16b5edca25e8d811b4efcefe5fb</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1176</data>
      <data key="d6">1474a72a5cff4b72ae6f99e804ceaa95</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ROI&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1">Return on Investment (ROI) is a performance measure used to evaluate the efficiency or profitability of an investment or to compare the efficiency of several different investments. It is calculated by dividing the net profit by the cost of the investment and is expressed as a percentage. Specifically, ROI can be calculated using the formula: (Net Profit / Operating Net Assets) * 100, or alternatively, Profit / Opening Investment (Net Book Value). This measure helps in assessing the profitability of an investment or division by comparing net profit to the capital employed.</data>
      <data key="d2">4e87d1e76027b0ff68b56a7c9c9c92c1,6cd8b16b5edca25e8d811b4efcefe5fb,81f2049ff66aba893fb4f7dc7f5bcf5e,b6f6408539084298539b791170ec9250,d0b8c2893afd98f99c4f5d857b8a7a02,ffdd70ec71109628006ce6c01c1335ad</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">8</data>
      <data key="d5">1177</data>
      <data key="d6">738fda68df7a49a0bae96673a8711afc</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RI&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"RI (Residual Income) is calculated as the net operating income minus the product of the investment cost and the cost of capital. It is used to measure the absolute amount of profit generated above the required return."</data>
      <data key="d2">81f2049ff66aba893fb4f7dc7f5bcf5e</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">1178</data>
      <data key="d6">89dd5a0943c64247adae624abbc95afb</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PROPOSAL 1&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Proposal 1 offers a 15% return ($0.15m/$1m), which is greater than the cost of capital. However, it leads to a decrease in divisional ROI, which could result in the divisional manager rejecting it. Residual income increases if Proposal 1 is adopted, leading to goal-congruent decisions."</data>
      <data key="d2">81f2049ff66aba893fb4f7dc7f5bcf5e</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1179</data>
      <data key="d6">405e9907440d4deab71f3960ae36f47b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PROPOSAL 2&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Proposal 2 is not acceptable to the company. The return on existing assets is 13% ($0.3m/$2.3m), which is greater than the cost of capital and hence should not be disposed of. However, divisional ROI rises, which could lead to the divisional manager accepting it. Residual income decreases if Proposal 2 is adopted, leading to goal-congruent decisions."</data>
      <data key="d2">81f2049ff66aba893fb4f7dc7f5bcf5e</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1180</data>
      <data key="d6">f91e7c9600ca4623a8cc4a56d2dccd07</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: RESIDUAL INCOME&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves evaluating the performance of divisional managers using residual income. It includes scenarios where managers must decide on investment projects based on residual income calculations."</data>
      <data key="d2">81f2049ff66aba893fb4f7dc7f5bcf5e</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1181</data>
      <data key="d6">3af2a8619c394be6adf06e4bc742b7ec</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ADVANTAGES OF RESIDUAL INCOME&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Residual income overcomes some of the problems associated with ROI, such as dysfunctional behavior and holding on to old assets. It can be linked to net present value, reflecting the best way to make investment decisions. A risk-adjusted cost of capital can reflect different risk positions of different divisions."</data>
      <data key="d2">81f2049ff66aba893fb4f7dc7f5bcf5e</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1182</data>
      <data key="d6">c10ffc51dcb54708a1dc757693010bfe</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DISADVANTAGES OF RESIDUAL INCOME&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Residual income has several disadvantages, including the definition of capital employed, the effect of depreciation, window dressing, and the challenge of comparing divisions of different sizes. It is also less easily understood than a percentage."</data>
      <data key="d2">81f2049ff66aba893fb4f7dc7f5bcf5e</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1183</data>
      <data key="d6">e67ce34d48364422973ccf3a6b57af83</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RESIDUAL INCOME&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Residual Income (RI) is calculated as the net profit after deducting an imputed interest charge on the capital employed. It is used to assess the profitability of an investment or division, as well as the performance of divisions within a company. Residual income represents the income that remains after subtracting the imputed interest charge on capital employed from the controllable profit."</data>
      <data key="d2">312c3cf9edbc058c6e810c1e9c9cd81a,47433af962a352cae0761ce18f9b4b82,4e87d1e76027b0ff68b56a7c9c9c92c1,a5a7a3e9a59209ce811c1f9470684fa6,b6f6408539084298539b791170ec9250</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">1184</data>
      <data key="d6">98773a34c9bb474d8a789ea08f57250e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DIVISIONAL PERFORMANCE MEASURES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Divisional performance measures should be goal-congruent, timely, and controllable by the divisional manager. The most suitable measures depend on whether the business unit is a cost, profit, or investment centre."</data>
      <data key="d2">4e87d1e76027b0ff68b56a7c9c9c92c1</data>
      <data key="d7">25</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1185</data>
      <data key="d6">ae260498423e4d55aa413423cd0eb20b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONTROLLABLE PROFIT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Controllable profit is the profit within the manager's control."</data>
      <data key="d2">312c3cf9edbc058c6e810c1e9c9cd81a,4e87d1e76027b0ff68b56a7c9c9c92c1</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1186</data>
      <data key="d6">4aeecb9d885743ca9373337a43957dd8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TRACEABLE PROFIT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Traceable profit is the profit after charging divisional costs outside the manager's control."</data>
      <data key="d2">4e87d1e76027b0ff68b56a7c9c9c92c1</data>
      <data key="d7">25</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1187</data>
      <data key="d6">1121b50f7858427fa679d81861238825</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TRANSFER PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Transfer pricing" refers to the price at which one division transfers goods or services to another division within the same company or from one subsidiary to another within a group. It involves the setting of prices for transactions between these divisions or subsidiaries, ensuring that the internal exchange of goods and services is conducted at an appropriate value.</data>
      <data key="d2">0622f4f26dbe7479c871198b2e72b940,078e47b3223db97709a37da2a01302c5,4e87d1e76027b0ff68b56a7c9c9c92c1</data>
      <data key="d7">25</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">1188</data>
      <data key="d6">6e3c8aa3abab475bb0148faa9112f0bf</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OBJECTIVES OF TRANSFER PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The objectives of transfer pricing are goal congruence, divisional autonomy, and divisional performance evaluation."</data>
      <data key="d2">4e87d1e76027b0ff68b56a7c9c9c92c1</data>
      <data key="d7">25</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1189</data>
      <data key="d6">948a00e8ee1246cc90c47b292d03ddff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF GOAL CONGRUENCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"EXAMPLE OF GOAL CONGRUENCE"

ABC Consulting, a firm with offices in several major cities, provides an example of goal congruence in transfer pricing. This occurs when consultants in one office make decisions that benefit the entire organization. However, there was an instance where ABC Consulting's internal transfer pricing led to a decision that was advantageous for the Budapest office but not for the overall company, illustrating goal incongruence. This highlights the importance of aligning individual office goals with the broader objectives of the company to achieve overall success.</data>
      <data key="d2">0622f4f26dbe7479c871198b2e72b940,4e87d1e76027b0ff68b56a7c9c9c92c1</data>
      <data key="d7">25</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1190</data>
      <data key="d6">45c42e619f5e488f914608780dcf0579</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ROI AND RESIDUAL INCOME CALCULATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">4e87d1e76027b0ff68b56a7c9c9c92c1</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1191</data>
      <data key="d6">2b3bea0d9ede41f193828526bcb8e02c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DIVISIONAL AUTONOMY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Divisional autonomy refers to the freedom of divisional managers to make their own decisions, which can improve motivation but may lead to imbalanced transfer pricing."</data>
      <data key="d2">0622f4f26dbe7479c871198b2e72b940</data>
      <data key="d7">25</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1192</data>
      <data key="d6">6b2586cc1f8e4dc8af64913af63d9837</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SUPPLYING DIVISION PERSPECTIVE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The supplying division will accept a minimum transfer price equal to the marginal (variable) cost plus the opportunity cost."</data>
      <data key="d2">0622f4f26dbe7479c871198b2e72b940</data>
      <data key="d7">25</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1193</data>
      <data key="d6">7983bfa8d173414685272b3844d6612e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SCENARIO 1 - OPPORTUNITY COST IS ZERO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"When there is no external market or there is spare capacity, the opportunity cost is zero, and the minimum transfer price is the marginal cost."</data>
      <data key="d2">0622f4f26dbe7479c871198b2e72b940</data>
      <data key="d7">25</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1194</data>
      <data key="d6">09294e8220a445e288ea8841f234a440</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: NO OPPORTUNITY COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves calculating the minimum transfer price when there is no opportunity cost and determining the actions of divisions in such a scenario."</data>
      <data key="d2">0622f4f26dbe7479c871198b2e72b940</data>
      <data key="d7">25</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1195</data>
      <data key="d6">d4e043cf972c4d129b6b855f1731caae</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SCENARIO 2 - OPPORTUNITY COST ARISES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"An opportunity cost arises when an internal sale sacrifices an external sale, and the supplying division operates at full capacity."</data>
      <data key="d2">0622f4f26dbe7479c871198b2e72b940</data>
      <data key="d7">25</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1196</data>
      <data key="d6">e0d63137270c426dbbfe7fcf78c474de</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ: WITH OPPORTUNITY COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves determining the minimum transfer price when there is an opportunity cost and evaluating the actions of divisions in such a scenario."</data>
      <data key="d2">0622f4f26dbe7479c871198b2e72b940</data>
      <data key="d7">25</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1197</data>
      <data key="d6">c50bca18bc454a98b935df012b7fd6f9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARKET PRICE METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The market price method sets the transfer price based on the external market price. It may need to be adjusted downwards if internal sales incur lower costs than external sales, such as lower delivery costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">e96e3681999d08ff8797d8716ea0a5c3</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1198</data>
      <data key="d6">434b133c64bd46219e67c6eb296ad0ff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FULL COST PLUS METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">The "FULL COST PLUS METHOD" sets transfer prices by adding a markup to the full cost of production. This method ensures that the supplying division covers its production costs. However, it may lead to dysfunctional decisions if there is spare capacity. Under this method, the supplying division charges the full absorption cost plus a markup. To avoid transferring inefficiencies from the selling division to the buying division, standard costs should be used rather than actual costs.</data>
      <data key="d2">34f2c5c9d893c1b631ed1646193eebf4,e96e3681999d08ff8797d8716ea0a5c3</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1199</data>
      <data key="d6">cb895bf7e7c147e6b5d923b6c8f67d63</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VARIABLE COST PLUS METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Variable cost plus is similar to full cost plus, where the transfer price is set at the variable cost plus a mark-up."</data>
      <data key="d2">e96e3681999d08ff8797d8716ea0a5c3</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1200</data>
      <data key="d6">87776e869a01402499a317cb9cf09453</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARGINAL COST METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Marginal cost method sets the transfer price at the variable cost plus any incremental fixed costs, such as stepped costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">e96e3681999d08ff8797d8716ea0a5c3</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1201</data>
      <data key="d6">d1e5359d2e344260bf1b83823df839b7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ADVANTAGES OF MARKET PRICE METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The market price method is optimal for goal congruence if the selling division is at full capacity and encourages efficiency as the supplying division must compete with external competition."</data>
      <data key="d2">e96e3681999d08ff8797d8716ea0a5c3</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1202</data>
      <data key="d6">0522f6580b824bc39792b695fc8be66b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DISADVANTAGES OF MARKET PRICE METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The market price method is only possible if a perfectly competitive external market exists, and market prices may fluctuate."</data>
      <data key="d2">e96e3681999d08ff8797d8716ea0a5c3</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1203</data>
      <data key="d6">580fd6d19460460fa40613f66b3ee200</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ADVANTAGES OF FULL COST PLUS METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The full cost plus method is easy to calculate if a standard costing system exists, covers all costs of the selling division, and may approximate to market price."</data>
      <data key="d2">e96e3681999d08ff8797d8716ea0a5c3</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1204</data>
      <data key="d6">84f4684a7a5241c18bb087ccb00550d3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DISADVANTAGES OF FULL COST PLUS METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The full cost plus method can lead to dysfunctional decisions as the fixed costs of the selling division become the variable costs of the buying division, and the markup is arbitrary."</data>
      <data key="d2">e96e3681999d08ff8797d8716ea0a5c3</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1205</data>
      <data key="d6">9607ba4a796f46be8d4f79bc7065d60b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ADVANTAGES OF MARGINAL COST METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The marginal cost method is optimal for goal congruence when the selling division has spare capacity or no external market exists."</data>
      <data key="d2">e96e3681999d08ff8797d8716ea0a5c3</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1206</data>
      <data key="d6">236dd7dce9ee4cf5918fddd44b4863e5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DISADVANTAGES OF MARGINAL COST METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The marginal cost method may be difficult to calculate as variable cost is often used as an approximation."</data>
      <data key="d2">e96e3681999d08ff8797d8716ea0a5c3</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1207</data>
      <data key="d6">9e92fed814a64d9d88bfab9a227859d3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF COST-BASED APPROACHES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"An example of cost-based approaches involves a division (A) transferring its production to another division (B). The example illustrates the impact of using variable cost, full cost, and full cost plus methods on divisional and group profits."</data>
      <data key="d2">e96e3681999d08ff8797d8716ea0a5c3</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1208</data>
      <data key="d6">7dccecb29d3a419093b279b22e207539</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DYSFUNCTIONAL DECISION-MAKING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Dysfunctional decision-making occurs when transfer prices lead to decisions that are not aligned with the overall goals of the company."</data>
      <data key="d2">5ad3a043b58cedf0d850b61a9e407269</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1209</data>
      <data key="d6">89857eb61e63461cbad7c5014f5098f9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INCONGRUENT GOAL BEHAVIOUR&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Incongruent goal behaviour refers to situations where the transfer price may lead to behaviour that is not congruent with the overall goals of the company."</data>
      <data key="d2">5ad3a043b58cedf0d850b61a9e407269</data>
      <data key="d7">24</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1210</data>
      <data key="d6">7b2e7a0d910c4988a7b64489f4159a65</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXAMPLE OF LACK OF GOAL CONGRUENCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A selling division with spare capacity produces Product B at a marginal cost of $10 per unit. The buying division can obtain Product B externally for $15 per unit. If the transfer price exceeds $15, the buying division will buy externally, leading to an extra cost of $5 per unit for the company."</data>
      <data key="d2">5ad3a043b58cedf0d850b61a9e407269</data>
      <data key="d7">24</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1211</data>
      <data key="d6">38630cf0996f4cff8d32b2dbdaa5ba85</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DUAL PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Dual pricing is a system where a higher price is used for the selling division's revenue and a lower price for the buying division's costs, with the head office absorbing the difference."</data>
      <data key="d2">5ad3a043b58cedf0d850b61a9e407269</data>
      <data key="d7">24</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1212</data>
      <data key="d6">bd0fb68ac7014b91a314c93ec55897f5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SUMMARY OF TRANSFER PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Transfer prices are needed for internal transactions within a company. The primary objective is goal congruence. The minimum transfer price is the marginal cost, and the maximum is the lower of the external market price or net revenue. An economic transfer price lies between these two limits."</data>
      <data key="d2">5ad3a043b58cedf0d850b61a9e407269</data>
      <data key="d7">24</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1213</data>
      <data key="d6">f24dcb3cd6d644f8af2b6c47983e280b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INFORMATION SYSTEMS FOR OPERATIONS QUIZ&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz asks which type of information system is most likely to assist managers involved with day-to-day operations of a business. The correct answer is C. Transaction processing system."</data>
      <data key="d2">5ad3a043b58cedf0d850b61a9e407269</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1214</data>
      <data key="d6">b1cad695afbc4ec3bbcd46ea34bd26ca</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PASSWORD CONTROLS QUIZ&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz asks which of the following would NOT be an effective control over the use of passwords. The correct answer is B. Keeping a written record of passwords."</data>
      <data key="d2">5ad3a043b58cedf0d850b61a9e407269</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1215</data>
      <data key="d6">72f7974758d74e5d89ddb64ad739abb8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STAFF RECRUITMENT REPORTS QUIZ&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz asks which type of report is most likely to be used for staff recruitment and turnover. The correct answer is C. Tactical management."</data>
      <data key="d2">5ad3a043b58cedf0d850b61a9e407269</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1216</data>
      <data key="d6">e6ee83249adf4e14b98d1676b1c6b05f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DATA VISUALISATIONS FOR REVENUE TRENDS QUIZ&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz asks which data visualisation would be most suitable to show management how total revenue changes over time. The correct answer is B. Line chart."</data>
      <data key="d2">5ad3a043b58cedf0d850b61a9e407269</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1217</data>
      <data key="d6">f805fd9fe42947a38b92a3db6e8cc986</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TRANSFER PRICE&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1">"TRANSFER PRICE" refers to the price at which goods or services are transferred between divisions within the same company. For example, Division M might sell 25,000 units to Division S at a transfer price of $760.</data>
      <data key="d2">0cafbc1007afddae5f416e6fb910386a,34f2c5c9d893c1b631ed1646193eebf4,5ad3a043b58cedf0d850b61a9e407269,e7252c8498b73faa26b2d497f6c99eca</data>
