      <data key="d6">744f492f46d841c0b0fee5f4a9b40b6c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIAL PRICE VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Material price variance is the difference between the actual cost of materials and the standard cost, given as $4,800A."</data>
      <data key="d2">a2b172963f635500ceb4bcd40e29a190,b3b56fd239dac9dbd52c81d7357fc19b</data>
      <data key="d7">28</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1500</data>
      <data key="d6">d59386dbfa0349b49f7b904e288b21ad</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIAL USAGE VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Material usage variance" is calculated as the difference between the actual quantity of materials used and the standard quantity allowed or expected to be used, multiplied by the standard cost per unit or per kilogram. This variance measures the effect of the actual quantity of materials used differing from the standard quantity, evaluated using the standard price per unit. For example, a material usage variance might be given as $100A.</data>
      <data key="d2">31513de544b09bc77695e746ff044232,a2b172963f635500ceb4bcd40e29a190,a3550b57bf20a6d9132ffc81fb1444d1,b2fef5f7c017e4d460ee5bc5f0a369ef,b3b56fd239dac9dbd52c81d7357fc19b</data>
      <data key="d7">28</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">8</data>
      <data key="d5">1501</data>
      <data key="d6">1005971b7e764bffa0a4610ad403976b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIAL MIX VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Material mix variance is calculated as the difference between the actual quantity at standard mix and the actual quantity at actual mix, multiplied by the standard cost per unit. It measures the effect of the actual mix of materials used differing from the standard mix, evaluated using the standard price per unit. The formula for material mix variance is (Actual mix - Standard mix) * Standard price. For instance, in a specific calculation, the material mix variance was determined to be $800A.</data>
      <data key="d2">31513de544b09bc77695e746ff044232,5083b641e457d160a51be1a4c3595318,a3550b57bf20a6d9132ffc81fb1444d1,b3b56fd239dac9dbd52c81d7357fc19b</data>
      <data key="d7">28</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">1502</data>
      <data key="d6">1eaf3527e2804c75bbd9e3ccac9d760e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIAL YIELD VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Material yield variance" is a metric used to measure the efficiency of material usage in production. It is calculated by comparing the actual yield to the standard yield, with the difference then multiplied by the standard cost per unit. The formula for material yield variance is (Actual yield - Standard yield) * Standard cost per unit. This variance highlights the effect of the actual yield differing from the expected yield based on the standard input, and it is evaluated using the standard price per unit. For instance, a material yield variance can be calculated as $700F, indicating a favorable variance.</data>
      <data key="d2">31513de544b09bc77695e746ff044232,5083b641e457d160a51be1a4c3595318,a3550b57bf20a6d9132ffc81fb1444d1,b3b56fd239dac9dbd52c81d7357fc19b</data>
      <data key="d7">28</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">1503</data>
      <data key="d6">301ab7b5f81d40788e46dacb09579b50</data>
    </node>
