    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LIFE-CYCLE COSTING ANALYSIS FOR NUCLEAR AND WIND POWER STATIONS AT VOLT CO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Volt Co generates and sells electricity through nuclear and wind power stations. The case involves analyzing the life-cycle costs of these power stations, including operating costs, decommissioning costs, and the total life-cycle cost per gigawatt."</data>
      <data key="d2">7b3dd175d38a9f290c9e33467fc9f8a0</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1583</data>
      <data key="d6">aadd82f0e70c4fc49b1bdee3f60c1890</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NUCLEAR STATION LIFE-CYCLE COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Life-cycle cost per gigawatt of a nuclear station = Total life-cycle costs / Total gigawatts generated over the station's useful life."</data>
      <data key="d2">7b3dd175d38a9f290c9e33467fc9f8a0</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1584</data>
      <data key="d6">9528d92ccc10454793c4df59e24586db</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;WIND STATION LIFE-CYCLE COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Life-cycle cost per gigawatt of a wind station = Total life-cycle costs / Total gigawatts generated over the station's useful life."</data>
      <data key="d2">7b3dd175d38a9f290c9e33467fc9f8a0</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1585</data>
      <data key="d6">80618f4e809e4af1bcdb59342c375377</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DISPOSAL COST OF SPENT NUCLEAR FUEL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The disposal cost of spent nuclear fuel is categorized as an internal failure cost in environmental management accounting (EMA). It is incurred by Volt Co as a result of its activities and is disposed of in a safe manner to ensure it does not become a cost borne by society."</data>
      <data key="d2">7b3dd175d38a9f290c9e33467fc9f8a0</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1586</data>
      <data key="d6">32d785e275be458fb7178ad2021ecdfc</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LIFE-CYCLE COSTING AND STRATEGIC PLANNING FOR MIDHURST CO'S NEW AIR CONDITIONING UNIT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Midhurst Co is considering an investment in a new air conditioning unit that utilizes advanced technology to efficiently regulate airflow and temperature, providing a competitive edge in the market. This new unit is designed for use in modern office buildings and is more sensitive to changes and variations in temperature, allowing it to regulate airflow and heating more efficiently than any current competitor products.

The company plans to use life-cycle costing to evaluate the unit's profitability, taking into account various costs over the product's predicted five-year life cycle. These costs include research and development ($6,200,000), design ($33,450,000), marketing ($177,685,000), variable production costs per unit ($42), fixed production costs ($98,470,000), variable distribution costs per unit ($9), fixed distribution costs ($10,300,000), variable selling costs per unit ($4), fixed selling costs ($7,790,000), and administration costs ($23,450,000). Midhurst Co expects to sell 10,000 units over this period.

The finance director has prepared the initial costings and plans to use life-cycle costing to measure the new product's profitability. The chief executive, who is seeking to understand the benefits of life-cycle costing for strategic decision-making, has requested more information about this method. Meanwhile, the production director has reviewed the costings in detail, suggested possible cost reductions, and is enthusiastic about the product. He believes that modifications could be made to extend the product's life cycle but is considering the optimal timing for these changes.

Overall, Midhurst Co aims to leverage life-cycle costing to make informed strategic decisions regarding the new air conditioning unit, ensuring it remains competitive and profitable throughout its life cycle."</data>
      <data key="d2">7b3dd175d38a9f290c9e33467fc9f8a0,ae4f9eb0f940c70c89837f1343567883</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1587</data>
      <data key="d6">0757f97d1fbf49748169ba696a364e4c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRODUCT LIFECYCLE STAGES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The product lifecycle consists of five stages: development, introduction, growth, maturity, and decline. During the development stage, the product is designed, and manufacturing processes are established, with negative cash flow as no revenue is generated. As the product moves through the introduction, growth, and maturity stages, pricing strategies evolve to maximize demand and profits, while in the decline stage, demand and prices may decrease unless a niche market is found."</data>
      <data key="d2">7b3dd175d38a9f290c9e33467fc9f8a0,ae4f9eb0f940c70c89837f1343567883</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1588</data>
      <data key="d6">ca9a355bf38b452cbde62dba747ec65f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BENEFITS OF LIFE-CYCLE COSTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Life-cycle costing helps management plan pricing strategies over the entire product lifecycle, leading to better cost control and understanding. By monitoring cumulative revenues and costs, it provides more meaningful information for decision-making than traditional period-based monitoring. Additionally, it allows for cost reduction during the design phase, improving profitability and informed decision-making on product development and continuation."</data>
      <data key="d2">7b3dd175d38a9f290c9e33467fc9f8a0,ae4f9eb0f940c70c89837f1343567883</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1589</data>
      <data key="d6">ba297c67512447e4b86f0cbc39fbc301</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ ON LIFE-CYCLE COSTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves multiple questions about life-cycle costing, including the stages of the product lifecycle, cost per unit calculations, material cost revisions, and the implications for production planning. It also covers the advantages of using life-cycle costing for strategic decision-making."</data>
      <data key="d2">ae4f9eb0f940c70c89837f1343567883</data>
      <data key="d7">2</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1590</data>
      <data key="d6">00a9c8745b404b659c76a694dba9851c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TARGET COSTING CHALLENGES AND STRATEGIC PLANNING FOR DARASK CO'S D-PAAD LAUNCH&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Darask Co, a global consumer electronics manufacturer, is considering launching a new device, the D-Paad, with a three-year life cycle. The company uses target costing to ensure profitability. Market research has been conducted to determine the price customers are willing to pay at different stages of the product life cycle. The board has set a total product cost limit of $13,000m for the D-Paad. Additionally, the company is exploring the feasibility of using target costing for new retail outlets that will offer free services and repairs."</data>
      <data key="d2">14d295eb69556ed8203b13909d341a07</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">1591</data>
      <data key="d6">eb338f2214414f0f9fa396f06ca12860</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LIFE CYCLE COSTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Life cycle costing (LCC) is a method of calculating the total cost of ownership of a product, asset, or system over its entire life cycle. This comprehensive approach includes initial costs, operating costs, maintenance costs, and disposal costs. Additionally, life cycle costing is a system that tracks and accumulates the actual costs and revenues attributable to each product from development through to abandonment."</data>
      <data key="d2">1198b5b37a51d0315db68af2bdb139bd,14d295eb69556ed8203b13909d341a07</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1592</data>
      <data key="d6">d119680bac3744e58d2ed3273b1208b6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;D-PAAD FEASIBILITY STUDY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The feasibility study for the D-Paad includes estimates of sales volumes and prices at different stages of the product life cycle, as well as variable and fixed costs. The study aims to ensure a profit mark-up of 60% and sets a total product cost limit of $13,000m."</data>
      <data key="d2">14d295eb69556ed8203b13909d341a07</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1593</data>
      <data key="d6">d60eefaddf1e4b1db125d8f9ac49bacb</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;D-PAAD MARKET RESEARCH ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Market research for the D-Paad estimates sales volumes and prices at various stages of the product life cycle: Introduction (8 million units at $425), Growth (14 million units at $300), Maturity (56 million units at $220), and Decline (2 million units at $120)."</data>
      <data key="d2">14d295eb69556ed8203b13909d341a07</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1594</data>
      <data key="d6">6058343c0824402e9843c92b2991f778</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RETAIL OUTLETS FOR DARASK CO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Darask Co is considering opening retail outlets in major cities worldwide. These outlets will sell Darask Co's products and offer free services and repairs. The feasibility of using target costing for these outlets is being discussed."</data>
      <data key="d2">14d295eb69556ed8203b13909d341a07</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1595</data>
      <data key="d6">383a003edc5a4f2387c7dd7865a984c9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INTRODUCTION STAGE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Introduction stage is the initial phase of a product's lifecycle where it is launched into the market, characterized by lower sales units and higher sales prices."</data>
      <data key="d2">afe505b1f94b0e6d25ef40e510dfada7</data>
      <data key="d7">13</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1596</data>
      <data key="d6">6bf9623c44824e48b7451bdfa1b47816</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GROWTH STAGE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Growth stage is the phase in a product's lifecycle where sales units increase significantly, and sales prices may start to decrease."</data>
      <data key="d2">afe505b1f94b0e6d25ef40e510dfada7</data>
      <data key="d7">13</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1597</data>
      <data key="d6">cc62f333666e427eb1c66ec3f12a7a55</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATURITY STAGE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Maturity stage is the phase in a product's lifecycle where sales units peak and stabilize, and sales prices are lower."</data>
      <data key="d2">afe505b1f94b0e6d25ef40e510dfada7</data>
      <data key="d7">13</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1598</data>
      <data key="d6">c6d99481f5f545278ca8a73650b66e87</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DECLINE STAGE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Decline stage is the final phase in a product's lifecycle where sales units and sales prices decrease."</data>
      <data key="d2">afe505b1f94b0e6d25ef40e510dfada7</data>
      <data key="d7">13</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1599</data>
      <data key="d6">5a0887b99d8b4bd89286962cd6f07037</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TARGET REVENUE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Target revenue is the projected total income that a company aims to achieve from sales of a product."</data>
      <data key="d2">afe505b1f94b0e6d25ef40e510dfada7</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1600</data>
      <data key="d6">75174e7af26f434c9154b182087b58dc</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PROPOSALS TO CLOSE COST GAP&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Proposals to close the cost gap include introducing 24-hour working in factories, incorporating quality assurance inspections, and increasing sales and marketing spend."</data>
      <data key="d2">afe505b1f94b0e6d25ef40e510dfada7</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1601</data>
      <data key="d6">0c43dd117fe6495991d4b4d8c2f5d70e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EVALUATING THE FINANCIAL IMPACT OF SUNDAY TRADING FOR BITS AND PIECES RETAIL STORE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Bits and Pieces (B&amp;P) is considering opening for trading on Sundays to increase revenue. The case evaluates the financial impact, including additional revenue, costs, and potential supplier discounts."</data>
      <data key="d2">afe505b1f94b0e6d25ef40e510dfada7</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1602</data>
      <data key="d6">65e5d27c4f8a4dfa8ad92f227964b9cf</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SUNDAY TRADING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sunday trading refers to the practice of opening a retail store for business on Sundays, which can lead to increased revenue and additional costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">afe505b1f94b0e6d25ef40e510dfada7</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1603</data>
      <data key="d6">63c4595187884af29aa46d03319acded</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SUPPLIER DISCOUNT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Supplier discount is a reduction in the purchase price offered by a supplier when certain conditions, such as a minimum annual spend, are met."</data>
      <data key="d2">afe505b1f94b0e6d25ef40e510dfada7</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1604</data>
      <data key="d6">b32482039edd4d50bc43514570500345</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MANAGER'S BONUS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Manager's bonus is an additional payment made to a manager based on the extra sales generated by Sunday trading."</data>
      <data key="d2">afe505b1f94b0e6d25ef40e510dfada7</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1605</data>
      <data key="d6">f3e6e2c82bab4430a33987a19e3d1835</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ENERGY COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Energy costs refer to the expenses incurred for energy consumption. In this context, it is calculated based on the total hours worked and the cost per hour. Additionally, energy costs encompass the expenses for lighting and heating the store during Sunday trading."</data>
      <data key="d2">2343dedcae64d2e174ab981dfc3b23a0,afe505b1f94b0e6d25ef40e510dfada7</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1606</data>
      <data key="d6">6768cc24da5d4a2492ff936dd4b35661</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STAFF COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"STAFF COSTS" refer to the wages and premiums paid to employees working on Sundays and the cost of hiring additional part-time employees. Staff cost growth is calculated as $91,000/$65,000, resulting in a +40% increase. In absolute terms, average staff costs were $16,250 in 20X0, calculated from a total of $65,000 divided by four employees. The additional staff cost amounted to $26,000, which is the difference between $91,000 and $65,000, covering the expenses for two additional people.</data>
      <data key="d2">afe505b1f94b0e6d25ef40e510dfada7,f41491fbf8c72d2afdc444dec24f9e1e</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1607</data>
      <data key="d6">223e1e3e7c4f4282b086e940f8c935c2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES UNITS&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">afe505b1f94b0e6d25ef40e510dfada7</data>
      <data key="d7">13</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1608</data>
      <data key="d6">f5bb365c9a814b909df0351498d79bb5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ADDITIONAL GROSS PROFIT FROM SUNDAY OPENING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Additional gross profit from Sunday opening is calculated as follows: (16,000 per day (10,000 + 60%) * 50 days) = 800,000, Additional cost of sales (GP margin is 70%) = (240,000), Less additional supplier discounts (W2) = 57,000, Additional gross profit from Sunday opening = 617,000."</data>
      <data key="d2">97c32504d2870c2f5acc1ff972ad9478</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">1609</data>
      <data key="d6">ab4ad26863b44497a1e48aa7c17a096c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ADDITIONAL SUPPLIER DISCOUNTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Additional supplier discounts are calculated as follows: Annual revenue without Sunday opening = 6 * 50 * 10,000 = $3,000,000, Annual purchases without Sunday opening = $900,000, Therefore, the company would not qualify for the discount. Annual purchases with Sunday opening (900,000 + 240,000) = $1,140,000, Over $1,000,000 so discount given on all purchases = 5% * $1,140,000 = $57,000."</data>
      <data key="d2">97c32504d2870c2f5acc1ff972ad9478</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1610</data>
      <data key="d6">145bc384290c49228a231ac124ce88a8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ANNUAL RELEVANT COST OF THE MANAGER FOR SUNDAY TRADING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The annual relevant cost of the manager for Sunday trading is calculated as follows: The salary is fixed, so the only additional cost of the manager working on Sunday is the bonus, being 1% of the additional revenue: (1% * ($10,000 + 60%) * 50 Sundays) = $8,000."</data>
      <data key="d2">97c32504d2870c2f5acc1ff972ad9478</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1611</data>
      <data key="d6">f64c99537adf489ea58940e417cb5924</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ANNUAL RELEVANT COST OF LIGHTING AND HEATING THE STORES FOR SUNDAY TRADING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The annual relevant cost of lighting and heating the stores for Sunday trading is calculated as follows: Lighting (6 hours * $30 per hour * 50 days) = $9,000, Heating (8 hours * $45 per hour * 25 days) = $9,000, Total = $18,000."</data>
      <data key="d2">97c32504d2870c2f5acc1ff972ad9478</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1612</data>
      <data key="d6">fe98ea566cf6486b85f8ed14aabb2618</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ANNUAL RELEVANT COST OF RENT FOR SUNDAY TRADING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The annual relevant cost of rent for Sunday trading is zero because it is not an incremental cost. Annual rent is not relevant because it does not increase (i.e. is not incremental)."</data>
      <data key="d2">97c32504d2870c2f5acc1ff972ad9478</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1613</data>
      <data key="d6">6bfb83cb716745fcb591c8d2fb54f8f4</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ANNUAL RELEVANT COST OF THE LABOUR FOR SUNDAY TRADING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The annual relevant cost of the labour for Sunday trading is calculated as follows: The relevant cost is the incremental cost: Premium paid to existing staff (2 * 30 * 50 weeks) = $3,000, Replacement staff on Saturday (2 * 20 * 50 weeks) = $2,000, Temporary staff for Sundays (2 * 30 * 50 weeks) = $3,000, Total = $8,000."</data>
      <data key="d2">97c32504d2870c2f5acc1ff972ad9478</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1614</data>
      <data key="d6">9866640f891944c7bb0a08748aa8b91f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ANALYSIS OF CEASING TUMBLE DRYER PRODUCTION AND PRICING STRATEGIES FOR STAY CLEAN&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Stay Clean manufactures and sells a small range of kitchen equipment, including a dishwasher (DW), a washing machine (WM), and a tumble dryer (TD). The TD has been generating negative contribution and is expected to become obsolete in a year. Stay Clean is deciding whether to cease TD production now or in 12 months when a new combined washing machine/dryer will be ready. The decision involves considering normal selling prices, annual sales volumes, total variable costs, potential loss of sales for other products, redundancy costs, and material cost savings."</data>
      <data key="d2">97c32504d2870c2f5acc1ff972ad9478</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1615</data>
      <data key="d6">b0d513adad104e14a89a767a66f30848</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NORMAL SELLING PRICES, ANNUAL SALES VOLUMES, AND TOTAL VARIABLE COSTS FOR DW, WM, AND TD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The normal selling prices, annual sales volumes, and total variable costs for the three products are as follows: DW: Selling price per unit = $200, Material cost per unit = $70, Labour cost per unit = $50, Contribution per unit = $80, Annual sales (units) = 5,000. WM: Selling price per unit = $350, Material cost per unit = $100, Labour cost per unit = $80, Contribution per unit = $170, Annual sales (units) = 6,000. TD: Selling price per unit = $80, Material cost per unit = $50, Labour cost per unit = $40, Contribution per unit = -$10, Annual sales (units) = 1,200."</data>
      <data key="d2">97c32504d2870c2f5acc1ff972ad9478</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1616</data>
      <data key="d6">db37a25770a34437b472fa0038837868</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;POTENTIAL LOSS OF SALES FOR WM AND DW IF TD CEASES PRODUCTION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"It is estimated that 5% of the sales of WM and DW will be lost if the TD ceases to be produced."</data>
      <data key="d2">97c32504d2870c2f5acc1ff972ad9478</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1617</data>
      <data key="d6">67746ba67d80491da102aab7704dfd30</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REDUNDANCY AND RETRAINING COSTS FOR TD LABOUR FORCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"All the direct labour force currently working on the TD will be made redundant immediately if TD is ceased now, costing $6,000 in redundancy payments. If Stay Clean waits for 12 months, the existing labour force would be retained and retrained at a cost of $3,500 to enable them to produce the new washing/drying product. Recruitment and training costs of labour in 12 months' time would be $1,200 if redundancy takes place now."</data>
      <data key="d2">97c32504d2870c2f5acc1ff972ad9478</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1618</data>
      <data key="d6">873a1ca522e6461090d5cdebc2c9ae98</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIAL COST SAVINGS AND SUPPLIER DISCOUNT SCHEME&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Stay Clean operates a just-in-time (JIT) policy, so all material costs would be saved on the TD for 12 months if TD production ceased now. Equally, the material costs relating to the lost sales on the WM and the DW would also be saved. The material supplier has a volume-based discount scheme in place as follows: Total annual expenditure ($) 0-600,000 = 0% discount, 600,001-800,000 = 1% discount, 800,001-900,000 = 2% discount."</data>
      <data key="d2">97c32504d2870c2f5acc1ff972ad9478</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1619</data>
      <data key="d6">d919ccd28e2248b5ab1dcdd7af8b00cf</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SUBLET INCOME&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Rental income of $12,000 that Stay Clean would receive if the space currently used for TD production is sublet for 12 months."</data>
      <data key="d2">12bf561fb0f443af5c38c4055dae476d</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1620</data>
      <data key="d6">1883a3ca4d6a4bfd984e7053e2553e16</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SUPERVISOR COST ALLOCATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The supervisor oversees the production of all three products, spending approximately 20% of his time on TD production. He would remain fully employed even if TD production ceases."</data>
      <data key="d2">12bf561fb0f443af5c38c4055dae476d</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1621</data>
      <data key="d6">2a0c93cf781a4020aceef7230b286bbf</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DECISION TO CEASE TD PRODUCTION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"An analysis to determine whether it is financially beneficial for Stay Clean to stop producing the TD product now rather than waiting 12 months. The analysis includes various cost and revenue factors such as lost revenue, saved labor costs, lost contribution from other products, redundancy and recruitment costs, supplier payments saved, sublet income, and supervisor costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">12bf561fb0f443af5c38c4055dae476d</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1622</data>
      <data key="d6">06282cc8998f4b2ea43e0a9522383639</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRICING STRATEGIES TO IMPROVE FINANCIAL POSITION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Two pricing strategies that could be used to improve the financial position of the business in the next 12 months if TD production continues. These strategies could involve adjusting the price of TD or other products to increase revenue or market share."</data>
      <data key="d2">12bf561fb0f443af5c38c4055dae476d</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1623</data>
      <data key="d6">182efa2240c14212bb021746a18936bd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OUTSOURCING CONSIDERATIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Two issues that Stay Clean should consider if it decides to outsource the manufacture of one of its future products. These considerations could include factors such as cost, quality control, and supply chain reliability."</data>
      <data key="d2">12bf561fb0f443af5c38c4055dae476d</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1624</data>
      <data key="d6">727bc610ea9a4393bfa5de453b84340f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONTRIBUTION LOST ON TD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The contribution lost on the TD of 1,200 units is calculated as 1,200 units * $10 per unit = $12,000."</data>
      <data key="d2">5e775105680e2df0d9faf2b40f9036a4</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1625</data>
      <data key="d6">960c3b508a294332ba7c05ffd897db31</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LOST CONTRIBUTION FROM OTHER PRODUCTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The loss of sales of other products will cost a lost contribution of 5% of the total sales of 5,000 units at $80 each and 6,000 units at $170 each, which equals $71,000."</data>
      <data key="d2">5e775105680e2df0d9faf2b40f9036a4</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1626</data>
      <data key="d6">bd0c1d79ef1144a49f3ce09d4cdf099b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CURRENT BUYING COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The current buying cost for DW, WM, and TD is $350,000, $600,000, and $60,000 respectively, totaling $1,010,000. With a 5% discount, the total gross cost is $1,063,158."</data>
      <data key="d2">5e775105680e2df0d9faf2b40f9036a4</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1627</data>
      <data key="d6">b8ae79ed2d6d43f98e0808b5bea884dd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NEW BUYING COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The new buying cost for DW, WM, and TD is $332,500, $570,000, and $0 respectively, totaling $902,500. With a 5% discount, the total gross cost is $950,000."</data>
      <data key="d2">5e775105680e2df0d9faf2b40f9036a4</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1628</data>
      <data key="d6">a03b33a4ee97467c808946679e240ddf</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COMPLEMENTARY PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Complementary pricing is a strategy where products that are used together are sold at a discount when purchased together. For example, buying a TD for $80 and getting a WM for $320, resulting in a positive contribution of $130."</data>
      <data key="d2">5e775105680e2df0d9faf2b40f9036a4</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1629</data>
      <data key="d6">00b685bcb7a54c4493cd78da1f4752ab</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRODUCT LINE PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Product line pricing involves offering a package price for related products, such as those used in a utility room or kitchen, to make a positive contribution on the overall deal."</data>
      <data key="d2">5e775105680e2df0d9faf2b40f9036a4</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1630</data>
      <data key="d6">9a54e0361b684d24aefdc05fc340cf41</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OUTSOURCING DECISION FACTORS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Outsourcing decisions should consider the cost of manufacture versus buying, the reliability of the outsourcer, the quality of work, and the loss of control over the manufacturing process."</data>
      <data key="d2">5e775105680e2df0d9faf2b40f9036a4</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1631</data>
      <data key="d6">d423b97f085947bd89529bc1ed2c41a7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RELEVANT COST ANALYSIS FOR TELEPHONE CO'S CONTRACT PRICING DECISION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Telephone Co (T Co) is considering a contract with Push Co to install a telephone system. The analysis includes costs for sales visits, engineer salaries, penalties for contract delays, technical advisor overtime, site inspector fees, system trainer commissions, and the cost of telephone handsets."</data>
      <data key="d2">5e775105680e2df0d9faf2b40f9036a4</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">1632</data>
      <data key="d6">6fd2b0d5156c424a89cb1c068cf1e076</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ENGINEER SALARIES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Engineers are paid a monthly salary of $4,000. For the Push Co contract, one engineer has spare capacity, while two others would need to be moved from another contract, incurring a penalty of $500."</data>
      <data key="d2">5e775105680e2df0d9faf2b40f9036a4</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1633</data>
      <data key="d6">a8c8dd8ddbc44363ac2102b9b8989c6d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TECHNICAL ADVISOR OVERTIME&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The technical advisor would need to work overtime at a rate of $40 per hour plus a 50% premium, totaling $60 per hour."</data>
      <data key="d2">5e775105680e2df0d9faf2b40f9036a4</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1634</data>
      <data key="d6">00cb0db6e46749f7af97701ad26e23be</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SITE INSPECTOR FEES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The site inspector charges $200 per visit and is an independent contractor."</data>
      <data key="d2">5e775105680e2df0d9faf2b40f9036a4</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1635</data>
      <data key="d6">4baa53e4336d4807964fa8d186b32bc5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SYSTEM TRAINER COMMISSIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The system trainer is paid a monthly salary of $1,500 and receives a commission of $125 for each day spent delivering training at a client's site."</data>
      <data key="d2">5e775105680e2df0d9faf2b40f9036a4</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1636</data>
      <data key="d6">f325a83e0c854a7ba5d46663ddff1a29</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TELEPHONE HANDSETS COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The current cost of telephone handsets is $18.20 each, but T Co has 80 handsets in inventory bought at $16 each."</data>
      <data key="d2">5e775105680e2df0d9faf2b40f9036a4</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1637</data>
      <data key="d6">c2b7e5d9761e423a81149a94537f6def</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MODIFICATION COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Modification cost refers to the expenses incurred to alter or adapt an existing asset to meet specific requirements. In this context, the modification cost of $4,600 is the expense required to convert Swipe 1."</data>
      <data key="d2">77d0f2f7f5d6dc47dd22962bc1f3d777</data>
      <data key="d7">18</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1638</data>
      <data key="d6">3d1ccd312d3a4e7387e888aaa137c7c2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RELEVANT COSTING PRINCIPLES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Relevant costs are those costs that change as a result of making a particular decision. They must meet three criteria: they must be future costs, involve cash flow, and be a direct consequence of the decision."</data>
      <data key="d2">77d0f2f7f5d6dc47dd22962bc1f3d777</data>
      <data key="d7">18</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1639</data>
      <data key="d6">840966e7ac4a4b14ac912e75102d50b7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MINIMUM PRICE CALCULATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"MINIMUM PRICE CALCULATION" is the process of determining the lowest price at which a company can sell a product without incurring a loss. This calculation includes relevant costs and may also consider opportunity costs and overheads. For instance, the minimum price per unit that Skulpt Co could set for LOK Co's order of the GSA is $60. This price is calculated by considering only the relevant costs: $30 for production, $24 for selling and distribution, and $6 for additional production costs.</data>
      <data key="d2">33d735a6b75645248eabb5d1c5835d61,77d0f2f7f5d6dc47dd22962bc1f3d777</data>
      <data key="d7">18</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1640</data>
      <data key="d6">f0ede764bdb1437b8cfcc20ca9598712</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OUTSOURCING DECISION FOR KEY COMPONENTS: MAKE-OR-BUY ANALYSIS AND STRATEGIC CONSIDERATIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Robber Co manufactures control panels for burglar alarms and is considering outsourcing the production of keypads and display screens due to labor constraints. A company in Burgistan has offered to supply these components at a fixed price for two years. The case involves analyzing the costs and strategic implications of making or buying these components."</data>
      <data key="d2">77d0f2f7f5d6dc47dd22962bc1f3d777</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1641</data>
      <data key="d6">dd38d562c21f444190768c8a154280da</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MAKE-OR-BUY ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Make-or-Buy Analysis is a decision-making process used to determine whether a company should manufacture a product in-house or purchase it from an external supplier. It involves comparing the costs and benefits of both options."</data>
      <data key="d2">77d0f2f7f5d6dc47dd22962bc1f3d777</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1642</data>
      <data key="d6">1e66c1cbb56b41269555d27e1505ec92</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DISPLAY SCREENS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Display screens are another component produced by Robber Co, with an annual production of 80,000 units. The production involves direct materials, direct labour, heat and power costs, machine costs, and depreciation and insurance costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">5c4312b5c5c803bc38cc120660340db3</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">1643</data>
      <data key="d6">a653bd47ad3d4009ab6a5b8e6ff18679</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MAKE OR BUY DECISION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The make or buy decision involves evaluating whether Robber Co should continue to manufacture keypads and display screens in-house or outsource their production to a supplier in Burgistan. The decision is based on comparing the total incremental costs of in-house production with the cost of outsourcing."</data>
      <data key="d2">5c4312b5c5c803bc38cc120660340db3</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1644</data>
      <data key="d6">37b7cf055e604ec6927a9f0b15b2698d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LABOUR HOURS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Labour hours" refer to the total number of hours worked by employees and are a critical factor in the production process. Specifically, for Robber Co, labour hours are required to produce keypads and display screens. It takes 0.5 labour hours to produce a keypad and 0.75 labour hours to produce a display screen. There is a total labour hour restriction of 100,000 hours, which serves as a limiting factor in production, particularly noted for month 2.</data>
      <data key="d2">5a645510a423feead88fce4460595798,5c4312b5c5c803bc38cc120660340db3</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1645</data>
      <data key="d6">182e0f3d0abd4181820acdd2bf8e5eaf</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;KEYPADS&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">5c4312b5c5c803bc38cc120660340db3</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">1646</data>
      <data key="d6">6fd6398a9bfd496f9a0505d9f3190362</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RELEVANT MANUFACTURING COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Relevant manufacturing costs are the costs that will be directly affected by a decision to make or buy a product. These include variable costs, avoidable fixed costs, and any other costs that can be directly attributed to the production process."</data>
      <data key="d2">fcd99d5b276a15877e82656bf9c54923</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1647</data>
      <data key="d6">2192d6436ca840a1bce77dbf9fd354af</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INCREMENTAL COST OF BUYING IN&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Incremental cost of buying in is calculated as the difference between the cost per unit of buying a product and the relevant cost per unit of making it in-house."</data>
      <data key="d2">fcd99d5b276a15877e82656bf9c54923</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1648</data>
      <data key="d6">ef5e0bbdb3774a22900cf45e9b8863ad</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NON-FINANCIAL FACTORS IN MAKE OR BUY DECISION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Non-financial factors in a make or buy decision include supplier reliability, quality of components, continuity of supply, and potential risks associated with new suppliers. These factors can significantly impact the overall decision beyond just cost considerations."</data>
      <data key="d2">fcd99d5b276a15877e82656bf9c54923</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1649</data>
      <data key="d6">307de250d35e43a8b122c4232fa8fb7c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EVALUATION OF INCREMENTAL CASH FLOWS AND STRATEGIC CONSIDERATIONS FOR BELTON PARK RESORT'S JANUARY OPERATIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Belton Park Resort must decide whether to shut down the entire resort or just the theme park during January, considering limited historical data on costs and revenues. The decision involves evaluating incremental cash flows and strategic considerations for keeping the hotel and/or water park open."</data>
      <data key="d2">fcd99d5b276a15877e82656bf9c54923</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1650</data>
      <data key="d6">0e2f68c8ff734b279b7aad333bcf2fda</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MAKE OR BUY ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">fcd99d5b276a15877e82656bf9c54923</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1651</data>
      <data key="d6">172b0d0fa0794494a3c50b135c1f2cd6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;IMPACT OF COST CHANGES AND BREAK-EVEN ANALYSIS FOR PICO'S PRODUCTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Pico makes two products, P1 and P2, with budgeted details including selling price, cost per unit, and profit per unit. The case involves calculating the number of units needed to achieve a target profit, break-even revenue, and the impact of changes in material costs and fixed costs on break-even revenue."</data>
      <data key="d2">4a96eda99b984c39366e7b2eb363fe96</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1652</data>
      <data key="d6">96f016e343b34ac894b0b7153f474ab0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BREAK-EVEN ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Break-even analysis involves calculating the selling price or volume needed to cover all costs and achieve zero profit or loss. It is a method used to determine the level of sales volume at which total revenues equal total costs, resulting in neither profit nor loss."</data>
      <data key="d2">4a96eda99b984c39366e7b2eb363fe96,853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d7">3</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1653</data>
      <data key="d6">d356499ae9a345b6bbfb33b5fa01f47b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MULTI-PRODUCT BREAK-EVEN ANALYSIS AND PROFIT CALCULATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Nerville makes and sells a range of three gardening products, E375, F294, and G142, with budgeted data including selling price, variable cost, contribution per unit, fixed cost, and profit per unit. The case involves calculating the break-even point and profit for multiple products."</data>
      <data key="d2">4a96eda99b984c39366e7b2eb363fe96</data>
      <data key="d7">3</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1654</data>
      <data key="d6">d7ebead985b34576821f30d83a416cd2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BREAKEVEN POINT OF PROJECT 1&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The breakeven point in sales value for Project 1 is calculated by dividing the fixed costs by the contribution-to-sales (C/S) ratio. The sales value of two room nights is $135, and the sales value of a pair of theatre tickets is $100, making a total of $235. The variable costs are $120 for two room nights and $95 for a pair of theatre tickets, resulting in a contribution of $20. The C/S ratio is 8.51% (20/235), and the breakeven point in revenue is $235,000 ($20,000/0.0851)."</data>
      <data key="d2">445f863fb31fb04b5dfcf56f11b94426</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1655</data>
      <data key="d6">02c1447586fc46dfa65b793e0105a878</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FINANCIAL EFFECT OF PROJECT 2&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Project 2 will increase the fixed costs of the hotel from $600,000 to $800,000 per year. The revenue per occupied room will rise from $180 to $250, reflecting extra guest expenditure in the restaurant. The total cost at 8,000 occupied rooms is $1,560,000, with variable costs of $760,000 ($1,560,000 - $800,000 fixed costs), resulting in a variable cost per occupied room of $95. The breakeven point increases from 5,000 to 5,161 occupied rooms, but the budgeted occupancy is 7,300 occupied room nights, giving a margin of safety of 2,139 occupied room nights or 29%. The budgeted profit at 7,300 occupied room nights is $331,500."</data>
      <data key="d2">445f863fb31fb04b5dfcf56f11b94426</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1656</data>
      <data key="d6">1b1560bb4b0447e5860f8ba351af112e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FINANCIAL VIABILITY ANALYSIS OF REPLACING CAF&#201; WITH CR&#200;CHE AT HEALTH NUTS FITNESS CENTRE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Health Nuts Fitness Centre is considering replacing its onsite caf&#233; with a cr&#232;che. The fitness centre offers 'pay-as-you-go' gym facilities, with a capacity of 200 users and 100 car parking spaces. Customers pay $8.40 for gym access and unlimited time in the caf&#233;, with an additional $1 for car park use. The average number of customers per day is 330, with 40 attending between 9.00am and 5.00pm. The total costs for June, excluding the caf&#233;, are $48,000 in fixed costs and $1.20 in variable costs per customer. Half of the customers use the caf&#233;, with an average spend of $2.20 per customer, 60% of which is on drinks with a 60% profit margin, and the remainder on food with a 40% profit margin."</data>
      <data key="d2">445f863fb31fb04b5dfcf56f11b94426</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1657</data>
      <data key="d6">23b929895979486cba3bf6a13f4ce655</data>
    </node>
