    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TOTAL SALES FROM CRECHE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The total revenue generated from the creche, which is $28,800."</data>
      <data key="d2">4435163b259d1a0d68e055b03df87004</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1665</data>
      <data key="d6">35688e258b0e4cc78c8b92ef8a13d3e3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TOTAL CONTRIBUTION FROM GYM AND CRECHE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The combined total contribution from both the gym and the creche, which is $133,200."</data>
      <data key="d2">4435163b259d1a0d68e055b03df87004</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1666</data>
      <data key="d6">3a9503f2d69343c396c9b1d842d1aa74</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TOTAL SALES FROM GYM AND CRECHE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The combined total sales revenue from both the gym and the creche, which is $153,000."</data>
      <data key="d2">4435163b259d1a0d68e055b03df87004</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1667</data>
      <data key="d6">39516d28d39e49a2b80e6cfac32e2609</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BUDGETED PROFIT PER MONTH WITH CRECHE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The budgeted profit per month when including the creche, which is $77,200."</data>
      <data key="d2">4435163b259d1a0d68e055b03df87004</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1668</data>
      <data key="d6">43cf2e01543540789eb8781fdb5f287d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPTIMAL PRODUCTION STRATEGY AND THROUGHPUT ACCOUNTING FOR YAM CO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Yam Co processes sheet metal into products A, B, and C using pressing, stretching, and rolling processes. The company aims to maximize contribution per hour of pressing time, with pressing identified as the limiting factor. The case involves determining the optimal production mix to maximize profitability."</data>
      <data key="d2">4435163b259d1a0d68e055b03df87004</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">1669</data>
      <data key="d6">54beb6d012d844058715f8ef8a91c5da</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONTRIBUTION PER HOUR OF PRESSING TIME&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Contribution per hour of pressing time" is calculated by dividing the contribution per unit by the pressing time per unit for each product. This metric, known as the contribution margin per hour of pressing time, is a key factor in determining the optimal production mix for Yam Co.</data>
      <data key="d2">4435163b259d1a0d68e055b03df87004,8c5f3adb7ce0099b89e3e7e2687c2a68</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1670</data>
      <data key="d6">5a291bf96ac141b98730ac27c96e829e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LIMITING FACTOR&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The resource that restricts the production capacity, identified as pressing time for Yam Co."</data>
      <data key="d2">4435163b259d1a0d68e055b03df87004</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1671</data>
      <data key="d6">5e572d8b0a614ce1839ec9a568078cdc</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MAXIMUM DEMAND FOR EACH PRODUCT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The maximum demand for each product per year, which is 200,000 metres."</data>
      <data key="d2">4435163b259d1a0d68e055b03df87004</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1672</data>
      <data key="d6">3f7b36b371da40568ce15510a35b58e7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LABOUR HOURS PER YEAR&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The total number of labour hours available per year, which is 700,000."</data>
      <data key="d2">4435163b259d1a0d68e055b03df87004</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1673</data>
      <data key="d6">6db7771bcc674e4ead899fbdd417930f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LABOUR COST PER HOUR&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Labour cost per hour" refers to the expense incurred for each hour of labour. The current cost of labour per hour is $10.</data>
      <data key="d2">4435163b259d1a0d68e055b03df87004,d4cbc64c9c49dd951f9997a26ee9d9f9</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1674</data>
      <data key="d6">176a96262ad64ccbacb1efdfb36bd88a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;THROUGHPUT CONTRIBUTION PER HOUR OF PRESSING TIME&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Throughput contribution per hour of pressing time is calculated by dividing the throughput contribution per unit by the pressing time per unit."</data>
      <data key="d2">8c5f3adb7ce0099b89e3e7e2687c2a68</data>
      <data key="d7">12</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1675</data>
      <data key="d6">bd120225f7b84bbdb0567048ca803e3c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;THROUGHPUT ACCOUNTING RATIO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The "Throughput Accounting Ratio" is a financial metric used to evaluate the efficiency of a production process. It is calculated by dividing the throughput return per hour of the bottleneck resource for a specific product, such as product B, by the overall total overhead cost per hour of the bottleneck resource. Essentially, it measures the return per hour in relation to the factory cost per hour, providing insight into how effectively the bottleneck resource is being utilized to generate profit.</data>
      <data key="d2">39e1257b70d1902a0d6b2502ce5b27b5,727bae9b2b77a13f165dd415aa129b20,8c5f3adb7ce0099b89e3e7e2687c2a68</data>
      <data key="d7">12</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1676</data>
      <data key="d6">8ecda003a3d044279b1f0bdc1c96c25e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRODUCT C&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Product C is one of the products manufactured by Yam Co. It has a selling price of $70, raw materials cost of $10, labour cost of $15, and pressing time per unit of 0.4 hours."</data>
      <data key="d2">8c5f3adb7ce0099b89e3e7e2687c2a68</data>
      <data key="d7">12</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1677</data>
      <data key="d6">8e02a61bda6a4470b693e7e234abfc94</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRODUCT D&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Product D is a fourth product made by Yam Co. It has a throughput accounting ratio of less than one, indicating it may not be profitable under current conditions."</data>
      <data key="d2">8c5f3adb7ce0099b89e3e7e2687c2a68</data>
      <data key="d7">12</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1678</data>
      <data key="d6">b62e3858d801445facc3a501c5100723</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPTIMAL SUIT PRODUCTION STRATEGY AND RESOURCE ALLOCATION FOR CUT AND STITCH&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Cut and Stitch (CS) make two types of suits using skilled tailors (labour) and a delicate and unique fabric (material). Both the tailors and the fabric are in short supply, and the accountant at CS has produced a linear programming model to help decide the optimal production mix. The model includes variables for work suits and lounge suits, an objective to maximize contribution, and constraints related to tailors' time, fabric, and production limits. The feasible region and optimal point are identified on a graph, with point B being the optimal point where contribution is maximized. The case involves determining the optimal production strategy and resource allocation."</data>
      <data key="d2">64dc637d9fd89ad41762620a1229b806,8c5f3adb7ce0099b89e3e7e2687c2a68</data>
      <data key="d7">12</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1679</data>
      <data key="d6">64e8971970e94ea79d10e46c55b3e761</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;YAM CO&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">8c5f3adb7ce0099b89e3e7e2687c2a68</data>
      <data key="d7">12</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">8</data>
      <data key="d5">1680</data>
      <data key="d6">b10fd3628e7a45d29a2814771f53ad60</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LINEAR PROGRAMMING MODEL FOR CUT AND STITCH&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The linear programming model for Cut and Stitch includes variables for the number of work suits (W) and lounge suits (L) produced, an objective function to maximize contribution (C = 48W + 40L), and constraints related to tailors' time (7W + 5L &#8804; 3,500 hours), fabric (2W + 2L &#8804; 1,200 meters), and production limits for work suits (W &#8804; 400). The feasible region and optimal point are identified on a graph."</data>
      <data key="d2">64dc637d9fd89ad41762620a1229b806</data>
      <data key="d7">11</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">7</data>
      <data key="d5">1681</data>
      <data key="d6">826bb16575a141d683fb871ec94517e0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPTIMAL POINT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The optimal point in a linear programming model is the point within the feasible region that maximizes or minimizes the objective function. For Cut and Stitch, point B is the optimal point where contribution is maximized."</data>
      <data key="d2">64dc637d9fd89ad41762620a1229b806</data>
      <data key="d7">11</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1682</data>
      <data key="d6">52384316108d433397224cb36486407c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GRAPHICAL METHOD FOR LINEAR PROGRAMMING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The graphical method for solving linear programming problems involves plotting the constraints on a graph, identifying the feasible region, and finding the optimal point where the objective function is maximized or minimized. It is typically used for problems with two variables."</data>
      <data key="d2">64dc637d9fd89ad41762620a1229b806</data>
      <data key="d7">11</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1683</data>
      <data key="d6">9a27717e1a1b499981031fd69c58aff1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;WORK SUITS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Work suits are one of the two types of suits produced by Cut and Stitch, with a production limit of 400 units and a contribution of $48 per unit."</data>
      <data key="d2">64dc637d9fd89ad41762620a1229b806</data>
      <data key="d7">11</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
