      <data key="d5">1709</data>
      <data key="d6">a37bd07ff1694b6c90572399f084e1ec</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SHADOW PRICE OF MATERIAL IN THE LARGE APPLIANCES DIVISION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The shadow price of material in the Large Appliances division is $0, as material is not a binding constraint."</data>
      <data key="d2">88e696361bcc111f3d87032d375208f9</data>
      <data key="d7">11</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1710</data>
      <data key="d6">826e32d5ea1d455f8ae2d3b77cd2b41e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPTIMUM PRODUCTION PLAN FOR LARGE APPLIANCES DIVISION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The optimum production plan for the Large Appliances division is 240 units of Product F and 200 units of Product D, calculated using linear programming."</data>
      <data key="d2">88e696361bcc111f3d87032d375208f9</data>
      <data key="d7">11</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1711</data>
      <data key="d6">1a3bd511e04d4929a45a36fb80127353</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUIZ ON LINEAR PROGRAMMING AND LIMITING FACTORS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves questions on linear programming and limiting factors, including calculating contribution per unit of limiting factor, total contribution using simultaneous equations, and understanding shadow prices and slack values."</data>
      <data key="d2">88e696361bcc111f3d87032d375208f9</data>
      <data key="d7">11</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1712</data>
      <data key="d6">d0cd49577d6a49f4a21fdc389aa84805</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LABOUR AND MACHINE TIME INTERSECTION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Labour and machine time intersect at the optimum point if shown on a graph."</data>
      <data key="d2">10a6cfb7beb226418463ca4749be7451</data>
      <data key="d7">26</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1713</data>
      <data key="d6">aa667f462aae45a8a700d83a68c1982f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPTIMUM PRODUCTION PLAN&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The "OPTIMUM PRODUCTION PLAN" involves maximizing contribution while considering constraints such as labor and machine time. This plan is determined by calculating the contribution per unit and per square meter of timber for each product, ranking them, and then allocating the available timber to maximize profit while meeting minimum order requirements.</data>
      <data key="d2">10a6cfb7beb226418463ca4749be7451,e7783a6241d7d8fbb8f2530d08f784e9</data>
      <data key="d7">26</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1714</data>
      <data key="d6">37f40795969a42b3b50e61b76a96fa07</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRICING STRATEGY ANALYSIS FOR THE LAUNCH OF HEAT CO&#8217;S ENERGY BUSTER&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Heat Co specializes in the production of air conditioning appliances and is launching a new product, the 'Energy Buster,' which uses minimal electricity. The company is determining the best pricing policy for the product, considering high development costs and a five-year life cycle. Demand is highly responsive to price changes, and the company has patented the technology to prevent competition for two years."</data>
      <data key="d2">10a6cfb7beb226418463ca4749be7451</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">1715</data>
      <data key="d6">6db48bd5e4ce4337aaac4648376ed07d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARGINAL COST CALCULATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The marginal cost for each air conditioning unit, after adjusting the labour cost, is calculated to be $49.90."</data>
      <data key="d2">10a6cfb7beb226418463ca4749be7451</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1716</data>
      <data key="d6">422e6a449e7e4ce69182113a6493a4e5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPTIMUM PRICE AND QUANTITY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The optimum price and quantity to maximize profits are determined by equating marginal revenue to marginal cost. The optimum price is $400, and the optimum quantity is 23,337 units."</data>
      <data key="d2">10a6cfb7beb226418463ca4749be7451</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1717</data>
      <data key="d6">68511afc6e204c0b996d76cb75de081c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PENETRATION PRICING STRATEGY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Penetration pricing involves initially charging a low price to attract customers and gain market share quickly."</data>
      <data key="d2">10a6cfb7beb226418463ca4749be7451</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1718</data>
      <data key="d6">050f02fbf9e64d08b108c5b921581335</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARKET SKIMMING STRATEGY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Market skimming involves setting a high price initially to maximize profits from early adopters before gradually lowering the price."</data>
      <data key="d2">10a6cfb7beb226418463ca4749be7451</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1719</data>
      <data key="d6">97367a34fd6b4451b6be397496d646ea</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PENETRATION PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Penetration pricing involves setting a low initial price to attract a large number of buyers and gain a significant market share. This strategy is suitable when demand is highly elastic, economies of scale can be achieved, new entrants are discouraged, or the company wants to quickly move through the product life cycle stages."</data>
      <data key="d2">a9f233b9fbfc7657e915ecc09cb7519c</data>
      <data key="d7">19</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1720</data>
      <data key="d6">80da3caff5344d56b6ca12660594949a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STRATEGIC PRICING AND REVENUE OPTIMIZATION FOR ALG CO&#8217;S NEW PRODUCT LAUNCH&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"ALG Co is launching a new product with a three-year life expectancy. The company aims to set the right price to recover high development costs. Market research indicates that demand decreases by 2,000 units for every $2 increase in price and increases by 2,000 units for every $2 decrease. The demand curve is expressed as P = 310 - 0.001Q."</data>
      <data key="d2">a9f233b9fbfc7657e915ecc09cb7519c</data>
      <data key="d7">19</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1721</data>
      <data key="d6">e7efb7b459ae4ed4aa412cd20d808970</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DEMAND CURVE FORMULA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The demand curve formula used in the case: P = 310 - 0.001Q, where P is the price and Q is the quantity demanded."</data>
      <data key="d2">a9f233b9fbfc7657e915ecc09cb7519c</data>
      <data key="d7">19</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1722</data>
      <data key="d6">f0cc756b32314a1aae3e3cbb507850a2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REVENUE MAXIMIZATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Revenue maximization occurs where marginal revenue equals zero. This is the point at which any additional unit sold would not increase total revenue."</data>
      <data key="d2">0279d26139c7d66d51896f7ebfe162ee</data>
      <data key="d7">19</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1723</data>
      <data key="d6">f3082b58c8a54c538cf3a0110296955b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRICING STRATEGY AND PROFIT MAXIMIZATION FOR TR CO&#8217;S PARAPAIN AND NEW ANTI-MALARIA DRUG&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"TR Co is a pharmaceutical company reviewing its pricing policy for Parapain, a pain relief drug, after its patent expired and competitors entered the market. The company is also launching a new anti-malaria drug with a patent, expected to save millions of lives. The case involves determining the optimal pricing strategy for Parapain and understanding the implications of market competition and production costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">0279d26139c7d66d51896f7ebfe162ee</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1724</data>
      <data key="d6">c5f2254b67c04ad4add88875e5623e5a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PARAPAIN&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Parapain is a pain relief drug used for the treatment of headaches. TR Co had a patent on Parapain, which has now expired, allowing competitors to enter the market with similar products."</data>
      <data key="d2">0279d26139c7d66d51896f7ebfe162ee,324c0fb49870acc800392f7d78685514</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1725</data>
      <data key="d6">6e151c66c5574df39a7f243858e2ad3f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NEW ANTI-MALARIA DRUG&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"TR Co's new anti-malaria drug is a revolutionary product expected to save millions of lives. The drug has a patent, and no similar drug exists in the market. The launch is eagerly anticipated worldwide."</data>
      <data key="d2">0279d26139c7d66d51896f7ebfe162ee</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1726</data>
      <data key="d6">166366ae9ec842ec9a1deeb13c94026e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ANTI-MALARIA DRUG&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">TR Co's new and unique anti-malaria drug, which cost millions of dollars to develop and has obtained a patent, is expected to save millions of lives. There are no similar drugs currently available in the market, making this drug particularly significant. Although the demand levels are unknown, the launch is eagerly anticipated worldwide. The anti-malaria drug is also used as an example to illustrate the application of penetration pricing and market skimming pricing strategies, due to its unique characteristics and patented status, making it suitable for market skimming.</data>
      <data key="d2">324c0fb49870acc800392f7d78685514,952e2d04d2cd9b755ccdb34c8be68396</data>
      <data key="d7">19</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1727</data>
      <data key="d6">cdecc293edb847ae92c3bf8ff39d1e9a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPTIMUM SELLING PRICE CALCULATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The process of calculating the optimum (profit-maximizing) selling price for Parapain, involving steps to establish the demand function, marginal cost, marginal revenue function, and solving for the optimum quantity and price."</data>
      <data key="d2">324c0fb49870acc800392f7d78685514</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1728</data>
      <data key="d6">3a615d980a124616a659136b4fd277b7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARKET PENETRATION PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"MARKET PENETRATION PRICING" is a pricing strategy where a low price is initially charged for a product, such as an anti-malaria drug, to make it accessible to a larger number of buyers. This approach aims for high sales volume to compensate for the lower price. By setting an initially low price, the strategy seeks to grow the customer base quickly, which helps to shorten the initial period of the product life cycle and reach the growth and maturity stages faster.</data>
      <data key="d2">324c0fb49870acc800392f7d78685514,33d735a6b75645248eabb5d1c5835d61,45374dd90ff15ce3c8e2a87bc484b028</data>
      <data key="d7">19</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">1729</data>
      <data key="d6">a9b46d1f9ef747b69d6211386b5aaa20</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TR CO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"TR Co is a company that produces the anti-malaria drug and is considering different pricing strategies to maximize its market potential and recover high development costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">952e2d04d2cd9b755ccdb34c8be68396</data>
      <data key="d7">19</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1730</data>
      <data key="d6">891a6dbec2ef4a039efaca78040b00c1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRICING STRATEGY AND DEMAND ELASTICITY ANALYSIS FOR SKULPT CO'S GSA PRODUCT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Skulpt Co is a manufacturer of electronic goods, specifically the GSA device. The company is analyzing pricing strategies and demand elasticity to optimize sales and market entry in new regions."</data>
      <data key="d2">952e2d04d2cd9b755ccdb34c8be68396</data>
      <data key="d7">19</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1731</data>
      <data key="d6">981d45442a11448097acebc6080da414</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GSA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The GSA is an electronic device produced by Skulpt Co. The company is considering a price reduction and analyzing the impact on demand and revenue."</data>
      <data key="d2">952e2d04d2cd9b755ccdb34c8be68396</data>
      <data key="d7">19</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1732</data>
      <data key="d6">fad1c8144b504954bea46ede106d93ec</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LOK CO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"LOK Co is a new customer that has placed a bespoke order for 5,000 units of the GSA, requiring additional production and packaging specifications."</data>
      <data key="d2">952e2d04d2cd9b755ccdb34c8be68396</data>
      <data key="d7">19</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1733</data>
      <data key="d6">53edb7e587204ed48e523c6f1f8f4056</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;HAREKISH MARKET ENTRY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Skulpt Co is planning to enter the Harekish market with its GSA product, aiming to set a minimum acceptable price to discourage new entrants and shorten the product life cycle to reach growth and maturity stages quickly."</data>
      <data key="d2">952e2d04d2cd9b755ccdb34c8be68396</data>
      <data key="d7">19</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1734</data>
      <data key="d6">f386b02e36884167a5db1a12ee6fcb1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MANUFACTURING COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Manufacturing costs" include variable labor production costs, other variable production costs, and fixed production costs. These costs must be covered in the long run and are a key factor in setting prices.</data>
      <data key="d2">33d735a6b75645248eabb5d1c5835d61,d4cbc64c9c49dd951f9997a26ee9d9f9</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1735</data>
      <data key="d6">2809d8a73b71495ca4220571dd54ba1e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COMPETITORS' PRICES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Competitors' prices are a key factor in setting prices, as large deviations in prices between competitors can cause customers to move to cheaper products when they are similar."</data>
      <data key="d2">33d735a6b75645248eabb5d1c5835d61</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1736</data>
      <data key="d6">49f82fa775fb466bb9ae3db14db5b29a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REVENUE CALCULATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"REVENUE CALCULATION" involves determining the total revenue by multiplying the number of customers (or quantity, Q) by the average revenue per customer (or price, P). For Cowly restaurant, the calculation is as follows: with 1,500 customers generating $75,000, the average revenue per customer is $50. When the number of customers increases to 1,800, the total revenue becomes $90,000 ($50 * 1,800). Additionally, revenue calculations at different price and quantity points are provided: at a price (P) of $250 and a quantity (Q) of 1,000, the revenue is $250,000 (1,000 * 250). At a price of $230 and a quantity of 1,100, the revenue is $253,000 (1,100 * 230).</data>
      <data key="d2">33d735a6b75645248eabb5d1c5835d61,ed11d697d920edcbfc6a01ce2c257056</data>
      <data key="d7">19</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1737</data>
      <data key="d6">f9312ee0bac24ea1b497e16e0958d621</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PROFIT-MAXIMIZING PRICE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Profit is maximized when marginal revenue (MR) equals marginal cost (MC). The profit-maximizing price for the GSA is $252."</data>
      <data key="d2">33d735a6b75645248eabb5d1c5835d61</data>
      <data key="d7">19</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1738</data>
      <data key="d6">c84bc84ffea84df9ad25ae9f972b4ec0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRICING STRATEGIES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Pricing strategies are methods used by companies to set the prices of their products. Examples include market skimming, market penetration, relevant cost pricing, and price discrimination by product version."</data>
      <data key="d2">33d735a6b75645248eabb5d1c5835d61</data>
      <data key="d7">18</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1739</data>
      <data key="d6">be1068c6efb24cde96e5a523eb04aee8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CUSTOMER DEMAND&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">33d735a6b75645248eabb5d1c5835d61</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1740</data>
      <data key="d6">ecc4f28a7d574a5886f4c80a0b7cddd4</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRICE DISCRIMINATION BY PRODUCT VERSION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Price discrimination by product version involves setting different prices for different versions of a product. Skulpt Co is following a price discrimination strategy based on location rather than product version."</data>
      <data key="d2">45374dd90ff15ce3c8e2a87bc484b028</data>
      <data key="d7">19</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1741</data>
      <data key="d6">b506a4813da44600b136e949db4f2832</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRICING STRATEGY ANALYSIS FOR STOW HOTEL: DECISION-MAKING UNDER UNCERTAINTY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The managers of Stow Hotel are deciding on their pricing strategy for the next financial year. They are considering charging $180, $200, or $220 per day, with variable costs being uncertain. A profit table summarizing possible levels of contribution for each price charged has been produced, and the probabilities of variable cost levels occurring at high, most likely, and low levels are estimated."</data>
      <data key="d2">45374dd90ff15ce3c8e2a87bc484b028</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1742</data>
      <data key="d6">77735209cabb415289c8ae4e102ff6df</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MAXIMAX DECISION RULE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The maximax decision rule involves choosing the option with the highest possible payoff. For Stow Hotel, a fee of $180 gives the highest potential return, so it would be chosen under the maximax rule."</data>
      <data key="d2">45374dd90ff15ce3c8e2a87bc484b028</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1743</data>
      <data key="d6">1f1d88a6f6ce46bab94a4b50693c89ff</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MAXIMIN DECISION RULE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The maximin decision rule involves choosing the option with the highest minimum return. For Stow Hotel, a fee of $200 has the highest minimum return, so it would be chosen under the maximin rule."</data>
      <data key="d2">45374dd90ff15ce3c8e2a87bc484b028</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1744</data>
      <data key="d6">03454aaf00c54112a09ea4e52185b195</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXPECTED VALUE OF CONTRIBUTION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Expected value for each fee strategy is calculated by multiplying each potential outcome by its probability and summing these. For example, for a fee of $180: (1,339 * 0.1) + (1,496 * 0.6) + (1,733 * 0.3) = $1,551."</data>
      <data key="d2">45374dd90ff15ce3c8e2a87bc484b028</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1745</data>
      <data key="d6">3c5cd9cbad0d456cab4c76f1dfcde25b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TABLE OF REGRETS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A table of regrets shows the difference between the best possible payoff for each state of nature and the actual payoff for each decision. For the low level of variable costs, the best fee strategy would be to charge $180, with regrets for other strategies calculated as the difference between their contributions and $1,733."</data>
      <data key="d2">45374dd90ff15ce3c8e2a87bc484b028</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1746</data>
      <data key="d6">8503eae9f6c746afae0caa58070f25e6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MAXIMIN&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Maximin is a decision-making technique used by risk-averse decision makers. It involves choosing the option with the best worst-case scenario."</data>
      <data key="d2">185572ab91ea67a36a262b55dffde450</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1747</data>
      <data key="d6">6e3c655e5b544277a62832a0974aa0ed</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MINIMAX REGRET&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Minimax regret is a decision-making technique used by risk-averse decision makers. It involves choosing the option that minimizes the maximum regret."</data>
      <data key="d2">185572ab91ea67a36a262b55dffde450</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1748</data>
      <data key="d6">bd0363bace6b42b0b3879bed5a064274</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BUDGETING STRATEGY AND PRICING DECISIONS FOR GAM CO'S NEW PRODUCT LAUNCH&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Gam Co is launching a new electronic product and needs to prepare its budget for the coming year. The company is deciding between two price points, $30 and $35 per unit, and has gathered market research data on sales volumes and probabilities. The case involves calculating profit outcomes, expected values, and discussing decision-making rules like maximin."</data>
      <data key="d2">185572ab91ea67a36a262b55dffde450</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1749</data>
      <data key="d6">99969eec8bf8441eaf9cb004cb61a13e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MAXIMAX&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">185572ab91ea67a36a262b55dffde450</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1750</data>
      <data key="d6">0bcceb946a94486faf935f58dabea978</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES MIX CONTRIBUTION VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The "Sales Mix Contribution Variance" measures the impact on profit due to the change in the proportion of different products sold compared to the budgeted mix. Specifically, it assesses the effect on profit when the actual sales mix deviates from the standard or budgeted mix. In Noble's case, this variance is $1,014 adverse, indicating that the actual sales mix was less profitable than the budgeted mix. This adverse variance occurs when a higher contribution product is sold less than expected, leading to a less favorable profit outcome.</data>
      <data key="d2">2343dedcae64d2e174ab981dfc3b23a0,8f25b512050c59a9f6a09fd4549bce3c,adea171e6847df263c60c9085bf66897</data>
      <data key="d7">27</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1751</data>
      <data key="d6">4d8421b4a6c74627afaa45aefa08c43a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;HALF-PRICE DRINKS PROMOTION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The half-price drinks promotion at Noble for the month of May resulted in customers ordering an average of six drinks each instead of the usual four, but paying only half the usual price for each drink. This led to a sales price variance for drink sales of $11,700 adverse."</data>
      <data key="d2">8f25b512050c59a9f6a09fd4549bce3c</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1752</data>
      <data key="d6">f879674860784f9eb4289aeb91728351</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STAFF WAGES CALCULATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The calculation for staff wages in the flexed budget involves determining the average number of orders per day, calculating the extra hours worked by staff due to increased orders, and multiplying the extra hours by the overtime rate. The total flexed wages are then the sum of the standard wages and the extra wages."</data>
      <data key="d2">8f25b512050c59a9f6a09fd4549bce3c</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1753</data>
      <data key="d6">dea50b1765e54936b3d0b1e499ab2053</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ENERGY COSTS CALCULATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The calculation for energy costs in the flexed budget involves determining the total hours worked by staff and relating it to the energy costs, which are deemed to be variable and related to the total number of hours worked."</data>
      <data key="d2">8f25b512050c59a9f6a09fd4549bce3c</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1754</data>
      <data key="d6">26634913d18f4629b39dffa19c1df734</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXTRA HOURS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Extra hours refer to the additional working hours required to handle the extra orders. Here, it is calculated as 288 extra hours."</data>
      <data key="d2">2343dedcae64d2e174ab981dfc3b23a0</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1755</data>
      <data key="d6">a69bde74fc9d41cfa669f148c7c43dd8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXTRA WAGES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Extra wages refer to the additional wages paid for the extra hours worked. In this case, it amounts to $3,456."</data>
      <data key="d2">2343dedcae64d2e174ab981dfc3b23a0</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1756</data>
      <data key="d6">e65667ec99e145fea2055d6b583cb05b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TOTAL FLEXED WAGES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Total flexed wages = Standard wages + Extra wages. Here, it is calculated as $12,672."</data>
      <data key="d2">2343dedcae64d2e174ab981dfc3b23a0</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1757</data>
      <data key="d6">cdfcbba5664d42508cd34df9af42b0dc</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRICE VARIANCE FOR DRINKS SALES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Price variance for drinks sales measures the difference between the actual selling price and the standard selling price of drinks."</data>
      <data key="d2">2343dedcae64d2e174ab981dfc3b23a0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1758</data>
      <data key="d6">570de818eba04615a6afb3a573e82ff1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES VOLUME VARIANCE FOR DRINKS SALES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sales volume variance for drinks sales measures the difference between the actual volume of drinks sold and the standard volume expected."</data>
      <data key="d2">2343dedcae64d2e174ab981dfc3b23a0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1759</data>
      <data key="d6">473533c454d34975a17a0193e39e0bac</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPERATIONAL VARIANCE FOR DRINKS SALES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Operational variance for drinks sales measures the part of the sales margin variance that is within the manager's control."</data>
      <data key="d2">2343dedcae64d2e174ab981dfc3b23a0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1760</data>
      <data key="d6">e22af264c702440f93070465f45e630e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PLANNING VARIANCE FOR DRINKS SALES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Planning variance for drinks sales measures the part of the sales margin variance that is due to planning errors, such as last-minute decisions."</data>
      <data key="d2">2343dedcae64d2e174ab981dfc3b23a0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1761</data>
      <data key="d6">ad95fbd957ae4c22859f58446dd8c9cc</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES MARGIN VOLUME VARIANCE FOR FOOD SALES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sales margin volume variance for food sales measures the effect on profit of the difference between the actual and expected volume of food sales."</data>
      <data key="d2">2343dedcae64d2e174ab981dfc3b23a0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1762</data>
      <data key="d6">37d42129ca4d49dea240f66d1fdd4b78</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BUDGETING APPROACHES AT NEWTOWN SCHOOL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Newtown School's head teacher uses incremental budgeting to prepare the budget for the year ending 31 May 20X5. The government pays the school based on the number of pupils registered at the beginning of the school year and those joining part-way through the year. The head teacher calculates budgeted revenue using a simple average for new joiners and adjusts expenditure for inflation."</data>
      <data key="d2">2343dedcae64d2e174ab981dfc3b23a0</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1763</data>
      <data key="d6">1f40481f4ee342d4be51d33ffafc17d1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALARIES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Salaries for the year ended 31 May 20X5, including a 2% pay rise for all staff effective from 1 December 20X4, and accounting for the departure of one teacher earning $26,000."</data>
      <data key="d2">e8a4cdc58604c69a847f56ea49d24b6c</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1764</data>
      <data key="d6">e892d46e07e44bd5a2d1626875cc024f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CAPITAL EXPENDITURE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Capital expenditure for the year ended 31 May 20X5, including improvements to the school canteen with a 0.7 probability of costing $145,000 and a 0.3 probability of costing $80,000."</data>
      <data key="d2">e8a4cdc58604c69a847f56ea49d24b6c</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1765</data>
      <data key="d6">fcb033a54d734ce5a87e0d8ad555867a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BUDGET SURPLUS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The budget surplus for the year ended 31 May 20X5, initially calculated as $6,680 but questioned by the board of governors for accuracy based on expected income and expenditure."</data>
      <data key="d2">e8a4cdc58604c69a847f56ea49d24b6c</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1766</data>
      <data key="d6">964fc01bfd9a400eb668761539dc9d9f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BUDGET DEFICIT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The budget deficit for the year ending 31 May 20X5, recalculated based on expected income and expenditure, resulting in a deficit of $5,740."</data>
      <data key="d2">e8a4cdc58604c69a847f56ea49d24b6c</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1767</data>
      <data key="d6">86b0d920fa504eba81c26cfc3f4d2b9f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NEWTOWN SCHOOL BUDGETING PROCESS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Newtown School's budgeting process for the year ending 31 May 20X5, including recalculating the budget surplus/deficit, discussing the advantages and disadvantages of incremental budgeting, and considering the application of zero-based budgeting."</data>
      <data key="d2">e8a4cdc58604c69a847f56ea49d24b6c</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1768</data>
      <data key="d6">e0221df7b7e44dd7956c8d0348d46b6d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BUDGETED EXPENDITURE&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">e8a4cdc58604c69a847f56ea49d24b6c</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1769</data>
      <data key="d6">a20d7f4fee104273b9628d648c05a5ac</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;USE OF ZBB AT NEWTOWN SCHOOL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Newtown School faces recurring unexpected cash shortages due to incremental budgeting. Zero-based budgeting (ZBB) could help by establishing decision packages for discretionary activities, such as different levels of lunch service and sports education, to prioritize spending more effectively. However, ZBB is time-consuming and may not be suitable for all categories of expenditure."</data>
      <data key="d2">f39e983f452f0497b116e09b2dd273ee</data>
      <data key="d7">5</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1770</data>
      <data key="d6">b352398c5b1742d8a61acd8534ef0f53</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PERFORMANCE MANAGEMENT AND BUDGETING APPROACHES FOR YUMI CO'S RESTAURANTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Yumi Co owns several rural restaurants with a loyal customer base and low profit margins. The company uses annual budgets prepared by head office, split into monthly targets. A new competitor in Cowly has raised concerns about achieving profit targets. The monthly performance statement for the Cowly restaurant shows variances in revenue and costs, highlighting the need for effective cost monitoring and performance management."</data>
      <data key="d2">f39e983f452f0497b116e09b2dd273ee</data>
      <data key="d7">5</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1771</data>
      <data key="d6">38b778af3c3f4be2a23e3932c94390c3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PARTICIPATIVE BUDGETING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Participative budgeting is a budgeting process where all levels of management are involved in the budget preparation. This inclusive approach promotes ownership and accountability among managers at various levels. By involving multiple tiers of management, participative budgeting can make budgets more realistic and increase commitment to the financial plans. However, this method is more time-consuming compared to other budgeting processes.</data>
      <data key="d2">6cf39866faa0b75b5fd5a86e16914122,dcff42ba3ed5843954c648603089a728,ed11d697d920edcbfc6a01ce2c257056</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">9</data>
      <data key="d5">1772</data>
      <data key="d6">35d528e52a6441a58e58385d85bfae4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COWLY RESTAURANT BUDGET ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Cowly restaurant's budget analysis involves preparing a flexed budget to adjust for the actual number of customers served and identifying weaknesses in the current budget statements for managing performance."</data>
      <data key="d2">ed11d697d920edcbfc6a01ce2c257056</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1773</data>
      <data key="d6">06d0d34ab3d043c689044a0fbfc65e10</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FOOD AND DRINK COST CALCULATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Food and drink cost = Number of customers * Average cost per customer. For Cowly restaurant: $22,500/1,500 = $15 per customer; $15 * 1,800 = $27,000."</data>
      <data key="d2">ed11d697d920edcbfc6a01ce2c257056</data>
      <data key="d7">19</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1774</data>
      <data key="d6">9e0ec036c91e44daa8e1a2af50df2081</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STAFF COST CALCULATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Staff cost = Number of customers * Average cost per customer. For Cowly restaurant: $31,500/1,500 = $21 per customer; $21 * 1,800 = $37,800."</data>
      <data key="d2">ed11d697d920edcbfc6a01ce2c257056</data>
      <data key="d7">19</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1775</data>
      <data key="d6">580b2395e68442539a606d37ddba691d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;HEAT, LIGHT, AND POWER COST CALCULATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Heat, light, and power cost = Number of customers * Average cost per customer. For Cowly restaurant: $7,500/1,500 = $5 per customer; $5 * 1,800 = $9,000."</data>
      <data key="d2">ed11d697d920edcbfc6a01ce2c257056</data>
      <data key="d7">19</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1776</data>
      <data key="d6">370fd1c6563045499e1d711fcd9ef9d5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RENT, RATES, AND OTHER OVERHEADS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Rent, rates, and other overheads are fixed annual charges apportioned to Yumi Co's restaurants by the head office."</data>
      <data key="d2">ed11d697d920edcbfc6a01ce2c257056</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1777</data>
      <data key="d6">3b6c4319026844ecb645f650e30b7d1a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;WEAKNESSES IN CURRENT BUDGET STATEMENTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The main weaknesses in the current budget statements include not flexing the budget for actual customer numbers, assuming all costs are variable, and not accounting for semi-variable costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">ed11d697d920edcbfc6a01ce2c257056</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1778</data>
      <data key="d6">e044334b7d2e426ca2cab7eb763d8bc9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ADVANTAGES OF PARTICIPATIVE BUDGETING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Advantages of participative budgeting include increased ownership and accountability, better information sharing, and more realistic budgets."</data>
      <data key="d2">ed11d697d920edcbfc6a01ce2c257056</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1779</data>
      <data key="d6">4a2fa382e77946d2be8e95edc04c6a64</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DISADVANTAGES OF PARTICIPATIVE BUDGETING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Disadvantages of participative budgeting include potential for budgetary slack, time-consuming process, and possible conflicts among managers."</data>
      <data key="d2">ed11d697d920edcbfc6a01ce2c257056</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1780</data>
      <data key="d6">cd015281a069460e844faeb327b7d65f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ACTIVITY-BASED BUDGETING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">Activity-based budgeting (ABB) is a budgeting method where activities that incur costs in every functional area of an organization are recorded, analyzed, and researched. This approach focuses on the relationship between activities and costs, allocating resources based on the activities that drive costs. By doing so, ABB helps to manage costs more effectively.</data>
      <data key="d2">6cf39866faa0b75b5fd5a86e16914122,ed1f837be30c9135b0fe794ec0162540</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1781</data>
      <data key="d6">c7a9fbf22a054056bf4f4562eaecfc08</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;YUMI CO'S BUDGETING PROCESS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Yumi Co's current budgeting process is centralized and top-down, meaning restaurant managers do not influence their budgets. The company is considering whether incremental budgeting is appropriate and exploring participative budgeting to make budgets more effective and realistic."</data>
      <data key="d2">6cf39866faa0b75b5fd5a86e16914122</data>
      <data key="d7">7</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1782</data>
      <data key="d6">44bf341f78d74c4bb15ae209649d0ca9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES TRENDS AND SEASONAL VARIATIONS FOR PONDTAIL CO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Pondtail Co's sales revenue over the last three years shows seasonal variations, with higher sales in autumn and winter. The company is analyzing these trends to understand the increase in the four-quarter moving average for sales revenue."</data>
      <data key="d2">6cf39866faa0b75b5fd5a86e16914122</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1783</data>
      <data key="d6">045ff6885d424b4caeabc76c50468c7c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES DATA ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The management accountant of Wetmay Clothes Co is analyzing the extent to which sales of different products vary according to the amount of rainfall. The analysis for the sales of overcoats includes various statistical calculations such as correlation coefficient and regression analysis to determine the relationship between rainfall and sales."</data>
      <data key="d2">df5e50672b5795ed072403e633c26e7f</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">1784</data>
      <data key="d6">543a52396f0b4f7f99ea755fba11d290</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REGRESSION EQUATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The regression equation is used to predict the value of a dependent variable (y) based on the value of an independent variable (x). It is expressed as y = a + bx, where a is the y-intercept and b is the slope of the line."</data>
      <data key="d2">df5e50672b5795ed072403e633c26e7f</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1785</data>
      <data key="d6">33e487870db646e5b3d9c1f2962a7c6a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CORRELATION AND REGRESSION ANALYSIS QUIZ&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz involves questions about correlation and regression analysis, including calculating the correlation coefficient, regression equation, coefficient of determination, and understanding the assumptions and implications of these statistical methods."</data>
      <data key="d2">df5e50672b5795ed072403e633c26e7f</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1786</data>
      <data key="d6">b5b628d809514bfe9bbb3bd362815e79</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LEARNING CURVE AND OVERHEAD COSTS ANALYSIS FOR BEAR CO'S NEW TELEVISION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Bear Co has developed a new television model and is analyzing the expected labor time and overhead production costs. The analysis includes calculating the expected time for production using a learning curve and examining historical overhead costs to forecast future expenses."</data>
      <data key="d2">df5e50672b5795ed072403e633c26e7f</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1787</data>
      <data key="d6">9d9ae51d2af44ebe8324dd2dd1dcd83b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LEARNING INDEX&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The learning index is used to calculate the expected time for production based on the learning rate. For a 75% learning rate, the learning index is -0.415."</data>
      <data key="d2">df5e50672b5795ed072403e633c26e7f</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1788</data>
      <data key="d6">b7c606aa6ad1416e9f934628acce5f24</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PENETRATION PRICING POLICY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Penetration pricing policy is a strategy where a product is introduced at a low price to gain market share quickly, discourage new entrants, and achieve economies of scale."</data>
      <data key="d2">f00d919ad915af3f9caac5db3ddec274</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1789</data>
      <data key="d6">4521342f29774fab85e6acb0490d46e5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COST ANALYSIS AND LEARNING CURVE IMPLICATIONS FOR BIG CHAIRS CO'S NEW MASSAGING CHAIR&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Big Chairs Co (BCC) is considering launching a new massaging chair into a competitive market. Using a target costing system, BCC has set a competitive selling price of $120 per chair, aiming for a 20% margin on the selling price. The frame and massage mechanism will be bought for $51 per chair, and BCC will upholster and assemble it. Leather costs $10 per meter, with two meters needed per chair, although 20% of the leather is wasted."</data>
      <data key="d2">f00d919ad915af3f9caac5db3ddec274</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1790</data>
      <data key="d6">e7ac741e4aa4433ca5f2379726f90b33</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COMPETITIVE SELLING PRICE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The competitive selling price is the price at which a product is sold in the market, determined by market conditions and competition. For the chair, it is set at $120."</data>
      <data key="d2">30748d6dcf5a2da70804db75296cee3c</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1791</data>
      <data key="d6">43645eb9258244a8bd334ce77216b1c0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARGIN ON SELLING PRICE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Margin on selling price refers to the percentage of the selling price that is profit. BCC wants a margin of 20% on the selling price of the chair."</data>
      <data key="d2">30748d6dcf5a2da70804db75296cee3c</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1792</data>
      <data key="d6">0c9c52488ad647abbaf2b4589c976957</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FRAME AND MASSAGE MECHANISM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The frame and massage mechanism are components of the chair, costing $51 per chair."</data>
      <data key="d2">30748d6dcf5a2da70804db75296cee3c</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1793</data>
      <data key="d6">0e8fb49a531e4ea48fece73957bd8a54</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LEATHER COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Leather costs $10 per metre, and two metres are needed for a complete chair, with 20% waste in the upholstery process."</data>
      <data key="d2">30748d6dcf5a2da70804db75296cee3c</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1794</data>
      <data key="d6">6187217c38ca4225b97d04d9644dcdf0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LABOUR COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Labour cost is $15 per hour, and the first chair takes two hours to prepare, subject to a 95% learning rate."</data>
      <data key="d2">30748d6dcf5a2da70804db75296cee3c</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1795</data>
      <data key="d6">8c8330abe276487294eba3a341ee9e0c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LEARNING FORMULA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The learning formula is Y = a * x^b, where Y is the time for the xth unit, a is the time for the first unit, x is the cumulative number of units, and b is the learning rate exponent."</data>
      <data key="d2">30748d6dcf5a2da70804db75296cee3c</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1796</data>
      <data key="d6">200df54d93964e81ae2dcf727bffb23c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;METHODS FOR CLOSING THE COST GAP&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Methods for closing the cost gap include redesigning the chair, negotiating with suppliers, reducing waste, improving the learning rate, and employing cheaper labour."</data>
      <data key="d2">30748d6dcf5a2da70804db75296cee3c</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1797</data>
      <data key="d6">4d0478c05f614675b336a76a0c088b3e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COST OF THE 128TH CHAIR&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The cost of the 128th chair is calculated to be $95.35, which is below the target cost of $96, indicating that the required return is being achieved."</data>
      <data key="d2">30748d6dcf5a2da70804db75296cee3c</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1798</data>
      <data key="d6">c0dc4d618b5e49f7a18efa34dbf450ac</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COST ANALYSIS, LEARNING CURVE IMPACT, AND BUDGETING IMPLICATIONS FOR MIC CO'S MICROPHONE PRODUCTION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Mic Co produces microphones for mobile phones and operates a standard costing system. The case involves analyzing the cost, learning curve impact, and budgeting implications for the production of microphones."</data>
      <data key="d2">30748d6dcf5a2da70804db75296cee3c</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1799</data>
      <data key="d6">dec05f79120940b78cd921a0a67f1540</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TARGET COSTING SYSTEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">30748d6dcf5a2da70804db75296cee3c</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1800</data>
      <data key="d6">8edbf3e4f0d94f6ab78127c61bf87b76</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STANDARD COSTING SYSTEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">A standard costing system involves setting predetermined costs for products and services, which are then used to measure performance by comparing actual costs to these standards. This cost accounting method assigns expected costs to materials, labor, and overheads, and then compares these standards to actual costs to determine variances. The system is instrumental in budgeting, cost control, and performance evaluation. Mic Co uses this system to allocate resources and estimate costs for its microphone production.</data>
      <data key="d2">57d99cfb0b92fd81cb25374c021a6024,f8ef013188b41d62318c1306ced4944f</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1801</data>
      <data key="d6">1d722426930a42eeadfa624a6eb2408f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COST PLUS PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Cost plus pricing is a pricing strategy where the selling price is determined by adding a specific markup to the cost of producing the product. Mic Co uses this method to establish the selling prices for its microphones."</data>
      <data key="d2">57d99cfb0b92fd81cb25374c021a6024</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1802</data>
      <data key="d6">6d22f2009f6a4df9a242f03e2642981e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MONTHLY LABOUR COSTS CALCULATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The monthly labor costs for producing the microphones are calculated by multiplying the incremental total hours by the standard labor cost per hour. For example, in August, the incremental total hours were 152, and the labor cost per hour was $12, resulting in a total labor cost of $1,824."</data>
      <data key="d2">57d99cfb0b92fd81cb25374c021a6024</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1803</data>
      <data key="d6">db5035c544214c72987eed4d4d9e327f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BUDGETING IMPLICATIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Budgeting implications refer to the effects that changes in production efficiency and cost estimates have on the budgeting process. In this case, the end of the learning effect means that future budgets should be based on the constant time taken to produce each batch after the learning period."</data>
      <data key="d2">57d99cfb0b92fd81cb25374c021a6024</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1804</data>
      <data key="d6">fd00e337b5c4465cbcbdf07bc294a3a8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SENIOR STAFF INVOLVEMENT IN BUDGET SETTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Involving senior staff in the budget-setting process can lead to more accurate and realistic budgets, as they bring valuable insights and experience. This can improve resource allocation, cost estimation, and overall decision-making."</data>
      <data key="d2">57d99cfb0b92fd81cb25374c021a6024</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1805</data>
      <data key="d6">ea1e51b558c149649711a29157f4e604</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COST ANALYSIS FOR MIC CO'S MICROPHONE PRODUCTION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Mic Co produces microphones for mobile phones and operates a standard costing system. The case involves analyzing the impact of the learning curve on labor costs, the implications for budgeting, and the potential advantages and disadvantages of involving senior staff in the budget-setting process."</data>
      <data key="d2">57d99cfb0b92fd81cb25374c021a6024</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">1806</data>
      <data key="d6">b888ad14e84347f8831a7dd2cea294fd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RESOURCE ALLOCATION AND COSTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Resource allocation and costing decisions should be based on the time taken to produce the 8th batch of microphones, as the previous data was inaccurate due to being based on a standard time per batch of 200 hours."</data>
      <data key="d2">01d1ff33e985b6f8cd09ff45ebfedc0e</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1807</data>
      <data key="d6">0e2323c0256d40579e7526dbdd019a8d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;IMPROVING PRODUCTION PROCESS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Mic Co could try to improve its production process to extend the learning period by increasing staff training or motivating staff through bonuses, while maintaining production quality."</data>
      <data key="d2">01d1ff33e985b6f8cd09ff45ebfedc0e</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1808</data>
      <data key="d6">deb3bc5537a14352b22a0a473a59d8c7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INVOLVING SENIOR STAFF IN BUDGET SETTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Involving senior staff in the budget setting process has advantages such as improved accuracy, increased motivation, better morale, pooled knowledge, and improved coordination. However, it also has disadvantages like being time-consuming, potential for budgetary slack, disagreements, and resource hoarding."</data>
      <data key="d2">01d1ff33e985b6f8cd09ff45ebfedc0e</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1809</data>
      <data key="d6">ba445c400c8e405bb646387eab98a62b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REVISING LABOUR STANDARDS AND ANALYZING VARIANCES FOR BOKCO'S NEW PRODUCT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Bokco, a manufacturing company, relies on temporary workers and uses cost-plus pricing. The company began production of a new product with a standard cost card for labor. The production manager realized that a learning rate of 90% should have been anticipated. The revised standard time for the first 460 units was calculated based on this learning rate."</data>
      <data key="d2">01d1ff33e985b6f8cd09ff45ebfedc0e</data>
      <data key="d7">17</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1810</data>
      <data key="d6">95a90d05e82d44ada6f8577ca49dd491</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LABOUR EFFICIENCY VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Labour efficiency variances are calculated to measure the difference between the standard hours for actual production and the actual hours worked, adjusted for the learning rate. These variances help in evaluating the efficiency of labor usage in production. In Bokco's case, variances were calculated based on both 90% and 85% learning rates.</data>
      <data key="d2">01d1ff33e985b6f8cd09ff45ebfedc0e,dafeac07a3bcfef066cd6672e6b6711a</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1811</data>
      <data key="d6">fa15140701a54689835604665d187c54</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;END OF LEARNING PERIOD&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">01d1ff33e985b6f8cd09ff45ebfedc0e</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1812</data>
      <data key="d6">8346468f7f4c46bebe1eaafd9753d55f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LABOUR EFFICIENCY PLANNING VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Labour efficiency planning variance" arises when the standard hours need to be revised due to factors beyond the control of operational managers, such as changes in employment legislation, customer demands for higher quality, or incorrect estimates of the learning effect. It is calculated as the difference between the standard hours for actual production and the revised hours for actual production, multiplied by the standard rate.</data>
      <data key="d2">dde6d5d3f80c5f7be94b41e612ddb0c0,f6982a4563820b317a7b745f9ea9c299</data>
      <data key="d7">17</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1813</data>
      <data key="d6">46ddbfe32d444912b423dd1769fbaa43</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LABOUR EFFICIENCY OPERATIONAL VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Labour efficiency operational variance is calculated as (Revised hours for actual production - actual hours for actual production) * standard rate."</data>
      <data key="d2">dde6d5d3f80c5f7be94b41e612ddb0c0</data>
      <data key="d7">17</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1814</data>
      <data key="d6">ffce5a64e9394d1399319588d7fd4e3e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PLANNING VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Planning variances reflect factors outside of the control of operational managers and are calculated using the original standard."</data>
      <data key="d2">dde6d5d3f80c5f7be94b41e612ddb0c0</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1815</data>
      <data key="d6">e934202aa3b344ba9fef89ecb42530b4</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EVALUATING MANAGER PERFORMANCE AND CALCULATING VARIANCES FOR CHAFF CO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Chaff Co processes and sells brown rice, using a standard costing system to monitor performance. The case involves evaluating manager performance based on variances calculated for month 1, including material price, material usage, labour rate, labour efficiency, variable overhead expenditure, and variable overhead efficiency variances."</data>
      <data key="d2">dde6d5d3f80c5f7be94b41e612ddb0c0</data>
      <data key="d7">14</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1816</data>
      <data key="d6">22d5ff62439047ccaeaa63fd8a30f3e5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VARIABLE OVERHEAD EXPENDITURE VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Variable overhead expenditure variance is the difference between the actual variable overhead costs incurred and the standard variable overhead costs expected to be incurred, based on actual hours worked."</data>
      <data key="d2">a2b172963f635500ceb4bcd40e29a190</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1817</data>
      <data key="d6">9b2f77b408ec4147bd5dd67a01d9f439</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STANDARD CONTRIBUTION PER TONNE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Standard contribution per tonne = Standard selling price - Standard variable costs"</data>
      <data key="d2">a2b172963f635500ceb4bcd40e29a190</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1818</data>
      <data key="d6">96b1264e89394adfaf026471e3b6ad47</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BUDGETED PRODUCTION AND SALES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Budgeted production and sales refer to the planned quantity of production and sales for a specific period."</data>
      <data key="d2">a2b172963f635500ceb4bcd40e29a190</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1819</data>
      <data key="d6">00741dfb8f6d477f913d20406dfcd65d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ACTUAL PRODUCTION AND SALES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Actual production and sales refer to the actual quantity of production and sales achieved during a specific period."</data>
      <data key="d2">a2b172963f635500ceb4bcd40e29a190</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1820</data>
      <data key="d6">3eb344aa8b05448984dacac93482ebc4</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PURCHASING MANAGER PERFORMANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The performance of the purchasing manager is evaluated based on variances such as material price variance and material usage variance, and their impact on overall costs and quality."</data>
      <data key="d2">a2b172963f635500ceb4bcd40e29a190</data>
      <data key="d7">28</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1821</data>
      <data key="d6">8db8a8680d534161b0772d7a771df6bd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRODUCTION DIRECTOR PERFORMANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The performance of the production director is evaluated based on variances such as labour rate variance and labour efficiency variance, and their impact on productivity and morale."</data>
      <data key="d2">a2b172963f635500ceb4bcd40e29a190</data>
      <data key="d7">20</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1822</data>
      <data key="d6">7f2c628b4fa54c0b9254049602ed20d2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MAINTENANCE MANAGER PERFORMANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The performance of the maintenance manager is evaluated based on variances such as fixed overhead expenditure variance and the impact of maintenance decisions on production and costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">a2b172963f635500ceb4bcd40e29a190</data>
      <data key="d7">20</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1823</data>
      <data key="d6">2f8f5d33916d4824bec6773bacd37d87</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES VOLUME CONTRIBUTION VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The "SALES VOLUME CONTRIBUTION VARIANCE" is calculated by comparing the actual volume to the budgeted volume, then multiplying the difference by the standard contribution per unit. The formula for this calculation is (Actual volume - Budget volume) * Standard contribution. This variance helps in assessing the impact of sales volume differences on the overall contribution margin by taking into account the standard contribution per unit.</data>
      <data key="d2">5083b641e457d160a51be1a4c3595318,b2fef5f7c017e4d460ee5bc5f0a369ef</data>
      <data key="d7">28</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1824</data>
      <data key="d6">b8e1f95f9d3e497393d86e6bd137fe10</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VARIABLE OVERHEAD RATE (EXPENDITURE) VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Variable overhead rate (expenditure) variance is calculated by comparing the hours worked with the standard hours for actual output, multiplied by the standard variable overhead rate per hour."</data>
      <data key="d2">b2fef5f7c017e4d460ee5bc5f0a369ef</data>
      <data key="d7">20</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1825</data>
      <data key="d6">13a41e2ff8b847ee8073e1e23b0bffc6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EVALUATING THE IMPACT OF ORGANIC INGREDIENT USAGE ON PRODUCTION AND SALES PERFORMANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Crumbly Cakes, a company that makes cakes sold directly to the public, evaluated the impact of using only organic ingredients on production and sales performance. The new production manager, a celebrity chef, argued that organic ingredients would improve flavor and health benefits, potentially increasing demand and allowing for a price increase. The company operates a responsibility-based standard costing system, and the variance reports for February and March showed mixed results, with the production manager facing adverse variances and the sales manager seeing favorable variances."</data>
      <data key="d2">b2fef5f7c017e4d460ee5bc5f0a369ef</data>
      <data key="d7">28</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1826</data>
      <data key="d6">9c61fb5ee44744a48bc5638bd42f654b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES CONTRIBUTION VOLUME&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sales contribution volume refers to the total contribution margin generated by the sales of a product. It is calculated as the sales price minus variable costs, multiplied by the number of units sold."</data>
      <data key="d2">8cdb68f181943c62464c2058a7ab3d96</data>
      <data key="d7">13</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1827</data>
      <data key="d6">946213d345b64cbaa6becb8723b01d87</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;JIT INVENTORY SYSTEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Just-In-Time (JIT) inventory system is a methodology where materials are only ordered and received as they are needed in the production process. This minimizes inventory costs and reduces waste."</data>
      <data key="d2">8cdb68f181943c62464c2058a7ab3d96</data>
      <data key="d7">13</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1828</data>
      <data key="d6">e75c65762f064dfc95787fa331c95392</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STANDARD SALES PRICE OF A CAKE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The standard sales price of a cake is $0.85."</data>
      <data key="d2">8cdb68f181943c62464c2058a7ab3d96</data>
      <data key="d7">13</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1829</data>
      <data key="d6">9a586c1629464133920fb19d8bd1e690</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STANDARD CONTRIBUTION PER CAKE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The standard contribution per cake after all variable costs is $0.35."</data>
      <data key="d2">8cdb68f181943c62464c2058a7ab3d96</data>
      <data key="d7">13</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1830</data>
      <data key="d6">e7a82e12e4f84f3e82c1ec74d3088235</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIAL PRICE VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Material price variance is calculated as (Actual Price - Standard Price) * Actual Quantity. It measures the difference between the actual cost of materials and the standard cost. Material price variances are calculated by comparing the actual price per kilogram of ingredients to the standard price per kilogram, multiplied by the actual quantity used. The formula is (AP - SP) * AQ."</data>
      <data key="d2">5083b641e457d160a51be1a4c3595318,8cdb68f181943c62464c2058a7ab3d96</data>
      <data key="d7">28</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1831</data>
      <data key="d6">51828127e71d40829039e033add265c4</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIAL MIX VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Material mix variance is calculated as (Actual Mix - Standard Mix) * Standard Price. It measures the cost impact of using a different mix of materials than planned."</data>
      <data key="d2">8cdb68f181943c62464c2058a7ab3d96</data>
      <data key="d7">13</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1832</data>
      <data key="d6">04918b80bc714753b00af559d439a4ec</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIAL YIELD VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Material yield variance is calculated as (Actual Yield - Standard Yield) * Standard Price. It measures the efficiency of material usage in the production process."</data>
      <data key="d2">8cdb68f181943c62464c2058a7ab3d96</data>
      <data key="d7">13</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1833</data>
      <data key="d6">3b4dbcb1c7c24bf8b6d55485c0304f7e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES PRICE VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sales price variance is calculated as (Actual Sales Price - Standard Sales Price) * Actual Quantity Sold. It measures the impact of selling at a different price than planned."</data>
      <data key="d2">8cdb68f181943c62464c2058a7ab3d96</data>
      <data key="d7">13</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1834</data>
      <data key="d6">fdd2a43d9b9f450c899adfb60b05e711</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES CONTRIBUTION VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sales contribution variance is calculated as (Actual Contribution - Standard Contribution) * Actual Quantity Sold. It measures the impact of changes in sales volume and contribution margin."</data>
      <data key="d2">8cdb68f181943c62464c2058a7ab3d96</data>
      <data key="d7">13</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1835</data>
      <data key="d6">bced585ff9d54fb7acd03f54f5729391</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CRUMBLY CAKES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Crumbly Cakes is a company that operates a JIT inventory system and produces organic cakes. The company faced variances in material prices, mix, yield, and sales prices, impacting the performance evaluation of the production and sales managers."</data>
      <data key="d2">8cdb68f181943c62464c2058a7ab3d96</data>
      <data key="d7">13</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">1836</data>
      <data key="d6">50aec048280a4cdb8572993faab794dd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES PERFORMANCE VARIANCE ANALYSIS FOR VALET CO AMID ECONOMIC CHALLENGES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Valet Co, a car valeting company in Strappia, faced economic challenges due to a global financial crisis. Despite increased petrol and food prices and a decrease in disposable household income, Valet Co's actual figures for full and mini valets exceeded budgeted figures. The case involves analyzing the company's sales performance variance, considering factors like increased car repair business and the closure of a competitor."</data>
      <data key="d2">5083b641e457d160a51be1a4c3595318</data>
      <data key="d7">28</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1837</data>
      <data key="d6">e128a7179b6e476c98d6bbfecf2a3f9a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STANDARD CONTRIBUTION PER UNIT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Standard contribution per unit for Full valet = $50 * 44.6% = $22.30 per valet; for Mini valet = $30 * 55% = $16.50 per valet."</data>
      <data key="d2">adea171e6847df263c60c9085bf66897</data>
      <data key="d7">27</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1838</data>
      <data key="d6">a3fa60c3370e4d5e8147250e2a18104a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TOTAL SALES MIX CONTRIBUTION VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Total sales mix contribution variance = (actual sales quantity - actual sales quantity in budgeted proportions) * standard contribution per unit."</data>
      <data key="d2">adea171e6847df263c60c9085bf66897</data>
      <data key="d7">27</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1839</data>
      <data key="d6">1a7ef91522514b9f8b1ddaf68424351d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TOTAL SALES QUANTITY CONTRIBUTION VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Total sales quantity contribution variance = (actual sales quantity in budgeted proportions - budgeted sales quantity) * standard contribution per unit."</data>
      <data key="d2">adea171e6847df263c60c9085bf66897</data>
      <data key="d7">27</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1840</data>
      <data key="d6">e5f094bf02d84a0889cd041199156ad7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES PERFORMANCE OF THE BUSINESS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The sales performance of the business has been very good over the last year, as shown by the favourable sales quantity variance of $48,144. Overall, total revenue is 33% higher than budgeted due to an increase in the total number of valets performed. The number of mini valets increased dramatically by 99%, while full valets increased by 11%. The adverse sales mix variance of $6,554 is reflective of changes in consumer behavior due to decreased disposable incomes and longer car retention periods."</data>
      <data key="d2">adea171e6847df263c60c9085bf66897</data>
      <data key="d7">27</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1841</data>
      <data key="d6">5c64fc0a74044110906120ca1d5c7919</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ANALYSIS OF PRODUCTION VARIANCE AND MARKET SHARE IN STANDARD COSTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Safe Soap Co makes environmentally-friendly soap using three basic ingredients. The standard cost of one batch of soap was $6.4. The budget for production and sales in September was 120,000 batches, but actual production and sales were 136,000 batches. The production manager made changes to improve quality and reduce material waste, including using a higher quality supplier, adjusting the product mix, and using new machinery. The sales manager reported positive customer feedback and increased orders."</data>
      <data key="d2">ab526e2c1a180897995765c0573772d5</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1842</data>
      <data key="d6">524d1b6a01d34b0098a0da8af056bfc8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STANDARD COST OF ONE BATCH OF SOAP&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The standard cost of one batch of soap was $6.4, calculated as follows: Lye (0.25 kg at $10 per kg), Coconut oil (0.6 kg at $4 per kg), and Shea butter (0.5 kg at $3 per kg)."</data>
      <data key="d2">ab526e2c1a180897995765c0573772d5</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1843</data>
      <data key="d6">73af37cadd3c4d3dbfb8bfd697aeef58</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;YIELD VARIANCE FOR SEPTEMBER&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The yield variance for September was $9,899 favorable, calculated as follows: Total kg of materials per standard batch (0.25 + 0.6 + 0.5) = 1.35 kg. Total kg used: 181,512 should yield (181,512/1.35) 134,453.33 batches. Actual output: 136,000 batches. Surplus: 1,546.67 batches. Standard cost per batch: $6.4. Yield variance: $9,898.67 favorable."</data>
      <data key="d2">ab526e2c1a180897995765c0573772d5</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1844</data>
      <data key="d6">c6b26fcc94044c368b2fe0db4b9b72f2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ACTUAL QUANTITIES OF LYE AND SHEA BUTTER USED COMPARED WITH THE STANDARD MIX&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The actual quantities of Lye and Shea Butter used compared with the standard mix were as follows: Lye: More than the standard mix, Shea Butter: Less than the standard mix."</data>
      <data key="d2">ab526e2c1a180897995765c0573772d5</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1845</data>
      <data key="d6">36b9f94e17c6481fb83670b70b192eb7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SAFE SOAP CO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Safe Soap Co makes a contribution of $3.6 on each batch of soap sold. The budgeted sales of 120,000 batches were based on achieving a market share of 10%. The actual sales of the total market in September were 1.4 million units. The market share variance for the month of September was calculated to be $14,400 adverse."</data>
      <data key="d2">24cd8c3feefdefe57b7e7da7db59d031</data>
      <data key="d7">28</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1846</data>
      <data key="d6">24c63641b4e241589336236d5f916e34</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STANDARD COSTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Standard costing is a cost accounting method that assigns expected costs to products and services. It involves setting standard costs for materials, labor, and overheads, and then comparing these standards to actual costs to identify variances. This method allows for variance analysis to identify differences between actual and expected costs, providing valuable insights for cost control and management.</data>
      <data key="d2">24cd8c3feefdefe57b7e7da7db59d031,dafeac07a3bcfef066cd6672e6b6711a</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">8</data>
      <data key="d5">1847</data>
      <data key="d6">718e03207dcd44a080806880d08268ea</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VARIANCE ANALYSIS AND IMPACT OF PRODUCTION MIX ON ORGANIC BREAD COMPANY'S COSTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Organic Bread Company (OBC) makes a range of breads for sale direct to the public. The production process involves weighing ingredients, mixing, shaping, baking, and inspecting loaves. The standard cost card for OBC's Mixed Bloomer includes white flour, wholegrain flour, and yeast. Budgeted production was 1,000 units, but actual production was 950 units. The material mix variance for the period was calculated to be an adverse variance of $16.51."</data>
      <data key="d2">24cd8c3feefdefe57b7e7da7db59d031</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1848</data>
      <data key="d6">6d0efadfba5046eb86869827544c2703</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIAL MIX VARIANCE FOR OBC&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Material mix variance = (Actual quantity used - Actual quantity in Standard) * Standard price"</data>
      <data key="d2">24cd8c3feefdefe57b7e7da7db59d031</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1849</data>
      <data key="d6">2c33b12183ad4722ab1ab2cbd75f8312</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIAL VARIANCE ANALYSIS AND PERFORMANCE ASSESSMENT CHALLENGES AT KAPPA CO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Kappa Co produces Omega, an animal feed made by mixing and heating three ingredients: Alpha, Beta, and Gamma. The company uses a standard costing system to monitor its costs. The standard material cost for 100 kg of Omega is calculated based on the input quantities and costs of Alpha, Beta, and Gamma. The case highlights the challenges in material variance analysis and performance assessment due to factors like standard evaporation loss, varying quality and price of agricultural products, and outdated standard mix settings."</data>
      <data key="d2">f8ef013188b41d62318c1306ced4944f</data>
      <data key="d4">8</data>
      <data key="d5">1850</data>
      <data key="d6">f334bc9701204b1b943f9ece317ca68a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIAL VARIANCE ANALYSIS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Material variance analysis involves comparing the actual material costs to the standard costs to identify variances. These variances can be due to differences in material prices, usage, or mix. The analysis helps in understanding the reasons behind cost deviations and in making informed decisions to control costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">f8ef013188b41d62318c1306ced4944f</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1851</data>
      <data key="d6">4ea3ecb74c91452da866f4c9163386e2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ALPHA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Alpha is an agricultural product used in the production of Omega, an animal feed. It is one of the three ingredients required for Omega's production. The quality and price of Alpha are variable and can change significantly from year to year. The standard cost for Alpha is $2.00 per kg.</data>
      <data key="d2">a3550b57bf20a6d9132ffc81fb1444d1,f8ef013188b41d62318c1306ced4944f</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1852</data>
      <data key="d6">a12fe8fd9bc34db69d8de6944283d3c9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BETA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Beta is an agricultural product used in the production of Omega, an animal feed. It is one of the three ingredients required for Omega's production. The quality and price of Beta are variable and can change significantly from year to year. The standard cost for Beta is $5.00 per kg.</data>
      <data key="d2">a3550b57bf20a6d9132ffc81fb1444d1,f8ef013188b41d62318c1306ced4944f</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1853</data>
      <data key="d6">02b877f830cc4bb58dfad02f13a6d6ce</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GAMMA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Gamma is an agricultural product used in the production of Omega, an animal feed. It is one of the three ingredients essential for creating Omega. The quality and price of Gamma are variable and can change significantly from year to year. Despite these fluctuations, the standard cost for Gamma is typically $1.00 per kg.</data>
      <data key="d2">a3550b57bf20a6d9132ffc81fb1444d1,f8ef013188b41d62318c1306ced4944f</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1854</data>
      <data key="d6">abffcf93dc114332a181990ad56b7863</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STANDARD MIX&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The "STANDARD MIX" refers to the predetermined proportions of Alpha, Beta, and Gamma used in the production of Omega. This mix is set by the finance department and has not been updated since the product launch five years ago.</data>
      <data key="d2">a3550b57bf20a6d9132ffc81fb1444d1,f8ef013188b41d62318c1306ced4944f</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1855</data>
      <data key="d6">f894b0ae91eb412d93b6b06d4a73f350</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STANDARD EVAPORATION LOSS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Standard evaporation loss refers to the expected loss of material during the mixing and heating process in the production of Omega. This loss is accounted for in the standard costing system."</data>
      <data key="d2">f8ef013188b41d62318c1306ced4944f</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1856</data>
      <data key="d6">75e06eb1f93c4ee38b782965ea905b5b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PURCHASING MANAGER&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The purchasing manager at Kappa Co is responsible for pricing and supplier contracts for the ingredients Alpha, Beta, and Gamma. The manager plays a crucial role in managing material costs and ensuring the quality of inputs.</data>
      <data key="d2">a3550b57bf20a6d9132ffc81fb1444d1,f8ef013188b41d62318c1306ced4944f</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1857</data>
      <data key="d6">70fd5c73bbe34d918b3dca3fc7294d28</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STANDARD PRICES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Standard prices are set at the average market price over the last five years for agricultural products like Alpha, Beta, and Gamma."</data>
      <data key="d2">a3550b57bf20a6d9132ffc81fb1444d1</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1858</data>
      <data key="d6">8f1edc1d00764d6fb23859242c659deb</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OMEGA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Omega is a product produced by Kappa Co using inputs like Alpha, Beta, and Gamma."</data>
      <data key="d2">a3550b57bf20a6d9132ffc81fb1444d1</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1859</data>
      <data key="d6">c8554314efb44679a898bbce08372abe</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STANDARD COST OPERATING STATEMENT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The standard cost operating statement contains material price and usage variances, labour rate and efficiency variances, and overhead expenditure and efficiency variances for the previous month."</data>
      <data key="d2">a3550b57bf20a6d9132ffc81fb1444d1</data>
      <data key="d7">28</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1860</data>
      <data key="d6">a41dbc4319f74bc995a93dbe0f4d9aee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRODUCTION MANAGER&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The production manager at Kappa Co is responsible for the efficiency of the Omega production process and receives a standard cost operating statement at the end of each month."</data>
      <data key="d2">a3550b57bf20a6d9132ffc81fb1444d1</data>
      <data key="d7">28</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1861</data>
      <data key="d6">ef76a41bf9bf45c893c475a7bd5a2938</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES PERFORMANCE FOR THE YEAR&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sales performance for the year involves comparing budgeted revenues to actual revenues, analyzing variances in sales volume and selling price, and understanding the impact of market conditions and competitive actions on sales outcomes."</data>
      <data key="d2">f97d81426ba6b512862db11eb6fe561a</data>
      <data key="d7">27</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1862</data>
      <data key="d6">88f486cbb1904425a5fd5dfa268cf85d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LOCK CO'S OPERATIONAL EFFICIENCY AND VARIANCE MANAGEMENT IN MAY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Lock Co makes a single product, a lock, and uses marginal costing. The variance statement for May shows variances in revenue, direct materials, direct labor, and variable overheads, highlighting areas of operational efficiency and inefficiency."</data>
      <data key="d2">f97d81426ba6b512862db11eb6fe561a</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1863</data>
      <data key="d6">ec10a8695b1a4e8787d9d29114e9d5ce</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ADVERSE SALES VOLUME CONTRIBUTION VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The adverse sales volume contribution variance for the month of May is calculated as follows: Budgeted sales (units) - Actual sales (units) * Standard contribution per unit."</data>
      <data key="d2">1aa84a5288fe62c1d778b9f9013d51c3</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1864</data>
      <data key="d6">9397185bb4d7492b88eaa20fa10c0ae5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PLANNING PRICE VARIANCE FOR MATERIALS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The planning price variance for materials for May is calculated as follows: Actual materials at original standard price - Actual materials at revised standard price."</data>
      <data key="d2">1aa84a5288fe62c1d778b9f9013d51c3</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1865</data>
      <data key="d6">2b1b9b1ed49c4ace91ff099752b8c0a5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PERFORMANCE ANALYSIS OF LABOUR RATE AND EFFICIENCY VARIANCES AT TRUFFLE CO IN NOVEMBER&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Truffle Co makes high quality, hand-made chocolate truffles which it sells to a local retailer. The standard cost of labour for each batch is $6.00 and the standard labour time for each batch is 30 minutes. In November, Truffle Co had budgeted production of 24,000 batches; actual production was only 20,500 batches. 12,000 labour hours were used to complete the work and there was no idle time. All workers were paid for their actual hours worked. The actual total labour cost for November was $136,800. The production manager at Truffle Co has no input into the budgeting process. At the end of October, the managing director held a meeting and offered staff the choice of either accepting a 5% pay cut or facing a certain number of redundancies. All staff subsequently agreed to accept the 5% pay cut with immediate effect. At the same time, the retailer requested that the truffles be made slightly softer. This change was implemented immediately and made the chocolates more difficult to shape. When recipe changes such as these are made, it takes time before the workers become used to working with the new ingredient mix, making the process 20% slower for at least the first month of the new operation."</data>
      <data key="d2">1aa84a5288fe62c1d778b9f9013d51c3</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1866</data>
      <data key="d6">62c66c25992d4974829678313ed60b1d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIAL PRICE OPERATIONAL VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Material price operational variance is calculated as (Revised price - actual price) * actual quantity."</data>
      <data key="d2">d1ec505d57aaab095501408bc8aca972</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1867</data>
      <data key="d6">26a889667b614ab890d863c4b8762e69</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIAL USAGE PLANNING VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Material usage planning variance is calculated as (Standard quantity for actual production - revised quantity for actual production) * standard price."</data>
      <data key="d2">d1ec505d57aaab095501408bc8aca972</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1868</data>
      <data key="d6">30461855b0604128a4f10d0b348ce60f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIAL USAGE OPERATIONAL VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Material usage operational variance is calculated as (Actual quantity - revised quantity for actual production) * standard price."</data>
      <data key="d2">d1ec505d57aaab095501408bc8aca972</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1869</data>
      <data key="d6">edef06de541f493f98d9281a704d785d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VARIANCE ANALYSIS OF MATERIAL AND LABOUR COSTS FOR SU CO IN FEBRUARY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The School Uniform Company (SU Co) manufactures school uniforms and faced variances in material and labor costs in February. The case involves calculating and assessing the variances for material price planning, material price operational, material usage planning, and material usage operational for both bed sheets and pillowcases."</data>
      <data key="d2">d1ec505d57aaab095501408bc8aca972</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1870</data>
      <data key="d6">0016a9dec22543e9b203f540860bf2e7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PERFORMANCE OF THE PRODUCTION MANAGER&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The performance of the production manager is assessed based on the variances calculated. The manager is not responsible for the increase in cotton prices or the design change requested by the customer, but is responsible for the operational variances in material usage."</data>
      <data key="d2">d1ec505d57aaab095501408bc8aca972</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1871</data>
      <data key="d6">4f79558a259f4de58df5b022b68a459e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GIRLS' PRIVATE SCHOOL TRUST (GPST)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Girls' Private School Trust (GPST) oversees 35 schools across the country, all with the same school uniform. Recently, the GPST redesigned the spring/summer dress to incorporate a dropped waistband, requiring more material and a new sewing technique."</data>
      <data key="d2">dafeac07a3bcfef066cd6672e6b6711a</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1872</data>
      <data key="d6">ca07919df74f4e5abfbd370c50eacc00</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIAL VARIANCES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Material variances refer to the differences between the expected cost and the actual cost of materials used in production. These variances can be broken down into price variances and usage variances, which help in assessing the efficiency and cost-effectiveness of material usage."</data>
      <data key="d2">dafeac07a3bcfef066cd6672e6b6711a</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1873</data>
      <data key="d6">94b8715919cd49d08ac0ce99b930ea53</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SCHOOL UNIFORM COMPANY (SU CO)&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">dafeac07a3bcfef066cd6672e6b6711a</data>
      <data key="d7">22</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1874</data>
      <data key="d6">4a10c341918b4d888b8b0466bd101b1d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIALS PRICE PLANNING VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Materials price planning variance compares the original standard price to the revised standard price and multiplies the difference by the actual quantity of material used."</data>
      <data key="d2">f6982a4563820b317a7b745f9ea9c299</data>
      <data key="d7">17</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1875</data>
      <data key="d6">5173ce4188034717b9c90eef40b94932</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LABOUR RATE OPERATIONAL VARIANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Labour rate operational variance compares the revised standard rate per hour to the actual rate per hour and multiplies the difference by the number of hours worked."</data>
      <data key="d2">f6982a4563820b317a7b745f9ea9c299</data>
      <data key="d7">17</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1876</data>
      <data key="d6">cff3415902bf4745992473697570aef0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PERFORMANCE ASSESSMENT FOR ACCOUNTANCY TEACHING CO (AT CO) IN 20X9&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Accountancy Teaching Co (AT Co) faced a 20% decline in demand for accountancy training in 20X9, leading to smaller class sizes. Despite this, AT Co improved its service quality through several developments, including a 24-hour student helpline, an interactive website, a new staff training program, and electronic systems for student enrolment and marking. These improvements were expected to reduce marking costs by $4m."</data>
      <data key="d2">f6982a4563820b317a7b745f9ea9c299</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1877</data>
      <data key="d6">4c0cf727ec2843a288aa00b43f25b2de</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DEVELOPMENTS AT AT CO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Developments at AT Co in 20X9 included a new 24-hour student helpline, an interactive website, a new staff training program, an electronic student enrolment system, and an electronic marking system. These improvements aimed to enhance service quality and reduce costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">f6982a4563820b317a7b745f9ea9c299</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1878</data>
      <data key="d6">87ece3a4dcc84c98a291c1138ae56544</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COST OF SALES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Cost of sales, also known as cost of goods sold (COGS), represents the direct costs attributable to the production of the goods sold by a company. For the year 20X9, the expected cost of sales was $47.738 million, but the actual cost of sales was $42.056 million, showing a reduction of $5.682 million.</data>
      <data key="d2">a22eae134ce57b58870ae60a9afaf634,e46ba1df72ea3be49ae00b5c572153aa</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">1879</data>
      <data key="d6">143dc5f4cb4b4596900ee5158594b1b0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INDIRECT EXPENSES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Indirect expenses are costs that are not directly tied to the production of goods or services, such as marketing, property, staff training, and other operational costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">a22eae134ce57b58870ae60a9afaf634</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1880</data>
      <data key="d6">3c222c5fdfab46e1ac1352a0f85a5fdd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NET OPERATING PROFIT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Net operating profit" is the profit earned from a firm's normal core business operations, excluding deductions of interest and tax. Recently, net operating profit fell from $3.635 million to $2.106 million. Despite this decline, the outcome was viewed positively considering the challenging market conditions.</data>
      <data key="d2">a22eae134ce57b58870ae60a9afaf634,e46ba1df72ea3be49ae00b5c572153aa</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">1881</data>
      <data key="d6">8c13a465b483417691c9b8d40b913da3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FREELANCE LECTURERS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Freelance lecturers are non-employee instructors hired by the company to teach students when there are not enough of the company's own lecturers to meet tuition needs."</data>
      <data key="d2">a22eae134ce57b58870ae60a9afaf634</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1882</data>
      <data key="d6">51633d2f0adf4123a23eeb292d95e649</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PERFORMANCE ASSESSMENT OF AT CO IN 20X9&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The performance assessment of AT Co in 20X9 involves evaluating various financial and non-financial metrics, including revenue, cost of sales, gross profit, indirect expenses, and net operating profit, as well as non-financial performance indicators such as student transfer rates, late enrolments, exam pass rates, labor turnover, and student complaints."</data>
      <data key="d2">a22eae134ce57b58870ae60a9afaf634</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">1883</data>
      <data key="d6">849136ae8c9f4f9589a989bfe4c4155d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FREELANCE LECTURER COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Freelance lecturer costs fell by $2.188m, contributing to the overall reduction in cost of sales."</data>
      <data key="d2">e46ba1df72ea3be49ae00b5c572153aa</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1884</data>
      <data key="d6">84b11b37d1dd4e75b4c453669fbd4df9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ONLINE MARKING SYSTEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The online marking system was expected to cut costs by $4m, but it likely saved $3.494m, contributing to the reduction in cost of sales."</data>
      <data key="d2">e46ba1df72ea3be49ae00b5c572153aa</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1885</data>
      <data key="d6">373c198a0ed2402cb885b8d9f9de92f3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARKETING COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Marketing costs are the expenses related to promoting and selling a new product. In 20X9, marketing costs increased by 42.1%, which was essential for attracting new students and improving service awareness."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4cbc64c9c49dd951f9997a26ee9d9f9,e46ba1df72ea3be49ae00b5c572153aa</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1886</data>
      <data key="d6">64ec8c4eb0734d60a5287e3df62652bd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PROPERTY COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Property costs remained largely the same in both years."</data>
      <data key="d2">e46ba1df72ea3be49ae00b5c572153aa</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1887</data>
      <data key="d6">7636104f26794a4e9e74b2d6943c879d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STAFF TRAINING COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Staff training costs increased by over $2m, a 163.9% increase, to address staff retention issues and train staff on new systems."</data>
      <data key="d2">e46ba1df72ea3be49ae00b5c572153aa</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1888</data>
      <data key="d6">fc4b406a34ea4b2d9f305600aab14ea3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INTERACTIVE WEBSITE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The interactive website was introduced to improve service quality and pass rates, contributing to higher student numbers and revenue."</data>
      <data key="d2">e46ba1df72ea3be49ae00b5c572153aa</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1889</data>
      <data key="d6">5400473bab9d4105a1517fdc55c58f17</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STUDENT HELPLINE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The student helpline was introduced to improve service quality and pass rates, contributing to higher student numbers and revenue."</data>
      <data key="d2">e46ba1df72ea3be49ae00b5c572153aa</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1890</data>
      <data key="d6">624a1e6ea1d248f8b5126527e82e76c0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ENROLMENT COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Enrolment costs fell dramatically by 80.9% due to the introduction of a new electronic system."</data>
      <data key="d2">e46ba1df72ea3be49ae00b5c572153aa</data>
      <data key="d7">10</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1891</data>
      <data key="d6">66e53a4f6fc740aaaa379aa63d15f0e9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ADVERTISING COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Advertising cost refers to the expenses incurred for promoting products or services. In this case, $200,000 was spent on advertising in a fashion magazine, significantly impacting the net profit margin."</data>
      <data key="d2">2207ef547588f07b856f3a5c961e39a0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1892</data>
      <data key="d6">e676d0167a3f43478a209ec9526c90df</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SEARCH ENGINE CONSULTANT FEE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The search engine consultant fee is the amount paid for optimizing search engine results. A fee of $20,000 was paid, which contributed to an increase in website visits."</data>
      <data key="d2">2207ef547588f07b856f3a5c961e39a0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1893</data>
      <data key="d6">44fa3d2247904198b1c776e060d35eb2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NUMBER OF VISITS TO WEBSITE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The number of visits to the website increased from 101,589 to 141,714, a 39.5% increase, attributed to both the fashion magazine's website and the search engine consultant's work."</data>
      <data key="d2">2207ef547588f07b856f3a5c961e39a0</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">1894</data>
      <data key="d6">a135859c7d3d4d3596f1e4ab218eff8a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NUMBER OF ORDERS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The number of orders received increased from 40,636 to 49,600, a 22% increase, indicating higher customer engagement and purchase activity."</data>
      <data key="d2">2207ef547588f07b856f3a5c961e39a0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1895</data>
      <data key="d6">5e6fd98384a24a34b80311842661e00a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CUSTOMERS SPENDING MORE THAN $100&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The number of customers spending more than $100 per visit increased from 4,650 to 6,390, reflecting a higher average order value."</data>
      <data key="d2">2207ef547588f07b856f3a5c961e39a0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1896</data>
      <data key="d6">3a10d5261d4240c7b05b6cdb7838ff24</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CONVERSION RATE - VISITOR TO PURCHASER&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The conversion rate of visitors to purchasers decreased from 40% to 35%, possibly due to curiosity-driven visits from the fashion magazine's website."</data>
      <data key="d2">2207ef547588f07b856f3a5c961e39a0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1897</data>
      <data key="d6">ec595c7b07e148dba900040a68ef0fdb</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SUBSCRIBERS TO ONLINE NEWSLETTER&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Subscribers to the online newsletter increased by 159%, although the impact on repeat customers is unclear."</data>
      <data key="d2">2207ef547588f07b856f3a5c961e39a0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1898</data>
      <data key="d6">4b43619c5c6a4ea3826bfd3c06aa6e66</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FAST TRACK SERVICE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Fast Track service is a delivery option that did not incur additional costs despite the overall fall in net profit."</data>
      <data key="d2">2207ef547588f07b856f3a5c961e39a0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1899</data>
      <data key="d6">3173671571f14c75bfb9141754424efa</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ANALYSIS OF BEST NIGHT CO'S FINANCIAL AND NON-FINANCIAL PERFORMANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This case analyzes the financial and non-financial performance of Best Night Co, focusing on metrics such as net profit margin, advertising costs, website visits, order numbers, customer spending, conversion rates, and newsletter subscriptions."</data>
      <data key="d2">2207ef547588f07b856f3a5c961e39a0</data>
      <data key="d4">9</data>
      <data key="d5">1900</data>
      <data key="d6">1675e75d7b524d4ab236eeaefd2dc992</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NET PROFIT MARGIN (NPM)&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">2207ef547588f07b856f3a5c961e39a0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1901</data>
      <data key="d6">bb906c8e869141aa9be12118dcd3d3b5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CUSTOMERS ACCESSING WEBSITE THROUGH MAGAZINE LINE FORMULA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Customers accessing website through magazine line = 141,714 * 19.9% = 28,201. This formula calculates the number of customers accessing the website through a specific magazine line by applying the given percentage."</data>
      <data key="d2">fadb4fab0783e39959f216c49d498be1</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1902</data>
      <data key="d6">27c95f7d6c3d4732897ae7bffd7c5dc8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INCREASE IN SUBSCRIBERS TO NEWSLETTER FORMULA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Increase in subscribers to newsletter = (11,900 - 4,600)/4,600 = 159%. This formula calculates the percentage increase in newsletter subscribers by comparing the current number of subscribers to the previous number of subscribers."</data>
      <data key="d2">fadb4fab0783e39959f216c49d498be1</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1903</data>
      <data key="d6">b63c467faf714acd8a006431faf7a141</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ANALYSIS OF BEST NIGHT CO'S FINANCIAL AND NON-FINANCIAL PERFORMANCE FOR YEAR ENDED 30 JUNE 20X7&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Best Night Co operates a chain of 30 hotels in Essland, focusing on room comfort and service quality. Despite a 6.6% increase in gross room revenue due to higher occupancy rates and room prices, the net revenue increase was only 1.8% after significant discounts. The company faced declining business customers and postponed a planned refurbishment program due to economic conditions. The case discusses the financial and non-financial performance, including customer satisfaction and occupancy rates."</data>
      <data key="d2">fadb4fab0783e39959f216c49d498be1</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1904</data>
      <data key="d6">19a5840a67e14c468f9f3d6851eaee5c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OCCUPANCY RATES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Occupancy rates increased by 2.8% (from 72% to 74% which now exceeds the budgeted level), revenue, net of discounts, only increased by 1.8%. This means that revenue per room per night after discounts in 20X7 was lower than in 20X6, despite the standard rate being higher ($140 v $135)."</data>
      <data key="d2">c559ece83ebebc82b7241fbb0cd0dd92</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1905</data>
      <data key="d6">7a58673144d849e7a784caee9d9d4e99</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ADDITIONAL REVENUE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"One of the potential benefits of increased occupancy rates, even if guests are paying less per room per night, is that they will generate additional revenue from food and drink sales. This appears to be the case because additional revenues have increased by approximately 5%."</data>
      <data key="d2">c559ece83ebebc82b7241fbb0cd0dd92</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1906</data>
      <data key="d6">8076db94b7214fdf9e006ce5a7e1cbe2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPERATING PROFIT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Despite the increase in revenue, operating profits have fallen by $0.3m (1.3%) between 20X7 and 20X6, due to a sizeable increase in operating costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">c559ece83ebebc82b7241fbb0cd0dd92</data>
      <data key="d7">6</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1907</data>
      <data key="d6">e733886404db4d46862bdddb2aee5211</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPERATING COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"There is no detail about Best Night Co's operating costs, for example, the split between fixed and variable costs. However, in an increasingly competitive market, cost control is likely to be very important. As such, the $3m (3.3%) increase in operating costs between 20X6 and 20X7 is potentially a cause for concern, and the reasons for the increase should be investigated further."</data>
      <data key="d2">c559ece83ebebc82b7241fbb0cd0dd92</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1908</data>
      <data key="d6">b75594a9d9c8404688a5cfe02272cdfc</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPERATING PROFIT MARGIN&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The "Operating Profit Margin" is calculated as (Operating profit / Revenue) * 100. This metric indicates the percentage of revenue that remains after covering operating expenses. Recently, there has been a decline in the operating profit margin from 20.8% to 20.0%, attributed to an increase in costs. When considering standard room rates per night, which reflect the impact of discounts and increased costs, the margin falls further from 18.9% to 17.6%.</data>
      <data key="d2">312c3cf9edbc058c6e810c1e9c9cd81a,92d19303f11122ce7fe6d2e698547f59,bc0524558467e4e3eec1a2e2e05b5d33,c559ece83ebebc82b7241fbb0cd0dd92</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">1909</data>
      <data key="d6">f253ff2311024729a758bb77b14bf72d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ROCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Return on Capital Employed (ROCE) has fallen slightly from 62% ($24.2m/$39.1m) to 60.5% ($23.9m/$39.5m). This suggests that the value which Best Night Co is generating from its assets is falling."</data>
      <data key="d2">c559ece83ebebc82b7241fbb0cd0dd92</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1910</data>
      <data key="d6">1f0cb1e7fae64c238efb659d254d6221</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CUSTOMER SATISFACTION SCORES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The reduction in customer satisfaction scores should potentially be seen as a greater cause for concern. The scores suggest that, in the space of one year, Best Night Co hotels have gone from being in the top 10% of hotels to only just being in the top 25%. This is a significant decline in one year, and one which Best Night Co cannot afford to continue."</data>
      <data key="d2">c559ece83ebebc82b7241fbb0cd0dd92</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1911</data>
      <data key="d6">6740be36e0e14774a5551a17db648a13</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FINANCIAL ANALYSIS AND BALANCED SCORECARD EVALUATION FOR EASYAIR CO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Easyair Co was founded seven years ago, and is one of a growing number of low-cost airlines in the country of Shania. Summarised financial information for the most recent financial year is provided below: Operating profit: $700m, Interest payable: $100m, Profit before tax: $600m, Tax: $200m, Profit after tax: $400m, Non-current liabilities: $300m, Share capital: $100m, Retained earnings: $2,000m."</data>
      <data key="d2">c559ece83ebebc82b7241fbb0cd0dd92</data>
      <data key="d7">6</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1912</data>
      <data key="d6">0f926e9dfaae4615b16a794e984b85ae</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PERFORMANCE EVALUATION OF THE PEOPLE'S BANK USING THE BALANCED SCORECARD APPROACH&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The People's Bank uses the balanced scorecard approach to evaluate its performance. The bank's vision is to be 'the bank that gives back to its customers,' and it aims to help the people and businesses of Nawkrei live better lives and achieve their ambitions. The bank's values include putting customers' needs first, making business simple, and making a difference to the communities they serve. The balanced scorecard helps the bank measure performance across financial, customer, internal business processes, and innovation and learning perspectives."</data>
      <data key="d2">92d19303f11122ce7fe6d2e698547f59</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1913</data>
      <data key="d6">47851446a4df4f5aa4505c999daaaaf7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CUSTOMER PERSPECTIVE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">The "Customer Perspective" evaluates The People's Bank's performance in terms of customer satisfaction and service delivery. It includes metrics such as the number of mortgages provided to new homeowners, customer complaints, and services for the disabled and visually impaired. Additionally, the customer perspective considers how the organization appears to customers, identifying the customer and market segments in which the business units will compete and linking customer objectives to revenue objectives.</data>
      <data key="d2">1d33c979d505d0dcd027d816d2ab2695,9e7686d21dc44e02903d60f691c5a4bb</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1914</data>
      <data key="d6">c3e51a2782ba4f86b49b4038a316d9fb</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INTERNAL PROCESSES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Internal processes at The People's Bank involve simplifying procedures and improving IT systems to enhance efficiency and reduce fraud. The bank also aims to introduce new services via mobile banking and manage CO2 emissions."</data>
      <data key="d2">9e7686d21dc44e02903d60f691c5a4bb</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1915</data>
      <data key="d6">8f09d5749e034c579f2ac191e22e1087</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LEARNING AND GROWTH&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Learning and growth at The People's Bank focus on community involvement, employee training, and supporting small businesses and disadvantaged groups. It includes metrics such as hours of paid volunteer work, community organizations supported, and training for employees to advise SMEs."</data>
      <data key="d2">9e7686d21dc44e02903d60f691c5a4bb</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1916</data>
      <data key="d6">2ce5d7d975834096a3ec7e484035cdfe</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PERFORMANCE ANALYSIS OF THE ONE STOP CAR CO USING FITZGERALD AND MOON'S BUILDING BLOCK MODEL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The One Stop Car Co (OSC Co) operates 55 service centers across the country, offering various car maintenance services. Each center operates autonomously, and the company aims to make car maintenance a pleasure. The case analyzes the performance of the Midlands Service Centre (MSC) using Fitzgerald and Moon's Building Block Model, comparing it to the OSC average."</data>
      <data key="d2">9e7686d21dc44e02903d60f691c5a4bb</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1917</data>
      <data key="d6">65cfb89a8a4547c2af0d579a69acd6ee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FITZGERALD AND MOON'S BUILDING BLOCK MODEL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">Fitzgerald and Moon's Building Block Model is a performance management model that includes dimensions such as competitiveness, financial performance, quality of service, flexibility, resource utilization, and innovation. This performance measurement framework evaluates business performance based on three building blocks: standards, rewards, and dimensions. It is used to assess the performance of service centers, such as those of The One Stop Car Co.</data>
      <data key="d2">9e7686d21dc44e02903d60f691c5a4bb,e7d75450db353b8413fb68bdd98ac99c</data>
      <data key="d4">9</data>
      <data key="d5">1918</data>
      <data key="d6">2eb9b76789344bac852d2b437ef334d4</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MIDLANDS SERVICE CENTRE (MSC)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Midlands Service Centre (MSC) is one of the 55 service centers operated by The One Stop Car Co. The case study provides performance metrics for MSC, including sales revenue, gross profit, number of mechanics, new service packs developed, website hits, jobs booked and completed, and customer feedback."</data>
      <data key="d2">9e7686d21dc44e02903d60f691c5a4bb</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1919</data>
      <data key="d6">5b0884a87f274d1889c78ecf668fbbb3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;THE PEOPLE'S BANK&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">9e7686d21dc44e02903d60f691c5a4bb</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1920</data>
      <data key="d6">37df9f0676344c0c9ddb4b21fa09b8c2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;JUNIOR MECHANICS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Junior mechanics include both trainee mechanics who are unqualified and mechanics who have been qualified for less than five years."</data>
      <data key="d2">e7d75450db353b8413fb68bdd98ac99c</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1921</data>
      <data key="d6">244eececc7724e2fb4c83ab04fe7200f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FREE VALETS SERVICE PACK&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A service pack offering free valets for orders over $100, generating $66,000 in revenue."</data>
      <data key="d2">e7d75450db353b8413fb68bdd98ac99c</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1922</data>
      <data key="d6">4dee41bcdebc44b3b24ce187b2b07d43</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SAFETY CHECK SERVICE PACK&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A service pack offering a safety check costing $20 instead of the usual $40 for customers booking a full service, generating $58,000 in revenue."</data>
      <data key="d2">e7d75450db353b8413fb68bdd98ac99c</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1923</data>
      <data key="d6">bd0247986b95433793c35f11064bb309</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;AIR CONDITIONING EFFICIENCY CHECK SERVICE PACK&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A service pack offering a $10 air conditioning efficiency check, which usually costs $20, for customers booking an oil change, generating $54,000 in revenue."</data>
      <data key="d2">e7d75450db353b8413fb68bdd98ac99c</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1924</data>
      <data key="d6">2087291be35447268a45622f4740360e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STANDARDS BLOCK&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"STANDARDS BLOCK" is a component of Fitzgerald and Moon's Building Block Model that supports the dimensions block by setting performance standards. It establishes the target for performance indicators chosen for each dimension. These targets must be achievable, fair, and encourage employees to take ownership. Properly set standards ensure that organizational performance does not suffer.</data>
      <data key="d2">b302d47d456dc3a1adafa01592a31745,e7d75450db353b8413fb68bdd98ac99c</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1925</data>
      <data key="d6">4c253b3a37f64616849850643372e13c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REWARDS BLOCK&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">The "REWARDS BLOCK" is part of Fitzgerald and Moon's Building Block Model that supports the dimensions block by providing incentives and rewards for achieving performance standards. The rewards block ensures that employees are motivated to achieve these standards. Effective reward schemes should be clear, motivating, and based on controllable factors. Properly set rewards engage and motivate staff, making it more likely that organizational goals will be achieved.</data>
      <data key="d2">b302d47d456dc3a1adafa01592a31745,e7d75450db353b8413fb68bdd98ac99c</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1926</data>
      <data key="d6">d6f1e619b75d4b978dbedd50c9a3a3cc</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INNOVATION IN SERVICE PACKS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Innovation in service packs refers to the creation and offering of new service packages to customers. MSC has outperformed other service centers by generating a larger portion of its revenue from new service packs, indicating a strong performance in innovation."</data>
      <data key="d2">b302d47d456dc3a1adafa01592a31745</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1927</data>
      <data key="d6">ea69097de9324d1f8c9b3b701bb99ab0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ROBINHOLT UNIVERSITY'S STRATEGIC AIMS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Robinholt University has five strategic aims: providing high-quality education, an efficient learning environment, leadership in sustainable practices, attractive conference facilities, and national and international recognition for research."</data>
      <data key="d2">b302d47d456dc3a1adafa01592a31745</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1928</data>
      <data key="d6">802e4dc8beaf4f378d82cf7c00bbc654</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ROBINHOLT UNIVERSITY'S INCOME STATEMENT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The income statement for Robinholt University for the years 20X6 and 20X5 includes tuition fees, research grants, conference income, and various expenditures such as staff costs and facilities."</data>
      <data key="d2">b302d47d456dc3a1adafa01592a31745</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1929</data>
      <data key="d6">58aa65ee9222436b85f1a1ec18f3de31</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STUDENT SATISFACTION SURVEY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The National Organisation for Students conducts an annual survey where final-year students rate their satisfaction with various aspects of their course, including teaching quality, academic support, organization, learning resources, and personal development."</data>
      <data key="d2">b302d47d456dc3a1adafa01592a31745</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1930</data>
      <data key="d6">8e0b0422f02a46e7b5ff44d2fff72a5f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STAFF RETENTION RATE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The staff retention rate indicates the percentage of staff members who remain employed at the university over a given period. A high retention rate suggests stability and satisfaction among staff, while a low rate may indicate issues such as dissatisfaction or better opportunities elsewhere."</data>
      <data key="d2">5b4478b6f85065f23259c933dd9f0ab2</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1931</data>
      <data key="d6">a4b839eb98f048f28c8f7bb09ac07423</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GREEN ENVIRONMENTAL AWARD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"In 20X5, Robinholt University won the Green Environmental award for their campuses, which all have extensive recycling facilities."</data>
      <data key="d2">5b4478b6f85065f23259c933dd9f0ab2</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1932</data>
      <data key="d6">53c6a4f85e5f42c8b33298f94e7c7907</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GROW-TO-GIVE FOOD SHARING PROJECT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"In 20X5, students at Robinholt University were involved in a local 'Grow-to-Give' food sharing project that provided thousands of pounds worth of fresh produce to food banks offering food to poorer residents."</data>
      <data key="d2">5b4478b6f85065f23259c933dd9f0ab2</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1933</data>
      <data key="d6">8d5a44e256b04421b169b942bc1cf787</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INNOVATION AWARD&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"In 20X5, Robinholt University won an Innovation award for its new innovative conference facilities which have attracted a number of new clients in the last year."</data>
      <data key="d2">5b4478b6f85065f23259c933dd9f0ab2</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1934</data>
      <data key="d6">dc1bb549036045d1b46c02e05deeeb40</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STRATEGIC AIMS OF ROBINHOLT UNIVERSITY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Robinholt University's five strategic aims include providing education that promotes intellectual initiative, creating an organized and efficient learning environment, and ensuring high academic standards to prepare graduates for success in life and the workplace."</data>
      <data key="d2">5b4478b6f85065f23259c933dd9f0ab2</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1935</data>
      <data key="d6">70890fae70dc43e59b7f33f364a25171</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PERFORMANCE INDICATORS FOR ROBINHOLT UNIVERSITY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Performance indicators for Robinholt University include student satisfaction percentages, staff retention rates, employer satisfaction with graduates, and the percentage of students obtaining graduate jobs within a year."</data>
      <data key="d2">5b4478b6f85065f23259c933dd9f0ab2</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">1936</data>
      <data key="d6">60e7c322568d45f88e7076d2a62caa04</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INTERNAL BUSINESS PROCESS PERSPECTIVE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This perspective focuses on having an effective and efficient administration. Measures include the number of times a guest request is not received at the resort prior to arrival and the average number of corrections to booking due to administrative errors."</data>
      <data key="d2">5a3ea6b3010def70205c6c8c68b8cfc4</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1937</data>
      <data key="d6">b7392c87755f4a45b86142f12502e9fc</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INNOVATION AND LEARNING PERSPECTIVE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This perspective aims to match leading competitor's facilities. Measures include the number of in-room appliances offered by rivals but not by Hammocks Co and the number of new items offered on the menu each month."</data>
      <data key="d2">5a3ea6b3010def70205c6c8c68b8cfc4</data>
      <data key="d7">4</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1938</data>
      <data key="d6">e69274b7c1c04989a8ba478ed51c3647</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CHALLENGES IN EVALUATING SCHOOL PERFORMANCE IN DUCLAND&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"All schools in Ducland are state-funded and accountable to the Department of Education (DoE). The DoE's objectives include continuous improvement in performance standards, providing a supportive learning environment, preparing pupils for adult life, and ensuring access to high-quality education for all children. Performance data for each school is accessible via the DoE's website, and inspectors visit each school to monitor performance."</data>
      <data key="d2">5a3ea6b3010def70205c6c8c68b8cfc4</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1939</data>
      <data key="d6">da6c34b4130e46f2aec17b2ad8a02a6d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DEPARTMENT OF EDUCATION (DOE)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Department of Education in Ducland oversees educational standards and monitors the performance of all state-funded schools. Its objectives include continuous improvement in performance standards, providing a supportive learning environment, preparing pupils for adult life, and ensuring access to high-quality education for all children."</data>
      <data key="d2">5a3ea6b3010def70205c6c8c68b8cfc4</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1940</data>
      <data key="d6">ff020126e2d6442daab7710101ddd370</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PUPIL PROGRESS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Pupil progress is an indicator of how well pupils have performed in compulsory subjects in their final exams at age 16 compared to their performance in intermediate exams at age 11. Academic grades are given numerical values, and the pupil progress score is the movement in the average of pupils' grades. Scores typically range between -0.5 and +0.5."</data>
      <data key="d2">1e37a7be9b892b604c2e7b6cf6a2c49f</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1941</data>
      <data key="d6">c7a22a40a42c4b2f8f3986418a13cb51</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INSPECTION GRADE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"INSPECTION GRADE"

The school's inspection grade is higher than it was five years ago and is above the national target, suggesting that the school is improving and performing relatively well. There are six inspection grades: excellent, very good, good, average, poor, and very poor.</data>
      <data key="d2">1e37a7be9b892b604c2e7b6cf6a2c49f,f63f63312db6b8a5607cefd34d4c8d89</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1942</data>
      <data key="d6">d9fb3e6c98424dcf88a740ad59c75357</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PUPIL/TEACHER RATIO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The DoE recommends that the pupil/teacher ratio should be less than 22:1."</data>
      <data key="d2">1e37a7be9b892b604c2e7b6cf6a2c49f</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1943</data>
      <data key="d6">0d9ebe3e0b524f15ba79552322b14029</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TONFORD SCHOOL'S PERFORMANCE DATA&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Tonford School's performance data includes exam results, pupil progress, inspection grade, pupil numbers, and number of teaching staff. The data is compared against national targets and previous performance."</data>
      <data key="d2">1e37a7be9b892b604c2e7b6cf6a2c49f</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1944</data>
      <data key="d6">33c93e67a09c41c183d87702ec83b2c4</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DOE'S OBJECTIVES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The DoE's objectives include: 1. Strive for continuous improvement in performance standards. 2. Ensure pupils are prepared for adult life and have the skills and character necessary to contribute to society and the economy. 3. Provide all children with access to high quality education, regardless of their location or background. 4. Summary performance data for each school is accessible via the DoE's website."</data>
      <data key="d2">1e37a7be9b892b604c2e7b6cf6a2c49f</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1945</data>
      <data key="d6">bb0fe1ea421d41c58fa48285da4149f8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PUPIL PROGRESS SCORE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The pupil progress score suggests the school is providing children with a high-quality education and a learning environment which encourages a high standard of pupil achievement."</data>
      <data key="d2">f63f63312db6b8a5607cefd34d4c8d89</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1946</data>
      <data key="d6">b596464c77764115bbc2e898bb427eed</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TEACHER/PUPIL RATIO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Tonford School's teacher/pupil ratio has remained essentially the same over the last five years, at 19 pupils per teacher, which is favorable compared to the national target of 22 pupils per teacher."</data>
      <data key="d2">f63f63312db6b8a5607cefd34d4c8d89</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1947</data>
      <data key="d6">911fb51b4dea4ab69791038c407ba168</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OBJECTIVE 2: PROVIDE A SUPPORTIVE LEARNING ENVIRONMENT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Objective 2 aims to provide a supportive learning environment that encourages a high standard of pupil achievement. The pupil progress score and inspection grade suggest the school is meeting this objective."</data>
      <data key="d2">f63f63312db6b8a5607cefd34d4c8d89</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1948</data>
      <data key="d6">b263fe88607d4fd7a2f6c1a0a64a2082</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OBJECTIVE 3: ENSURE PUPILS ARE PREPARED FOR ADULT LIFE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Objective 3 aims to ensure pupils are prepared for adult life and have the skills and character necessary to contribute to society and the economy. The inspector highlighted the school's strong sense of community values and citizenship."</data>
      <data key="d2">f63f63312db6b8a5607cefd34d4c8d89</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1949</data>
      <data key="d6">33326db2b31a47d89b4a56eb309eda87</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OBJECTIVE 4: PROVIDE ALL CHILDREN WITH ACCESS TO HIGH QUALITY EDUCATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Objective 4 aims to provide all children with access to high-quality education, regardless of their location or background. The inspector's report highlighted the school's diverse backgrounds and improved grading over the last five years."</data>
      <data key="d2">f63f63312db6b8a5607cefd34d4c8d89</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1950</data>
      <data key="d6">6119401d1da642bba8a57cd73b950dfe</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DIFFICULTIES IN ASSESSING PERFORMANCE DUE TO THE QUALITATIVE NATURE OF OBJECTIVES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Assessing performance against qualitative objectives is challenging due to difficulties in measurement and subjectivity. Quantifiable objectives like exam success rates are easier to measure, but qualitative aspects like the overall quality of education are harder to assess."</data>
      <data key="d2">f63f63312db6b8a5607cefd34d4c8d89</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1951</data>
      <data key="d6">dd5c1864109c40f3bc7051980d97c837</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CASE: EVALUATING PERFORMANCE AND INVESTMENT DECISIONS AT WELCO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Welco is a trading company with two divisions: the Design."</data>
      <data key="d2">f63f63312db6b8a5607cefd34d4c8d89</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1952</data>
      <data key="d6">02847ddc858d4515b975cc3acf01fa78</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TONFORD SCHOOL'S PERFORMANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">f63f63312db6b8a5607cefd34d4c8d89</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1953</data>
      <data key="d6">4211020c8e3748e6a16cab138394b172</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INSPECTOR'S REPORT&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">f63f63312db6b8a5607cefd34d4c8d89</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1954</data>
      <data key="d6">567af1fdee6847dcbaccda00dcb5a0c5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;WELCO&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">f63f63312db6b8a5607cefd34d4c8d89</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1955</data>
      <data key="d6">df03e7a7f0114b6cbdfc5cd5e67268f1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EVALUATING PERFORMANCE AND INVESTMENT DECISIONS AT WELCO&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">bc0524558467e4e3eec1a2e2e05b5d33</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1956</data>
      <data key="d6">bbbe9d67867543348a27f3677fad75c8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NON-FINANCIAL PERFORMANCE MEASURES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Non-financial performance measures are metrics that assess aspects of a business's performance that are not directly related to financial outcomes, such as customer satisfaction, employee engagement, and product quality. These measures can provide a more comprehensive view of a company's performance but may be subject to manipulation."</data>
      <data key="d2">47433af962a352cae0761ce18f9b4b82</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1957</data>
      <data key="d6">282bc7cc13974e51a566f8d1ed5c98ee</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GEARBOX DIVISION CAPITAL EQUIPMENT INVESTMENT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Gearbox division is considering investing in capital equipment costing $2.7m with an expected useful economic life of 50 years and no resale value. The forecast return on the initial investment is 15% per year before depreciation, and the division's cost of capital is 7%. The expected annual residual income of the initial investment is calculated to be $162,000."</data>
      <data key="d2">47433af962a352cae0761ce18f9b4b82</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1958</data>
      <data key="d6">733f2ad4c32c434cb8599e808a9cbdd9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ASSESSING DIVISIONAL PERFORMANCE AND INVESTMENT DECISIONS AT A MANUFACTURING COMPANY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Biscuits division (Division B) and the Cakes division (Division C) of a large manufacturing company are evaluated based on their ROI and residual income. Senior management has decided to recharge head office costs to the divisions, affecting their net profit and ROI calculations. The case involves calculating the expected annualized ROI and residual income for each division, discussing their performance, and considering the impact of a new machinery investment on Division B's ROI and residual income."</data>
      <data key="d2">47433af962a352cae0761ce18f9b4b82</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1959</data>
      <data key="d6">471b73b5f8754d5a98d4d57c65bbeda6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;HEAD OFFICE COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Head office costs refer to the expenses incurred by the central administrative functions of a company. These costs are often recharged to individual divisions or departments to reflect their share of the overall administrative burden."</data>
      <data key="d2">47433af962a352cae0761ce18f9b4b82</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1960</data>
      <data key="d6">7693177793d34cffb43f158154f63c6f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COST OF CAPITAL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Cost of capital" is the rate of return required by a company to justify an investment. It represents the opportunity cost of using capital resources for a specific purpose. Additionally, it serves as the rate of return required to make a capital investment project worthwhile and is often used as a benchmark for evaluating investment decisions.</data>
      <data key="d2">312c3cf9edbc058c6e810c1e9c9cd81a,47433af962a352cae0761ce18f9b4b82</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1961</data>
      <data key="d6">22ee92e6ace3450ba29667b1f6bd5883</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PERFORMANCE OF DIVISIONS B AND C&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The performance of Divisions B and C is evaluated using ROI and residual income. Both divisions have improved their performance when uncontrollable head office costs are excluded from the ROI calculation."</data>
      <data key="d2">b6f6408539084298539b791170ec9250</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1962</data>
      <data key="d6">43f5a008807945a2becc44df4909478e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DIVISION B ROI WITH INVESTMENT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"ROI with investment for Division B = (Annualised Net Profit / Operating Net Assets after investment) * 100. This formula is used to assess the impact of new investments on the division's profitability."</data>
      <data key="d2">b6f6408539084298539b791170ec9250</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1963</data>
      <data key="d6">7de698bb82e74b149ab4e13c7ce45836</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DIVISION B RI WITH INVESTMENT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"RI with investment for Division B = Net Profit with investment - Imputed Interest. This formula helps determine whether the investment increases the residual income, aligning with the goal of maximizing shareholder wealth."</data>
      <data key="d2">b6f6408539084298539b791170ec9250</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1964</data>
      <data key="d6">572252c70e734ec19d6518f4cc97dd52</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BEHAVIOURAL PROBLEMS DUE TO ROI TARGETS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The inclusion of uncontrollable head office costs in ROI calculations can demotivate staff, leading to frustration, reduced productivity, and potential opposition to the new system. Revising ROI targets is necessary to maintain staff motivation and performance."</data>
      <data key="d2">b6f6408539084298539b791170ec9250</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1965</data>
      <data key="d6">cb427af4c5dc406aa53332c441f06bcb</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EVALUATING DIVISIONAL PERFORMANCE AND INVESTMENT DECISIONS AT CARDALE INDUSTRIAL METAL CO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Cardale Industrial Metal Co (CIM Co) evaluates the performance of its divisions, Division F and Division N, using ROI and residual income. Each division operates as an investment center with full control over its assets and liabilities. The case highlights the importance of fair performance metrics and the impact of uncontrollable costs on staff motivation."</data>
      <data key="d2">b6f6408539084298539b791170ec9250</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1966</data>
      <data key="d6">cc08fc303cdc4177ad77e6e7d3d15cfd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NON-CURRENT ASSETS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Non-current assets are long-term investments or assets that are not expected to be converted into cash within a year, such as property, plant, and equipment."</data>
      <data key="d2">312c3cf9edbc058c6e810c1e9c9cd81a</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1967</data>
      <data key="d6">318a9d64ba7c4d7a97934947b423a0fb</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INVENTORY AND TRADE RECEIVABLES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Inventory and trade receivables represent the value of goods available for sale and the amounts owed to the company by customers for goods or services delivered."</data>
      <data key="d2">312c3cf9edbc058c6e810c1e9c9cd81a</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1968</data>
      <data key="d6">b5037ba29ea143a88adb2d45fabe3bd0</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TRADE PAYABLES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Trade payables are amounts a company owes to suppliers for items or services purchased on credit."</data>
      <data key="d2">312c3cf9edbc058c6e810c1e9c9cd81a</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1969</data>
      <data key="d6">026660a4f8db4165a94c630ce2014d12</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PERFORMANCE-RELATED BONUS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A performance-related bonus is an additional compensation paid to managers based on the achievement of specific performance metrics, such as ROI."</data>
      <data key="d2">312c3cf9edbc058c6e810c1e9c9cd81a</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1970</data>
      <data key="d6">34bceac6fb00492591f999b46c4e3335</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INVESTMENT DECISION BASED ON RESIDUAL INCOME&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Investment decisions based on residual income consider whether the residual income generated by a project exceeds the cost of capital, guiding whether to proceed with the investment."</data>
      <data key="d2">312c3cf9edbc058c6e810c1e9c9cd81a</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1971</data>
      <data key="d6">a089c5933f2441e4bc0b1ec8770c4f5f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INVESTMENT DECISION FOR DIVISION A&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Division A would choose to invest in the respective projects based on the residual income calculation, which shows a positive residual income of $1.06m."</data>
      <data key="d2">adc4ed8e6245dc6b569294fed0446801</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1972</data>
      <data key="d6">41b0067895a148bc8cf3837f73b8e35e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RESIDUAL INCOME CALCULATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Residual income is calculated as Profit - Imputed interest charge. For Division A: $14.4m * 30% - $32.6m * 10% = $1.06m. For Division B: $8.8m * 24% - $22.2m * 10% = $(0.108)m."</data>
      <data key="d2">adc4ed8e6245dc6b569294fed0446801</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1973</data>
      <data key="d6">52302f152728451ca77f95dec6f63f91</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PERFORMANCE MEASURES FOR PROFIT CENTRE MANAGERS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"QUIZZES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"This quiz question involves identifying appropriate measures for assessing the performance of profit centre managers. The correct measures are % of products returned for warranty repairs each year and sales price and volume variances."</data>
      <data key="d2">adc4ed8e6245dc6b569294fed0446801</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1974</data>
      <data key="d6">ac7f2e662e70464da560d94ac5a5ebe1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PERFORMANCE MEASUREMENT AND INVESTMENT DECISIONS AT SPORTS CO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sports Co is a large manufacturing company with two divisions: Clothing (Division C) and Equipment (Division E). The company uses return on investment (ROI) to measure divisional performance but is considering introducing residual income (RI) to discourage dysfunctional behavior. The case includes calculations and discussions on ROI and RI for both divisions."</data>
      <data key="d2">adc4ed8e6245dc6b569294fed0446801</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1975</data>
      <data key="d6">44d02c1ff86f40e8819b8ad5f57d61d9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RETURN ON INVESTMENT (ROI) CALCULATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"ROI is calculated as Controllable profit / Average divisional net assets. For Division C: (Net profit + Depreciation on non-controllable assets + Head Office costs) / (Opening net assets + Closing net assets) / 2. For Division E: (Net profit + Depreciation on non-controllable assets + Head Office costs) / (Opening net assets + Closing net assets) / 2."</data>
      <data key="d2">adc4ed8e6245dc6b569294fed0446801</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1976</data>
      <data key="d6">cc66c92d4b1541e5a2952950f97dbade</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RESIDUAL INCOME (RI) CALCULATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"RI is calculated as Controllable profit - (Average divisional net assets * Cost of capital). For Division C: Controllable profit - (Average divisional net assets * 12%). For Division E: Controllable profit - (Average divisional net assets * 12%)."</data>
      <data key="d2">adc4ed8e6245dc6b569294fed0446801</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1977</data>
      <data key="d6">9e81bc2228ff4984b230e9571c39ba2a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DIVISION B&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Division B is a part of Bath Co that manufactures and sells fittings both internally to Division A and externally. It does not save costs by supplying internally. Additionally, Division B is the battery division of Portable Garage Co, producing portable battery chargers that can also charge mobile devices and laptops.</data>
      <data key="d2">078e47b3223db97709a37da2a01302c5,34f2c5c9d893c1b631ed1646193eebf4</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">9</data>
      <data key="d5">1978</data>
      <data key="d6">48b2311395554b4384ea59b806ba3eed</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PROFIT STATEMENT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A profit statement is a financial document that shows the revenue, costs, and profit for each division and the company as a whole. It includes external sales, inter-divisional transfers, variable costs, and fixed costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">078e47b3223db97709a37da2a01302c5</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1979</data>
      <data key="d6">75777fa86f1a4320a5fa1cd4e25a040e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPTIMIZED TRANSFER PRICING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Optimized transfer pricing refers to setting transfer prices in a way that maximizes the overall profit of the company while considering the autonomy and motivation of divisional managers."</data>
      <data key="d2">078e47b3223db97709a37da2a01302c5</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1980</data>
      <data key="d6">a27cb6c3891b48ed9c3aa18b24186ae9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ENCOURAGING DIVISIONAL MANAGERS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Encouraging divisional managers involves creating policies and incentives that align the decisions of divisional managers with the overall interests of the company, especially in the context of transfer pricing."</data>
      <data key="d2">078e47b3223db97709a37da2a01302c5</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1981</data>
      <data key="d6">80f575fd73264110a83a911db7b9e02f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIAL COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Material costs refer to the expenses incurred for the raw materials used in production. In this case, Division A's material costs are calculated as $19,900 and Division B's as $1,000."</data>
      <data key="d2">0cafbc1007afddae5f416e6fb910386a</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1982</data>
      <data key="d6">4bbc24770d6e44cbad52ab2513b96cd8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DIVISIONAL PERFORMANCE METRICS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Divisional performance metrics are used to assess the performance of divisional managers. These metrics can include profit for the period, residual income, or return on capital employed."</data>
      <data key="d2">0cafbc1007afddae5f416e6fb910386a</data>
      <data key="d7">24</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1983</data>
      <data key="d6">42e88e5d61bf452691d65457a059b73d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NEGOTIATED TRANSFER PRICES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Negotiated transfer prices are prices agreed upon by the buying and selling divisions within a company. This method ensures that both divisions are satisfied with the transaction, promoting overall company profitability."</data>
      <data key="d2">0cafbc1007afddae5f416e6fb910386a</data>
      <data key="d7">24</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1984</data>
      <data key="d6">35f5e57ccff5460a90ab286ef0182c6e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPTIMIZING TRANSFER PRICING FOR MOBE CO'S ELECTRONIC MOTORS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Mobe Co manufactures electronic mobility scooters and is split into two divisions: the scooter division (Division S) and the motor division (Division M). Division M supplies electronic motors to both Division S and external customers. The case discusses the optimal transfer pricing strategy to maximize overall company profit while maintaining divisional autonomy."</data>
      <data key="d2">0cafbc1007afddae5f416e6fb910386a</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1985</data>
      <data key="d6">a53ab7f8a4bf44e586ded41a6a60498b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DIVISION S&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Division S is the scooter division of Mobe Co, which requires 35,000 electronic motors for the coming year. It has the option to buy these motors either from Division M or from an external supplier at $800 each."</data>
      <data key="d2">0cafbc1007afddae5f416e6fb910386a</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1986</data>
      <data key="d6">4627da3aacd54a4494f16496c90db8f8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DIVISION M&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Division M is the motor division of Mobe Co, with the capacity to produce 60,000 electronic motors per year. It sells motors both to Division S and to external customers, with a selling price of $850 per unit for external sales and variable costs of $770 per unit."</data>
      <data key="d2">0cafbc1007afddae5f416e6fb910386a</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">1987</data>
      <data key="d6">74132aaff6a44423a997f56a5c5964ac</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXTERNAL SALES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"External sales" refer to transactions with customers outside the company. Specifically, for Division M of Mobe Co., external sales are made to customers outside of Mobe Co. The selling price per unit for these sales is $850, with variable costs of $770 per unit. Additionally, Division A engages in external sales by selling adaptors to other companies, while also selling internally to Division B.</data>
      <data key="d2">0cafbc1007afddae5f416e6fb910386a,34f2c5c9d893c1b631ed1646193eebf4</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1988</data>
      <data key="d6">63a5c40131e340efa6240fe9ae6c4b65</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SPARE CAPACITY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Spare capacity" refers to the unused production capacity that can be utilized without incurring additional fixed costs. Division M has spare capacity to produce 28,000 motors. This spare capacity is the unused production capacity of Division M, which is 25,000 units per year after meeting the maximum external demand of 35,000 units.</data>
      <data key="d2">0cafbc1007afddae5f416e6fb910386a,34f2c5c9d893c1b631ed1646193eebf4</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">1989</data>
      <data key="d6">600d932263974c14bb04769a0a46463c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INCREMENTAL COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Incremental cost is the additional cost incurred when producing one more unit. For Division S, the incremental cost of buying from outside the group is $60 per unit."</data>
      <data key="d2">34f2c5c9d893c1b631ed1646193eebf4</data>
      <data key="d7">6</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1990</data>
      <data key="d6">e3d482e8b39e43fea19728dd1e22a878</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GROUP PROFITS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Group profits refer to the total profits of the entire organization, considering both internal and external sales."</data>
      <data key="d2">34f2c5c9d893c1b631ed1646193eebf4</data>
      <data key="d7">6</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1991</data>
      <data key="d6">49c04c581feb424e98da0b5e2e93db26</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ETHICAL TRANSFER PRICING SYSTEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"An ethical transfer pricing system ensures decisions are in the best interest of the organization, gives divisional managers autonomy, and allows fair measurement of divisional performance."</data>
      <data key="d2">34f2c5c9d893c1b631ed1646193eebf4</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1992</data>
      <data key="d6">b6a86944bda14b5cb575b5a37aa38a3c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPTIMIZING ADAPTOR SUPPLY FOR PORTABLE GARAGE CO (PGC)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Portable Garage Co (PGC) has two divisions: Division B (battery division) and Division A (adaptor division). Division B uses adaptors from Division A for its upgraded portable batteries, which can charge mobile devices and laptops. Division A also sells adaptors externally. The case involves optimizing the supply and pricing of adaptors between the divisions to maximize group profits."</data>
      <data key="d2">34f2c5c9d893c1b631ed1646193eebf4</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">1993</data>
      <data key="d6">283dd6d57a444f648a40aa998fd1709f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PORTABLE BATTERY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"A portable battery is a product sold by Division B that can start a car's engine and charge mobile devices and laptops."</data>
      <data key="d2">34f2c5c9d893c1b631ed1646193eebf4</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1994</data>
      <data key="d6">d60b39889adc4be9ac6d1107a41f8a81</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ADAPTOR&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"An adaptor is a product sold by Division A, used to charge mobile devices and laptops by attaching them to a car's internal power source."</data>
      <data key="d2">34f2c5c9d893c1b631ed1646193eebf4</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1995</data>
      <data key="d6">12449a1dacf04c23b388dc5edb12b33c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INTERNAL SALES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Internal sales refer to transactions between divisions within the same company. Division B buys adaptors from Division A."</data>
      <data key="d2">34f2c5c9d893c1b631ed1646193eebf4</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">1996</data>
      <data key="d6">0a20ff2849de4679b892a98385f03f1e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MAXIMUM ANNUAL MARKET DEMAND&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Maximum annual market demand is the highest number of units that can be sold in a year. Division B's maximum annual market demand for portable batteries is 180,000 units."</data>
      <data key="d2">34f2c5c9d893c1b631ed1646193eebf4</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1997</data>
      <data key="d6">222220ba01c14a9684f2d7ec20fbf57b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CURRENT ANNUAL PRODUCTION CAPACITY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Current annual production capacity is the maximum number of units that can be produced in a year. Division A's current annual production capacity for adaptors is 350,000 units."</data>
      <data key="d2">34f2c5c9d893c1b631ed1646193eebf4</data>
      <data key="d7">15</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">1998</data>
      <data key="d6">aa51d362c5aa417e9b629446ca2bf1d4</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MAXIMUM ANNUAL EXTERNAL DEMAND&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Maximum annual external demand is the highest number of units that can be sold to external customers in a year. Division A's maximum annual external demand for adaptors is not specified."</data>
      <data key="d2">34f2c5c9d893c1b631ed1646193eebf4</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">1999</data>
      <data key="d6">dfe1ca77c8be47ed9215a3aa125f220f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIALS COST PER ADAPTOR&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The cost of materials per adaptor is $3."</data>
      <data key="d2">dbd7075a4d389f8431dc97dd0557c95d</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2000</data>
      <data key="d6">ea19191a49ca4d52b13f28d5aa52a421</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LABOUR COST PER ADAPTOR&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The labour cost per adaptor is $4."</data>
      <data key="d2">dbd7075a4d389f8431dc97dd0557c95d</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2001</data>
      <data key="d6">50afa3abd00a41aeb41b16de722d60a2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ANNUAL FIXED OVERHEADS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The annual fixed overheads for the production of adaptors are $2,200,000."</data>
      <data key="d2">dbd7075a4d389f8431dc97dd0557c95d</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2002</data>
      <data key="d6">99e168a09fe24b6987ee4e898f182c33</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CURRENT ANNUAL PRODUCTION CAPACITY AND SALES OF ADAPTORS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The current annual production capacity and sales of adaptors, including both internal and external sales, is 350,000 units."</data>
      <data key="d2">dbd7075a4d389f8431dc97dd0557c95d</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2003</data>
      <data key="d6">cfc64ac6e5834d28bde61298b4a8f712</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MAXIMUM ANNUAL EXTERNAL DEMAND FOR ADAPTORS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The maximum annual external demand for adaptors is 200,000 units."</data>
      <data key="d2">dbd7075a4d389f8431dc97dd0557c95d</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2004</data>
      <data key="d6">76f30bc7758a4cb9ac3296762e0900a9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VARIABLE COST PER ADAPTOR FOR EXTERNAL SALES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"In addition to the materials and labour costs, Division A incurs a variable cost of $1 per adaptor for all adaptors it sells externally."</data>
      <data key="d2">dbd7075a4d389f8431dc97dd0557c95d</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2005</data>
      <data key="d6">ac27bd83e8c14c7697ab31863bc89aa9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CURRENT TRANSFER PRICING SYSTEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The current transfer pricing system only allows Division B to purchase adaptors from Division A, but Division A has refused to sell more than the current level of adaptors it supplies to Division B."</data>
      <data key="d2">dbd7075a4d389f8431dc97dd0557c95d</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2006</data>
      <data key="d6">df6dacf780cc45e088ecb84c39401e80</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NEW GROUP PURCHASING POLICY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The new group purchasing policy allows Division B to buy adaptors externally, provided that it optimizes the profits of the group as a whole."</data>
      <data key="d2">dbd7075a4d389f8431dc97dd0557c95d</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">2007</data>
      <data key="d6">a9e9ad953ea74dbd9a59cd49bc8fcffc</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PROFIT STATEMENT FOR CURRENT POSITION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"EXAMPLES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The profit statement for the current position shows the profit for each division and for The Portable Garage Co (PGC) as a whole, with sales and costs figures split into external sales and inter-divisional transfers."</data>
      <data key="d2">dbd7075a4d389f8431dc97dd0557c95d</data>
      <data key="d4">6</data>
      <data key="d5">2008</data>
      <data key="d6">e9ac664970914b85bea6b75efbebc545</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MINIMUM TRANSFER PRICE PER UNIT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The minimum transfer price per unit for any additional adaptors supplied above the current level by Division A to Division B is calculated to ensure Division B can meet its maximum annual demand for the new portable batteries."</data>
      <data key="d2">dbd7075a4d389f8431dc97dd0557c95d</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2009</data>
      <data key="d6">3130824eb1854f37b0bab21b7324fb46</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PHYSICAL CONTROLS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Physical controls should exist to stop unauthorized access to the personal computers that are linked into the servers. Offices should be locked, using keypads or swipe cards, so personnel can only enter the offices where they actually work. This would mean that nurses would not be able to enter the accounts office, for example, unless accompanied by a member of the accounts staff."</data>
      <data key="d2">dadf38de734316ede827c46363bb8d38</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2010</data>
      <data key="d6">4805040f8dc04f07b44ab9e2b2cc37ce</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PERSONNEL CONTROLS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Personnel controls aim to stop employees from deliberately or accidentally compromising security. These may include recruitment of honest individuals, training emphasizing the importance of security, regulations relating to security (such as not allowing staff to share passwords) that are enforced strictly, supervision, and system logs that automatically monitor what employees do while online. These logs may produce exception reports to alert management to unusual activities or repeated attempts to log on with different passwords."</data>
      <data key="d2">dadf38de734316ede827c46363bb8d38</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2011</data>
      <data key="d6">f64701c341ed46d49860b53552107f3e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FIREWALLS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Firewalls are designed to prevent unauthorized access to the system from outside the organization, especially when the system is connected to the Internet or an intranet."</data>
      <data key="d2">dadf38de734316ede827c46363bb8d38</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2012</data>
      <data key="d6">1f5beb046c54479fb011ef73d62e2f3c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ANTI-VIRUS SOFTWARE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Anti-virus software protects the system from viruses (or malware), which are malicious programs that aim to harm the system or gain access to confidential information. Viruses can be imported into the system by e-mail or by connecting an infected flash drive or other storage device to the system. A particular risk to security is spyware, which watches what users of the system do and then sends the information to a third party (e.g., key logging programs which can be used to discover passwords)."</data>
      <data key="d2">dadf38de734316ede827c46363bb8d38</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2013</data>
      <data key="d6">343a594ef34e4b34a634dad089b71bfb</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REPORTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Reports should be relevant to the personnel receiving them to avoid information overload. Procedures should be put in place to ensure that reports are only sent to personnel to whom they are relevant. All reports should contain distribution lists, and the people on the distribution list should be asked regularly whether the report is still relevant. Standards should exist for all reports to ensure consistency, such as standard fonts, inclusion of the name of the person who prepared them, page numbers, standard report headers, the date of preparation, and the date of the information on the report. There should also be clear standard definitions of measures used in reports."</data>
      <data key="d2">dadf38de734316ede827c46363bb8d38</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2014</data>
      <data key="d6">acfef991c86244b3b7524d59cb8d4c77</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;IMPROVING SECURITY AND INTERNAL DISTRIBUTION PROCEDURES AT ST PEREGRINE'S HOSPITAL&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">dadf38de734316ede827c46363bb8d38</data>
      <data key="d4">5</data>
      <data key="d5">2015</data>
      <data key="d6">edb5bb32781540de9ad1f6f9a59a5c4d</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COST BENEFIT ANALYSIS FOR REPORTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"If reports have to be specially programmed, a cost benefit analysis should be carried out before the report is commissioned. This involves ascertaining the cost of preparing the report and evaluating the benefits, even if they are difficult to quantify in financial terms."</data>
      <data key="d2">9f2566c80157a915eedb77a1d6dc9dad</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2016</data>
      <data key="d6">690dfcef383c47debc9e5af3cd3f496c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;E-MAIL COMMUNICATION ISSUES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"E-mail can be a useful tool for communication but can lead to problems such as over-communication, sending trivial messages, and copying unnecessary recipients. It can also result in informal communication being recorded and seen by unintended recipients."</data>
      <data key="d2">9f2566c80157a915eedb77a1d6dc9dad</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2017</data>
      <data key="d6">7f21aad2916445a0bb68078b6a1f9a6b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SECURITY PROCEDURES FOR REPORTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"There should be security procedures in place for the distribution of reports, including marking confidential reports as 'private and confidential', ensuring they are not left out on desks, and having disciplinary procedures for mishandling confidential information."</data>
      <data key="d2">9f2566c80157a915eedb77a1d6dc9dad</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2018</data>
      <data key="d6">9f78a76823c94d54ab0148939fce26ac</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MOFFAT CO'S DECISION TO INVEST IN AN ENTERPRISE RESOURCE PLANNING SYSTEM&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Moffat Co, which supplies and fits tyres and exhaust pipes and services motor vehicles at 30 locations, is considering investing in an enterprise resource planning system (ERPS) to improve decision-making and information flow across the organization."</data>
      <data key="d2">9f2566c80157a915eedb77a1d6dc9dad</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">2019</data>
      <data key="d6">4b84b87422534ddeae6e7a479341cfcf</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;STRATEGIC INFORMATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Strategic information is required by management to take a longer-term view of the business and assess its performance over time. It is holistic and summary in nature and used for activities like SWOT analysis and assessing new service developments or potential acquisitions."</data>
      <data key="d2">9f2566c80157a915eedb77a1d6dc9dad</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">2020</data>
      <data key="d6">4e3462762fda4feba4ee6050627c9a54</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TACTICAL INFORMATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Tactical information facilitates management planning and control for shorter time periods than strategic information. It relates to specific actions to achieve certain goals, such as opening new outlets or employing additional supervisors."</data>
      <data key="d2">9f2566c80157a915eedb77a1d6dc9dad</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">2021</data>
      <data key="d6">982b77e9c3a44e43bd9050c4ceb707bd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OPERATIONAL INFORMATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Operational information relates to short time scales and is used for immediate actions by day-to-day management. It includes data on customer sales, vehicles serviced, and complaints received, and helps determine staffing needs and training requirements."</data>
      <data key="d2">9f2566c80157a915eedb77a1d6dc9dad</data>
      <data key="d7">21</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">2022</data>
      <data key="d6">28f0aa46a7844e8fa03ddb4de8df18f5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DECISION ANALYSIS FOR GYM BUNNIES' EXPANSION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Gym Bunnies (GB) is a health club considering whether to expand its exercise studio to improve membership numbers in response to a competitor opening a new gym. The case involves analyzing two options: no expansion, which would result in a decline in membership, and expansion, which has varying probabilities of affecting membership and operational costs. The decision analysis includes constructing a decision tree, calculating expected values, and discussing the problems of using expected values for such decisions."</data>
      <data key="d2">857af82bcdb30f5b84388c178c088d79</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2023</data>
      <data key="d6">a9c14e5c3ed244a9a5d3584df177969e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VALUE OF PERFECT INFORMATION (VPI)&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"VPI is the difference between the expected value with perfect information and the expected value without perfect information. It represents the maximum price that should be paid for the information."</data>
      <data key="d2">039a2a6ce8c94f49aa8954c72332cea2</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2024</data>
      <data key="d6">7e566c0408b74d40877a38a3bfbee497</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PROBLEMS OF USING EXPECTED VALUES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Expected values provide a long-run average outcome, which may not be useful for one-off decisions. Estimating accurate probabilities is difficult, and the actual outcome may not be close to the expected value. The EV criterion is useful for risk-neutral investors, but the risk attitude of the management is unknown."</data>
      <data key="d2">039a2a6ce8c94f49aa8954c72332cea2</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">2025</data>
      <data key="d6">a132186569574b259d8f6c3630b4b5c8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EVALUATING THE IMPACT OF EXPANDING SERVICES ON OLIVER'S SALON PERFORMANCE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Oliver's Salon expanded its services to include male clients, resulting in increased sales but only a slight increase in profit. The expansion led to higher staff costs and some female clients' dissatisfaction, affecting the overall atmosphere and performance of the salon."</data>
      <data key="d2">039a2a6ce8c94f49aa8954c72332cea2</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2026</data>
      <data key="d6">5703d1b10f344694bce131dbb9cff3cc</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NON-FINANCIAL MEASURES OF SUCCESS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Non-financial measures of success introduced by Oliver include the number of complaints, number of male client visits, number of female client visits, and the number of specialist hairdressers for male and female clients."</data>
      <data key="d2">6d999a904458a382baf0c5f112c1be0f</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2027</data>
      <data key="d6">df8705e0618a4ce89698bdcbaf760a78</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;AVERAGE PRICE PER CLIENT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The average price per client is calculated by dividing the total revenue by the number of visits. For example, in 20X0, female clients paid $200,000 for 8,000 visits, resulting in an average price of $25 per visit."</data>
      <data key="d2">6d999a904458a382baf0c5f112c1be0f</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">2028</data>
      <data key="d6">c2d25d822f2742f684845bc10f2053fa</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FINANCIAL PERFORMANCE ASSESSMENT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The financial performance assessment of Oliver's Salon includes hairdressing sales growth, gross margin, staff costs, advertising spend, rent, administrative expenses, electricity costs, and net profit."</data>
      <data key="d2">6d999a904458a382baf0c5f112c1be0f</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">2029</data>
      <data key="d6">a7f5dcf4ed364feba93d788a572e3695</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;QUALITY PERFORMANCE ASSESSMENT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The quality performance assessment of Oliver's Salon includes the number of complaints and the impact of changes in the salon's atmosphere and staff wages on customer satisfaction."</data>
      <data key="d2">6d999a904458a382baf0c5f112c1be0f</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">2030</data>
      <data key="d6">ad71cd13592144738b072262c694daaf</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OLIVER'S SALON&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">6d999a904458a382baf0c5f112c1be0f</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">2031</data>
      <data key="d6">22dc64e73efe47c1be1be0552c3e935a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GROSS MARGIN&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">Gross margin is the difference between sales revenue and the cost of goods sold, expressed as a percentage of sales revenue. It indicates the efficiency of a company in managing its production costs. For instance, the gross margin overall was calculated as $106,000/$200,000 or 53% in 20X0 and $112,500/$238,500 or 47.2% in 20X1. This metric can also be analyzed between female and male clients.</data>
      <data key="d2">d0b8c2893afd98f99c4f5d857b8a7a02,f41491fbf8c72d2afdc444dec24f9e1e</data>
      <data key="d7">23</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">2032</data>
      <data key="d6">0a983d6c050f4933b957169a9211c4a7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CLIENTS PER SPECIALIST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Number of female clients per specialist is 8,000/4 or 2,000 in 20X0 and 6,800/5 or 1,360 in 20X1. Number of male clients per specialist is 3,425 in 20X1."</data>
      <data key="d2">f41491fbf8c72d2afdc444dec24f9e1e</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2033</data>
      <data key="d6">5fe1812bb7594cf0b12bb33eaba2f29b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PERFORMANCE COMPARISON BETWEEN PUBLIC AND PRIVATE SCHOOLS IN BIGTON&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Education ministry of Homeland wishes to introduce performance measurement into schools as a way of improving efficiency and quality of education. As a pilot exercise, staff from the ministry of education have selected two schools in Bigton, Northtown and St Trinian's, and obtained comparative financial data for the most recent school year."</data>
      <data key="d2">f41491fbf8c72d2afdc444dec24f9e1e</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2034</data>
      <data key="d6">997d443695124a298646b2369ab8b727</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ST TRINIAN'S&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"St Trinian's is a school with 700 pupils, an average class size of 15, and total costs of $3,343,000. The costs include teaching, back office, buildings maintenance, internet and computers for students, and energy."</data>
      <data key="d2">40c0903c50afcc65cc0b38a3e29447bc</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">2035</data>
      <data key="d6">d710bc3008f04dbea4d630c8b11871cf</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CHARACTERISTICS OF PUBLIC SECTOR ORGANISATIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Public sector organisations often have a broader group of stakeholders, customers do not pay for the services they receive, they are often monopoly providers, and it is difficult to measure their output. These characteristics differentiate them from commercial organisations."</data>
      <data key="d2">40c0903c50afcc65cc0b38a3e29447bc</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">2036</data>
      <data key="d6">8683ac2cb3244f1e8398350c3058c46e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EVALUATION OF NORTHTOWN VS ST TRINIAN'S&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The evaluation compares the performance of Northtown and St Trinian's using benchmark data. It calculates the cost per pupil for each category and highlights that St Trinian's has higher teaching costs due to smaller class sizes and potentially higher salaries, while Northtown has higher back office costs, suggesting inefficiency."</data>
      <data key="d2">40c0903c50afcc65cc0b38a3e29447bc</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">2037</data>
      <data key="d6">24d7ae2b34524df1a60a95cbed1abf59</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NORTHTOWN&quot;">
      <data key="d0" />
      <data key="d1" />
      <data key="d2">40c0903c50afcc65cc0b38a3e29447bc</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">2038</data>
      <data key="d6">36d06ab4230c41319df4c66ee67b4f97</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BAR SALES REPORT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The bar sales report compares total billing without distinguishing between residents and non-residents due to the high number of cash transactions."</data>
      <data key="d2">7ec0c404cb341da6ab1e2341852f4c97</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">2039</data>
      <data key="d6">494fe8ba041349908bef07b28c16ee97</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RESTAURANT AND BAR INVENTORY REPORT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The restaurant and bar inventory report involves physical control over inventory, with head office officials attending physical counts and using these as benchmarks for subsequent movements. The report highlights significant percentage variations from preceding months to indicate pilferage and misappropriation."</data>
      <data key="d2">7ec0c404cb341da6ab1e2341852f4c97</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">2040</data>
      <data key="d6">fcf38d5f0ce644139b138e0c1b6cb15b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;CASH AVAILABILITY REPORT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The cash availability report summarizes cash takings and receipts from bar and restaurant operations, comparing them across hotels while accounting for differences in resident types."</data>
      <data key="d2">7ec0c404cb341da6ab1e2341852f4c97</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">2041</data>
      <data key="d6">937bd81e59ed4051a32058f364621769</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;WAGES REPORT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The wages report details the number of waged staff per week and their wages, comparing this to revenue reports to identify inefficiencies or potential fraud."</data>
      <data key="d2">7ec0c404cb341da6ab1e2341852f4c97</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">2042</data>
      <data key="d6">60d0320fae7142d0bd94b258b49863b9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ERROR/EXCEPTION REPORTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FEATURES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Error/exception reports are automatically generated by computer systems to highlight significant deviations such as hotel revenue falling below budget, cash reserves exceeding limits, or rooms being given below approved rates."</data>
      <data key="d2">7ec0c404cb341da6ab1e2341852f4c97</data>
      <data key="d4">4</data>
      <data key="d5">2043</data>
      <data key="d6">2edf3e83c1c64da393d5206ce5b352a3</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COST ANALYSIS OF PRODUCTS A, B, AND C: TRADITIONAL VS. ACTIVITY-BASED COSTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Gadget Co produces three products (A, B, and C) and is considering switching from traditional absorption costing to activity-based costing to improve profitability. The case involves calculating the full cost per unit for each product under both costing methods and analyzing how activity-based costing can enhance profitability."</data>
      <data key="d2">7ec0c404cb341da6ab1e2341852f4c97</data>
      <data key="d7">0</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">2044</data>
      <data key="d6">58eda2766aa04ebfac14c4443bb14d4c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ACTIVITY BASED COSTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Activity based costing (ABC) is a costing method that assigns overhead and indirect costs to related products and services by identifying cost drivers."</data>
      <data key="d2">bc96081078db9cb11a132fcb669135c0</data>
      <data key="d7">1</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">2045</data>
      <data key="d6">8f3c848ea47e4563886f53fd67acfc4f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;COST POOLS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Cost pools are groups of individual costs, typically by department or service center, from which cost allocations are made later."</data>
      <data key="d2">bc96081078db9cb11a132fcb669135c0</data>
      <data key="d7">1</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2046</data>
      <data key="d6">29ab334c5a9543fabccf9284ba474a3b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MAXIMIZING NET PROFIT AND THROUGHPUT ACCOUNTING ANALYSIS FOR PRODUCTS A AND B&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Flopro makes and sells two products, A and B, each passing through the same automated production operations. The case involves analyzing the profitability and throughput accounting for these products."</data>
      <data key="d2">bc96081078db9cb11a132fcb669135c0</data>
      <data key="d7">12</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">2047</data>
      <data key="d6">22135e6db1d34a129f2c84f6a0eb251e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FLOPRO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Flopro makes and sells two products, A and B, each of which passes through the same automated production operations. The company faces a bottleneck in one of the production operations, limiting the overall production/sales of products A and B. The case involves calculating the mix of products A and B that will maximize net profit and the value of the maximum net profit using throughput accounting principles."</data>
      <data key="d2">727bae9b2b77a13f165dd415aa129b20</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2048</data>
      <data key="d6">9a2b30dd43214ae5934e6f8330f06734</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;THROUGHPUT RETURN PER PRODUCTION HOUR&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Throughput return per production hour = (selling price - material cost) / bottleneck hours per unit"</data>
      <data key="d2">727bae9b2b77a13f165dd415aa129b20</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2049</data>
      <data key="d6">bd865fbe0c5a44f69b44ffdb97283c3c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;THROUGHPUT RETURN&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Throughput return is the revenue generated from a product minus the direct material costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">39e1257b70d1902a0d6b2502ce5b27b5</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2050</data>
      <data key="d6">f2f6da3b743e46348abe2ee7235d2595</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BOTTLENECK HOURS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Bottleneck hours refer to the limited hours available for production due to constraints in the production process."</data>
      <data key="d2">39e1257b70d1902a0d6b2502ce5b27b5</data>
      <data key="d7">12</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2051</data>
      <data key="d6">9e7e9a723c8240268a9d523e29d7c6ab</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;IMPORTANCE AND IMPLEMENTATION OF ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT ACCOUNTING AT LITTLE CHEMICAL CO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The Little Chemical Co (LCC) faced significant fines and loss of customers due to excessive chemical emissions, prompting a need for better environmental management. The company&#8217;s management has recognized the importance of environmental management accounting (EMA) to address and manage environmental costs and impacts effectively. EMA provides both physical and monetary information, utilizing techniques like activity-based costing (ABC) to improve environmental performance and decision-making."</data>
      <data key="d2">39e1257b70d1902a0d6b2502ce5b27b5</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">2052</data>
      <data key="d6">9a3fca1dae06405cac1347598e839773</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PROFIT ANALYSIS AND COST CALCULATION FOR PRODUCT D&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Scovet Co has identified a market for a new product D and provided estimated sales revenue, contribution percentage, fixed costs, and capital investment. The case involves calculating the total profit over the product's life and the cost per unit, including absorption of all product-specific costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">1198b5b37a51d0315db68af2bdb139bd</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2053</data>
      <data key="d6">050dbae05905411781cb6564b8c7737a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ANALYSIS OF LIFECYCLE COSTS AND STRATEGIC DECISIONS FOR A NEW FITNESS MONITOR&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Fit Co is considering the development of a new fitness monitor with a commercial life of two years. The case includes cost estimates for research, design, marketing, and manufacturing, and involves strategic decisions based on lifecycle costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">1198b5b37a51d0315db68af2bdb139bd</data>
      <data key="d7">16</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2054</data>
      <data key="d6">e6777aff5a8d437e8b5288aec49ba5ec</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PRODUCT DESIGN COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Product design costs are the expenses incurred during the design phase of a new product."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4cbc64c9c49dd951f9997a26ee9d9f9</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2055</data>
      <data key="d6">eed5f201acf54266a66a11ca8e0785ea</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;VARIABLE LABOUR PRODUCTION COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Variable labour production costs are the expenses related to the labour required to produce each unit of a product."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4cbc64c9c49dd951f9997a26ee9d9f9</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">2056</data>
      <data key="d6">263ca07305d34d9b90caddbf847102ab</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;OTHER VARIABLE PRODUCTION COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Other variable production costs are the expenses related to the production of each unit of a product, excluding labour."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4cbc64c9c49dd951f9997a26ee9d9f9</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2057</data>
      <data key="d6">6f718637288140098fcbdd55f4f7da57</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FIXED PRODUCTION COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Fixed production costs are the expenses that do not vary with the level of production."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4cbc64c9c49dd951f9997a26ee9d9f9</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2058</data>
      <data key="d6">276b61986cad4365a52bf7b894a9c90b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DISTRIBUTION COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Distribution costs are the expenses related to distributing the product to customers."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4cbc64c9c49dd951f9997a26ee9d9f9</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2059</data>
      <data key="d6">93a68a4260d94f16ae7613c402d270de</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SELLING COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Selling costs are the expenses related to selling the product."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4cbc64c9c49dd951f9997a26ee9d9f9</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2060</data>
      <data key="d6">83a0e2bc32f34933b72eb6dcb75d63f8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ADMINISTRATION COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Administration costs" are the expenses related to the general administration and operation of the business. These costs include salaries of administrative staff, office supplies, and rent. Additionally, administration costs will increase by $37,500 every quarter, starting from Q2, due to the employment of a change manager with an annual salary of $150,000. A 3% increase in administration costs has already been adjusted in the figures provided.</data>
      <data key="d2">16965b8a36bbe6bac45c7b81a6b17c48,2df3be986166cb71a016998a16e5349a,d4cbc64c9c49dd951f9997a26ee9d9f9</data>
      <data key="d7">9</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">2061</data>
      <data key="d6">59dba2e970ac4f4386d86045390e6637</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LIFE CYCLE COST PER UNIT&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Life cycle cost per unit = Total costs / Number of units produced over the life cycle"</data>
      <data key="d2">d4cbc64c9c49dd951f9997a26ee9d9f9</data>
      <data key="d7">9</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2062</data>
      <data key="d6">8542e01c57864eef978b622641a060f6</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LEARNING EFFECT ON PRODUCTION PROCESS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The learning effect on the production process refers to the reduction in labour time per unit as workers become more efficient with experience."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4cbc64c9c49dd951f9997a26ee9d9f9</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">2063</data>
      <data key="d6">f99931406ffb454f990fc9a83a57568a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REVISED VARIABLE LABOUR PRODUCTION COST&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Revised variable labour production cost = Total revised labour hours * Labour cost per hour"</data>
      <data key="d2">d4cbc64c9c49dd951f9997a26ee9d9f9</data>
      <data key="d7">8</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2064</data>
      <data key="d6">713ea2c6c56c470abad127f3278ea9d1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SERVICE AND ABANDONMENT PHASE COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Service and abandonment phase costs are the expenses incurred during the service and eventual abandonment of a product."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4cbc64c9c49dd951f9997a26ee9d9f9</data>
      <data key="d4">3</data>
      <data key="d5">2065</data>
      <data key="d6">47dc1f419ac743c1b707aeddbf952b4b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DECOMMISSIONING OF FACTORIES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Decommissioning of factories refers to the process and costs associated with closing down and dismantling production facilities."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4cbc64c9c49dd951f9997a26ee9d9f9</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2066</data>
      <data key="d6">26bba97ff19f40778a0a1419550f18a7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DESIGN UPDATING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Design updating refers to the process and costs associated with updating the design of a product."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4cbc64c9c49dd951f9997a26ee9d9f9</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2067</data>
      <data key="d6">71a8cb0ed9f44a008b93c035053f91d7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SERVICING AND WARRANTY COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Servicing and warranty costs are the expenses related to servicing the product and fulfilling warranty obligations."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4cbc64c9c49dd951f9997a26ee9d9f9</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2068</data>
      <data key="d6">96ebe9ca010846ecbb5d51a736df1c59</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DISPOSING OF PRODUCTS AS REQUIRED BY LOCAL ENVIRONMENTAL LAWS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Disposing of products as required by local environmental laws refers to the costs associated with the proper disposal of products in compliance with environmental regulations."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4cbc64c9c49dd951f9997a26ee9d9f9</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2069</data>
      <data key="d6">62c9143b8bf8453fb09a82da499767dd</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LIFECYCLE REVENUE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Lifecycle revenue is the total revenue generated from a product over its entire lifecycle."</data>
      <data key="d2">d4cbc64c9c49dd951f9997a26ee9d9f9</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2070</data>
      <data key="d6">cf868d3ae8204beea6067cbbba31fb97</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LIFECYCLE COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"LIFECYCLE COSTS" refer to the total costs incurred for a product over its entire lifecycle. This includes all expenses associated with the product from its development, through production and marketing, to its eventual abandonment.</data>
      <data key="d2">d4cbc64c9c49dd951f9997a26ee9d9f9,e0431b989a9611549dff83d93fe89d4b</data>
      <data key="d4">1</data>
      <data key="d5">2071</data>
      <data key="d6">d541270bd9a04754843bbac753b4d6c4</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;ABANDONMENT PHASE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The abandonment phase is the final stage in a product's lifecycle where the product is discontinued, and no further costs are incurred."</data>
      <data key="d2">e0431b989a9611549dff83d93fe89d4b</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2072</data>
      <data key="d6">4165d831dd5a4430b3233968e0c42aac</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RELEVANT COST ANALYSIS FOR SPECIAL ORDER AT PARSER CO&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Parser Co is considering a one-off contract and needs to determine the relevant costs for pricing the special order. The analysis includes direct wages, supervisor costs, general overheads, machine depreciation, machine overheads, and materials, along with opportunity costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">e0431b989a9611549dff83d93fe89d4b</data>
      <data key="d7">18</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">2073</data>
      <data key="d6">63ec55a345fd4a2e82624f209e1ec03f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;RELEVANT COSTING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"METHODOLOGIES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Relevant costing involves identifying and considering only the costs that will be affected by a specific decision, including opportunity costs, to make informed financial decisions."</data>
      <data key="d2">e0431b989a9611549dff83d93fe89d4b</data>
      <data key="d7">18</data>
      <data key="d8">0</data>
      <data key="d4">2</data>
      <data key="d5">2074</data>
      <data key="d6">a525fd1ec2e84ecd895b5a568c637a04</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;REVISED COSTS FOR SPECIAL ORDER&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Revised costs for special order include subcontractor costs, supervisor costs, general overheads, machine maintenance, machine overheads, materials, and interest costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2075</data>
      <data key="d6">e06d00243d9c4e6491c60cff9caa7bef</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EVALUATING FURTHER PROCESSING FOR SNIFF CO&#8217;S PERFUME PRODUCTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CASES"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sniff Co manufactures and sells its standard perfume and is considering further processing by adding hormones to appeal to members of the opposite sex. The case involves evaluating the financial and other factors for further processing, including costs and potential revenues for a test month."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2076</data>
      <data key="d6">a67a4f2ee378423aa0612dd2d3db2388</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARKET RESEARCH COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Market research costs refer to the expenses incurred to gather information about market conditions, customer preferences, and potential demand for a new product or service."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2077</data>
      <data key="d6">fa9e7b8014594e9bb9bd314b78f23416</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SUBCONTRACTOR COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Subcontractor costs are the expenses associated with hiring external contractors to perform specific tasks or processes that cannot be handled by the company's existing workforce."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2078</data>
      <data key="d6">5aa93cac1db24b658cff491bc8814e0a</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SUPERVISOR COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Supervisor costs refer to the expenses related to the supervision of a specific process or activity, including the salary and any additional payments for the supervisor's time and effort."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2079</data>
      <data key="d6">31aac0c6b0d74c23a030af0b906622eb</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;GENERAL OVERHEADS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"General overheads are the indirect costs associated with running a business, such as utilities, rent, and administrative expenses, which are not directly tied to a specific product or service."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2080</data>
      <data key="d6">ef1a2b0711464c60b32e4cefd694d143</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MACHINE MAINTENANCE COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Machine maintenance costs are the expenses incurred to keep machinery and equipment in good working condition, including repairs and routine maintenance."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2081</data>
      <data key="d6">de63fae6541a4e4ebaa604f15f664e85</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MACHINE OVERHEADS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Machine overheads refer to the indirect costs associated with operating machinery, such as electricity, depreciation, and other related expenses."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2082</data>
      <data key="d6">84ebf26300cc45c1994eb94ae4bf08a5</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MATERIALS COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Materials costs are the expenses associated with the raw materials used in the production of goods or services."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2083</data>
      <data key="d6">f4d7e32dfac94fb9b3de4b8e87f453fc</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INTEREST COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Interest costs refer to the expenses incurred from borrowing funds, including the interest payments on loans or overdrafts."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2084</data>
      <data key="d6">bb6566e403fd41969edfab3a3c790134</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SPECIAL ORDER COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Special order costs are the additional expenses incurred when fulfilling a specific, non-standard order, which may include subcontractor costs, supervisor costs, and other relevant costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2085</data>
      <data key="d6">c92df34470b94cb382ee6ab5a668bf32</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;HORMONE-ADDED PERFUME&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Hormone-added perfume refers to the standard perfume that has been further processed by adding hormones to appeal to members of the opposite sex."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2086</data>
      <data key="d6">a5173a8fa2df4327ab07371828719d4f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;TEST MONTH&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Test month refers to the period during which the new process or product is tested to evaluate its feasibility, costs, and potential revenues."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2087</data>
      <data key="d6">68b1467c630447aca7b5c878f9294329</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MALE VERSION OF HORMONE-ADDED PERFUME&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The male version of hormone-added perfume is the product variant designed for male customers, with specific hormones added to appeal to them."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2088</data>
      <data key="d6">88158e66558f4177af0cfcd2b1a069a8</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FEMALE VERSION OF HORMONE-ADDED PERFUME&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"The female version of hormone-added perfume is the product variant designed for female customers, with specific hormones added to appeal to them."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2089</data>
      <data key="d6">3224536ef2984db6814661a7e0504b1e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES PRICES FOR HORMONE-ADDED PERFUME&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sales prices for hormone-added perfume refer to the prices at which the male and female versions of the hormone-added perfume are sold during the test month."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2090</data>
      <data key="d6">726f9d7e848a425f8dd188968073c455</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FINANCIAL FACTORS IN FURTHER PROCESSING DECISION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Financial factors in further processing decision include incremental revenue, incremental costs, and potential profitability of the new process or product."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2091</data>
      <data key="d6">d04f699dee9f4441b7bd04a20fef8683</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NON-FINANCIAL FACTORS IN FURTHER PROCESSING DECISION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Non-financial factors in further processing decision include market acceptance, health concerns, and potential impact on the company's reputation."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2092</data>
      <data key="d6">91c3641fb8124bf49975a87b10209b9b</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LABOUR COSTS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Labour costs refer to the expenses associated with the workforce required to produce goods or services, including wages, salaries, and benefits."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2093</data>
      <data key="d6">a494ecba8c904b0580d0d9a3239aab38</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FIXED OVERHEAD ALLOCATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Fixed overhead allocation refers to the process of distributing fixed overhead costs, such as rent and utilities, across different products or services for the purpose of reporting profits."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2094</data>
      <data key="d6">c1387925a4584c41ae8c9bfad7f5c764</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SUPERVISOR'S TIME ALLOCATION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Supervisor's time allocation refers to the distribution of a supervisor's time and effort across different processes or activities, which may impact the associated costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2095</data>
      <data key="d6">29914fb54fb74c3a8790800779f07ba2</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXISTING MACHINERY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Existing machinery refers to the equipment and machinery that a company already owns and uses for production, which may be utilized for new processes or products."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2096</data>
      <data key="d6">4765d2ba673d45d58c71bc8dbf1ffe58</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;HEALTH CONCERNS WITH HORMONE-ADDED PERFUME&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Health concerns with hormone-added perfume refer to the potential negative health effects and public perception issues associated with adding hormones to perfumes."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2097</data>
      <data key="d6">51c7245aaf984c5193f90bc6c9c631be</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;MARKET ACCEPTANCE OF HORMONE-ADDED PERFUME&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Market acceptance of hormone-added perfume refers to the degree to which customers are willing to purchase and use the new hormone-added perfume, influenced by factors such as perceived benefits and health concerns."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2098</data>
      <data key="d6">1a64384d6e4047d9a933744954453021</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;POTENTIAL PROFITABILITY OF HORMONE-ADDED PERFUME&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Potential profitability of hormone-added perfume refers to the expected financial gains from selling the new hormone-added perfume, considering incremental revenue and costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2099</data>
      <data key="d6">ac61fd2545a141bf807af7f27e975a06</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SELLING PRICE PER 100 ML FOR BREAK-EVEN&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Selling price per 100 ml for break-even is the price at which the product must be sold to cover all costs and achieve zero profit or loss."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d3">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2100</data>
      <data key="d6">7683b9b483814c97a3db9057801c4a64</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FURTHER PROCESSING DECISION FACTORS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Further processing decision factors include both financial and non-financial considerations, such as incremental revenue, costs, market acceptance, and health concerns."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2101</data>
      <data key="d6">b980ce9af0c847abb0fe18096fefd50c</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;PERFUME PRODUCTION PROCESS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Perfume production process refers to the steps and activities involved in creating the standard perfume, including blending aromatic oils with diluted alcohol and any additional processing."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2102</data>
      <data key="d6">140831da2a7d400ab2d8abe7a4a9e6b1</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;AROMATIC OILS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Aromatic oils are the expensive, fragrant oils used in the production of perfume, which are blended with diluted alcohol to create the final product."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2103</data>
      <data key="d6">c6407c3c0b814668a644246116071b02</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;DILUTED ALCOHOL&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Diluted alcohol is the primary component of the standard perfume, making up 99% of the product's volume."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2104</data>
      <data key="d6">d1a8c97b85014fe8a7fdfc7d1f675063</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;HORMONES FOR MALE AND FEMALE PERFUMES&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Hormones for male and female perfumes are the specific additives used to create the hormone-added versions of the perfume, designed to appeal to members of the opposite sex."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2105</data>
      <data key="d6">d6211c7a766f46f380d4bf5ef96f6957</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;LABOUR FOR FURTHER PROCESSING&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Labour for further processing refers to the additional workforce required to carry out the hormone-adding process for the new perfume variants."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2106</data>
      <data key="d6">21f7415fd74c4de191d2b8b455ec97c7</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FIXED OVERHEAD RATE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Fixed overhead rate is the predetermined rate used to allocate fixed overhead costs to products based on labour hours or other cost drivers."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2107</data>
      <data key="d6">aa516e96dc914fb287c278e89b32c98f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SALES PRICES FOR MALE AND FEMALE VERSIONS&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Sales prices for male and female versions refer to the prices at which the hormone-added perfumes for male and female customers are sold during the test month."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2108</data>
      <data key="d6">fe0c865b2c3b451dbf212775b34ebcb9</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;SUPERVISOR'S ANNUAL SALARY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Supervisor's annual salary is the yearly compensation paid to the supervisor, a portion of which is allocated to the hormone-adding process during the test month."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2109</data>
      <data key="d6">90121ff29690453b98df789f5a12a634</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;EXTRA LABOUR FOR HORMONE-ADDED PERFUME&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Extra labour for hormone-added perfume refers to the additional workforce required to further process the perfume by adding hormones, beyond the labour needed for the standard product."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2110</data>
      <data key="d6">1a23c3b4aed04ae6b5721da9d166fa9f</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;NEW LABOUR AVAILABILITY&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"New labour availability refers to the availability of additional skilled workers needed for the further processing of the perfume, which may be limited in the short term."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2111</data>
      <data key="d6">2d9b30dcab804d389b9dc08e85c4d25e</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;FIXED OVERHEAD ALLOCATION RATE&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Fixed overhead allocation rate is the rate used to distribute fixed overhead costs across different products or services, based on labour hours or other cost drivers."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d3">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2112</data>
      <data key="d6">664cf2f1710d497a8768a4dcf9275227</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;INCREMENTAL COSTS FOR HORMONE-ADDED PERFUME&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"CONCEPTS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Incremental costs for hormone-added perfume refer to the additional expenses incurred for further processing the perfume by adding hormones, including labour, materials, and overhead costs."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2113</data>
      <data key="d6">e249188e99ea48e586bf9d1afcf9fe77</data>
    </node>
    <node id="&quot;BREAK-EVEN SELLING PRICE FOR FEMALE VERSION&quot;">
      <data key="d0">"FORMULAS"</data>
      <data key="d1">"Break-even selling price for female version is the price at which the female hormone-added perfume must be sold to cover all costs and achieve zero profit or loss."</data>
      <data key="d2">853a1c1f12ff5eee7a78129a3fed226f</data>
      <data key="d4">0</data>
      <data key="d5">2114</data>
      <data key="d6">1d63f45462a54fc6b05e0e3db7ba1682</data>
    </node>
