      <data key="d9">1.0</data>
      <data key="d10">"The Example of Cost-based Approaches includes the Variable Cost Plus Method."</data>
      <data key="d11">e96e3681999d08ff8797d8716ea0a5c3</data>
      <data key="d12">6c15d0cbc35c43ffb563c3d1b697cb62</data>
      <data key="d13">1200</data>
      <data key="d14">0</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="&quot;MARGINAL COST METHOD&quot;" target="&quot;ADVANTAGES OF MARGINAL COST METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d9">1.0</data>
      <data key="d10">"The Marginal Cost Method has advantages such as being optimal for goal congruence when the selling division has spare capacity or no external market exists."</data>
      <data key="d11">e96e3681999d08ff8797d8716ea0a5c3</data>
      <data key="d12">558419012ee6497fa3ce4c7b31c668a4</data>
      <data key="d13">1201</data>
      <data key="d14">0</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source="&quot;MARGINAL COST METHOD&quot;" target="&quot;DISADVANTAGES OF MARGINAL COST METHOD&quot;">
      <data key="d9">1.0</data>
      <data key="d10">"The Marginal Cost Method has disadvantages such as being difficult to calculate as variable cost is often used as an approximation."</data>
      <data key="d11">e96e3681999d08ff8797d8716ea0a5c3</data>
      <data key="d12">54d788c02fe8436fb83341a4ad7a5aee</data>
      <data key="d13">1202</data>
      <data key="d14">0</data>
    </edge>
